</MAP><!-- title map end -->

<!-- title image start -->
<center>
<img border = 0 src = "/graphics/title_banner.gif" usemap = "#titlemap">
<p>
</center>
<!-- title image end -->


<table border><tr><td><IMG ALIGN=TOP SRC="/graphics/logos/fssa.gif"></td>
<td align=center>
<font size=6> Indiana Family and Social Services Administration </font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<hr>
<b>Indiana Family and Social Services Administration</b> <br>
402 West Washington Street, Room W341 <br>
Indianapolis, IN 46024 <br>
(317) 233-4452 <br>
<p>
Cheryl Sullivan, Secretary, Indiana FSSA <br>
<hr>
<p>
The <b>Indiana Family and Social Services Administration (FSSA) </b> was created in
1991 to strengthen families.  Families are the source of Indiana's rich heritage
and diversity.  They create our neighborhoods and communities.
<p>
Indiana has worked to strengthen the ability of families and individuals to
move toward self-sufficiency.  FSSA was established to be a catalyst in
developing a comprehensive service system that addresses the needs of individuals
and families through prevention, early intervention, and preservation.
<p>
The creation of FSSA brought programs from the former Departments of Human
Services. Public Welfare, and Mental Health into a single agency.  For the
first time, program staffs that had been separated by bureaucracy have the
chance to work together to address problems confronting families.  FSSA 
maximizes limited resources by working closely with other state agencies
through the Indiana Collaboration Project, local Step Ahead Councils, and
federal agencies.  The goals and priorities of local communities are reshaping
service systems to put the family at the heart of them, with parents empowered 
to really help themselves and to fulfill their obligations to their children.
<p>
Click here for further information on the <a href=#STEP>Step Head </a> concept.
Click here for <a href="/indiana/home.html">
local Step Head </a> contact information.
<p>
FSSA is organized into three divisions:  
<ul>
<li> <a href=#DMH>The Division of Mental Health,</a>
<li> <a href=#DFC>The Division of Family and Children, and </a>
<li> <a href=#DDARS>The Division of Disability, Aging and 
Rehabilitative Services. </a>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<a name=DMH><h3>Division of Mental Health.</h3> </a>
<p>
<b>Indiana Division of Mental Health </b> <br>
402 West Washington Street, Room W353 <br>
Indianapolis, IN 46204-2739
(317) 232-7800 <br>
<p>
Under the aegis of the Indiana Family and Social Services Administration,
the Division of Mental Health (DMH) is responsible for assuring that
Indiana citizens have access to appropriate menatl health and addictions
services that promote the greatest extent of self-sufficiency possible.
<p>
To accomplish these purposes, DMH carries five overarching functions:
<ul>
<li> DMH certifies all substance abuse treatment services and licenses all
free-standing psychiatric and alcoholism/drug abuse inpatient treatment
facilities;
<li> DMH certifies all Indiana community mental health centers and other
managed care providers;
<li> DMH contracts with community mental health centers and other agencies
providing a variety of mental health and alcohol and other drug abuse 
treatment or services to assure a continuum of community-based care for
individuals in the following four target populations who are eligible by
diagnosis, functioning level, and income:
<ul>
<li> persons with serious mental illness,
<li> persons with chronic chemical addictions,
<li> children and adolescents with serious emotional disturbance, and
<li> persons in crisis; 
</ul>
<li> DMH provdies funding support, with the assistance of the federal 
government, for projects that enchance the mental health of Indiana
Citizens, including alcohol and other drug prevention and research
projects, and mental illness research projects;
<li> DMH operates six state mental hospitals that provide inpatient care
for persons whose illness does not respond to short-term intervention in
the community, and those who need an intensive level of care for an
extended period of time because they pose a danger to themselves or to
others at less-restrictive levels of care  These hospitals include:
<ul>
<li> Logansport State Hospital
<li> Richmond State Hospital
<li> Madison State Hospital
<li> Evansville State Hospital
<li> Larue D. Carter Memorial Hospital, Indianapolis
<li> Evansville Psychiatric Children's Center
</ul>
</ul>
<p>
The Division of Mental Health is Indiana's designated "single state agency" 
for coordination of alcohol and other-drug issues.  
<p>
Director, Division of Mental Health
<ul>
<li> Patrick Sullivan, Ph.D. <br>
(317) 232-7800
</ul>
<p>
AOD Policy Bureau Chief
<ul>
<li> Janet Meegan <br>
Bureau Chief, Chemical Addictions <br>
(317) 232-7816 <br>
</ul>
<p>
Prevention Coordinator/NPN Representative
<ul>
<li> Sally Shearer Fleck <br>
Coordinator, Prevention Services <br>
(317) 232-7880
</ul>
<p>


<p>
<hr>
<a name=DFC><h3>Division of Family and Children. </h3></a>
<p>
<b> Indiana Division of Family and Children </b><br>
402 West Washington Street, Room W381<br>
Indianapolis, IN 46204<br>
(317) 232-   <br>
<p> 
<ul>
<li> Child Support
<li> Child Development
<li> Family Protection & Preservation
<li> Family Resources (AFDC, Food Stamps, Mediciad)
</ul>

<p>
<hr>
<a name=DDARS><h3>Division of Disability, Aging, and Rehabilitative Services.
</h3></a>
<p>
<b>Indiana Division of Disability, Aging, and Rehabilitative Services </b><br>
402 West Washington Street, Room W451 <br>
Indianapolis, IN 46204 <br>
(317) 232-7000 <br>
<p>
<ul>
<li> Blind & Visually Impaired Services
<li> Deaf & Hard of Hearing Services
<li> Vocational Rehabilitation Services
<li> Developmental Disabilities Services (includes 4 state facilities>
<ul>
<li> Ft. Wayne State Developmental Center
<li> Muscatatuck State Developmental Center
<li> New Castle State Developmental Center
<li> Northern Indiana State Developmental Center
</ul>
<li> Disability Determination
<li> Aging and IN-HOME Services
</ul>
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<a name=STEP><h3> Step Ahead </h3></a>
<p>
<b>Step Ahead</b> <br>
Indiana Family and Social Services Administration <br>
402 West Washington Street, Room 386 <br>
Indianapolis, IN 46204 <br>
(317) 232-1145 <br>
<p>
<h4>What Is Step Ahead> </h4> 
<p>
Maybe it's easier to say what Step Ahead is NOT.  It's not a new state
program or agency.  Instead, it's a way of mobilizing community resources
and services, putting each county at the center of decision-making.  By
focusing on the county level -- closest to our families -- Indiana is
finding new ways to streamline the system and work together to get help
to families more quickly.
<p>
Step Ahead is a coordinated effort that allows children and families 
the opportunity to reach their full potential.
<p>
<center><i>Working Together to Put Indiana Families a Step Ahead </i> </center>
<p>
Over the years, a vast array of prorgams and services for children and
families have emerged, and families are left to find their way to the 
services they're seeking.  Too many Indiana's children and families were
not always getting the help that was available -- but unknown or not 
easily accessible -- to them.
<p>
Now the time has come for an effective way to channel those resources, so
that each one builds upon the work of others.  That new way is Step Ahead -- 
a bold new approach to human services that has moved Indiana into a
leadership position as our nation seeks better ways to serve families and
children.
<p>
<h4> How Does It Work? </h4>
<p>
Thousands of Indiana residents are working in every county across the state to
improve how we help our neighbors.  They are active on 
<a href="/indiana/home.html">county Step Ahead 
councils </a> that include parents, lcoal and state agencies, schools, 
churches, businesses, and community services.
<p>
Through county Step Ahead councils, they work together to mobilize resources
and identify unmet needs -- applying common sense and real-life experience 
to th ways families can get access to services.
<p>
Since 1991, when Step Ahead councils were formed, counties are starting
to demonstrate success:
<ul>
<li> New efficiencies that will reduce government paperwork.
<li> New funding sources.
<li> New collaboration networks and connections among service providers.
<li> Increased availability and quality of child care and other services.
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<!-- footer start -->
<a href="http://www.drugs.indiana.edu">Indiana Prevention Resource Center</a>
<p>
