 Our telephone system is TDD (telecommunications device
for the deaf) capable.  Please ask to be transferred to our TDD, or
request the relay operator to arrange for TDD service.<p>
</ul>        
        
<h2>SERVICES PROVIDED BY THE INDIANA PREVENTION RESOURCE CENTER</h2><p>
<img src="/graphics/clipart/books1.gif">
<a name = "library">

<b>Library Resources:</b></a><p>
        
        The Indiana Prevention Resource Center Library maintains a collection
of print microforms, and reference materials on
alcohol, tobacco, and other drugs. Our staff provide CD-ROM and other
computer reference searches upon request.  All library services are provided
without charge to residents of the State of Indiana.

The audiovisual collection includes a broad selection of videotapes, curricula
and leader's guides, and kits.
Free loans of these materials are provided to prevention programs
located in the State of Indiana.<p>
        

        
<a name = "radar">        
<b>RADAR Network State Center:</b></a><p>
        
        As Indiana's officially designated RADAR Network (Regional
Alcohol and Drug Awareness Resource Network) State Center, the Indiana
Prevention Resource Center serves as a liaison with the National
Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information (NCADI) and the federal
Center for Substance Abuse Prevention (CSAP).  We are linked by
computer with NCADI, and to other RADAR Network State Centers,
specialty centers, and associate centers through-out the country.  The
IPRC coordinates distribution of government publications for NCADI
within the State of Indiana.<p>


<a href="/publications/ncadi/primer/radar.htm"> Click here for more information on the RADAR Network.</a><p>

<a name = "tech">        
<b>Prevention Technical Assistance</b></a><p>
        
        The IPRC provides a wide range of technical assistance and
support services to alcohol, tobacco, and other drug prevention
programs within the State of Indiana.  Services include program
planning and needs assessment services, assistance in selection of
materials and strategies, community analysis, identification and
analysis of target audiences, social marketing assistance, education
and training, and program evaluation services.  Our clients include
community agencies, schools, social service and youth-serving
organizations, local governments, associations, and others providing
prevention services in Indiana.<p>
        
        Sophisticated planning and needs assessment services include
detailed community analysis using desktop demographics software,
psychodemographic analysis of audiences, and use of social indicators
of prevention needs, including neighborhood-by-neighborhood
analysis. These services are provided without charge to ATOD
prevention programs in the State of Indiana.<p>
        
<a name="grant"><b>Grantwriting Technical Assistance:</b></a><p>
        
        The IPRC provides a wide range of grantwriting assistance to
ATOD prevention programs in Indiana, including assistance in locating
potential funding sources, development of proposal writing skills,
proposal writing and critiquing assistance, and sponsorship of
week-long grant-writing training workshops conducted by the staff of
The Grantsmanship Center.  Technical assistance services are provided
without charge to Indiana-based prevention programs.  Participants in
the week-long grantwriting training workshops pay a minimal charge for
meals and refreshment breaks, but the cost of materials and the
training is absorbed by the Indiana Prevention Resource Center.<p>
        
        We have extensive print references, and on-line and CD-ROM
databases on potential governmental, foundation, and corporate funding
sources.  We also can provide detailed profiles of foundation sources,
along with information on funding restrictions, contact people and
submission procedures.  These reference services are provided without
charge to Indiana-based prevention programs.<p>
        
        Indiana applicants who are eligible to apply for large federal
or foundation grants may request our intensive grantwriting
assistance. This service includes up to 200 hours of proposal writing,
typing and duplicating, and proposal submission services. Due to staff
limitations, only a limited number of the most promising PREVENTION
proposals are selected to receive this intensive level of service.<p>
        
<a href="/about/other_services/grants.html">Click here for grantwriting information.</a><p>
        
<a name="survey">
<b>Drug Use Surveys</b></a><p>
        
        The Indiana Prevention Resource Center coordinates collection
of data on alcohol, tobacco, and other drug use by children and
adolescents in Indiana through a statewide confidential survey
conducted each spring.  Statewide statistics are reported publicly,
and each participating school or school corporation receives a
confidential report of their own aggregate statistics. More than
170,000 students in more than 600 schools have participated in this
survey over the past two years.  These services are provided to
Indiana schools without charge.<p>
        
<a href="/survey/home.html">Click here to see results of the 1995 survey.</a><p>
        

<b>Publications and Outreach Activities</b><p>
        
        The IPRC publishes a quarterly newsletter, Prevention
Newsline, which is available to Indiana based prevention programs
without charge.  This information also will be published on the World
Wide Web.  A print subscription to this newsletter is available to
out-of-state subscribers at a cost of $20 per year (prepaid, no
purchase orders).<p>
        
<a href="/publications/iprc/home.html#newsline">Click here to see Prevention Newsline.</a><p>
        
        IPRC also publishes a series of Factlines, fact sheets about
alcohol-, tobacco-, and other drugs-related topics.  Single copies are
available without charge to Indiana residents.  These Fact-lines also
are available on the World Wide Web.<p>
        
<a href="/publications/iprc/home.html">Click here to see Factlines.</a><p>
        
        IPRC also publishes occasional monographs and other
specialized publications.  Those published after July 1, 1995 will be
available on the World Wide Web.<p>
        
        IPRC staff participate in or exhibit at more than 20 conferences and professional meetings in Indiana each year.  Consultation, publications, and program information are available at IPRC exhibits.<p>
        
        To facilitate our outreach activities, IPRC has established
this World Wide Web service to bring many IPRC services directly into
our patrons' offices, classrooms, and homes.  This service is
presently "under construction," and additional WWW services will be
added each week during the next year.  Check the "What's New" section
of our home page for these additions.<p>
        
<b>Evaluation Services</b><p>
       
        The IPRC provides evaluation technical assistance and
monitoring services to all of the local prevention programs funded by
the Indiana Family and Social Services Administration - Division of
Mental Health.  These services include assistance with the development
of measurable process, outcome, and impact objectives; evaluation
instrumentation; data collection and analysis consultation; and
assistance in interpreting and reporting results.  All evaluations
include direct or indirect measurements of behaviors related to
alcohol, tobacco, and other drug use; and comparison or control
groups.  No charge to participating agencies is made for these
services.<p>
        
The IPRC also provides evaluation technical assistance and
consultation services to other Indiana-based ATOD prevention programs,
without charge.<p>
        
        
        

