<h1>Grantwriting Assistance</h1>
<p>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <a href=#Techn>Grantwriting Technical Assistance</a>
<li> <a href=#Intensive>Intensive Grantwriting Assistance services</a>
<li> <a href=#Course>The Grantsmanship Center Training Programs </a>
<ul>
<li> <a href="course1.html">The Grantsmanship Center's Proposal Writing Workshop </a>
<li> <a href="course2.html">The Grantsmanship Center's Strategic Fundraising Workshop </a>
</ul>
<li> <a href=#FundRef>Funding Source Locator References</a>
<li> <a href=#Links>Links to Internet Grantwriting Resources</a>
<li> <a href=#NonProf>Information for and about Non-Profit Organizations </a>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h2><a name=Techn>Grantwriting Technical Assistance</h2></a>
<p>
The IPRC provides a wide range of grantwriting assistance to ATOD prevention programs in 
Indiana, including assistance in locating potential funding sources, development of proposal 
writing skills, proposal writing and critiquing assistance, and sponsorship of week-long 
grantwriting training workshops conducted by the staff of The Grantsmanship Center.  
Technical assistance services are provided without charge to Indiana-based prevention 
programs.  Participants in the week-long  proposal writing workshops pay a minimal charge 
for meals and refreshment breaks, but the cost of materials and the training is absorbed by the 
Indiana Prevention Resource Center.
<p>
Grantwriting Technical Assistance services include:<br>
<p>
<ul>
<li> research assistance locating potential funding sources
<li> research assistance locating potential partner agencies and consultants
<li> review and critique of proposal drafts
<li> assistance in identifying and locating instructional information on program planning and 
proposal writing
<li> training in granstmanship and strategic fundraising skills
</ul>
<p>
We have extensive print references, and on-line and CD-ROM databases on potential 
governmental, foundation, and corporate funding sources.  We also can provide detailed 
profiles of foundation sources, along with information on funding restrictions, contact people 
and submission procedures.  These reference services are provided without charge to Indiana-
based prevention programs.
<p>
Indiana applicants who are eligible to apply for large federal or foundation grants may request 
our intensive grantwriting assistance.  This service includes up to 200 hours of proposal 
writing, typing and duplicating, and proposal submission services.  Due to staff limitations, 
only a limited number of the most promising PREVENTION proposals are selected to receive 
this intensive level of service.
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h2><a name=Intensive>Intensive Grantwriting Assistance Service</h2>
<p>
The purpose of the Intensive Grantwriting Assistance Service is to increase the amount of 
funding for alcohol, tobacco, and other drug <b>prevention</b> programs available in the 
State of Indiana, by providing grantwriting technical assistance to qualified applicant agencies, 
and assisting them in developing fundable grant applications and contract proposals for federal 
agencies, foundations, or corporations.
<p>
The Indiana Prevention Resource Center will select up to eight grassroots <b>prevention 
</b> organizations per year, that have a project with a high probability of receiving funding, 
to receive this exceptional level of assistance.
<p>
Intensive Grantwriting Assistance Services include up to 200 hours of technical assistance 
services such as:<br>
<ul>
<li> assessment of local readiness to proceed with a full proposal or application
<li> development of concept and funding strategy
<li> consultation on information-gathering tasks
<li> development of local coalitions and partnerships
<li> preparation of draft application or proposal
<li> preparation of budget and final application or proposal documents
<li> compliance monitoring for all technical rules and regulations
<li> typing, duplication, and submission services.
</ul>
<p>
The Intensive Grantwriting Assistance Service is limited to applications for competitive or 
"sole source" programs (not "formula grant" or entitlement programs) and must be of 
sufficient size, scope, and duration to warrant 200 hours of technical assistance.
<p>
Applicant agency must be a viable candidate to receive a federal or foundation grant award 
(incorporated entity with a good track record and acceptable fiscal and management control, 
and able to provide or acquire the technical expertise in needs assessment, planning, 
implementation, and evaluation of the project).
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h2><a name=Course>The Grantsmanship Center Training Programs </a></h2>
<center> <img src="tgci.gif"> </center>
<p>
The Indiana Prevention Resource Center, in cooperation with 
<a href="http://www.tgci.com/">The Grantsmanship Center </a> offers
week-long intensive training programs to assist Indiana prevention
professionals develop skills in proposal writing and fundraising.
<p>
These workshops are offered to representatives of registered
Indiana prevention programs at a subsidized rate of $100, which
partially covers the cost of meals and refreshment breaks.  
The fee for out-of-state or non-prevention participants is
$800.
For further information on The Grantsmanship Center trainings
sponsored by the Indiana Prevention Resource Center, "click" on
the hypertext links below:
<ul>
<li> <a href="course1.html">The Grantsmanship Center's Proposal Writing Workshop </a>
<li> <a href="course2.html">The Grantsmanship Center's Strategic Fundraising Workshop </a>
</ul> 

<hr>
<p>
<p>
<h2><a name=FundRef>Funding Source Locator References</a></h2>
<p>
The Indiana Prevention Resource Center grantwriting technical assistance service utilizes the 
following reference materials to assist clients locate potential funding sources:<br>
<p>
<h3>Print Funding Reference Materials </h3>
<p>
The materials listed below are reference materials housed in the IPRC's grantwriting
technical assistance department.  They are available for use at the IPRC, but 
do not circulate.
<p>
<ul>
<li> Foundation Center publications
<ul>
<li> Corporate Foundation Profiles, 7th edition
<li> Directory of New and Emerging Foundations, 1994
<li> Foundation Giving, 1994
<li> Grant$ for Alcohol and Drug Abuse, 1995/96
<li> Grant$ for Children and Youth, 1993/94
<li> Guide to U.S. Foundations, Their Trustees, Officers, and Donors,Vols. 1 and 2, 1995
<li> National Data Book of Foundations, Vols. 1 and 2), 14th edition
<li> National Directory of Corporate Giving, 1995
<li> National Guide to Funding for Children, Youth, and Families, 2nd ed.
<li> National Guide to Funding in Substance Abuse, 1995
<li> National Directory of Grantmaking Public Charities, 1995
<li> Foundation 1000, 1995/96
<li> The Foundation Directory, 1996
<li> The Foundation Directory, Part 2, 1996
<li> The Foundation Grants Index, 1992 to 1995
</ul>
<li> Government Information Services
<ul>
<li> Guide to Federal Funding for Education, 1995
<li> Guide to Federal Funding for Anti-Drug Programs, 1993
<li> Guide to Federal Funding for Volunteer Programs, 1991
</ul>
<li> Research Grant Guides
<ul>
<li> Directory of Operating Grants, 1992
<li> Directory of Building and Equipment Grants, 1992
<li> Directory of Computer and High Technology Grants, 1991
</ul>
<li> Indiana Donors Alliance
<ul>
<li> Directory of Indiana Foundations, 1995/96
</ul>
</ul>
<p>
<h3> Computer Databases of Funding Reference Materials </h3>
<p>
<ul>
<li><i>FC Search </i> The Foundation Center's Database on CD-ROM.  Over
43,000 grantmakers on searchable database.
<li><i>Grants on Disc</i> searchable database of over 200,000 grant awards
made by various grantmakers - updated quarterly.
<li><i>Prospector's Choice</i> CD-ROM Database of Foundation Information <br> 
searchable database with detailed information on more than 9,000 foundations
<li><i>BoardLink</i> CD-ROM Database<br> searchable biographies of foundation 
board members
<li><i>Chronicle of Philanthropy Guide to Grants</i> CD-ROM Database<br>
data on over 30,000 govenmental and foundation grants awarded in past 3 years
<li><i>Federal Register</i> On-Line <br>
official publication listing federal funding opportunities, grant announcements, rules and 
regulations, etc. <br>
<li><i>Database of Corporate America </i> comprehensive directory of the
largest businesses in the U.S.
</ul>
<p>
Due to copyright restrictions, we are unable to provide direct Internet access to most of the on-
line reference databases that we use to assist local prevention programs identify potential 
funding sources.  We will be happy to conduct the necessary searches for Indiana-based 
<b>prevention</b> programs, without charge, as part of our technical assistance service.  
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
