<HEAD>
<TITLE>Clearing the Marijuana Smokescreen - Indiana PRC </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<!-- header start -->
<!-- header end -->

<!-- title map start -->
<MAP NAME="titlemap">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="70,68,142,83" HREF=/about/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="146,67,212,83" HREF=/prevention/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="217,67,276,83" HREF=/druginfo/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="278,67,341,83" HREF=/drug_stats/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="345,67,420,83" HREF=/publications/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="425,68,492,83" HREF=/resources/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="497,68,546,83" HREF=/prclib/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="550,67,592,83" HREF=/search/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=default HREF=/home.html>
</MAP><!-- title map end -->

<!-- title image start -->
<center>
<img border = 0 src = "/graphics/title_banner.gif" usemap = "#titlemap">
<p>
</center>
<!-- title image end -->


<h2><i>Indiana Prevention Resource Center at Indiana University</i></h2>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/photographs/drugs/marijuana.jpg" Align=left hspace=12>
<h1> Clearing the <br>
Marijuana Smokescreen</h1>
<p>
<p>
<h5>optimal viewing requires Netscape v1.1 or better, or equivalent HTML v3.0
compliant browser software</h5>
<p>
by William J. Bailey, M.P.H. <br>
Executive Director, Indiana Prevention Resource Center<br> 
and Associate Professor of Applied Health Science<br>
Indiana University - Bloomington <br>
<hr size=10>
&copy; Copyright 1995, The Trustees of Indiana University. <br>
Permission is granted for reproduction for non-profit educational use.
All other rights reserved.

<p>
Recent media coverage of marijuana issues, much of it orchestrated by 
pro-marijuana activists, has presented a one-sided argument in favor 
of legalization of marijuana smoking.  If left unchallenged, this might 
leave the erroneous impression that the myths and misperceptions 
on which the argument is based represent factual evidence that 
is widely accepted by the general public.  
Nothing could be further from the truth.
<p>
While I concede the existence of some factual controversy, and that 
informed individuals may disagree over policy, the so-called "facts" 
presented by the pro-marijuana activists are not generally accepted 
by the scientific community.  Just as the Tobacco Institute is not 
accepted as a reliable source of scientific information about cigarette 
smoking, the de facto "Marijuana Institute" should not be accepted as a 
reliable source of scientific information about marijuana smoking.  
The vast majority of experts on health and drug issues dispute much of 
the disinformation used to support the pro-marijuana arguments.
<p>
The pro-marijuana activists base their arguments upon five myths that 
create a smokescreen that attempts to obscure the real concerns that health 
and law enforcement professionals have about marijuana legalization.  
Using side issues, such as hemp as a commercial crop, or the proposed medical 
use of marijuana, they have diverted attention away from their real goal, 
which is the removal of legal sanctions against smoking marijuana to get high.
<p>
<h3>Myth #1 - Decriminalization Won't Increase Use</h3>
The pro-marijuana activists insist that removal of legal sanctions will not 
increase use.  Common sense and history suggest otherwise.  While it is 
obvious that current users ignore the law, a sizable majority of adult 
Americans do not use marijuana.  At least some of those people avoid using 
because it is illegal to do so.  Removal of legal sanctions and the inevitable 
advertising and marketing of the product, once legal, would certainly induce 
at least some additional use.  During the late 1970's, when about half of 
the states passed decriminalization laws, use of marijuana in the U.S. hit 
an all-time high.  By the late 1980's, after the repeal of these state 
decriminalization laws, use dropped to less than a third of its previous 
levels. 
<p>
<center>
<IMG SRC=/graphics/publications/mjchart.jpg>
<p>
</center>
<h3>Myth #2 - Marijuana Smoking is "Risk-Free"</h3>
Smoking anything is a health hazard.  Consuming any intoxicating substance 
creates risks associated with impaired judgment and increased risk of 
accidents.  To suggest that people can smoke an intoxicating substance and 
not expose themselves to risks is to ignore reality.  
<p>
Recently, yet another study was published showing evidence of a strong 
statistical link between marijuana smoking and lung cancer.  This latest 
report was published in the prestigious <i>Journal of Psychoactive Drugs.</i>   
This journal is published by the Haight Ashbury clinic in San Francisco, 
and is considered to be quite liberal.  It's editorial and advisory 
boards include such people as Andrew Weil, Peter Bourne, 
Eugene Schoenfeld (Dr. HIP-pocrates), and Michael Aldrich.  
These experts are often cited by the pro-marijuana activists in 
support of their arguments.  The latest research is consistent with 
evidence of abnormal cell development discovered in the lungs of marijuana 
smokers over a decade ago by Donald Tashkin and his colleagues.  Inhaling 
any type of smoke damages the lungs.
<h5>Sridhar KS et al., <i>Journal of Psychoactive Drugs</i>26:285-289, 1994.</h5>
Marijuana smoking also has been associated with chronic bronchitis, 
lowered hormonal levels, decreases in activity in the immune system, 
and other significant health risks.  While the statistical evidence from 
these studies may not "prove" causation, they certainly establish a 
rational basis upon which public policymakers can make decisions.
<p>
Intoxication from any source impairs judgment and increases accident risks.  
The two most widely quoted studies on accident risk and marijuana use, 
the <i>Baltimore Trauma Study</i> and the <i>California Young Male 
Driver Study</i> 
both showed strong evidence that marijuana use significantly increases 
accident risks.  
<h5>Soderstorm, et al.,<i> Archives of Surgery</i> 123:733-737, 1988.<br>
William, et al., <i>Public Health Reports</i> 100:19-25, 1985. 
</h5>
<h3>Myth #3 - "Not One Single Death" Has Been Caused by Marijuana</h3>
While THC, the active ingredient in marijuana is unlikely to cause acute 
overdoses by lethal toxicity, marijuana's link with accident deaths and 
lung cancer are ignored by the activists when they argue that marijuana 
use doesn't kill anyone.  Also left out of the equation are deaths 
associated with criminal activities.  Even if one eliminates those crimes 
associated with drug dealing, Bureau of Justice Statistics
evidence shows that about half of all criminals commit their crimes while 
intoxicated -- at least some intoxicated by marijuana.  
<h5> Bureau of Justice Statistics, <i>Profile of State Prison Inmates -
1986.</i>  U.S. Department of Justice, January, 1988 </h5>
Does marijuana kill as many people as tobacco or alcohol?  Obviously not.  
Does marijuana cause <b>any</b> deaths?  Obviously yes.  How many deaths are 
caused by marijuana?  A flip answer might be, "Fewer than by R. J. Reynolds, 
and more than O.J. Simpson was accused of."
<p>
<h3>Myth #4 - Marijuana as Miracle Drug</h3>
The pro-marijuana activists have recently focused their attention on 
so-called "medical benefits" of marijuana for controlling nausea in certain 
chemotherapy patients, or in the treatment of glaucoma, as a smokescreen 
for legalizing marijuana.  They argue that THC, the active ingredient in 
marijuana, has some unique medical benefit that cannot be obtained from 
other drugs.  They suggest that the only solution is to make marijuana 
cigarettes available as prescription drugs.  
<p>
Before getting into the dispute over the merits of medical use of THC, 
one has to question the logic in using cigarettes of any type as a vehicle 
for administering medication.  More than half of the active dose of the 
drug is destroyed by the combustion, and the remaining drug is commingled 
with toxic tars and particulate matter in the smoke.  We don't smoke 
aspirin when we have a headache and don't smoke penicillin for an infection.  
Inhaling any type of smoke is injurious to one's health.  Smoking is an 
inefficient and potentially deadly means of drug administration. 
<p>
A national scientific consensus panel of the National Institutes
of Health studied 
the issue of potential medical use of marijuana.  It concluded:
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Scientists at the National Institutes if Health indicate that, after
carefully examining the existing preclinical and human data, there
is no evidence to suggest that smoked marijuana might be superior
to currently available therapies for glaucoma, weight loss associated
with AIDS, nausea and vomiting associated with cancer chemotherapy,
muscle spasticity associated with multiple sclerosis, or intractable
pain. 
<h5>Voth EA, Marihuana and its reviews. <i>JAMA: Journal of the
American Medical Association</i> 332:274, 1995. </h5>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

Despite the scientific consensus that there is no unique medical benefit
from marijuana use, physicians who sincerely believe that their 
chemotherapy or glaucoma patients would benefit from the so-called 
medicinal effects of marijuana are already able to legally prescribe 
THC in a tablet, called <i>Marinol</i> (dronabinol), that can be swallowed.  
This option allows for a more efficient system for absorption of the THC, 
and avoids the health hazards associated with breathing any type of smoke.  
<p>
The pro-marijuana activists don't like this option, since users of the 
tablet don't get very high.  Also, their arguments for legalizing pot 
smoking are diminished if they admit that the tablets are legally available, 
so they pretend that <i>Marinol</i> doesn't exist, and lobby naive 
politicians to support "compassionate medical use" of marijuana cigarettes.
<p>
The suggestion that marijuana smoking is beneficial in the treatment of 
asthma defies logic.  Inhalation of any type of smoke creates serious 
problems for asthma patients.
<p>
<h3>Myth #5 - Hemp: New Wave Crop to Save the Planet</h3>
The latest tactic used by the pro-marijuana activists is to promote 
the commercial cultivation of "hemp" as a source of products such as fiber for 
cloth and paper, or as a source of protein or seed oil.  Often they cite 
some supposed ecological benefit as a means of getting the support of 
environmental activists.
<p>
It is true that, with significant effort and chemical treatment, usable 
cloth can be produced from the fibers of the hemp plant.  The fibers are 
naturally quite scratchy and need to be treated chemically or physically 
to soften them.  During the Middle Ages, penitents wore scratchy hemp 
garments, "sackcloth and ashes," an penance for their sins -- it was a 
mild form of torture.  To suggest that coarse, brown fibers from the hemp 
plant are somehow superior to soft white cotton or linen is ludicrous.   
The cost of making this fiber commercially viable, as clothing that is
acceptible to anyone but the fringe elements of society, is too high to 
be practical.
<p>
Likewise, with effort, the fiber can be made into paper.  But even clear 
cutting of forests every fifty years to make paper from wood is less 
damaging to the environment than planting, cultivation, fertilization, 
weed control, and harvesting of fields full of annual crops. Marijuana 
plants produce much less seed per acre than corn, so its use as a 
source of food or seed oil is of dubious value.  It is questionable
whether the amount of oil produced by an acre of hemp would generate
as much fuel oil as would be needed to operate the farm implements
needed to plant, cultivate, and harvest the crop.
<p>
<p>
The pro-marijuana activists want us to forget that three generations 
of policymakers have looked at the evidence and determined that legalization 
of marijuana is a bad idea.  A smokescreen of myths and misperceptions won't 
change that.
<p>
<p>
<p>
<hr size=4>
<p>
<p>
updated September 25, 1995
<p>
<p>
<p>
