<p>
<a name="cover">
<P>
October 1994
<P>
Governor Evan Bayh and Members of the Indiana General Assembly,
<P>
In September 1990, The Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
issued its first strategic report detailing sixty recommended
actions to address alcohol and other drug problems described as
&quot;of immense proportions, threatening the health and well-being
of every citizen in our state&quot;. In the intervening four years,
in spite of an economic slow-down that impeded the development
of resources needed to implement some of the report's recommended
actions and changing federal priorities that diminished the attention
to alcohol and other drug abuse issues, remarkable progress has
been made. Of the sixty recommended actions in the 1990 report,
forty-two have been implemented as of this writing.
<P>
We are most proud of the progress that has been made in bringing
about planning and action partnerships at the state and local
levels and, most importantly, between local communities and state
government. What we have accomplished is due in large part to
the willingness of citizens all across Indiana to rise to the
challenge and a growing responsiveness of state government to
support community decision-making.
<P>
While there is clear evidence of success in the reduction of alcohol
and other drug-related problems in Indiana since 1990, much remains
to be done. Deaths and injuries related to alcohol and other drug-impaired
driving are down, but still unacceptably high. Use of alcohol
by school-age children is down, as is the consumption rate for
adults. But in the last two years, we have observed an increase
in the use of tobacco, marijuana, inhalants, and other illegal
drugs by youth, a disturbing departure from earlier trends.
<P>
As evidenced by the street cost of illegal drugs, Indiana's interdiction
efforts appear to have been successful with respect to intercepting
the supply of cocaine, including crack cocaine. On the other hand
the price of marijuana has dropped, a reflection of an expanding
supply which contributed to increased use of this drug by school-age
youth in 1993-94.
<P>
This report is the result of a planning process that featured
citizen participation. Beginning with Drug Summit II, proceeding
through four regional input forums, and concluding with the Governor's
Conference on Violence and Drugs, we heard from Hoosiers from
all across our state. They offered their views on the most pressing
problems needing attention as well as recommendations for action.
This sharing of information and ideas is evidence that there remains
a strong citizen commitment for making Indiana a safer and healthier
place in which to live through the further reduction of the problems
associated with the use and abuse of alcohol and other drugs.
<P>
Jeff Modisett
<P>
Chairman
<P>
Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana 
<p>
<p>

