<p>
<blockquote>

Indiana Division of Mental Health Adopts New Prevention Model<p>


<pre>
The Indiana Division of Mental Health (DMH) has announced the 
adoption of a new model for the delivery of direct prevention 
services, to be implemented July 1, 1997.  The new model 
will better focus the Division's efforts to reduce the 
prevalence of alcohol, tobacco, and other drug abuse by 
establishing an absolute priority for funding programs 
that will serve those most likely to begin use during the 
next 24 months.
<p>
According to data developed from six years of surveys by 
the Indiana Prevention Resource Center, nearly three-fourths 
of all new experimentation with drugs, and more than two-thirds 
of all new regular use begins during the middle school years.  
Data from other sources verifies that the majority of new 
use in this age group occurs during the after-school hours 
from 3 pm to 6 pm, when the young adolescents are left 
without adult supervision.
<p>
The new DMH prevention delivery model will establish 14 
regional prevention coalitions that will develop between 
250 and 300 local direct prevention services programs aimed
at 10- through 14-year olds.  All programs funded by DMH 
will be aimed at primary prevention target audiences (those 
who are not yet regular users), and will provide positive 
youth development experiences in after school hours that 
will focus on the development or enhancement of "protective 
factors" to reduce the likelihood of future drug use.
<p>
DMH has issued a Broad Agency Announcement soliciting 
applicants for to manage the 14 regional prevention coalitions.  
Proposals are due February 17, 1997.
<p>
 

</pre>


<b>Date:</b> 1/17/97<p>

<i>Distributed by <a href="http://www.drugs.indiana.edu">The Indiana Prevention Resource Center</a>.
<p>
<a href="home.html">Return to Indiana News</a>
</blockquote>
