<p>
<blockquote>

Indiana's "Zero Tolerance" Law Now in Effect<p>


<pre>

Drivers under Indiana's legal drinking age of 21 risk a fine and
a one year license suspension if they drive an automobile with any
measurable amount of alcohol on their breaths. <p>

Effective January 1, 1997, Indiana's new "Zero Tolerance" law makes it
a Class A Infraction for a person under the age of 21 to operate a
vehicle in Indiana with a blood alcohol concentration (BAC) of 0.02%
or more alcohol by volume. Those operating with a BAC of 0.10% or
more are subject to prosecution as a Class C misdemeanor.  Anyone
operating a vehicle while impaired by alcohol and/or another drug or
medicine may be prosecuted for a Class A misdemeanor. <p>

The new law, passed in 1996 by the Indiana General Assembly,
recognizes that alcohol and other drugs can impair inexperienced
drivers at levels far lower than the 0.10% presumptive level of
intoxication used in Indiana law to enforce the impaired driving
statutes.  The rationale for imposing a 0.02% level is to allow for
trace amounts of alcohol that may be present in foods or some legal
over-the-counter medications, while still making it clear that Indiana
will not tolerate underage drinking.  It was believed that suspension
of a drivers license may be seen as a greater penalty by most youth
than fines or even short executed jail sentences. <p>

The full text of Indiana's "Zero Tolerance" law may be found at <b> IC 9-30-5-8.5 </b> <p>
 

</pre>


<b>Date:</b> 1/17/97<p>

<i>Distributed by <a href="http://www.drugs.indiana.edu">The Indiana Prevention Resource Center</a>.
<p>
<a href="home.html">Return to Indiana News</a>
</blockquote>
