<p>
<blockquote>

Carmel-Clay Schools to Drug Test Smokers<p>


<pre>
Beginning with the start of the second semester, January 29, students in the
Carmel-Clay School Corporation who violate school rules on smoking on school
property will be subject to drug testing.  The Carmel-Clay drug test policy
will require students violating any school rule that is serious enough to subject 
them to a three-day or longer suspension to participate in the school corporation's
drug testing plan, as a condition of continued enrollment.
<p>
Information meetings for students at the high school and two middle schools are
planned for the next two weeks, prior to implementation of the policy.  The
Carmel-Clay drug testing plan is a "for cause" testing program, and not a
"random" testing program.  It is targeted at students who violate rules and
are most likely to use drugs.
<p>
During the school board discussion prior to last fall's vote approving the plan,
the district's above-the-state average rates of self-reported drug use, and the 
powerful statistical link ("gateway drug effect") between cigarette smoking and 
use of other illicit drugs were cited as the rationale for implementing the drug
test plan and for including students who are caught smoking on school property 
in the drug testing plan.
 

</pre>


<b>Date:</b> 1/18/97<p>

<i>Distributed by <a href="http://www.drugs.indiana.edu">The Indiana Prevention Resource Center</a>.
<p>
<a href="home.html">Return to Indiana News</a>
</blockquote>
