<p>
<blockquote>

Increase in Violent Crime in Indiana Blamed on Crack Cocaine Epidemic<p>


<pre>
In his annual "State of the Streets" address, Marion County Prosecutor
Scott Newman blamed the increase in violent crime in such major Indiana 
cities as Indianapolis, Fort Wayne, and Gary, along with other Midwestern 
cities such as Kansas City and Louisville, on the rapid rise in crack
cocaine use in the Midwest.
<p>
"Like a wave that works back and forth across the country to different 
tiers of cities, crack cocaine has brought a wave of violence with it 
wherever it goes," Newman told the members of the Kiwanis Club of 
Indianapolis, hosts of the annual event.  While some large cities in the
U.S. saw a decline in murders last year, Indianapolis experienced its
highest total ever.  In the inner city areas patrolled by the Indianapolis 
Police Department, there were 120 homicides in 1996 among the 374,000 
residents.  In the outer areas of the city patrolled by the Marion County
Sheriff's Department, there were 19 homicides among the 443,000 residents.
Newman said this was a case of a "Tale of Two Cities" in one, with the 
crack-ridden inner city areas burdened with violence related to crack cocaine
dealing.
<p>
According to Newman, dealers feel a need to demonstrate their violent tactics 
as a means of "protecting" their turf from competitors, to collect drug-related 
debts, and to take over new territory.  He suggested that only by involving 
neighborhoods in formulating solutions, can the problem be effectively 
addressed.  He cited the inner city neighborhoods of Stringtown and Haughville 
as areas where homicides and violent crime dropped after neighborhood groups 
teamed with law enforcement to protect the neighborhoods from crack dealing.


</pre>


<b>Date:</b> 1/18/97<p>

<i>Distributed by <a href="http://www.drugs.indiana.edu">The Indiana Prevention Resource Center</a>.
<p>
<a href="home.html">Return to Indiana News</a>
</blockquote>
