<p>
<blockquote>

<!-- Headline Start -->
Tobacco Veto Heads for Showdown Vote<p>
<!-- Headline End -->

<pre>
<!-- Story Start -->
State officials charged with the responsibility of dealing with youth access
to tobacco products urged the Indiana General Assembly to sustain former Governor 
Evan Bayh's veto of a bill passed in the closing days of last Spring's session
that preempts local ordinances controlling conditions of tobacco sales.  The
veto override vote is expected in the next week or so.
<p>
State health organizations, associations of local governments, and the attorney
general, health commissioner, and superintendent of public instruction all are 
opposed to the veto override.  The tobacco industry, and cigarette retailers are
supporting the override.  If the bill becomes law over the governor's veto, it 
would invalidate local and county ordinances controlling such practices as 
licensing of tobacco retailers, bans on sales and advertising near schools, and 
local penalties for sales to minors or possession to tobacco by minors.
<p>
While the bill would toughen state-level regulation of tobacco possession by 
minors, the pro-health Tobacco-Free Youth Coalition opposes it, since it will 
eliminate some powerful controls on youth access to tobacco.  The Tobacco 
industry has supported local preemption statutes in many states over the past 
fifteen years, as their primary strategy for weakening the clout of pro-health
activists.  Local premption is the tobacco industry's top legislative priority 
at the state level across the nation, and this veto override vote is seen as
a test of the industry's clout.


<!-- Story End -->
</pre>


<b>Date:</b>
<!-- Date Start -->
1/19/97<p>
<!-- Date End -->

<i>Distributed by <a href="http://www.drugs.indiana.edu">The Indiana Prevention Resource Center</a>.
<p>
<a href="home.html">Return to Indiana News</a>
</blockquote>
