<p>
<blockquote>

<!-- Headline Start -->
Indiana Underage Drinking Coalition Receives Grant from Robt. Wood Johnson Foundation<p>
<!-- Headline End -->

<pre>
<!-- Story Start -->
The Indiana Underage Drinking Coalition was awarded a four-year $840,143 grant
from the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation (RWJF) to fund the startup of a new statewide
initiative to discourage underage drinking in Indiana.  The award to the 
<b>Indiana Communities for Drug-Free Youth, Inc. </b> will provide funding for 
public information campaigns, youth development activities, and the implementation
of a prevention plan.  The programs will focus on influencing the attitudes of 
youth, parents, and the general public to support policy changes that will 
discourage underage drinking.  The funds, however, will not be used for 
lobbying activities.
<p>
RWJF is funding eleven statewide coalitions, from Puerto Rico to Oregon, through 
its initiative "Reducing Underage Drinking through Community and State Coalitions."
The national initiative is being managed for RWJF by the American Medical 
Association.  The funded groups will combine -- and build upon -- hundreds of 
smaller organizations to change the environment in which young people learn 
about drinking.  
<p>
The new campaigns -- around policies, alcohol advertising and public attitudes -- 
will focus on various segments of the public and, to a degree not tried before, will 
involve young people and broader sections of American communities.  RWJF is 
investing $10.2 million in the four-year program nationwide.
<p>
In Indiana, youth will be intimately involved in every aspect of the new Coalition.  
There will be one youth partner for every adult representative on all Coalition committees
and councils, which will also have youth and adult co-chairs.  Together, the youth and 
adults will determine the Coalition's annual agenda and implementation.
<p> 
Indiana's proposal was prepared by Jean Pock, of Indiana Communities for Drug-Free 
Youth, Inc., and members of the Coalition.  Rosemary King, Grants Assistance Specialist 
with the Indiana Prevention Resource Center provided technical assistance in developing 
the funded proposal.  
<!-- Story End -->
</pre>


<b>Date:</b>
<!-- Date Start -->
1/21/97<p>
<!-- Date End -->

<i>Distributed by <a href="http://www.drugs.indiana.edu">The Indiana Prevention Resource Center</a>.
