<p>
<blockquote>

<!-- Headline Start -->
Bill to Increase Division of Mental Health's Share of Riverboat Tax Passes first step in House<p>
<!-- Headline End -->

<pre>
<!-- Story Start -->
House Bill 1135, which would increase the riverboat admissions tax from $3 to $4 
including increasing the Indiana Division of Mental Health's (DMH) allocation from 10 cents 
per admission to 35 cents per admission, has passed its first test.  The Committee on 
Ways and Means held its hearing on the bill on January 14, and made a "do pass" 
recommendation to the full House.  The bill has a very good chance of passing the
House in the next few weeks.
<p>
If both houses pass the bill as presently written, and it is signed into law by the
governor, DMH's revenue from the giverboat gambling tax would more than triple, and 
it would provide the first new revenue stream for addictions prevention and treatment in several years.
The funds generated under this bill would support prevention and treatment programs
for alcohol, other drugs, and gambling addiction.  At least 25% of the funds would be 
earmarked for gambling addiction prevention and treatment.  The remaining 75% can be 
used by DMH for alcohol, other drug, and/or gambling prevention and treatment programs. 
In the past, DMH has allocated approximately 20% of their addictions funds for ATOD
(alcohol, tobacco, and other drug) prevention programs, so some significant additional 
funding for prevention programs could be expected if the bill is signed into law.
<p>
When all ten riverboats are operating (expected within the next year), it is estimated 
that the tax will generate several million dollars per year (likely $4 to $6 million) for
DMH.
<p>
<a href=http://www.ai.org/bills/hb/hb1135.1.html>Click here to see text of bill. </a>
<p>
<!-- Story End -->
</pre>


<b>Date:</b>
<!-- Date Start -->
1/22/97<p>
<!-- Date End -->

