<p>
<blockquote>

<!-- Headline Start -->
Bill Providing Increased Addiction Funding Passes House<p>
<!-- Headline End -->

<pre>
<!-- Story Start -->
The Indiana House of Representatives passed HB1135, which would increase the 
riverboat casino admissions tax by $1 per ticket, and earmark 25 cents of 
that increase for the prevention and treatment of addiction to alcohol, drugs,
or gambling.  The bill passed the House on third reading by a vote of 55 to 43 
on January 30, 1997, and was referred to the Senate where it awaits action.
<p>
The bill would raise the Indiana Division of Mental Health's (DMH) share of
the riverboat admissions tax from ten cents to thirty-five cents per admission. 
Twenty five percent of that sum would be earmarked for gambling prevention and 
treatment, and the remaining 75% could be used for alcohol, drug, and/or 
gambling addiction prevention and treatment programs.  In the past, DMH has 
used approximately 20% of available revenues of this sort to fund prevention 
programs.  The bill is expected to add $7 to $8 million in new revenue each 
year for DMH programs.
<p>
<a href=http://www.ai.org/bills/hb/hb1135.2.html>Click here </a> to view entire text 
of the bill, as last amended on January 28, 1997.
<p>
 

<!-- Story End -->
</pre>


<b>Date:</b>
<!-- Date Start -->
2/3/97<p>
<!-- Date End -->

<i>Distributed by <a href="http://www.drugs.indiana.edu">The Indiana Prevention Resource Center</a>.
<p>
<a href="home.html">Return to Indiana News</a>
</blockquote>
