<!-- title image end -->

<h3>Indiana Prevention Resource Center</h3>
<img src = "/graphics/publications/factline_banner.gif" alt = "Factline">
<h2>on Very-Low Alcohol Beverages </h2>

Copyright 1995, The Trustees of Indiana University. <br>
Permission granted for free distribution of copies for non-profit educational
use.  All other rights reserved.<p>



<H3><A HREF="#legal"><img align = center border = 0 src="/graphics/icons/tri.gif">Legal Issues</A></H3>
<HR>

<P>
<B>VERY-LOW ALCOHOL BEVERAGES</B> 
<P>
What looks like a beer, smells like a beer, tastes like a beer,
even foams like a beer, but is <U>not</U> a beer? The answer is:
a <B>&quot;NON-ALCOHOLIC BEER,&quot;</B> a name that brewers have
given to very low-alcohol beverages. These so-called &quot;non-alcoholic&quot;
brews are not free of alcohol. By law, non-alcoholic beverages
may contain no more than 0.5 percent alcohol by volume. For products
to be treated as an alcoholic beverage under the law, they must
contain at least 0.5 percent alcohol by volume.
<P>
By comparison, natural fermentation produces similar low levels
of alcohol in most fruit juices. Typical levels of alcohol in
orange juice range from 0.2 percent to 0.5 percent. The alcohol
level in the two best selling &quot;non-alcoholic brews&quot;
is 0.28 percent and 0.37 percent. Most true beers in Indiana contain
about 4 percent alcohol, with low-alcohol beers having about 2.5
percent alcohol, and light beers about 3.2 percent alcohol (ranging
from 1.9 percent to 4 percent).
<P>
Although the very-low alcohol beverages do not contain enough
alcohol to cause intoxication when taken in reasonable doses --
it would take about 30 12-ounce servings in one hour to bring
a 150-pound man's blood-alcohol concentration up to about 0.10
percent alcohol by volume -- they have been the center of controversy
since more aggressive marketing efforts began a few years ago.
<P>
These products have been around since prohibition, but only in
the past few years have low- and non-alcoholic beers returned
as a major force on the market. Very-low alcohol brews represent
less than one-half of one percent of the total U.S. beer consumption.
They are, however, one of the fastest growing segments of the
beer industry. The number of users has been rising by 6 to 15
percent per year. Brewers report that annual sales were as low
as 4.5 million cases five years ago, climbed to 10 million cases
in 1990, and are predicted to triple in the next five years.
<P>
The increasing market for very-low alcohol brews could be attributed
to new marketing techniques, better tasting products, stricter
drinking and driving laws, greater health consciousness, or a
scheme to develop children's taste for beer.
<P>
Very-low alcohol brews are made using one of two methods. One
method stops the fermentation process before much alcohol is produced.
The other removes alcohol from regular beers using heat or vacuum
distillation.
<P>
Most of the controversy surrounding &quot;non-alcoholic brews&quot;
center around their similarity with true beer. The brews do contain
some, albeit a small, amount of alcohol and the taste of the brews
are much like the real thing. Addiction professionals have expressed
concern that relapse in recovering alcoholics may be triggered
by the taste, smell or appearance of the products. Children also
may acquire a taste for beer if the products are available to
them.
<P>
The consumption of &quot;non-alcoholic brews&quot; may cause harmful
physiological effects due to interaction of the small amounts
of alcohol with other drugs or medications. Those who are using
the anti-alcoholism drug Antabuse (disulfiram) should avoid &quot;non-alcoholic
brews&quot; because even trace amounts of alcohol can set off
an adverse reaction.
<P>
Alcohol use during pregnancy can be harmful to the fetus, so the
surgeon general of the United States has recommended that women
who are pregnant or
<P>
considering pregnancy abstain from using any alcoholic beverages.
Non-alcoholic brews should not be consumed because no level of
alcohol consumption is free of risk to the fetus.
<P>
While the physiological effects of these drinks are somewhat negligible
for most, they do pose a psychological danger to recovering alcoholics.
The familiar taste, albeit non-alcoholic, could trigger a response
that would lead to a relapse. A psychiatrist, who is recovering
from alcoholism, said he tried a non-alcoholic brew and, &quot;three-
quarters of the way through, I started feeling dizzy. I don't
know if it was the small amount of alcohol that affected me or
if I was affected psychologically.&quot;
<P>
These products have come under fire from pro-health groups, on
grounds that they may serve as &quot;training beers&quot; for
young people. The brews allow children to legally imitate adult
alcohol consumption.
<P>
&quot;We have serious concerns that these products, either by
design or actuality, may cause serious confusion among the young,
and that they may in fact represent a seductive introductory vehicle
to get the young to begin using a form of beer,&quot; says Hamilton
Beazley, former president of the National Council on Alcoholism
and Drug Dependence. &quot;This is kind of like candy cigarettes.
It's a poor model for kids.&quot;
<P>
Many people view &quot;non-alcoholic brews&quot; as a gateway
set up by the beer industry to get young people to acquire the
taste of beer. The beer industry claims the beverages are designed
for people who want beer, but don't want the alcohol - health-conscious
yuppies, for example.
<P>
The very-low alcohol brews also create enforcement problems for
police and school administrators. These brews can serve as decoys
that allow minors to defy laws that prohibit alcohol consumption.
Minors could fill the &quot;non-alcoholic brew&quot; containers
with regular beer, and argue that they are not drinking real beer.
It is virtually impossible to test each individual bottle or can,
or impound as evidence to test for alcohol content. It would be
too time-consuming and too expensive.
<P>
School administrators would be similarly perplexed, and there
are currently few, if any, policies to control use of the non-alcoholic
brews. Schools and colleges may have difficulty preventing possession
or use of &quot;non-alcohol brews&quot; on their premises if they
allow other carbonated sodas, such as Coke or Pepsi. It could
be argued that such regulations were unfair brand discrimination.
<P>
Another concern is that the new &quot;non-alcoholic brews&quot;
might be a ploy to get around pending advertising restrictions
on real beer. The NCAA, for example, has restricted the number
of beer commercials that can be shown on college basketball tournament
telecasts. If advertising time for alcohol on television is limited,
or if an outright ban of such promotions would occur, the alcoholic
beverage industry could run ads for these &quot;non-alcohol&quot;
beers. Commercials create a powerful visual stimulus, and that
just-grabbed-from-the-cooler-look might stimulate the desire for
a real beer.
<P>
Because &quot;non-alcoholic brews&quot; are not legally considered
to be alcoholic beverages, they are exempt from federal and state
excise taxes. But then why are they priced the same as, or higher
than, regular beer?<HR>

<P><a name="legal">
<B>LEGAL ISSUES: </B>
<P>
Because Indiana law defines an alcoholic beverage as a liquid
or solid that is or contains 0.5 percent or more alcohol by volume,
is fit for human consumption and is reasonably likely, or intended,
to be used as a beverage, alcoholic beverage laws do not apply
to &quot;non-alcoholic brews.&quot; This means there are no legal
restrictions on age of purchaser, hours of sale, etc.
<P>
In a February 1990 statutory interpretation, the Indiana Alcoholic
Beverage Commission classified &quot;non-alcoholic brews&quot;
as carbonated sodas. IABC determined it does not regulate sale
of carbonated sodas, except in package liquor stores, so it cannot
make rules about vending machine sales, sales to minors, etc.
Indiana law does not allow package liquor store permit holders
to sell cooled soft drinks, so liquor stores cannot sell &quot;non-alcoholic
brews&quot; cold. Other permittees, such as convenience stores,
have no such regulations, and may sell &quot;non-alcoholic brews&quot;
warm or cold. Some retail establishments and chains voluntarily
have decided to restrict sales of these beverages to individuals
over 21.
<P>
Because the products are not alcoholic beverages, proposed restrictions
on advertising of alcoholic beverages would not apply. Because
the brews look, smell and taste like alcoholic beers, enforcing
laws against minor possession or use of beer may be more difficult,
if accused minors claim the beverages in question are non-alcoholic.
But users of non-alcoholic beers may have unnecessary legal problems
if law enforcement officers mistake the non-alcoholic beverages
for alcoholic ones. 

