<h3><i>Demographic research improves social marketing of programs.....</i><br></h3>
<h2>High-tech Tools Aid Prevention Planning<br>
</h2>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
adapted from <i>Prevention Newsline</i>, Volume 5, Number 3, Spring, 1992<br>
revised September, 1995<br>
<p>
<h6>Copyright 1992, 1995, The Trustees of Indiana University. Permission is granted for 
free distribution for non-profit educational use.  All other rights reserved.</h6>
<p>
<p>
by William J. Bailey
Executive Director, Indiana Prevention Resource Center at Indiana University
<p>
<p>
<ul><i>
<li>The Westside PTA wants to determine the need for after-school programs that provide 
alcohol- and other drug-free supervised activities for "latchkey" children living in the school 
district.  The PTA needs to know the number of children under the age of 14 who live in 
single parent households and in households where both parents work outside the home.
<li> The Hoosier Ridge Neighborhood Association wants to survey residents living in  the 
neighborhood to determine the feasibility of establishing a drug-free zone.  The association 
needs to know the educational level of adult residents in the area bounded by West 7th Street, 
North Walnut Street, the Penn Central Railroad tracks, and North Adams Street, to make sure 
that the promotional materials and survey questions are written at an appropriate readability 
level.
<li>The Big Brothers program wants to expand its after-school programs for 9- to 12-year 
old boys who live in households headed by single mothers. The program needs information 
about the number of such boys living within walking distance of proposed satellite locations, to 
determine which location would be most convenient for the target population.
<li> The Hispanic League wishes to use Spanish-language billboards to reach residents living 
on the south side of the city.  The league would like to know the relative proportion of 
Spanish-speaking residents who live in the neighborhoods surrounding three proposed billboard 
sites, to determine which site would be most effective.
</ul></i>
<p>
As alcohol- and other-drug prevention programs become more sophisticated, they need precise 
data to assist with planning efforts.  Hunches, instinct, and good intentions are not enough.  
Today's prevention planners need detailed information about their target audiences to improve 
their ability to reach those audiences in the most effective and efficient ways.  They need data 
on age, education, income levels, family structure, and living patterns of their audiences.
<p>
When major corporations have questions such as these, they usually seek information from 
market research firms who scan existing demographic data from census reports and survey 
research.  In many cases, all of the needed data is available from the U.S. Census Bureau.  
The research firms simply extract the needed information and present it in a format that the 
corporations can use.
<p>
<b><i>Social marketing</b></i> is a system that utilizes the tools and techniques of 
marketing to sell an idea, concept, or behavior, rather than a product.  Just as the 
manufacturer researches markets for a new product. prevention agencies should research their 
"markets" prior to making decisions or implementing a new program.  The Winter 1992 issue
of <i>Prevention Newsline</i> described how communications research can improve the 
efficiency and effectiveness of prevention programs.  This article describes how market 
research about a target audience can assist prevention planners in program development and 
evaluation.
<p>
Marketing experts have learned that product sales can be increased by dividing their market 
into :market segments," and then directing specialized messages to each market segment.  For 
example, a detergent manufacturer may use one advertisement in magazines with a younger 
audience, and another ad for the same product when selling to senior citizens.
<p>
Problems can arise when advertising is inappropriately targeted to certain audiences, such as 
cigarette ads targeted toward children, but prevention professionals can use market 
segmentation for more positive purposes.  Using sophisticated demographic data, prevention 
messages can be directed at the appropriate audience segment.  For example, market research 
can help planners identify which parts of a city have the highest concentrations of children 
living in high-risk environments, so that prevention messages can be more efficiently directed 
to those children.
<p>
Much of the information needed by social marketers and prevention professionals can be found 
in U.S. Census Bureau data obtained from the regular decennial Census of Population and 
Households.  While no individually identifiable information is available, profiles of every 
"census tract" and "census block" allow the user to obtain information about the group 
characteristics of individuals living within those tracts or blocks.
<p>
A "census tract" is a distinct geographic area including about 500 to 1000 homes, with a 
population of several thousand people.  Census tracts often are the equivalent of distinct 
neighborhoods or large subdivisions.  A "census block" is a smaller geographic area including 
50 to 200 homes, and a population of several hundred people.  Within city limits, a census 
block may be the equivalent of several city blocks.  The Census Bureau calculates data on over 
3,200 variables for each census tract or block.
<p>
Since the 1970 census, this type of information has been available from the Census Bureau on 
computer tapes, but due to the need to use powerful mainframe computers, only the largest 
market research firms could provide the data.  The cost of obtaining demographic profiles 
often was prohibitive for most prevention programs.
<p>
Now, for the first time, data from the 1990 Census are available on CD-ROM disks that can be 
read by high-end desktop computers.  The era of "desktop demographics" has arrived.
<p>
The Indiana Prevention Resource Center (IPRC) recently acquired new computer software to 
allow it to help local prevention programs use 1990 Census data for program planning 
purposes.  Using an Intel Pentium-based computer workstation recently purchased by the 
Indiana University Institute for Drug Abuse Prevention (IU-IDAP), the IPRC now can provide 
demographic reports needed by Indiana prevention agencies.
<p>
<b><i>PCensus-USA</i></b> is a user-friendly computer software program that 
allows users to access and sort through census data in a matter of seconds.  
<i>PCensus</i> is a registered trademark of Tetrad Computer Applications, Ltd.
<p>
The IPRC has acquired this software, plus the entire Indiana data sets from the 1990 Census 
(STF-1A and STF-3A files), which allow us to provide detailed demographic information on 
more than 3,200 population and housing variables for each census tract and census block in 
Indiana.  Since these "geographic building blocks" can be structured together to create larger 
areas, this means that demographic profiles can be generated by the IPRC for any pre-defined 
or user-defined geographic area in Indiana.
<p>
<p>
<table border=2>
<tr><td colspan=3><center>Sample Profile from Two Census Tracts from <i>PCensus</i></center></td></tr>
<tr><td>Census Variable</td><td>Tract A</td><td>Tract B</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percent of Children Age 5 or Under Living in Single Parent Households</td><td>85 </td><td>17</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percent of Children Age 6 to 11 Living in Single Parent Households</td><td>77</td><td>14</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percent of African-Americans</td><td>68</td><td>23</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percent of Mexican-Americans</td><td>3</td><td>2</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percent of Caucasian Americans</td><td>29</td><td>75</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percent of Children Age 6 to 11 Living in Poverty</td><td>77</td><td>21</td></tr>
</table>
<p>
<p>
If a patron needs information about an existing, pre-defined geographic area such as a county, 
city, or town, the data are generated almost immediately.  If a patron needs information on a 
particular neighborhood or subdivision, the area can be user-defined through the use of 
detailed census maps.
<p>
If a patron needs information on a particular neighborhood or subdivision, the area can be 
user-defined through use of detailed census maps.  At present, IPRC is using 1/24,000 scale 
maps produced by the U.S. Geologic Survey, but use of computerized census maps (TIGER 
line files) is possible.  Because the Indiana Geologic Survey is located just a few blocks from 
the IPRC at Indiana University-Bloomington, we are able to obtain the paper maps easily for 
any location in Indiana.
<p>
Using the detailed maps, a user may define an area as a circle around a particular point, or a 
multi-sided polygon by defining the boundaries of the area to be searched.  A circle could be 
used, for example, to determine the characteristics of the population living within one or two 
miles of a particular location.  A polygon could be used to define a school attendance district, a 
neighborhood, or a political subdivision such as a precinct or city council district.
<p>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/publications/demomap.gif">

<p>
<h6>As illustrated above, desktop demographic software lets a user define a particular 
neighborhood for demographic analysis, such as this area of Indianapolis.<br></h6>
<p>
Demographic market research is no longer limited to census data.  Recently, the IPRC has 
purchased a detailed "psychodemographic" data system, <b>MicroVision 50</b>, 
developed by the National Decision Systems division of Equifax.  This system provides 
information about lifestyles and values.  In the <i>MicroVision</i> system, 50 "lifestyle 
clusters," with exotic names such as "Lap of Luxury" and "Movers and Shakers" are used to 
categorize clusters of individuals.  Although two clusters may appear similar in census data, 
their lifestyle patterns and values may be quite different.  For example, those young 
professionals in the "White Picket Fence" cluster may be more goal oriented and less 
hedonistic than others of similar age and income in the "Young and Carefree" cluster.  IPRC 
can now import these data into the <i>PCensus</i> data, allowing neighborhood-by-
neighborhood analysis of lifestyles and values.
<p>
In 1994, the Indiana Prevention Resource Center's affiliated research organization, IU-IDAP, 
began a three-year needs assessment project, the <b>Indiana Prevention Needs Assessment 
Studies</b>, which will help provide additional planning information.  This project consists 
of a "family" of five separate needs assessment studies.  Some of the data from these studies 
also will be available by census tract or census block.  By 1997, a whole new data set will be 
available to assist prevention planners in making decisions about how best to serve their target 
audiences.
<p>
IPRC prevention specialists can help local prevention programs obtain relevant demographic 
information needed to improve program planning and evaluation activities.  We can provide 
detailed reports similar to those previously provided only by large market research firms.  
However, due to the need to obtain and consult paper maps, and due to staffing limitations, 
demographic reports are not available on a walk-in basis, but must be scheduled by 
appointment.  Due to limited staffing levels, this service is currently restricted to use by bona-
fide <b>prevention</b> programs located in Indiana.
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>Demographic research helps reach populations, but won't let programs target specific 
individuals.</h3><br>
<p>
Although demographic research can provide prevention planners with a wealth of demographic 
information that is useful in prevention program development, there are limitations to its 
usefulness.
<p>
Just as a product marketer could not expect demographic research to identify a group in which 
100 percent of the members would need a particular product, a social marketer cannot expect 
market research to identify a target audience that is 100 percent in need of service.  All market 
research can do is improve the odds.
<p>
Fans of the TV series "LA Law" will remember the peripatetic direct mail mogul, David 
Meyer, talking endlessly about "response rates" to his mailings.  Two percent was "break 
even, 3 percent meant a profit, and a 5 or 6 percent response was a smashing success.  Meyer 
used market research to identify which target audiences were more likely to need or want his 
service,
<p>
Demographic research can help you identify populations that are more likely than the average 
to need your services.  If the rates of drug use are higher in groups that have certain 
demographic characteristics -- i.e. those who live in "high-risk environments" -- then market 
research can help you find groups that have those characteristics.
<p>
Demographic research cannot identify <b>individuals</b> within those groups that are in 
need of your services.
<p>
For example, if children living in single-parent households are more likely to have experienced 
the trauma of growing up with an alcoholic parent, demographic research can identify 
neighborhoods with high frequencies of single-parent families, but can't tell you which of those 
families have alcoholism within.
<p>
Demographic research can improve your odds of locating children in need of your services by 
identifying <b>groups</b> with characteristics similar to those in need.  It cannot 
distinguish single-parent families with an alcoholic parent from those without an alcoholic 
parent, nor can it identify <b>specific</b> families in need of your services.
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<p>
<h3> Demographics in Action:  How Research Could Be Used in Prevention
</h3>
<p>
Have you ever lost a policy battle, or failed to gain approval for one of your prevention 
initiatives due to a lack of hard information?  Consider the possibilities of how desktop 
demographics can provide the needed information to make you more effective.  Dream, for a 
moment, of the following hypothetical situation...
<p>
Officials at a university campus are alarmed upon learning of an application for a new liquor 
license adjacent to their campus.  The applicant plans to open a bar within walking distance of  
most campus undergraduate residence halls.  Knowing that research shows that the proximity 
of liquor outlets has a major impact upon underage alcohol consumption, the university seeks 
denial of the application based upon the potential adverse impact upon the surrounding 
neighborhood (mostly the campus), which houses many residents under the legal drinking age.
<p>
The applicants argue that they will avoid selling to minors and that there are plenty of potential 
customers over the legal drinking age in the neighborhood.  They also challenge campus 
administrators to document the character of the neighborhood and to describe how it might be 
adversely affected.
<p>
Using desktop demographic software, the university pinpoints the location of the proposed bar 
and establishes a "user-defined" area by drawing concentric circles that are one-half mile, one 
mile, and one and one-half miles from the location.  Then they use 1990 census data to show 
the percentage of 18- to 20-year olds living in each circle.  These data are used to support the 
university's contention that the neighborhood contains a disproportionate number of 18- to 20-
year olds, and that fewer than 20 percent of the neighborhood's residents are of legal drinking 
age.  Without precise data, it would be difficult to document a new liquor license's potential 
for adverse impact on the surrounding neighborhood.
<p>
Desktop demographic software also could be used to compare the density of liquor outlets in 
specific parts of town, to document over-saturation of outlets in a given neighborhood.  
Demographic data also can assist prevention programs in documenting the need for 
governmental action, funding, and programming.

