<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="550,67,592,83" HREF=/search/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=default HREF=/home.html>
</MAP><!-- title map end -->

<!-- title image start -->
<center>
<img border = 0 src = "/graphics/title_banner.gif" usemap = "#titlemap">
<p>
</center>
<!-- title image end -->


<center>
<h1>MOPS, BUCKETS, AND PREVENTION
</h1>
<h2>A metaphorical explanation of the value of prevention</h2>
<img src="bar3.gif"></center>
<p>
<p>
One day a few years ago, when I lived in a large apartment complex, I came
home from work to find my kitchen flooded, and water dripping from the
ceiling above.  I immediately called the emergency maintenance number, and
the person who answered suggested that I first "put a bucket under the drip,"
and, second, "then mop up the water." 
<p>
This approach reminded me of the problem with our current drug policies.  We
have a "mop and bucket" approach to dealing with drug problems.  The bucket
is a metaphor for drug law enforcement strategies -- "capture and contain." 
We arrest and convict drug users, and contain them in prisons.  The mop is a
metaphor for drug treatment strategies -- "clean up the mess after it occurs."
We wait for people to become addicts, and then try to help them become
abstinent.
<p>
The problem with these approaches, is that we will never be able to afford,
or even provide, enough mops and buckets to solve our drug problems.  We
build prison after prison, and fill them with users.  When they get full,
we must either build another prison, or release some of the old convicts
to make room for the new ones ("dump the bucket").  We mop and mop and mop,
and try to help addicts get sober, but there will never be enough mops to keep
the floor dry, and there will never be enough treatment slots to help every
addict.
<p>
Now, I'm a supporter of both law enforcement and treatment programs.  They
play important roles in the <b>short term</b> response to drug problems.
As long as the leak is dripping, we will need mops and buckets.  But just
like the leaky ceiling, something more is needed.  If we want to solve the
problem, we need to go to its source and "fix" the problem.  We need to find
the leak and repair it.  This is a metaphor for prevention.  Prevention seeks
to identify the source of a problem, and them seeks to repair the problem at
its source -- preventing the leak in the first place.
<p>
Good prevention programs examine the situation in their community, and find
existing problems and repair them (risk factor mitigation), or take a
proactive approach and do preventive maintenance to make sure that the leaks
never begin in the first place (protective factor enhancement).
<p>
<b>PREVENTION</b> is the key to a long-term solution to our drug problems.
<p>
<p>
<p>
William J. Bailey <br>
Executive Director <br>
<a href=http://www.drugsindiana.edu>Indiana Prevention Resource Center
at Indiana University </a>
<p>
<p>

</body>
