<h2>
<img src="tgci.gif" align right><a name=Course>The Grantsmanship Center's Strategic Fundraising Training
</a></h2>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
The Indiana Prevention Resource Center, in cooperation with the National Training Team from 
<b> The Grantsmanship Center, </b> sponsors a five-day Strategic Fundraising Training
each year, to improve the capacity of Indiana prevention 
professionals to develop fundraising strategies for their orgnaizations.
The usual cost of enrolling in this workshop, when purchased from The 
Grantsmanship Center, is approximately $800, including meals and materials.  Qualified 
prevention professionals from Indiana may participate in the IPRC-sponsored workshops for a 
reduced fee of $100 to partially cover the costs of meals and refreshment breaks.  The cost of materials and the training 
is absorbed by the Indiana Prevention Resource Center.  Each workshop is limited to a 
maximum enrollment of 25 persons.
<p>
The next workshop is scheduled for the week of May 12 to 16, 1997 in Bloomington.
<p>

For further information on this week-long workshop, contact the IPRC.
<p>

<center>
<table border=3><tr><td><IMG SRC="tgci.gif"></td></tr></table>
</center>

<p>
The Indiana Prevention Resource Center hasts a specially-tailored version of <b> The
Grantsmanship Center</b>'s five-day Strategic Fundraising Training, to help develop
fundraising capacity in alcohol and other drug prevention professionals.  
<b><i>This special version of the workshop focuses specifically on developing
alcohol, tobacco, and other drug (ATOD) prevention funding plans for prevention organizations.
 </i></b>
<p>
It takes more than passion and a good cause to ensure your organization's survival.
 It takes know-how. It takes planning. And it takes money. 
<p>
Like most nonprofits, your organization faces hard times ahead. Government funding is being drastically cut. Competition for foundation grants is more heated than ever. You need to
develop a comprehensive fundraising strategy now to secure your organization's future. 
<p>
That's what you'll learn to do in this intensive new workshop from The Grantsmanship Center. You will: 
<p>
      Evaluate your organization's fundraising potential, based on a realistic assessment of its mission, its resources, and its strengths and weaknesses. 
      Examine the full range of fundraising techniques - including direct mail, special events, membership programs, annual fund drives, capital campaigns, major gift solicitation,
      planned giving - and identify those that will work best for your agency. 
      Develop the core elements of a fundraising plan to meet your own organization's specific needs. 
<p>
This program combines structured analysis, focused discussions, and small-group exercises. Class size is limited to 25. 
<p>
You can expect to work hard and come away with a wealth of practical experience. Not only will you enhance your own professional skills, you will start designing a strategic
fundraising plan to keep your organization strong. 


<p>
Designed for both the novice and the experienced grant seeker, this workshop
covers all aspects of researching for grants, writing grant proposals, and
negotiating with funding sources.  The program teaches the use of the Center's
proposal writing format, the most widely used in the world.  During the class,
you will search out funding for your agency using a wealth of materials
available at the workshop.  With a team you will also develop a proposal for 
your agency or help a classmate develop a proposal.  You will leave this
workshop possessing new skills and understanding how to apply these skills
to the needs of your own organization.
<p>
<h3>The Workshop Agenda</h3>
This is an intensive five-day program combining instruction and practical
exercises to take you step-by-step through all the stages developing a strategic fundraising plan.


<p>
<h3>Fees</h3>
The Grantsmanship Center's usual registration fee for this workshop is $695 
per trainee for the training, plus registrants pay at least $100 for meals 
and breaks.  The Indiana Prevention Resource Center offers this training (to 
representatives of registered Indiana prevention programs only) 
for a reduced fee of $100, to partially cover the expenses of meals and
breaks.  The fee is non-refundable.  The remaining funding is provided by 
the Indiana Family and Social Services Administration - Division of 
Mental Health.  <b>Participants are responsible for providing their own
transportation to the training site, lodging, and evening meal expenses.</b>
<p>
Each workshop is limited to 25 participants, who are assigned to 
five-person workgorups to assure personal attention for each participant.  
Enrollment is limited to no more than two trainees per agency, and may
be apportioned by the IPRC to assure geographic equity within Indiana.
<hr>
p>
<hr>
<p>


