<html><head><title>
Specifications for Local Prevention Services Coalitions </title></head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<img src="http://www.drugs.indiana.edu/graphics/logos/fssa.gif" align=left><h1>Indiana Family and Social Services Administration <br>
Division of Mental Health </h1>
<hr>
<center>
<h2>SPECIFICATIONS FOR LOCAL PREVENTION SERVICES COALITIONS <br>
AND DIRECT PREVENTION SERVICES PROGRAMS IN INDIANA </h2>
<hr></center>
November, 1996
<p>
<p>
NOTE: These specifications describe the minimum standards expected for programs 
funded by the Division of Mental Health under its Broad Agency Announcement 
for Local Prevention Services Coalitions.  They do not apply to local prevention 
coalitions organized for other purposes.
<p>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <a href= "#back">I.Background </a>
<li> <a href= "define.html">II.Definitions </a>
<li> <a href= "principle.html">III. Principles of Prevention Program Design That Must Be Incorporated into the Design 
of Each Coalition and Each Services Program </a>
<li> <a href= "contract.html">IV. Minimum Requirements for Contractors </a>
<li> <a href= "contract.html#perform">V.  Minimum Performance Standards for Contractors </a>
<li> <a href= "coalitio.html">VI. Minimum Requirements for Local Prevention Services Coalitions </a>
<li> <a href= "programs.html">VII. Minimum Requirements for Direct Prevention Services Programs </a>
<li> <a href= "plans.html">VIII. Coalition Management Plan </a>
<li> <a href= "plans.html#transp">IX. Coalition Transportation Plan </a>
<li> <a href= "plans.html#market">X. Coalition Marketing Plan </a>
<li> <a href= "evalplan.html">XI. Evaluation Plan </a>
<li> <a href= "sample.html">Appendix. Sample Direct Prevention Services Program Profile </a>
</ul>
<p>
<p>
The State of Indiana, through the Division of Mental Health, is in the process of re-focusing its 
efforts to prevent alcohol, tobacco, and other drug problems, in order to make them more 
effective in reducing the prevalence of those problems in the state, and to reduce the fiscal and 
personal costs associated with substance abuse.  The division is committed to increasing the 
benefits that its funded prevention activities provide to Indiana residents.  This will be 
accomplished by re-focusing its community-based prevention efforts to reduce overlap with 
school-based efforts and to concentrate its efforts on that segment of the population most likely 
to initiate use and abuse, and whose behaviors are most likely to be affected by proven 
prevention strategies -- 10- through 14-year old youth at average or moderate risk of 
developing substance abuse problems.  To that end, the division wishes to establish a network 
of fourteen "Local Prevention Services Coalitions," operated and managed by contractor(s), which 
will coordinate "Direct Prevention Services Programs," in a defined service area.
<p>
Each contractor shall be responsible for creating, implementing, and managing a Coalition of 
Direct Prevention Service Programs in its defined service area.  The selected contractor will be 
expected to recruit collaborating member agencies in each county in its defined service area to 
implement Direct Prevention Services Programs in accordance with the specifications set forth 
below.  The Coalition will consist of at least six independent, service-providing organizations 
that provide direct substance abuse prevention services to targeted youth within the defined 
service area.  In order to implement these Direct Prevention Services Programs, the contractor 
will be required to enter into subcontracts with at least five other organizations, and to 
collaborate with other "volunteer collaborating organizations" that will provide assistance, 
materials, and/or services to the Direct Prevention Services Programs.
<p>
The selected contractor will be expected to provide fiscal oversight, technical assistance, and 
coordination for the members of the Coalition.  The selected contractor will be expected to 
implement an evaluation process specified by the Division of Mental Health to evaluate the 
processes, outcomes, and impacts of each Direct Prevention Services Program and of the 
Coalition.
<p>
<p>
<a name="back">
<h3>I.  Background</a></h3>
<p>
Since the federal Omnibus Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was signed into law in 
October, 1986, the federal government has provided more than $6 billion in funding for local 
substance abuse prevention programs -- mostly through block grants to the states.  Since 1987, 
the Indiana Division of Mental Health has awarded more than $50 million in federal block 
grant funding to community-based prevention programs; over the same period, the Indiana 
Department of Education has awarded an additional $40 million in federal block grant funding 
to local education agencies for school-based prevention programs.  In 1987, when this funding 
began, little was known about the types of prevention strategies that were most likely to 
produce positive results, and little was known about which target populations and which 
strategies produced the most efficient and effective impact upon reducing problems associated 
with substance abuse.  Without this information, the Division of Mental Health (DMH) relied 
upon funding rationales described in proposals submitted to it by potential prevention 
contractors around the state.  Without solid research and theoretical evidence on which to base 
a funding policy, potential contractors were free to propose any prevention program that 
appeared to be appropriate.  This resulted in the funding of many diverse programs which were 
individually logical and which were based upon "good faith" beliefs of program impact.  
However, this funding strategy did not focus upon any particular population segment, and did 
not produce an equitable geographic balance of funding.  Many of the funded programs served 
very small populations, or populations that were at such high risk that intervention and 
treatment strategies would have been more appropriate.  Large segments of the population 
were left unserved, and some programs served such small populations that they produced a 
very high per capita cost.
<p>
Now, with a decade of research and evaluation evidence from more than $6 billion of 
federally funded prevention programming, a much clearer image of effective prevention 
programming has emerged.  There now is sufficient evidence to suggest that certain prevention 
strategies have documented their effectiveness in reducing the consequences of alcohol and 
other drug use, and that focusing prevention efforts on certain populations are more likely to 
produce positive results.  As it entered its second decade of prevention funding, DMH 
determined to utilize this newly gained information to improve the statewide impact of its 
investment in prevention programs.  The guiding principle in the development of the new 
DMH funding policy is to direct the limited prevention dollars available to programs that are 
most likely to produce the greatest positive impact upon the prevalence of substance abuse 
problems in Indiana.  This meant that prevention funding needed to be focused upon those 
populations whose substance-abusing behaviors are most likely to be influenced by prevention 
strategies, and upon strategies that reach the largest numbers of those populations with 
prevention strategies that have demonstrated impact upon substance-abusing behaviors.  It also 
meant that a priority needed to be given to strategies that demonstrated their ability to produce 
the greatest behavioral impact at a reasonable per capita cost.
<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="define.html">Next Section </a>
<p>
<p>
<p>
</body>
</html>


