        <h1>Selected INDIANA ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGE LAWS
        </h1>
        <p>
        <hr>
        <p>
        
        Under the U. S. Constitution, each state maintains primary responsibility for regulating the use 
        of  alcoholic  beverages  within its borders. While many of  Indiana's  most  unusual  alcoholic 
        beverage  laws (such as the ban against drinking while standing up, or the ban  against  women 
        sitting on a bar stool) have been repealed, Indiana laws concerning the use of alcoholic  beverages
        differ from the laws in many other states. This brief summary of Indiana law is  intended 
        to assist adults in making responsible decisions about the use of alcohol.
        <p>
        <hr>
        <em>[A  complete listing of Indiana alcoholic beverage laws would occupy  several  hundred 
        pages.   The summary below is intended to provide an overview of some of the  sections  most 
        relevant to university students. It is not intended to provide legal advice. Persons needing legal 
        advice should consult an attorney.]</em>
        
        <hr>
        <p>
        <ul>
        <li> <a href=#Minors>Alcohol Use by Persons Under the Age of 21.</a>
        <li> <a href=#GenRule>General Rules (apply to everyone).</a>
        <li> <a href=#Driving>Drinking and Driving.</a>
        <li> <a href=#Penalties>Penalties.</a>
        <p>
        </ul>
        <a name=Minors>
        <h3>ALCOHOL USE BY PERSONS UNDER THE AGE OF 21.</h3></a>
        <p>
        Indiana law states "It is a class C misdemeanor for a minor to knowingly: (l) possess an alcoholic 
        beverage; (2) consume it; or (3) transport it on a public highway when not accompanied 
        by at least one of his parents or guardians." The term "minor" is defined by Indiana alcoholic 
        beverage laws as "a person less than twenty-one [21] years of age.
        <p>
        It also is illegal for a minor:
        <ul>
        <p>
        <li>To misrepresent his or her age for the purpose of obtaining alcoholic beverages.   (Class 
        C  infraction;  in addition, a minor who uses a false or altered driver's license, or  the  driver's 
        license of another person...shall have the minor's driver's license revoked for a period of up to 
        one year.)
        <li>To  furnish  false or altered identification of any type for the purpose of  providing  evidence
        of age to obtain alcohol. (Class C misdemeanor; if the fake i.d. is a driver's license, that license shall be revoked for a period of up to one year) 
        <li>To have in his or her possession false or fraudulent evidence of age. (Class C infraction)
        <li>To  drive an automobile being used to transport alcoholic beverages, unless  the  minor's 
        parent  or  legal guardian is present in the car. [Note: When a minor operates a  motor  vehicle 
        containing  ANY alcoholic beverage s/he is subject to arrest, unless a parent or legal  guardian 
        is in the car. A 21+ year-old friend does NOT qualify a minor to operate a vehicle  containing 
        an  alcoholic beverage. It is no defense that the beverage belongs to someone else or that it  is 
        unopened.] (Class C misdemeanor; the car may also be seized by the state.)
        <li>To  "be  in a tavern, bar, or other public place where alcoholic beverages are  sold, 
        bartered,  exchanged, given away, provided, or furnished." (Class C misdemeanor; in addition  to 
        the  criminal penalty, the minor's driver's license shall be revoked for up to one year  even  if  
        no i.d. was used) 
        </ul>
        <p>
        <h3>CAUTION ON FAKE I.D.s</h3>
        Under certain circumstances, local prosecutors have used the "criminal code," rather than the 
        "alcoholic beverage code," to prosecute users of fake IDs. Class A misdemeanor charges of 
        "deception," and Class C felony charges of "forgery" have sometimes been filed.  Also,  under 
        a new <B>federal</B> law possession or use of fake or altered driver's licenses or state or 
        federal ID cards can be punishable by a fine of up to $25,000 and/or a five year jail term!
        <p>
        <a name=GenRule>
        <h3>GENERAL RULES (Apply to Anyone, regardless of age):</h3></a>
        <p>
        It is illegal:
        <p>
        <ul>
        <li>To  be  in a public place in a state of intoxication (also known as  "public  intoxication"). 
        (Class B misdemeanor)
        <li>To  sell, barter, exchange, provide, or furnish an alcoholic beverage to a minor.   (Class 
        C misdemeanor)
        <li>To sell, barter, deliver, or give away an alcoholic beverage to person who is intoxicated. 
        (Class B misdemeanor)
        <li>To  sell,  barter, exchange, give, provide, or furnish an alcoholic beverage  to  a  person 
        known to be a habitual drunkard. (Class B misdemeanor)
        <li>To  hinder,  obstruct,  interfere with, or prevent the observance  or  enforcement  of  the 
        Indiana Alcoholic Beverage Code. (Class C misdemeanor)
        <li>For  a person 21 years of age or over to encourage aid, or induce a minor to  unlawfully 
        possess or use an alcoholic beverage. (Class C infraction)
        <li>To  take  an alcoholic beverage into a bar, restaurant, or place  of  public  entertainment. 
        (Class C misdemeanor) [Indiana Law prohibits patrons from taking any alcoholic beverage into 
        any  bar or other place with a liquor license. It also prohibits taking liquor into  any  restaurant 
        or place of public entertainment.]
        <li>To  Possess  alcoholic beverages on which Indiana tax has been unpaid  to  transport  un-
        taxed beverages into the state. (Class B misdemeanor)
        <li>To  directly  or  indirectly charge for alcoholic beverages  without  a  license  (including 
        charging  for  food, entertainment, cups, napkins, tokens, etc. where  alcoholic  beverages  are 
        distributed   there  are  no loopholes). (Class B misdemeanor) [NOTE: A  one-day  temporary  permit  is  easily obtained. This permit allows you to charge for beer or wine, but  also  allows police inspection of the premises without a warrant.  Rules on minors, etc. would still apply.]
        </ul>
        <p>
        <a name=Driving>
        <h3>DRINKING AND DRIVING:</h3></a>
        <p>
        It is illegal:
        <p>
        <ul>
        <li>To  operate  a motor vehicle while intoxicated (under the influence of alcohol,  any  
        controlled  substance,  any other drug, or any combination of alcohol, controlled  substances,  and 
        other drugs). (Class A misdemeanor; second offense is Class D felony) 
        <li>To  operate  a motor vehicle with 0.10% or more alcohol in the blood, even  if  intoxication
        is not proven. (Class C misdemeanor; second offense is Class D felony) 
        <li>To operate a motor vehicle while intoxicated or with 0.10% or more alcohol in the blood 
        if said operation results in serious bodily injury to another person. (Class D felony)
        <li>To operate a motor vehicle while intoxicated or with 0.10% or more alcohol in the blood 
        if said operation results in the death of another person. (Class C felony) 
        <li>To consume an alcoholic beverage while operating a vehicle. (Class B infraction)
        <li>To  operate a vehicle with a 0.04% or more alcohol in the blood if an open container  of 
        alcohol is present in the vehicle. (Class B infraction)
        <p>
        Indiana  law  states that anyone operating a motor vehicle within the state gives  "implied  consent"
        to submit to a chemical test of intoxication (breath, blood, or urine). Failure to submit  to 
        the  test  may  be presented as evidence against the driver in court and will  result  in  a  longer 
        driver's  license suspension than if the driver took the test and failed it. The courts  have  ruled 
        that  failure  to cooperate with a test will constitute refusal in the eyes of the  court.  Since  the 
        expert  testimony  of  police officers and videotapes of the driver after arrest  will  be  used  as 
        evidence  to prove intoxication, the consequences of refusing to take the test are almost  always 
        worse than the consequences of failing the test itself.
        <p>
        </ul>
        <p>
        <h4>"Open Container" Laws</h4>
        <p>
        Effective  July  1, 1994, two new sections were added to Indiana state law,  making  it  illegal:    
        (1)  for  a driver to consume an alcoholic beverage while the motor vehicle  is  being  operated 
        upon  a public highway (Class B Infraction), or (2) to operate a vehicle with a BAC  of  0.04% 
        or  more  alcohol  in  the blood and to knowingly allow a container  of  alcohol  that  has  been 
        opened,  that has a broken seal, or from which some of the contents have been removed, to  be 
        in the passenger compartment of the vehicle (Class B infraction).
        <p>
        At least 38 local communities (including Bloomington and Monroe County, Indianapolis, South 
        Bend, and West Lafayette) have enacted local "open container" ordinances that are more 
        restrictive than the state law.  Most ban any open container within a vehicle, regardless of the 
        driver's BAC.  Local laws may be enforced as well as the state law.
        <p>
        
        <h3>"Catch 22" Rule:</h3>
 <p>
        If you think you have discovered a "loophole" that would allow you to violate the law think 
        again. In order to close any such "loophole," the General Assembly passed a provision which 
        states: "For the purposes of this title [the Alcoholic Beverage code] whenever a person is 
        prohibited from doing a certain act...directly, he shall be prohibited also from doing that 
        act...indirectly."
        <p>
        <a name=Penalties>
        <h3>PENALTIES</h3></a>
        <p>
        <b>Statutory Penalties (Maximums):</b>
        <table border=2>
        <tr><td>Classification</td> <td>Imprisonment</td> <td>Fine</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Class C Felony</td>    <td>5 years usual (2 to 8)</td> <td>up to $10,000 </td></tr>
        <tr><td>Class D Felony</td>    <td>2 years usual (1 to 4)</td> <td>up to $10,000 </td></tr>                                                                                    
        <tr><td>Class A Misdemeanor</td> <td>up to 1 year </td> <td>up to $ 5,000 </td></tr>  
        <tr><td>Class B Misdemeanor</td> <td>up to 180 days</td> <td>up to $ 1,000 </td></tr>   
        <tr><td>Class C Misdemeanor</td> <td>up to 60 days</td> <td>up to $ 500 </td></tr>    
        <tr><td>Class B Infraction</td>  <td>none </td> <td>up to $ 1,000 </td></tr>
        <tr><td>Class C Infraction</td>  <td>none </td> <td>up to $ 500 </td></tr>     


        </table>
        <p>
        In addition to the penalties shown above, police will confiscate and dispose of all 
        alcoholic beverages and containers (including kegs and taps) involved in any violation of the 
        alcoholic beverage laws. Automobiles or other vehicles used to transport alcohol illegally may 
        also be seized and disposed of.
        <p>
        In addition to the criminal penalty for misdemeanors or felonies of driving while intoxicated or 
        with 0.10% or more alcohol in the blood, the driver's license shall be suspended for at least 90 
        days for a first offense and up to two years for a second offense. (On a first offense, the judge 
        is empowered to reduce the suspension to 30 days and then permit a "restricted" license limiting
        driving privileges to "to and from work or court" for 180 days.) A third offense could 
        result in a ten year suspension.
        <p>
        <p>
        
        <hr>
        <p>
        Prepared by:
        <p>
        Indiana Prevention Resource Center<br>
        Indiana University -Bloomington<br>
        Creative Arts Building Room 110<br>
