<HTML>
<title>IPRC - Female Adolescents and Marijuana Use
</title>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h3><i>Re-posted by the Indiana Prevention Resource Center at Indiana University<h3></i>
Indiana's <b>RADAR Network</b> State Center<br>

<CENTER>
<B>FEMALE ADOLESCENTS AND MARIJUANA USE--Fact Sheet for Adults</B>
</CENTER>

<P><IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="adsfeml.gif">National surveys show that marijuana use by female adolescents
has been increasing:
<UL>
<LI>The 1994 National Household Survey on Drug Abuse shows that
marijuana use among 12- to 17-year-old females has doubled since
1991.</LI>

<LI>The 1994 Monitoring the Future survey showed that marijuana
use by 8th, 10th, and 12th graders rose for the third straight
year.  Daily use by 8th graders doubled.</LI>
 
<LI>The DAWN (Drug Abuse Warning Network) Survey, 1994, revealed
that marijuana/hashish-related emergency room episodes among 12-
to 17-year-olds increased by 50 percent since last year.</LI>

<LI>The Centers for Disease Control report in their 1993 <I>Youth
Risk Behavior Surveys</I> that approximately 7 out of every 25
high school girls have tried marijuana, and approximately 4 out
of 25 are current users.</LI>
</UL></P>

<P>Marijuana has a definite physical and mental impact:
<UL>
<LI>Marijuana can distort perception and affect short-term memory.</LI>
<LI>Marijuana affects complex motor skills, which can significantly
impair performance, including driving ability.  Car crashes remain
one of the biggest killers of teenage girls.</LI> 
<LI>Marijuana can impair judgment.  Using poor judgment about
sex can place females at risk for unplanned pregnancies and sexually
transmitted diseases, including HIV/AIDS.</LI>
<LI>Chronic marijuana smoking can lead to impaired lung function,
including symptoms of bronchitis and increased susceptibility
to illness and infection.</LI> 
</UL></P>

<P>Female adolescents who become chronic marijuana smokers face a
greater risk of:
<UL>
<LI>lung cancer</LI>
<LI>raised testosterone levels, which can result in increased
facial and body hair and acne</LI>
<LI>increased risk of infertility</LI>
</UL></P>

<P>Marijuana use can impair memory, learning, and motivation.  Young
women who use marijuana regularly report that they are unable
to maintain satisfactory grades and performance levels.  With
chronic marijuana use, a girl's ambitions and dreams can go up
in smoke.</P>

<P>Preteen to young adolescence represents a particularly vulnerable
age for females, a time when values and attitudes are formed and
self-esteem is either strengthened or weakened.  Girls aged 9
to 14, in transition from childhood to adulthood, are especially
susceptible to social and environmental influences.  Peer pressure--the
&quot;everybody's-doing-it&quot; syndrome--and the pervasiveness
of pop culture icons that contain pro-marijuana messages can influence
girls to use this drug before they ever understand its consequences.</P>

<p>
<p>
<a href=http://www.drugs.indiana.edu>[Return to IPRC Home Page]</a>
