<h2>Indiana Together:  Strategies for A Drug-Free Indiana</h2>
<h3><i>Governor's Commission for a Drug Free Indiana</i></h3>
<HR>

<P>
<h3>INTRODUCTION</h3>
<HR>

<P>
Citizen input, using a consensus-building process, was extensively
utilized to build this report. Six events, two state-wide and
four regional, provided opportunities for field experts, volunteers,
local officials, and advocates to shape the report's contents.
<P>
The report is an accumulation of the problem statements and recommended
actions that were most strongly and consistently supported throughout
the public input phase. As each input session was concluded, a
record of the proceedings was evaluated and used to edit a &quot;rolling
document,&quot; which ultimately provided the bulk of the material
for the report.
<P>
Following the public input phase, the Commission, aided by members
of the Interagency Council on Drugs, worked over a period of three
months to shape the final report. Commission staff conducted the
research and gathered information to verify the problem statements.
<P>
The report contains eight problem statements. Each one is a statement
of a need for change. In some cases, the problem is identified
as the need for a shift in emphasis. In others, the problem is
an unacceptable level of the consequences of alcohol and other
drug use.
<P>
Following each problem statement is a supportive documentation
section, confirming that the problem statement is valid, accurate,
and clear. Data, research findings, information from state and
local documents, and testimony from the public input forums are
used to support the problem statement.
<P>
Recommended actions are grouped into three categories. They are:
<ul>
<li><b>Legislative</b> - recommendations that call for the State to pass
laws.

<li><b>Administrative</b> - recommendations that should be implemented through
state policy and/or rule.

<li><b>Advocacy</b> - recommendations for positions the State should take
with regard to supporting action by others.
</ul>
Each recommendation has a state agency identified as the &quot;lead  ð 7   3                     Šagency.&quot; This does not imply that the identified agency will
necessarily have the sole responsibility for carrying out the
action. The Commission strongly supports a collaborative approach
in carrying out the responsibilities of state government. The
designation of a lead agency is to identify a specific agency
that is charged with the responsibility to initiate the action
and follow up on progress. A list of the lead agencies is contained
at the end of the report on page 37.
<P>
Following the listing of recommended actions is a brief and general
description of the expected outcomes, should some or all of the
recommendations be implemented. The expected result statements
tie back to the problem statement and identify the areas for measuring
impact.
<P>
Benchmarks are targets for measuring the changes resulting from
actions. Most of the benchmarks will be measurable targets for
each of three years, beginning with 1995. In cases where the data
are not available at this time, the first year will be used to
establish base-line information upon which to build 1996 and 1997
benchmarks.
<P>
Resource development recommendations have been clustered, forming
a separate section of the report. In some cases, the recommended
action will address one or more specific problem statements, while
in others, no assumptions are made with respect to the use of
the additional resources.
<P>
A status report on the problem indicators adopted by the Commission
in 1992 concludes the report. The data, taken collectively provide
a snapshot of the extent and seriousness of problems related to
alcohol and other drug use in Indiana. Many of the indicators
will be found throughout the report as measures of progress in
addressing specific problems.<HR>

<a name="parents">
<P>
<B>PROBLEM STATEMENT A</B> <HR>

<P>
<B>There is not enough parent or other significant adult involvement
in alcohol, tobacco, and other drug strategies and services for
youth and families.</B> 
<P>
For the purposes of this section, the following definitions apply:
<P>
<U>Other significant adult</U> - recognizes that all children
are not living with their natural parents but have different family
configurations that need to be considered and included in discussing
&quot;parent involvement.&quot;
<P>
<U>Family focused/centered</U> - programs are community based,
respect cultural differences, and are easily accessible to parents
to be as responsive as possible to the families they serve; ensures
that families are in the forefront of decision-making processes  ð 7   3                     Šthat affect their lives and communities.
<P>
<B>SUPPORTIVE DOCUMENTATION</B> 
<P>
Prevention professionals have identified parent or other significant
adult involvement as a key ingredient in the success of prevention
programs. These adults continue to be the most important role
models and key influences in the lives of their children.
<P>
In the 1993 Governor's Drug Summit II and the 5 public input forums
that followed, more parent involvement in alcohol, tobacco and
other drug services was identified and remained a priority recommendation
by over 800 citizens from around the state. According to these
participants, parents have not been adequately engaged in the
planning, development and implementation of prevention strategies,
programs and services, often passing the responsibility for addressing
and resolving alcohol and other drug problems to schools and other
community institutions. Social service, education, addiction,
law enforcement and other professionals, students and parents
themselves further identified lack of parenting skills, unresponsiveness
of community institutions to the needs of parents, latch key situations
and disjointed family support services as contributing factors
to lack of parent involvement.
<P>
According to representatives from the Judicial system, juvenile
and family court judges have the authority to order parent participation
in court ordered alcohol, tobacco and other drug services for
minor children. While some judges routinely require parent involvement,
this practice varies considerably around the state.
<P>
During the past 4 years, over 60% of the comprehensive community
alcohol, tobacco and other drug plans, developed by Indiana's
92 Local Coordinating Councils, identified a need for more, programs
and services directed at parents and their children, and involving
parents as partners in the development and/or implementation of
programs and services. Further, many of the Step Ahead Councils'
county action plans identified alcohol and other drug abuse as
a problem for children and families, and recommended more family
centered programs to support families in crisis.
<P>
<B>RECOMMENDED ACTIONS</B> 
<P>
<B>ADMINISTRATIVE</B> 
<P>
Al. Identify and disseminate information about strategies that
reduce or eliminate barriers for involving parents or other significant
adults in programs that affect their children and families.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family and Social Services Administration
<P>
-Step Ahead: The Indiana Collaboration Project
<P>
A2. Work with local groups and consumers to identify and provide
incentives for parent or other significant adult involvement in
prevention planning and programming.  ð 7   3                     Š<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration
<P>
-Step Ahead: The Indiana Collaboration Project
<P>
<B>ADVOCACY</B> 
<P>
A3. Advocate for family interventions in schools, criminal justice
agencies, and other social service agencies.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
A4. Encourage parent or other significant adult involvement in
the identification, design, development and implementation of
all prevention strategies and programs.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
A5. Advocate for state and local collaboration to expand family-focused
community correction alternatives for juvenile offenders.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Corrections
<P>
A6. Work through the Judicial Conference Education Committee to
advocate for early court interventions that involve probation,
schools, families recovering abusers, etc.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Criminal Justice Institute
<P>
<B>EXPECTED RESULTS</B> 
<P>
<B>Parents or other significant adults will become visible and
active partners in alcohol,</B> <B>tobacco and other drug planning
and services. Planners and providers will utilize a more</B> <B>family-centered
approach in alcohol, tobacco and other drug planning and services.</B>

<P>
<B>BENCHMARKS</B> 
<P>
<B>1995</B> Utilizing the Indiana Prevention Resource Center's
annual evaluation of prevention programs, baseline data will be
collected about the extent of parent or other significant adult
involvement in design, development and/or implementation of prevention
programs.
<P>
By September, baseline data will be collected on the number of
Local Coordinating-Councils and Step Ahead Councils whose memberships
are composed of at least 10% parents, or persons acting in the
role of parent, who are not affiliated with service delivery agencies
and organizations.
<P>
The Indiana Criminal Justice Institute will conduct a research
study to determine the number of courts that conduct family interventions
in coordination with other youth-serving/interested agencies and
organizations.  ð 7   3                     Š<P>
The efficacy and the potential for replication of the multi-state
agency demonstration project focused on collaborative community
correction alternatives or juvenile offenders will be evaluated.
<P>
<B>1996</B> Parent or other significant adult involvement in the
design, development and/or implementation of prevention programs
will increase by 10% over the baseline data.
<P>
Parent or other significant adult representation on Local Coordinating
Councils and Step Ahead Councils will increase by at least 15%
over the baseline data.
<P>
Dependent upon the 1995 evaluation, the multi-state agency initiative
focused on collaborative community correction alternatives for
juvenile offenders will be replicated in 4 sites.
<P>
The number of courts using a family intervention model will increase
by 15% above the base.
<P>
<B>1997</B> Parent or other significant adult involvement in the
design, development and/or implementation of prevention programs
will increase by 15% over the baseline data.
<P>
Parent or other significant adult representation on Local Coordinating
Councils and Step Ahead Councils will increase by at least 20%
over the baseline data.
<P>
Dependent upon the 1995 evaluation, the multi-state agency initiative
focused on collaborative community correction alternatives for
juvenile offenders will be replicated in 6 additional sites for
a total of 11 sites.
<P>
The number of courts using a family intervention model will increase
by 25% above the base. 
<p>
<p>
