<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="550,67,592,83" HREF=/search/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=default HREF=/home.html>
</MAP><!-- title map end -->

<!-- title image start -->
<center>
<img border = 0 src = "/graphics/title_banner.gif" usemap = "#titlemap">
<p>
</center>
<!-- title image end -->


<h2>Indiana Together:  Strategies for A Drug-Free Indiana</h2>
<h3><i>Governor's Commission for a Drug Free Indiana</i></h3>
<HR>

<P>
<B>PROBLEM STATEMENT B</B> <HR>

<P>
<B>Communication and collaboration between government, private
agencies, and consumers in developing strategies and providing
alcohol, tobacco, and other drug strategies are insufficient.</B>

<P>
<B>SUPPORTIVE DOCUMENTATION</B> 
<P>
State government has initiated several interagency and public/private
collaborations during the past 6 years: the Governor's Commission
for a Drug-Free Indiana (the Commission), Step Ahead: the Indiana
Collaboration Project, and Project ASSIST are among the most visible
efforts. While making progress, State Government lacks a long
history of collaboration, and often continues to operate in ways
that hinder communication and collaboration at the state and local
levels. The design of government clearly identifies responsibility
and does not value sharing as a pattern of behavior.
<P>
Collaboration does not render a &quot;quick fix'' to critical
societal issues. It is instead a slow and intentional process
that requires long-term commitment. Government's shifting priorities
create a time and interest-limited focus on most issues.
<P>
Efforts of the administration to downsize government have intensified
the demand on limited resources within agencies. Without a history
upon which to draw, a clear understanding of the benefits, and
a lack of incentives for cooperation, most agencies view collaboration
as a low priority, when faced with pressures to carry out day-to-day
responsibilities.
<P>
Member agencies of the Interagency Council on Drugs continue to
struggle with the purpose and value of this collaboration model.
Although agency participants increasingly share information and
collaborate, it is difficult for participants to fully embrace
this non-traditional mode of operating and relating, and to advocate
for full agency commitment and involvement.
<P>
According to the Commission's Regional Coordinating Offices, local
partners comment that state planners need to identify existing
efforts of government before developing new community collaboration
initiatives. Not doing this has resulted in multiple organizations
or efforts with duplicative purposes, and limited the ability
of government to provide service and/or support to grassroots
projects.
<P>
Community partners also believe that local level collaborations
are working much better than state efforts and that the lack of
communication and collaboration at the state level limits the
effectiveness of the local agencies to work cooperatively. It
is further believed that there are no practiced policies at the
state level that foster and reward cooperation and collaboration
at the local level.
<P>
Private sector and youth partners have been identified as critically
missing in many local collaborations. Local partners say they
look to government to assist with these linkages. To date, state
government has been unsuccessful in attempts to involve private
sector participation to support local efforts. Although young
people are becoming more visible in local planning and programming
activity, there is minimal activity from state government to facilitate
youth as partners in the collaboration agenda.
<P>
<B>RECOMMENDED ACTIONS</B> 
<P>
<B>ADMINISTRATIVE</B> 
<P>
B1. Require evidence of collaboration as a condition of state
alcohol and other drug funding, certifying or licensing.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
B2. Improve the coordination efforts of the Interagency Council
on Drugs.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B3. Improve the working relationship between justice, education,
and treatment programs serving youthful offenders.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Criminal Justice Institute
<P>
B4. Develop opportunities to CO-train parents, teachers, law enforcement
and court personnel on how to recognize when youth need assistance.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
B5. Create opportunities and methods for state legislators and
other elected officials to learn about alcohol and other drug
issues.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B6. Expand opportunities for state/local discussion on policy
issues.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B7. Improve communication to youth about opportunities for involvement.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B8. Develop training opportunities for youth to learn how to participate
and for adults to learn how to involve and work with youth as
partners.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B9. Provide state level incentive funding and programming to encourage
and support local linkages and strategies for addressing community
alcohol, tobacco and other drug problems.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B10. Develop a common state application form and an application
process that can be used by multiple state agencies that fund
alcohol, tobacco and other drug programs and services.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B11. Organize a state focus group composed of private sector representatives
to advise the state about how to engage the private sector in
local alcohol and other drug collaborations and disseminate the
information to local partners.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
<B>ADVOCACY</B> 
<P>
B12. Encourage all state agencies to recognize Local Coordinating
Councils as local coordinating bodies for alcohol, tobacco and
other drug services as authorized through PL 39 Acts of 1991,
and to utilize the comprehensive community alcohol and other drug
plans developed by those councils.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B13. Advocate for the use of youth focus groups in the design
and evaluation of programs that serve youth.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B14. Advocate for more private sector involvement in local coordination.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
B15. Promote the Step Ahead Councils' efforts to bring a collaborative
approach to services for children and families, including Step
Ahead coordination with Local Coordinating Councils to identify
alcohol, tobacco and other drug problems and develop strategies
for children and parents.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration
<P>
-Step Ahead: The Indiana Collaboration Project
<P>
<B>EXPECTED RESULTS</B> 
<P>
<B>There will be greater effectiveness and efficiency in planning,
developing and funding alcohol, tobacco and other drugs strategies
and services. There will be improved resource utilization.</B>

<P>
<B>BENCHMARKS</B> 
<P>
<B>1995 </B>By May, 50 of the 92 Local Coordinating Councils and
Step Ahead Councils will collaborate about alcohol and other drug
community plans and planning initiatives related to children and
families.
<P>
A common application form and process for alcohol and other drug
funding will be developed.
<P>
Definitions and administrative standards that require evidence
of collaboration as a condition of state alcohol and other drug
funding, certifying or licensing will be determined.
<P>
Interagency agreements will be established between the Commission
and the Department of Education, Criminal Justice Institute, Division
of Mental Health and Department of Health about how they will
utilize Local Coordinating Councils and their comprehensive community
alcohol and other drug plans.
<P>
Baseline data about the number of opportunities available for
input into state alcohol and other drug planning and policy development
will be established.
<P>
Baseline data on state agencies' use of youth focus groups in
the design and evaluation of programs that serve youth will be
established.
<P>
A state focus group on private sector involvement in local alcohol
and other drug collaborations will be held by September; the resulting
information disseminated to local partners by December.
<P>
<B>1996</B> By May, 65 of the 92 Local Coordinating Councils and
Step Ahead Councils will collaborate about alcohol and other drug
community plans and planning initiatives related to children and
families.
<P>
All agencies funding alcohol and other drug programs and services
will use a common application form and process.
<P>
All state agencies will require evidence of collaboration as a
condition of state alcohol and other drug funding, certifying
or licensing.
<P>
All state agencies with alcohol and other drug responsibilities
will utilize local coordinating councils and their comprehensive
community alcohol and other drug plans when planning program and
funding initiatives.
<P>
Statewide, there will be at least 2 opportunities for public input
into alcohol and other drug planning and policy development.
<P>
All state agencies will use youth focus groups in the design and
evaluation of programs that serve youth.
<P>
<B>1997</B> By May, 80 of the 92 Local Coordinating Councils and
Step Ahead Councils will collaborate about alcohol and other drug
community plans and planning initiatives related to children and
families.
<P>
Statewide, there will be at least 2 opportunities for public input
into alcohol and other drug planning and policy development. 

<p>
<p>
