<h2>Indiana Together:  Strategies for A Drug-Free Indiana</h2>
<h3><i>Governor's Commission for a Drug Free Indiana</i></h3>
<HR>

<P>


<P>
<B>PROBLEM STATEMENT C</B> <HR>

<P>
<B>There is a continuing demand for alcohol, tobacco, and other
drug products by youth and adults, resulting in individual and
community impairment.</B> 
<P>
<B>SUPPORTIVE DOCUMENTATION</B> 
<P>
In its 1994 Prevalence Statistics Survey, the Indiana Prevention
Resource Center (PRC) reports an increased use of cigarettes,
marijuana, and inhalants by Indiana students. The PRC survey further
states that the rate of binge drinking remains static after a
two year decline, the use of other drugs remains virtually unchanged,
and the illegal use of prescription drugs remains significantly
higher than national usage rates. Early tobacco experimentation
also continues to be a problem.
<P>
According to a 1992 Indiana Department of Health tobacco analysis,
approximately 24% of adult citizens of Indiana smoke and about
3.4% chew tobacco and/or use snuff. Black adults have a higher
rate of use than do hispanics, whites, and adults of other ethnic
populations.
<P>
Among persons 35-64 years of age, Indiana rates well above the
national median for cigarette smoking prevalence according to
a 1990 report authorized by the Office of Smoking and Health,
National Center for Chronic Disease Prevention and Health Promotion.
<P>
There were 230 counts of alcohol sales to minors in 1993. Most
notable were: 1) in 55 of those counts, minors used false IDs
to buy alcohol, and 2) fifteen of the violations of sales to minors
were in grocery and drug stores. The State Excise Police point
out that enforcing minor sales laws in grocery and drug stores
is a major problem because of the range of products sold in these
types of outlets. These enforcement difficulties are thought to
result in a lower detection rate of violations in drug and grocery
stores.
<P>
Preliminary results from a survey of Indiana college students
between the ages of 18 and 24, conducted by the Indiana University
Institute for Drug Abuse Prevention, suggest that 48.7% of those
students surveyed possessed false evidence of age to obtain alcohol,
and 40.% used false evidence of age to obtain alcohol.
<P>
When asked about the difficulty for minors to buy alcohol in certain
types of establishments, students responded as follows:
<P>
<U>Easy or Moderate</U> <U>Difficult</U> 
<P>
Package liquor stores 76.2% 23.8%
<P>
Taverns or bars 89.3% 11.7%
<P>
Other restaurants 74.4% 25.6%
<P>
Convenience stores or mini marts 85.9% 14.1%
<P>
Full-service grocery stores 74.4% 25.6%
<P>
Drug Stores 70.1% 29.9%
<P>
In Indiana it is legal for 18-20 year-olds to sell alcohol in
convenience stores, mini marts, grocery stores and drug stores.
71.9% of the students surveyed said it was easier to buy alcohol
from underage clerks: as a minor, 31.5 % had purchased alcohol
from a clerk they believed to be underage, and 56.6% said underage
clerks were less likely to check IDs than clerks who were of legal
drinking age.
<P>
Preliminary results from the 1993 National Household Survey on
Drug Abuse suggest that the downward trend in prevalence of drug
use over the past ten years may have stopped. The data reflect
a leveling off of the prevalence rate and further suggests the
beginning of an upward trend in drug use for all age groups. The
survey also indicates a softening of anti-drug attitudes of youth.
Additionally, the survey reports the persistence of heavy, chronic
use of illegal drugs by the over 35 age group.
<P>

<P>
<B>RECOMMENDED ACTIONS</B> 
<P>
<B>LEGISLATIVE</B> 
<P>
C 1. Require the posting of health warning signs at all places
of retail sales of alcohol and tobacco products.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana State Department of Health
<P>
C2. Increase state funding for prevention planning and programming.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C3. Ban advertisements for alcohol beverages and tobacco products
in places where youth congregate such as parks, arcades, etc.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C4. Pass legislation prohibiting a minor 18 years of age and older
from ringing up a sale of alcoholic beverages in the course of
her/his employment, amending the current statue which allows such
activity.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C5. Increase excise taxes on tobacco and alcohol products. (See
Rl, p. 33).
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Alcoholic Beverage Commission
<P>
<B>ADMINISTRATIVE</B> 
<P>
C6. Assist organizations with the identification of alternative
funding sources for community events usually supported and promoted
by the alcohol beverage and tobacco industries.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C7. Develop and implement state and local enforcement strategies
to monitor tobacco sales to minors using collaboration models
which include the target population, consumers, community retailers,
law officials, health officials and other interested community
partners.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Alcoholic Beverage Commission
<P>
C8. Educate youth under 18, local retailers and the general public
about laws governing the sale and use of tobacco by minors, and
about local compliance ordinances.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana State Department of Health
<P>
C9. Improve the dissemination of alcohol, tobacco and other drug
education and drug prevention model program research information.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Education
<P>
C10. Intensify education efforts directed toward the general public
about alcohol, tobacco, and other drugs utilizing existing community
outreach mediums.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C11. Require that target populations be involved in developing
prevention strategies and programs.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
C12. Conduct counter-advertising to youth audiences through youth-oriented
television, movies, and videos.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C13. Work with people with disabilities and advocates to develop
prevention strategies and to improve access to prevention services
for people with disabilities.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
C14. Develop prevention linkages with the service network for
elderly citizens to expand drug abuse prevention activities.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
C15. Develop and promote unified and consistent statewide message
by coordinating the various tobacco, alcohol and other drug public
awareness campaigns of state government.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C16. Work with marketers and minority media to launch campaigns
about the impact of alcohol and tobacco in minority communities/populations.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C17. Work with Local Coordinating Councils to improve the enforcement
of current laws which address minors possessing or using alcohol.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Alcoholic Beverage Commission
<P>
C18. Increase monitoring of alcohol retail outlets.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Alcoholic Beverage Commission
<P>
C19. Improve the detectability of false identification and driver's
license cards.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Bureau of Motor Vehicles
<P>
C20. Strengthen safeguards against obtaining an illegal driver's
license at point of issuance.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Bureau of Motor Vehicles
<P>
C21. Provide for stricter enforcement of existing Alcohol Beverage
Commission administrative rules.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Alcoholic Beverage Commission
<P>
<B>ADVOCACY</B> 
<P>
C22. Encourage the development of local tobacco compliance ordinances
where none exist to address and support the enforcement of existing
laws about sales, possession and use of tobacco products for youth.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C23. Advocate for youth mentorship opportunities as positive alternatives
to alcohol, tobacco and other drug use.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C24. Advocate for the end of federal subsidies to tobacco growers
increasing the cost of tobacco products, thus reducing the demand
for the product.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C25. Advocate for the removal of alcohol advertisements from television,
especially during prime time.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C26. Advocate for local organizations to reject sponsorship of
events by the alcohol beverage and tobacco industries.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
C27. Oppose any legislation that would increase the number of
alcohol beverage outlets allowed in any community.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
<B>EXPECTED RESULTS</B> 
<P>
<B>There will be a decrease in the incidence, prevalence, and
negative consequences of alcohol, tobacco and other drug use among
the youth and adult populations. There will be an increase in
the average age of first use.</B> 
<P>
<B>BENCHMARKS</B> 
<P>
<B>1995</B> No more than 29.6% of young people age 12-17 will
have used alcohol in the past month.
<P>
No more than 22.9% of young people age 12-17 will have used tobacco
in the past month.
<P>
No more than 10.2% of young people age 12-17 will have used marijuana
in the past month.
<P>
The average age of first use of cigarettes will increase from
11.6 to 11.8.
<P>
The average age of first use of alcohol will increase from 13.0
to 13.1.
<P>
The average age of first use of marijuana will increase from 12.9
to 13.1.
<P>
No more than 24% of adults will use tobacco products.
<P>
Average per capita consumption of alcohol will be no higher than
1.99 gallons.
<P>
A method for collecting statewide data on emergency room visits
for alcohol and other drug emergencies will be developed by May.
<P>
There will be no more than 180 fatal alcohol-related crashes in
1995, resulting in no more than 184 fatalities and no more than
4,339 personal injury crashes, resulting in no more than 6,447
injuries.
<P>
<B>1996</B> No more than 26.2% of young people age 12-17 will
have used alcohol in the past month.
<P>
No more than 21.0% of young people age 12-17 will have used tobacco
in the past month.
<P>
No more than 9.0% of young people age 12-17 will have used marijuana
in the past month.
<P>
The average age of first use of cigarettes will increase from
11.8 to 12.0.
<P>
The average age of first use of alcohol will increase from 13.1
to 13.3.
<P>
The average age of first use of marijuana will increase from 13.1
to 13.3.
<P>
No more than 20.5% of adults will use tobacco products.
<P>
Average per capita consumption of alcohol will be no higher than
1.97 gallons.
<P>
Baseline data on emergency room visits for alcohol and other drug
emergencies will be established by January.
<P>
There will be no more than 171 fatal alcohol-related crashes in
1996, resulting in no more than 166 fatalities and no more than
4,122 personal injury crashes, resulting in no more than 6,125
injuries.
<P>
<B>1997</B> No more than 22.8% of young people age 12-17 will
have used alcohol in the past month.
<P>
No more than 19.3% of young people age 12-17 will have used tobacco
in the past month.
<P>
No more than 7.4% of young people age 12-17 will have used marijuana
in the past month.
<P>
The average age of first use of cigarettes will increase from
12 to 12.2.
<P>
The average age of first use of alcohol will increase from 13.3
to 13.5.
<P>
The average age of first use of marijuana will increase from 13.5
to 13.7.
<P>
No more than 17% of adults will use tobacco products.
<P>
Average per capita consumption of alcohol will be no higher than
1.95 gallons.
<P>
Emergency room visits for alcohol and other drug emergencies will
decrease by 5% below baseline date.
<P>
There will be no more than 162 fatal alcohol-related crashes in
1997, resulting in no more than 149 fatalities and no more than
3,916 personal injury crashes, resulting in no more than 5,819
injuries. 
<p>
<p>
