<h2>Indiana Together:  Strategies for A Drug-Free Indiana</h2>
<h3><i>Governor's Commission for a Drug Free Indiana</i></h3>
<HR>

<P>
<B>PROBLEM STATEMENT D</B> 
<P>
<B>The capacity to treat offenders in state correctional facilities
is inadequate, resulting in long waiting lists for services and
lapses in treatment continuity .</B> 
<P>
SUPPORTIVE DOCUMENTATION
<P>
The Indiana Department of Correction reports that for the year
ending June 30, 1994, the average number of offenders enrolled
in treatment programs per day was 1,920, with an average of 1,574
on waiting lists. The average length of time on a waiting list
was reported to be six to nine months. The factors identified
by DOC that impact upon their ability to meet the identified needs
and successfully treat inmates were:
<UL>
<LI>inadequate numbers of treatment professionals;
<LI>turnover of treatment staff;
<LI>insufficient space in which to conduct programs;
<LI>transfers of inmates between facilities due to capacity limitations;
and
<LI>the number of offenders waiting to be admitted.
</UL>

<P>
Further, DOC officials note that progress made in treatment is
sometimes negated by a breakdown in the continuity of treatment
between institutional and community programming.
<P>
RECOMMENDED ACTIONS
<P>
LEGISLATIVE
<P>
Dl. Increase state funding to significantly reduce waiting lists.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Correction
<P>
ADMINISTRATIVE
<P>
D2. Require that treatment programs for offenders incorporate
family issues.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Correction
<P>
D3. Develop more intensive treatment programs for offenders who
are about to be released.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Correction
<P>
D4. Increase space allocated in state institutions for treatment
programming.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Correction
<P>
D5. Expand opportunities for corrections and community treatment
professionals to interchange ideas on services to offenders.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Correction
<P>
D6. Improve DOC treatment personnel salaries to attract more qualified
clinicians.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Correction
<P>
EXPECTED RESULTS
<P>
There will be an increased number of DOC inmates identified as
needing treatment for alcohol and other drug problems who receive
more timely services prior to release. There will be improved
treatment continuity within DOC as well as with post-release treatment
services.
<P>
BENCHMARKS
<P>
1995 The waiting list will be reduced to no more than an average
of 1,200 for the year ending June 30, 1995.
<P>
The average number of offenders receiving treatment services will
not change for the year ending June 30, 1995.
<P>
Fewer than 12% of those offenders receiving services will have
treatment interrupted as a result of placement transfers during
the year ending June 30, 1995.
<P>
At least 70% of the offenders treated and referred for follow-up
services on parole will be successfully linked with community-based
treatment services within thirty days of their discharge date.
<P>
1996 The waiting list will be reduced to no more than an average
of 900 for the year ending June 30, 1996.
<P>
The average number of offenders receiving treatment services will
be 2,100 by June 30, 1996.
<P>
Fewer than 10% of those offenders receiving services will have
treatment interrupted as a result of placement transfers during
the year ending June 30, 1996.
<P>
At least 80% of the offenders treated and referred for follow-up
services on parole will be successfully linked with community-based
treatment services within thirty days of their discharge date.
<P>
1997 The waiting list will be reduced to no more than an average
of 600 for the year ending June 30, 1997.
<P>
The average number of offenders receiving treatment services will
be 2,250 by June 30, 1997.
<P>
Fewer than 7~o of those offenders receiving services will have
treatment interrupted as a result of placement transfers during
the year ending June 30, 1997.
<P>
At least 90% of the offenders treated and referred for follow-up
services on parole will be successfully linked with community-based
treatment services within thirty days of their discharge date.
<HR>
<a name="treat">
<P>
<B>PROBLEM STATEMENT E</B> 
<P>
<B>The treatment services continuum for youth and adults is inadequate,
resulting in delays in service provisions and persons going untreated
for their addictions problems.</B> 
<P>
SUPPORTIVE DOCUMENTATION
<P>
The state agency having primary responsibility for assessing the
needs for treatment services in Indiana and implementing a system
of publicly-supported treatment services is the Family and Social
Services Administration, Division of Mental Health (DMH). For
the state fiscal year ending June 30, 1993, the DMH reported that
21,850 persons were admitted to alcohol and other drug treatment
facilities for services supported in whole or part by state and
federal funds. The cost of the services was $38,011,610, or $1,740
per person admitted. The cost to the State of Indiana for each
person admitted was $1,261. The information below compares cost,
state funding, admissions, and state funding per admission data
for the past three years.
<P>
Year Cost State Funding Admissions State cost
<P>
Per Admission
<P>
1990-91 $33,842,544 $27,436,029 22,240 $1,233.63
<P>
1991-92 $36,920,106 $29,860,216 24,127 $1,237.63
<P>
1992-93 $38,011,610 $27,551,383 21,850 $1,260.93
<P>
The F&amp;SSA, Division of Mental Health has not compiled data
on the unmet treatment needs in Indiana nor is there currently
in place a performance monitoring system that includes treatment
outcomes. Beginning this year, the Division is conducting needs
assessment and actuarial studies to determine the state-wide service
needs and, as a part of the state's new mechanism for funding
treatment services, the Hoosier Assurance Plan, treatment outcomes
will be monitored.
<P>
Between July 1993 and July 1994, all ninety-two Indiana Counties
submitted comprehensive local plans to address alcohol and other
drug issues. Many of the counties identified the lack of services
available or accessible to persons needing treatment for an alcohol
or other drug problem. The data on the next page illustrates those
service needs.
<P>
Terms:
<P>
<U>Services for Indigents</U> - The plan specifically identifies
the lack of treatment service capacity for, or accessibility to
services by, low income, uninsured, underinsured, or indigent
residents.
<P>
<U>Services for Children</U> - The plan specifically identifies
the lack of treatment service capacity for, or accessibility to
services by, children and/or adolescent residents.
<P>
<U>One Gap in Service Continuum</U> - The plan contains a reference
to the absence or the inadequacy of one service type or services
for a specific population other than low income children and/or
adolescent residents.
<P>
<U>Two or More Gaps in The Service Continuum</U> - The plan contains
two or more separate references to the absence of service types
or services for specific populations other than low income or
children and/or adolescent residents.
<P>
Several counties reported having lost publicly-supported treatment
services during the past two years. Others cited changes in the
fee collection policies of state-supported providers, including
rate increases and institution of admission charges. Forty-eight
(48) counties reported waiting lists of more than two weeks for
one or more services, with some waiting lists reported as being
up to six weeks.<p>
<center><a href="table1.html"><font size=5>Table 1</a></center></font>
<P>
RECOMMENDED ACTIONS
<P>
LEGISLATIVE
<P>
El. Expand state funding for treatment to eliminate waiting lists,
expand community corrections treatment programming, and expand
treatment of youthful offenders.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
ADMINISTRATIVE
<P>
E2. Increase public awareness about need for substance abuse treatment
and the need for a continuum of treatment services.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
E3. Promote family treatment through the Hoosier Assurance Plan.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
E4. Improve relationships between correction, mental health, and
substance abuse treatment providers to better serve community
corrections inmates and parolees.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
E5. Revise judicial sentencing guidelines to incorporate more
treatment options.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Criminal Justice Institute
<P>
ADVOCACY
<P>
E6. Advocate for insurance coverage for alcohol and other drug
treatment, including non-hospital residential services, in private
and public health benefits programs.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
E7. Advocate for additional federal resources to be directed to
the study of the effectiveness of treatment models and that the
results be disseminated to state and local planners, policy makers,
providers, and to the general public.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
E8. Advocate for increased flexibility of Federal Block Grant
for addictions treatment.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
E9. Advocate that juvenile court judges require training for probation
staff on conducting alcohol and other drug assessments.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
EXPECTED RESULTS
<P>
Inclusion of alcohol and other drug treatment services in private
and public health benefits programs will more fully integrate
addictions treatment into the primary health care system and ensure
that more of the basic needs for services will be met. The extent
of coverage will determine the remaining need for states to provide
support for treatment services.
<P>
The other advocacy, legislative, and administrative actions will
result in a more complete continuum of publicly-supported, family-oriented,
treatment services. Services will be provided in a more timely
manner and will have improved outcomes.
<P>
BENCHMARKS
<P>
1995 Fewer than thirty-five counties will report waiting lists
of two weeks or more for state-supported treatment services.
<P>
Fewer than forty counties will report two or more gaps in the
service continuum.
<P>
Seventy-five percent of parolees and community correction inmates
who have been identified as needing treatment will be served in
community treatment programs.
<P>
The F&amp;SSA, Division of Mental Health, will establish base-line
data for assessing the effectiveness of treatment providers.
<P>
1996 Fewer than twenty counties will report waiting lists of two
weeks or more for state-supported treatment services.
<P>
Fewer than twenty-five counties will report two or more gaps in
the service continuum.
<P>
Eighty-five percent of parolees and community correction inmates
identified as needing treatment services will be served in community
treatment programs.
<P>
Treatment effectiveness norms will be established by which to
compare providers.
<P>
1997 No counties will report waiting lists of two weeks or more
for state-supported treatment services.
<P>
No counties will report two or more gaps in the treatment services
continuum.
<P>
One hundred percent of parolees and community correction inmates
who have been identified as needing treatment services will be
served in community treatment programs.
<P>
Minimum expectations of treatment effectiveness (outcomes) will
be established for state-supported providers. 

<p>
<p>
