<h2>Indiana Together:  Strategies for A Drug-Free Indiana</h2>
<h3><i>Governor's Commission for a Drug Free Indiana</i></h3>
<HR>


<P>
<B>PROBLEM STATEMENT F</B> 
<P>
<B>Continuing high rates of accidents, injuries, and death are
associated with impaired driving.</B> 
<P>
SUPPORTIVE DOCUMENTATION
<P>
According to the Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving, while statistics indicate that great strides have been
made to reduce the number of deaths and injuries which result
from alcohol-related crashes, driving under the influence of alcohol
or other drugs still presents a significant problem in Indiana.
<P>
In Indiana in 1993, there were 199 fatal alcohol-related crashes,
resulting in 228 fatalities and 4,807 personal injury crashes,
resulting in 7,144 injuries.
<P>
1992 Indiana FARS (Fatal Accident Reporting System) data indicates
that 35% of the drivers killed in crashes had BAC levels greater
than zero, while 32% had BAC levels over 0.05%. Drivers in the
25 to 34 age group had the highest percentage (52%) of alcohol-related
fatalities. Of younger drivers (24 years old or less), 35% killed
in crashes tested above zero, accounting for 29% of the fatalities
among drivers. Given the fact that this age group accounts for
only 15.8% of licensed drivers, drunk driving among youth is actually
a bigger problem than it may first appear.
<P>
The number of impaired driving arrests in Indiana decreased from
41,070 in 1991 to 38,244 in 1992. While there are many factors
to which this could be attributed, the Governor's Council on Impaired
and Dangerous Driving indicates that reductions in training funds,
overtime enforcement grants, police manpower, and equipment have
combined to bring about this decrease in arrests.
<P>
Another problem relating to impaired driving is the public's perception
of their chances of being caught. According to a 1993 survey,
66% of the sample felt their chance of being caught was less than
one in ten. Further, 37% indicated that the chance of being caught
was too low to deter them from driving while impaired. Related
to this, 31% of the youth surveyed did not know the consequences
of a drunk driving conviction. This survey was conducted before
these laws changed in 1994.
<P>
Economic costs related to impaired driving are also a significant
factor. For example, according to NHTSA studies, if the expected
decreases in fatalities, injuries, and property damage are reached
in 1994, this could result in a savings of $20,658,583 in economics
costs to Indiana, including health care and property costs.
<P>
Studies indicate the reduction of the legal blood alcohol limit
to 0.08 does have an effect on the reduction of alcohol-related
traffic crashes, particularly when combined with on-going public
awareness efforts. The states of New Hampshire, California, and
Vermont all show evidence of a decrease in traffic deaths attributed
to alcohol abuse since they instituted their 0.08 laws. Further
studies indicate, however, that when public reinforcement of the
message against drunk driving is lowered, fatality statistics
may again rise, as was the case in Maine, which also saw an initial
decrease after the passage of its 0.08 law.
<P>
Finally, a study by the Center for Substance Abuse Research at
the University of Maryland shows that the risk for reconviction
for drinking and driving is significantly lessened when alcohol
education and treatment are included in the sentencing conditions.
In a study of sentencing conditions in the state of Maryland,
it was shown that alcohol education and alcohol treatment reduced
the reconviction rate over a three-year period by 22% and 17%
respectively.
<P>
RECOMMENDED ACTIONS
<P>
LEGISLATIVE
<P>
Fl . Pass zero tolerance legislation applying mandatory suspension
of drivers licenses to all minors convicted of possessing, consuming,
and transporting alcohol.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
F2. Require use of ignition interlocks for multiple DUI offenders.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
F3. Increase the alcohol countermeasures fee for repeat DUI offenders.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
F4. Reduce the blood alcohol content standard for establishing
prima facie evidence from 0.10% to 0.08%.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
F5. Pass open container legislation that does not supersede stronger
local ordinances.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
ADMINISTRATIVE
<P>
F6. Educate the general public about existing DUI penalties.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
F7. Assist communities in developing local drunk driving awareness
programs.
<P>
<I>Lead Agencies</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving; Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
F8. Work through LCCs and organizations like M.A.D.D., etc., to
encourage courts and prosecutors to utilize strictest existing
penalties for offenders.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving; Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana
<P>
F9. Increase public awareness about dangers of driving with any
amount of alcohol or controlled substances in the person's body.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
F10. Develop a plan to better serve treatment needs of DUI offenders,
integrating these services with justice and prevention efforts.
(See Problem &quot;E&quot;).
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
ADVOCACY
<P>
F11. Promote the training of law enforcement officers in Standardized
Field Sobriety Testing and the Drug Evaluation and Classification
program.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
F12. Make available to the Judicial Conference information on
various model DUI court programs in order to further educate the
judiciary.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
F13. Advocate for greater use of community service sentencing
options for first time offenders.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Governor's Council on Impaired &amp; Dangerous
Driving
<P>
EXPECTED RESULTS
<P>
There will be a reduction in alcohol-related crashes, injuries,
fatalities.
<P>
BENCHMARKS
<P>
1995 There will be no more than 180 fatal alcohol-related crashes
in 1995, resulting in no more than 184 fatalities and no more
than 4,339 personal injury crashes, resulting in no more than
6,447 injuries.
<P>
1996 There will be no more than 171 fatal alcohol-related crashes
in 1996, resulting in no more than 166 fatalities and no more
than 4,122 personal injury crashes, resulting in no more than
6,125 injuries.
<P>
1997 There will be no more than 162 fatal alcohol-related crashes
in 1997, resulting in no more than 149 fatalities and no more
than 3,916 personal injury crashes, resulting in no more than
5,819 injuries.<HR>
<p>
<hr>
<a name="gang">
<P>
<B>PROBLEM STATEMENT G</B> 
<P>
<B>There is an increasing mobility of gang activity, spreading
to non-urban areas and using youngsters to sell drugs.</B> 
<P>
SUPPORTIVE DOCUMENTATION
<P>
Surveys of law enforcement officials in Indiana conducted by the
Indiana State Police showed a definite increase in identified
gangs and gang members between 1991 and 1993.
<P>
Seventy-seven percent (77%) of the respondents reported marijuana
being sold by gangs in their areas. Cocaine and crack were reported
by 56%. Heroin and LSD were also listed as drugs being sold. Many
respondents reported drugs and weapons being used as incentives
by gang recruiters.
<P>
Theft, stolen property, and narcotics were ranked one, two, and
three as the most prevalent crimes committed by street gangs in
Indiana.
<P>
The survey indicated that gangs are expanding to rural and smaller
communities. The 1991 survey reported no gangs in communities
under 2,000 population and in only 6.1% of cities with 2,000 residents.
In 1993, 24.5% of the respondents in cities under 2,000 and 50%
of these 2,000-3,000 reported gang activity. The smallest jurisdiction
reporting gang activity has a population of 443 persons. Various
reasons were given for this rapid change, including:
<UL>
<LI>Recruitment by gangs from other areas attempting to extend
their influence and gang mobility. New and emerging street gangs
were reported by over 46% of the responding jurisdictions. Eighty-two
percent (82%) of that number attributed the increase to recruitment
by major gangs from other areas.
<LI>Population shifts from larger cities to smaller towns. These
shifts sometimes are by parents moving away from the temptations
of gang involvement. However, often the children who were gang
members, or wanted to be, started their own gangs in these new
areas.
<LI>Offenders from smaller population centers were sent to correction
facilities where they learned to be gang members. Upon return
to their communities they attempt to form their own gangs.
</UL>

<P>
According to a 1992 Bureau of Justice Statistics report, 15% of
students reported gangs present at their schools. Of these, 35%
said they feared attack at school, 24% feared attack going to
or from school, and 13% said they avoided areas inside the school
for fear of attack.
<P>
RECOMMENDED ACTIONS
<P>
ADMINISTRATIVE
<P>
G1. Establish Law Enforcement Gang Task Force Coordinating Committees
within the regional areas observed by the Governor's Commission
for a Drug-Free Indiana, for purposes of coordination, program
development information sharing, and police-community relations.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana State Police
<P>
G2. Develop for interagency use a statewide automated information
system which would identify gang members, particularly leaders
and hard-core members.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana State Police
<P>
G3. Utilize existing Local Coordinating Councils to mobilize the
community around anti-gang initiatives, planning programs, services,
and activities; improve comrnunications; and coordinate efforts
within and across neighborhoods.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Criminal Justice Institute
<P>
G4. Incorporate alcohol, drug, and gang awareness education into
law enforcement training.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Law Enforcement Training Board
<P>
G5. Develop and implement a state training team tailored to instruct
in gang and drug awareness in non-urban areas. in
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana State Police
<P>
ADVOCACY
<P>
G6. Encourage law enforcement agencies to become more proactive
by increasing their commitment to understanding the communities
they serve and to solving gang problems.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Criminal Justice Institute
<P>
G7. Encourage prosecutors to establish special gang oriented prosecution
units and practices.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Prosecuting Attorneys' Council
<P>
G8. Encourage judges to consider the use of intermediate sanctions
such as periodic imprisonment, electronic detention, work release,
and house arrest for less committed gang members
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Criminal Justice Institute; Indiana
Judicial Center
<P>
G9. Encourage training in alcohol, drug, and gang education for
all school personnel in contact with students.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Education
<P>
G10. Encourage local school districts to establish and implement
a comprehensive K-12 alcohol, drug, and gang awareness prevention
education curriculum consistent with IC 20-10.1-4-9.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Education
<P>
EXPECTED RESULTS
<P>
There will be a reduced number of gang related incidents occurring
in Indiana. There will be a reduced number of jurisdictions reporting
gang activity. There will be a reduced number of gangs and gang
members statewide.
<P>
BENCHMARKS
<P>
1995 By the fall of 1995, the State Police will have in place
a standardized survey which will allow for the tracking of the
number of Indiana jurisdictions reporting gang activity, the number
of gangs statewide, and the number of gang members in Indiana
The Fall 1995 survey will also establish the baseline data for
measuring these statistics.
<P>
1996 The Fall 1996 survey will indicate a 10% decrease from the
1995 baseline data in the number of Indiana jurisdictions reporting
gang activity, the number of gangs statewide, and the number of
gang members in Indiana.
<P>
1997 The Fall 1997 survey will indicate a 10% decrease from the
1996 survey data in the number of Indiana jurisdictions reporting
gang activity, the number of gangs statewide, and the number of
gang members in Indiana. 

<p>
