<h2>Indiana Together:  Strategies for A Drug-Free Indiana</h2>
<h3><i>Governor's Commission for a Drug Free Indiana</i></h3>
<HR>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>PROBLEM STATEMENT H</B> 
<P>
<B>There are a high number of violent crimes connected to substance
abuse.</B> 
<P>
SUPPORTIVE DOCUMENTATION
<P>
A recent public opinion poll conducted by The Indianapolis Star
and Indiana University showed that drugs were ranked as the number
one cause of crime, with 24% of the 1,410 respondents agreeing.
<P>
A 1994 National Institute of Justice brief, &quot;Understanding
and Preventing Violence,&quot; indicates that there are many social,
psychological, and community-level influences on aggressive and
violent behavior. Long-range approaches are often needed to attack
these long-term problems. Shorter-range strategies, the brief
suggests, require &quot;altering or eliminating&quot; situational
elements that can facilitate violent acts. Three of these elements
that are singled out by the brief are alcohol, illegal drugs,
and firearms.
<P>
Research supported by the National Institute of Justice (NIJ)
states that criminals who use illegal drugs commit robberies and
assaults more frequently than do non-user criminals, particularly
during periods of heavy drug use. As for alcohol, the NIJ research
continues, &quot;for at least the last several decades, alcohol
drinking--by the perpetrator of a crime, the victim, or both--has
immediately preceded at least half of all violent events, including
murders.&quot;
<P>
According to the January 1994 National Crime Victimization Report,
&quot;female victims of rape and aggravated assault were significantly
more likely to perceive their attackers to be under the influence
of drugs or alcohol than females who experienced a robbery or
simple assault.&quot; Further, of those rape and assault offenders,
a higher percentage were reported to have been using alcohol rather
than drugs; while conversely, the offenders of robbery were more
often perceived to be under the influence of drugs other than
alcohol.
<P>
Of rape cases, the study continues, those where there was a prior
relationship between the offender and the victim were more likely
to have had drug or alcohol involvement. In fact, these offenders
were 70% more likely to have been under the influence than were
rapists who were strangers to the victims. And of all spousal
abuse cases, up to 50% show an association to alcohol and other
drugs.
<P>
In its 1994 Report &quot;The Impact of Illegal Drugs on America
and Our Most Critical Domestic Issues,&quot; the Partnership for
a Drug-Free America documented that 48% of those arrested for
homicide and assault test positive for drugs at the time of arrest.
Additionally, the Partnership reports that 79% of state prison
inmates say they used drugs at some point in their lives, and
nearly 62% use them on a regular basis. In Indiana prisons, the
number of offenders who were in substance abuse treatment during
1992 averaged 12.5% of all inmates per month, with an average
waiting list of 1,162, according the Department of Correction.
<P>
The frequency of drug use is also a factor relating to violence
according to the Bureau of Justice Statistics report, &quot;Drugs,
Crime, and the Justice System.&quot; &quot;As drug use increases,
so too does crime,&quot; the document states. &quot;Criminal activity
is as much as two to three times higher among frequent users of
heroin or cocaine than among irregular or non-users of drugs.&quot;
<P>
Crime rates can also be traced to the introduction of new drug
trends. According to a report by the Federal Bureau of Investigation,
violent crime in our cities increased dramatically between 1985
and 1990, the years of the crack epidemic. In urban areas alone,
violent crime increased by 37% and aggravated assaults by 43%
from 1989 to 1990.
<P>
RECOMMENDED ACTIONS
<P>
LEGISLATIVE
<P>
H1. Increase the existing penalty for the illegal use of firearms
when the use is connected with drug trafficking.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Criminal Justice Institute
<P>
ADMINISTRATIVE
<P>
H2. Integrate violence prevention and conflict resolution concepts
into school drug prevention curricula.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Indiana Department of Education
<P>
ADVOCACY
<P>
H3. Improve alcohol and other drug treatment interventions in
agencies working with clients on violence-related issues.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: Family &amp; Social Services Administration-Div.
of Mental Health
<P>
H4. Advocate that LCCs consider the connection between alcohol,
other drugs, and violence when developing their Comprehensive
Plans.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: The Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free
Indiana
<P>
H5. Advocate for reduced and responsible images of violence in
media, music, art, games, movies, videos, etc.
<P>
<I>Lead Agency</I>: The Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free
Indiana
<P>
EXPECTED RESULTS
<P>
Because of increased cooperation among anti-drug and anti-violence
initiatives, there will be a decrease in the rate of alcohol and
other drug-related violent crime.
<P>
BENCHMARKS
<P>
1995 By Fall of 1995, the Indiana Criminal Justice Institute will
have in place a mechanism for the tracking of drug and alcohol
related violent crimes that coincides with the data collected
at the national level. This information will be used to establish
baseline data on these crime statistics.
<P>
1996 There will be a 5% decrease from the 1995 baseline data on
drug and alcohol-related violent crimes.
<P>
1997 There will be a 5% decrease from the 1996 data on drug and
alcohol-related violent crimes.<HR>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<a name="resource">
<P>
RESOURCE RECOMMENDATIONS
<P>
R1. INCREASE EXCISE TAXES ON TOBACCO AND ALCOHOL PRODUCTS.
<P>
Indiana is heavily reliant upon federal funds to address alcohol
and other drug problems. In the prevention and education area,
federal funds constitute the vast majority of resources used by
the state agencies charged with specific drug prevention responsibilities.
Those agencies and the percent of expenditures which represent
federal funds are the Department of Education (98.8%), F&amp;SSA-Division
of Mental Health (100%), Department of Health (100%), Division
of Traffic Safety (84.1%), and the Indiana National Guard (100%).
<P>
The Indiana State Police utilizes state funding for virtually
all of its prevention (primarily public awareness) programming.
A number of other state agencies allocate small portions of state
funds for prevention efforts.
<P>
Community-based treatment programs funded by the state are heavily
reliant upon federal funds. The F&amp;SSA's Division of Mental
Health administers the largest amount of treatment funds and federal
dollars make up 79.7% of the funds awarded to treatment providers.
Federal funds amount to 34% of the resources used for treatment
of offenders by the Department of Correction.
<P>
Criminal justice expenditures by state government to address alcohol
and other drug problems are more difficult to calculate, since
enforcement, justice, and correction anti-drug efforts are not
calculated as cost centers. It is fair to say that the majority
of the costs of these efforts are borne by state funding appropriations.
<P>
The dependence on federal funding to support much of the prevention
and treatment, and some of the criminal justice services and activities
in Indiana subjects state and local planners and providers to
changing federal priorities, making continuity of effort difficult.
For example, at the time of this writing, Congress is preparing
to act on the 1994-95 appropriation for the Substance Abuse Prevention
and Treatment Block Grant. A provision of the proposal is to change
the formula that allocates the funds among the states. The new
formula, if enacted, will result in a loss of over $5,000,000
for Indiana programs.
<P>
Many federal administrative and legislative leaders have recognized
the appropriateness of increasing excise taxes on tobacco products
as not only a means of generating revenue for (health) programs
to offset the negative impact on society of those products, but
as a public policy action to impact the price of, thus reducing
demand for, those products. The same case can be made for increased
taxes on alcoholic beverages. With the exception of tobacco products,
alcoholic beverages are far more widely used and abused than any
of the illicit drugs. Decreased consumption rates will result
in lower problem levels.
<P>
Indiana's current excise taxes on tobacco and alcoholic beverage
products and comparable data from surrounding states are as follows:
<P>
Tobacco:
<P>
State Cigarettes (pack) Other Products
<P>
Indiana $0.155 15% of Wholesale Price
<P>
Illinois $0.440 20% of Wholesale Price
<P>
Ohio $0.240 17% of Wholesale Price
<P>
Kentucky $0.040 None
<P>
Michigan $0.750 16% of Wholesale Price
<P>
Alcoholic Beverages (per gallon):
<P>
State Beer Wine Distilled Spirits
<P>
Indiana $0.115 $0.4700 $2.68
<P>
Illinois $0.070 $0.2300* $2.00
<P>
Ohio $0.180 $0.3200** $3.38
<P>
Kentucky $0.081 $0.5000 $1.92
<P>
Michigan $0.203 $0.0572*** $3.37****
<P>
* Beverages with 14-20% alcohol content by volume are taxed at
$0.60 per gallon.
<P>
** For wine less than 14% alcohol by volume. Wine over 13.9% alcohol
by volume is $1.00 per gallon. Sparkling wine has a $1.50 rate,
vermouth is $1.10, and mixed beverages having less than 21% alcohol
by volume are $1.20 per gallon. Rates were last increased effective
January 1, 1993.
<P>
*** Beverages with 1~20% alcohol content by volume are taxed at
$.60 per gallon.
<P>
**** Rates vary considerably, with a 13.85% tax rate applied to
the wholesale price of each product. The $3.37 comparative rate
is on an 86 proof whisky product. The range is $1.44 per gallon
to $7.38 per gallon for whisky and scotch beverage products.
<P>
R2. INCREASE ALCOHOL COUNTERMEASURES FEES ON REPEAT DUI OFFENDERS.
<P>
The current alcohol countermeasures fee is fixed at $200 and applies
to those persons whose drivers licenses are suspended as a result
of committing an infraction or offense under IC 9-30-5. There
is no distinction made as to the amount of the fee for the different
offenses, which range from Class C misdemeanors to Class C Felonies.
<P>
Consideration should also be given to applying the $200 fee to
persons whose initial charges under IC 9-30-5 are deferred or
plea-bargained down to traffic offenses, to those found to have
committed an infraction under IC 9-30-15 (open container violations),
and those convicted of charges under IC 7.1-5-7 (minors and alcoholic
beverages).
<P>
The current alcohol countermeasures and interdiction, prosecution,
and corrections fees were established July 1, 1990. These fees
generate approximately $6.6 million a year. Seventy-five percent
of the fees collected remain in the county in which they are collected
and support prevention, treatment, and criminal justice services
and activities contained in comprehensive plans to address alcohol
and other drug problems at the local level.
<P>
R3. EDUCATE JUDGES ON THE USE OF THE INTERDICTION, PROSECUTION,
AND CORRECTIONS FEE.
<P>
Anecdotal reports from some local communities suggest that the
application of the alcohol countermeasures fee is becoming routine,
but that the use of the special fee on persons convicted of an
offense under IC 35-48-4 is spotty. An education program to remind
judges of the availability of this measure will increase the revenues.
<P>
R4. RAISE PERMIT FEES FOR ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGE MANUFACTURING, DISTRIBUTING.
AND RETAILING.
<P>
If the Alcoholic Beverage Commission is to increase the monitoring
of alcohol beverage retail outlets, additional excise police officers
will be needed. An increase in permit fees, with the increased
revenues targeted to additional enforcement, can make the additional
monitoring feasible.
<P>
A comparison of Indiana alcohol manufacturing, distributing, and
retailing permit fees to fees of surrounding states is difficult.
Fees of these types are complex, with a wide range of definitions
and categories. In general, Indiana's existing fees are lower
than other states, based on those fee structures that can be compared.
For example:
<UL>
<LI>Indiana's permit fee for a distiller of spirits is $2,000.
The range of fees in contiguous states is $1,500 to $10,000.
<LI>For wholesalers of beer, Indiana's fee is $1,000, with the
range in surrounding states of $200 to $2,500.
<LI>For retail outlets such as package stores, permit fees in
Indiana range from $105 to $255. The range in nearby states is
from $275 to $675.
<LI>For retail outlets such as drug stores selling liquor, beer,
and wine, permit fees in Indiana range from $255 to $455. The
range in nearby states is $275 to $675.
</UL>

<P>
In general, fees are lower in Kentucky, and higher in Illinois,
Ohio, and Michigan. 
<p>
<p>
