<P>
<p>
<a name="problem">
<hr size=5>
<center>
<h3>Problem Indicators Status Report</h3>
<b>October 1, 1994</b>
Governor's Commission for a Drug Free Indiana
</a>
<p>
</center>


In 1992, the Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana adopted
12 indicators to provide a statewide measure of progress
in the fight against alcohol and other drug problems, and to provide
information to communities to aid in the assessment of local problems.
Taken as a whole, the indicators describe the extent of the problems in
Indiana.
<P>
Through work on the 12 indicators, the Commission uncovered a
need for more state and local reporting and data collection on
alcohol and other drug problems. Where state or local data are unavailable, 
the most current and comprehensive national data is included.
<ol>
<li> Deaths caused by alcohol- or other drug-related crashes- continued
to decrease.

<li> Single vehicle nighttime crashes - continued to decrease.

<li> Deaths caused by cirrhosis - have not changed.

<li> Deaths caused b- drugs other than alcohol - increased.

<li> Emergency room visits Involving alcohol and other drugs - are
not documented in Indiana.

<li> Average age of first use of alcohol by school students - held
steady.

<li> Monthly use of alcohol, marijuana, cocaine, cigarettes, and
heroin by youth, ages 12 -17 - increased overall.

<li> Monthly use of alcohol, marijuana, cocaine, cigarettes, and
heroin by youth, ages 18 - 25 - data is not collected in Indiana.

<li> Incidence of heavy drinking by high school seniors - increased
and remains significantly higher than nationwide.

<li> Average per-capita consumption of alcohol - declined slightly.

<li> Average cost of street drugs - remained stable, except for
the cost of marijuana, which declined.

<li> Incidence of alcohol- and other drug-related negative birth
outcomes - increased statewide.
</ol>
<p>
<HR>

<H4>Problem Indicators Summary</H4>

<P>
October 1, 1994
<P>
Although some progress continues to be made in the fight against
alcohol and other drug problems, there is clear evidence that
advancement has slowed on some fronts and actually regressed in
others. The data in this report brings home the stark reality
that to achieve a drug-free Indiana will require a long-term sustained
effort, one that is continuously evaluated and adjusted according
to changing conditions and results of our strategies.
<P>
Heading the list of areas in which we continue to make good progress
is the reduction of problems associated with impaired driving.
Data on indicators 1 and 2 demonstrate that the combination of
tough state laws, state and local public awareness campaigns,
targeted law enforcement efforts, and coordinated community responses
is paying off. The rates of decline in the number of deaths attributed
to alcohol and other drug-related vehicle crashes and single vehicle
nighttime accidents appear to have slowed in 1993, suggesting
that we need to be alert to the possibility that new strategies
may need to be explored for the future.
<P>
The number of deaths, other than vehicle-related ones, attributed
to alcohol and other drugs, has not changed significantly. Deaths
attributed to cirrhosis of the liver, a measure of the consequences
of heavy extended use of alcohol, has not measurably changed since
1986. Other alcohol and drug-related deaths increased slightly
in 1993, after remaining relatively unchanged for the previous
three years.
<P>
The number of emergency room visits involving alcohol and other
drugs is believed to be a sound problem indicator, but the data
are not available on a routine basis from Indiana hospitals. This
measure is being retained in hopes that a reporting mechanism
will be developed.
<P>
Perhaps the most disturbing news in the report this year is clear
evidence that elementary and secondary school children in Indiana
are using drugs at higher rates than in previous years and that
rates of use are higher than the national average for youngsters
of the same ages. The most significant of the changes are increases
in the use of cigarettes, marijuana, and inhalants. The rate of
alcohol use, which had been declining for three years, did not
change in 1994.
<P>
In contrast to the rate of alcohol use by youth, which remains
higher than national averages, the overall consumption rate of
alcohol in Indiana remains lower than the national average and
continues to decline. Over half of the alcohol (pure ethanol)
consumed by Hoosiers is in beer products.
<P>
The data on the average cost of street drugs measures the supply
and demand for illegal drugs. Prices are affected by a large number
of variables including, but not limited to, source volume, the
perceived risk of apprehension, the effectiveness of interdiction
and law enforcement efforts, the availability of money for purchases,
and consumer demand. The 1994 data shows that the price of cocaine
and crack cocaine has risen in the past year while at the same
time, the price of marijuana has decreased.
<P>
Alcohol and other drug use by pregnant women, and perhaps by men,
is one factor which may contribute to low weights at birth. The
rates of low birth weight have not changed significantly between
1989 and the most recent year for which data are available, 1992.
<P>
In summary, the problem indicators status report contains both
good and bad news. While progress continues on some fronts, there
is disturbing news, particularly with respect to alcohol and other
drug use among our youth. This underscores the need for continuous
examination of strategies and the documentation of results at
both state and local levels . 


<p>
<p>
