</center>
<h2>CSAP Prevention Monographs Available from your <br>
RADAR Network State Center</h2>
<hr size=10>
NOTE:  Indiana residents may obtain copies of these documents from the <b>
Indiana Prevention Resource Center at Indiana University.</b>  Residents of
other states may obtain copies from their RADAR Network State Centers or
directly from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information
(NCADI).
<p>
<b>
<ul>

<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 2:  <i>Prevention of Mental Disorders, Alcohol,
and Other Drug Use in Children and Adolescents.
</i> 478pp. (1992). </b> Summarizes knowledge about prevention and intervention
in child and adolescent psychiatric illnesses.  Chapters examine AOD problems,
learning disabilities, conduct disorders, public policy, psychiatric disorders
in parents, chronic illness, post-traumatic stress disorders, and suicide.
(BK161).<b>


<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 3:  <i>Prevention Research Findings: 1988.
</i> 265pp.  (1990).  </b>  The proceedings of the First National Conference
on Prevention Research Findings:  Implications for Alcohol and Drug Abuse
Program Planning, held in March, 1988.  Papers cover such topics as State and
Federal roles in prevention, perspectives in prevention research, school- and
community-based prevention programs, health promotion and wellness, and
public policy prevention programs.  (BK162).<b>




<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 5:  <i>Communicating About Alcohol and Other
Drugs:  Strategies for Reaching Populations at Risk.
</i> 402pp.  (1992).  </b>  Represents a three-pronged initiative to 1)
identify the knowledge, attitudes, and practices of youth (and their families)
at special risk for developing AOD problems; 2) identify gaps in messages
and materials; and 3) recommend strategies to reach these populations.  The
focus is on reaching children of alcoholics, African-American youth, Hispanic
youth, parents, and health care providers.  (BK170).<b>


<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 6:  <i>Youth and Drugs:  Society's Mixed 
Messages.
</i>  174pp.  (1990).  </b> An in-depth discussion of how young people
are affected by the mixed messages that come from private enterprise,
advertising, and society's definition of the new behavioral norm.  
Suggests a new approach to prevention that addresses these environmental
factors.  (BK172).<b>





<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 8:  <i>Preventing Adolescent Drug Use:  From
Theory to Practice.
</i>  270pp.  (1991).  </b>Describes the complex world of adolescents, their
families, the transitions that influence their development and behavior,
and the factors that place them at risk for AOD use and addiction.  Contains
practical information about methods of identifying, reaching, retaining,
and serving youth, and the importance of early intervention.  (BK185).<b>


<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 9:  <i>Crack Cocaine:  The Challenge of
Prevention.
</i> 71pp.  (1991).  </b>Presents the history and epidemiology of crack
cocaine and demonstrates aspects of the drug and its use that pose unique
concerns to the field of prevention.  Examines problems specific to crack
cocaine that require specially focused prevention strategies, and
recommendations for a crack cocaine research agenda.  (BK190).<b>


<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 10:  <i>A Promising Future:  Alcohol and
Other Drug Problem Prevention Services Improvement.
</i> 127pp.  (1992).  </b>This volume includes discussions of the economic
and human costs of AOD-related problems and how these costs have led to
increased Federal Government support for AOD abuse prevention.  Also
addresses the prevention of HIV infection and the clinical epidemiology
of drug abuse and AIDS.  (BK191).<b>


<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 11:  <i>Identifying the Needs of Drug 
Affected Children:  Public Policy Issues.
</i> 169pp.  (1992).  </b>This volume is based on papers and discussions
from CSAP's first Issues Forum held in November, 1990, which brought
experts together to define the needs of AOD exposed children ages 2 to 5.  
The monograph describes the problem, our current solutions, and what more
needs to be done about this growing problem.  (BK195).<b>




<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 13:  <i>The Second National Conference on
Preventing and Treating Alcohol and Other Drug Abuse, HIV Infection, and
AIDS in Black Communities:  From Advocacy to Action.
</i>  500pp.  (1992).  </b>This monograph of conference presentations describes
initiatives against AOD abuse, HIV infection, and AIDS in African-American
communities.  Experts discuss resources to convert prevention and treatment
knowledge into practical efforts to eradicate these problems from communities
nationwide.  (BK78)<b>



<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 14:  <i>Experiences with Community Action 
Projects:  New Research in the Prevention of Alcohol and Other Drug
Problems.
</i> 301pp. (1993).  </b>  This monograph, the result of the second 
international research symposium, is the sequel to CSAP Prevention Monograph
No. 4 and the first symposium.  Following the format of the conference, papers
are organized under broad headings:  conceptual issues in evaluating
community action; experiences with policy adoption case studies; community 
trials design issues; and needs assessments or natural experiments in
special settings.  (BKD87).<b>


<li>CSAP Prevention Monograph No. 15:  <i>
</i>

</ul>
</b>                

<h3>ORDERING INFORMATION:</h3>

<b>INDIANA RESIDENTS ONLY:</b>  Indiana residents may order one copy each 
of up to five different publications every 30 days, from the 
Indiana Prevention Resource Center at Indiana University.  Orders may
be placed by E-Mail by <a href= mailto:"webmaster@www.drugs.indiana.edu">
CLICKING HERE.</a>  This temporary E-Mail interface is provided while a
more sophisticated on-line ordering system is being designed.  Make sure
to include a complete shipping address and a telephone number and/or 
e-mail address. <p>

<b>NON-INDIANA RESIDENTS:</b>  Orders may be placed with your own RADAR
Network State Center, or directly with the National Clearinghouse for
Alcohol and Drug Information (NCADI):  NCADI, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville,
MD 20847-2345.  Phone:  (800) 729-6686. <p>


