<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/titlesm.gif">
</center>
<h2>CSAP Technical Reports Available from your <br>
RADAR Network State Center</h2>
<hr size=10>
NOTE:  Indiana residents may obtain copies of these documents from the <b>
Indiana Prevention Resource Center at Indiana University.</b>  Residents of
other states may obtain copies from their RADAR Network State Centers or
directly from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information
(NCADI).
<p>

<hr>
<ul>
<b><li> CSAP Technical Report No. 1:<i>  Breaking New Ground for Youth at Risk:
Program Summaries.</i> 137pp. (1992). </b>
Summarizes the 130 demonstration grants funded by CSAP in 1987 to develop, 
test, and evaluate approaches for working with youth in high-risk
environments.  Approaches involve prevention, intervention, and treatment
programs, as well as comprehensive, community-wide projects.  (BK163)

<b><li> CSAP Technical Report No. 2:<i>  Legal Issues for Alcohol and Other 
Drug Use Prevention and Treatment Programs Serving High-Risk Youth.
</i> 31pp.  (1992).</b>  Examines the need for agencies offering AOD prevention
and treatment services to comply with Federal laws and regulations governing
confidentiality of patient records; when they may offer services to minors;
when and how they must report child abuse and neglect; how they should screen 
employees and volunteers; and whether they are in compliance with applicable
quality of care standards.  A list of questions useful for consulting with
an attorney is also provided.  (BK166)<br>

<b><a href="/const.html">Full-text version of this monograph.</a> - under construction!<p>
<li> CSAP Technical Report No. 3:<i>  Breaking New Ground for American Indian
and Alaska Native Youth at Risk:  Program Summaries.</i> 103pp.  (1990).</b>
Summarizes 16 demonstration grants that provide 
promising prevention models for working with these youth,  (BK174)<b>


<li> CSAP Technical Report No. 5:<i> Measurements in Prevention:  A Manual
on Selecting and Using Instruments to Evaluate Prevention Programs.
</i> 204pp. (1993).</b> Designed to help readers select instruments to 
evaluate ATOD prevention programs.  For each instrument, the manual 
provides the name of the instrument, the author, the age group for which the
instrument is designed, the method of administration, the scales included in 
the instrument, its statistical properties, language, cost and source
for obtaining.  (BK213)

<b><li> CSAP Technical Report No. 9:<i>  Toward Preventing Perinatal Abuse of
Alcohol, Tobacco, and Other Drugs. </i> 61pp.  (1993).</b>  Introduces the 
issues surrounding the prevention of perinatal abuse of alcohol, tobacco, 
and other drugs.  Also reviews how key 
professions view prevention, the approaches they use to plan programs and
strategies that can be used tp prevent perinatal ATOD abuse.  (BK211)

<b><li> CSAP Technical Report No. 11:<i>  Prevention Strategies Based on
Individual Risk Factors for Alcohol and Other Drug Abuse. </i> 38pp.  (1993).
</b> This report draws from the experience of CSAP grantees
as well as professional literature.  It focuses on state-of-the-art
strategies for individuals, particularly youth, individual risk and
protective factors are dicsussed.  (PHD630)

</ul>



<h3>ORDERING INFORMATION:</h3>

<ul>
<b>INDIANA RESIDENTS ONLY:</b>  Indiana residents may order one copy each 
of up to five different publications every 30 days, from the 
Indiana Prevention Resource Center at Indiana University.  Orders may
be placed by E-Mail by <a href= "mailto:webmaster@www.drugs.indiana.edu">
CLICKING HERE.</a>  This temporary E-Mail interface is provided while a
more sophisticated on-line ordering system is being designed.  Make sure
to include a complete shipping address and a telephone number and/or 
e-mail address. <p>

<b>NON-INDIANA RESIDENTS:</b>  Orders may be placed with your own RADAR
Network State Center, or directly with the National Clearinghouse for
Alcohol and Drug Information (NCADI):  NCADI, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville,
MD 20847-2345.  Phone:  (800) 729-6686. <p>

</ul>

