<HEAD>
<TITLE> USDOT-NHTSA Research Note on 0.08%BAC Standard - IN PRC</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<!-- header start -->
<!-- header end -->

<!-- title map start -->
<MAP NAME="titlemap">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="70,68,142,83" HREF=/about/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="146,67,212,83" HREF=/prevention/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="217,67,276,83" HREF=/drug_info/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="278,67,341,83" HREF=/drug_stats/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="345,67,420,83" HREF=/publications/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="425,68,492,83" HREF=/resources/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="497,68,546,83" HREF=/library/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="550,67,592,83" HREF=/search/home.html>
<AREA SHAPE=default HREF=/home.html>
</MAP><!-- title map end -->

<!-- title image start -->
<center>
<img border = 0 src = "/graphics/titlesm.gif" usemap="#titlemap">
<p>


<i>HTML Coding by the Indiana Prevention Resource Center at Indiana University </i>
<h2><IMG  align=left SRC=/graphics/logos/usdot.gif>Department of Transportation<br>
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration</h2>

<center>

                                      Research Note
<p>


                    Preliminary Assessment of The Impact of Lowering<br>
                          the Illegal BAC Per Se Limit to 0.08<br>
<p>
                                 Delmas Maxwell Johnson
<p>
                                      February 1995
<p>
</center>
Study of the implementation of 0.08 blood alcohol content (BAC)
laws (along with associated activities such as public information
campaigns drawing attention to the laws) provides a preliminary
indication that the laws are associated with reductions in driver
involvement in alcohol-related fatal crashes.  "A Preliminary
Assessment of the Impact of Lowering the Illegal BAC Per Se Limit
to 0.08 in Five States" examines the effects of the 0.08 BAC
legislation on reducing driver involvement in alcohol-related
fatal crashes in California, Maine, Oregon, Utah, and Vermont.
<p>
In 1994, as more states were considering the adoption of 0.08 BAC
legislation, NHTSA conducted a preliminary assessment of changes
in alcohol-related crashes in the states that had passed such
laws.  The five states studied had the 0.08 BAC legislation in
effect for at least two years.  The goal of the study was to
determine if changes in driver alcohol involvement in fatal
crashes had occurred in coincident with the effective date of the
0.08 BAC laws.  
<p>
Data from NHTSA Fatal Accident Reporting System (FARS) were used
to analyze the level of driver alcohol involvement in fatal
crashes comparing time periods before vs. after the 0.08 BAC
legislation became effective in each state.  Six different
measures of driver alcohol involvement in fatal crashes were
examined for changes in the level of crashes when the "before"
time periods were compared to the "after" time periods in each
state.  Using each of the six measures, the proportion of alcohol
involvement that was experienced before the 0.08 law was compared
to the proportion of alcohol involvement that was experienced
after the 0.08 law, by calculating the percentage change,
yielding thirty comparisons of the level of driver alcohol
involvement in fatal crashes.  Nine of the thirty comparisons
were found to be statistically significant decreases.  The
remaining 21 measures were not statistically significant at the
0.10 level of these, the majority, 16 measures, showed decreases. 
None of the comparisons using the same measures for the rest of
the nation were found to be statistically significant.  The
following table summarizes the findings for statistically
significant decreases.
<p>
<center>
<table border=3>

<tr> <th colspan=3>Summary of Significant Decreases in Driver 
Alcohol Involvement After .08 BAC Legislation</th></tr>

<tr><th>State</th><th>Measure</th><th>Percent Decrease</th><tr>

<tr><td>California</td><td>Alcohol > 10</td><td>-4%</td></tr>

<tr><td>Oregon</td><td>Any Alcohol</td><td>-9%</td></tr>
<tr><td> </td><td>Alcohol > 10</td><td>-11%</td></tr>
<tr><td> </td><td>Police Reported Alcohol</td><td>-13%</td></tr>
<tr><td> </td><td>Estimated Alcohol Involvement</td><td>-11%</td></tr>
                
<tr><td>Utah</td><td>Police Reported Alcohol</td><td>-30%</td></tr>

<tr><td>Vermont</td><td>Any Alcohol</td><td>-36%</td></tr>
<tr><td> </td><td>Alcohol > 10</td><td>-31%</td></tr>
<tr><td> </td><td>Estimated Alcohol Involvement</td><td>-40%</td></tr>

</table>
</center>
<p>
The comparisons of measures of driver involvement in alcohol-
related fatal crashes for the five states studied suggest that
significant decreases occurred following implementation of the
0.08 BAC legislation.  For Oregon and Vermont, significant
reductions were noted for several measures of driver alcohol
involvement, while California and Utah each exhibited one measure
achieving a significant reduction.  However, these findings are
preliminary and further analysis is warranted.  This analysis
does not account for other potentially important factors, e.g.,
other alcohol legislation, that could influence the impact of the
0.08 BAC legislation on reducing alcohol-related crashes.  More
analytical work is underway to further understand the changes in
the level of alcohol involvement in crashes that have occurred
coincident with the passage of 0.08 BAC legislation.
<p>
For a copy of the report contact the National Center for
Statistics and Analysis, NHTSA, NRD-31, 400 Seventh Street, S.W.,
Washington, DC 20590, (202) 366-1470 or the National Technical
Information Service, 5285 Port Royal Road, Springfield, Virginia
22161, or call NTIS at (703) 487-4650 or fax (703) 321-8547.
<p>
                
<p>

