<HTML>
<HEAD>

<title>Indiana PRC - Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana WWW Page
</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">


<table border>
<tr>
<td><img src=/graphics/logos/gcdfi.gif></td>
<td align=center>
<font size=6>GOVERNOR'S COMMISSION FOR A DRUG-FREE INDIANA</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<hr>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <a href=#Mission>Mission</a>
<li> <a href=#Structure>Structure</a>
<li> <a href=#Aware>Awareness Efforts</a>
<li> <a href=#StateHQ>State Headuqarters</a>
<li> <a href=#RCO>Regional Coordinating Offices</a>
<p>
</ul>
<p>
The  <b>Governor's  Commission  for a Drug Free Indiana</b> is  the  state  organization 
charged  with  developing  a  comprehensive  approach to  alcohol  and  other  drug  problems.  
Indiana is a nationwide leader in assisting communities in addressing their drug challenges  and 
is one of a very few states which has in place a funding mechanism for these efforts:  Indiana's 
Drug-Free Communities Fund.
<p>
<a name=Mission>
<h2>Mission:</a></h2>
<ul>
<li>  advise the governor and the Indiana General Assembly on legislative strategies;
<li>  mobilize communities to take drug-free action; and
<li>  coordinate statewide drug-free efforts.
</ul>
<p>
<p>
<a name=Structure>
<h2>Structure</a></h2>
<p>
<i>Local Efforts Are Key</i><br>
Each county in Indiana has a local coordinating council (LCC) which is the core of Indiana's 
community-based drug-free efforts.  These groups of local drug-free volunteers meet to assess 
county-wide alcohol and other drug challenges, and to form a comprehensive plan to address 
those challenges.  Each plan includes three major components:  prevention/education, treatment,  
and justice/law enforcement.  Many LCCs have a Youth Advisory Board.   LCC 
representatives meet monthly with other LCC representatives in a Regional Advisory Board.  
Funding for the local plans comes, in part, from Indiana's Drug-Free Communities Fund, 
which channels drug offender and driving-while-intoxicated fees back into local drug-free 
activities.
<p>

Click here to locate 
 <li>  <a  href= http://www.drugs.indiana.edu/indiana/home.html>Local Coordinating  Council  </a> 
contact information.

<p>
<i>Statewide Leadership</i><br>
The Governor's Commission for a Drug Free Indiana is guided by a State Steering Committee 
of 16 volunteers appointed by the governor, and four legislators, who make drug-free recom-
mendations.  They represent various sectors of the community:  labor, religion, community 
organizations, family, media, state government, medicine, judiciary, law enforcement, self-
help, education, youth, local government, and businesses.  In 1994, the State Steering Committee 
gathered input from drug-free advocates across the state to develop <i>Indiana  Together:  
Strategies for Developing a Drug-Free Indiana.</i>  The report forms the blueprint for  state 
government action over the next several years.
<p>
The Commission state staff consists of six agency professionals housed in Indianapolis, and 
19 regional coordinators who work out of offices located in six host agencies across the state.  
Their role is to offer technical assistance to the local coordinating councils (LCCs) in their 
efforts to create a comprehensive local drug-free strategy.
<p>
<p>
<a name=Aware>
<h2>Awareness Efforts</a></h2>
<p>
This statewide network carries out drug-free awareness campaigns and activities.  Currently, 
the Commission's major public awareness effort is the "Deal With It" campaign, which urges 
all Hoosiers to either seek help for an addiction problem, or to get involved and an advocate 
for a drug-free community.  "Deal With It" features various brochures and printed materials 
which can be ordered by community organizations, and a hotline which helps individuals get in 
touch with their local drug-free advocates or treatment options.  
     "Deal With It Hotline"    (800) 9-WITH-IT.
<p>
The  Commission  also  works  closely with the  <b>Governor's  Council  on  Impaired  and 
Dangerous  Driving</b>  on awareness activities and coordinated community efforts  to 
address youth access to alcohol and impaired driving.  The Council is the public opinion  catalyst 
and  the  implementing body for statewide action to reduce death and injury on  Indiana  roadways.
   The Council administers over $7 million in state and federal funding  targeted  through 
traffic safety grants to state and local organizations.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<a name=StateHQ>
<h2>State Headquarters</a></h2>
<p>
Governor's Commission for a Drug Free Indiana<br>
ISTA Building<br>
150 West Market Street, Ste. 320<br>
Indianapolis, IN 46204<br>
(317) 232-4219<br>
(800) 9-WITH-IT<br>
Staff:  Lillian Henegar (Executive Director), Marilyn Bassett (Deputy Director),
     Rob Bryant ( Regional Office Coordinator), Jeff Todd (Program Director),
     Debbie Milas (Communications Director), Cathy Orosz (Media Relations Manager)
<p>
<p>
