<p>
</center>
<!-- title image end -->


<h2>Indiana State Excise Police</h2>
<p>
<hr>
<p>

The Indiana State Excise Police are the enforcement arm of the Indiana
Alcoholic Beverage Commission, charged with the primary responsibility
of policing the alcoholic beverage industry in the State.  The State
Excise Police enforce the laws which regulate permit holders --those
who are legally permitted to sell and serve alcoholic beverages, as
well as those not legally entitled to sell alcoholic beverages.  <p>
Protecting the welfare of Hoosiers, as well as the alcoholic beverage
industry, is an extensive job.  Officers conduct investigations of
violations by permit holders such as illegal Sunday sales, sales of
alcohol to minors, and bootlegging.  State excise officers also
represent the State on local Alcoholic Beverage Boards in each county.
The boards meet monthly to review applications and renewals for every
alcoholic beverage permit in their county.  Officers must investigate
each permit location before it's permit is reviewed to determine
whether it has met legal standards and is qualified to continue
selling and serving alcoholic beverages.  The officer also votes with
the board on the renewal or issuance of new permits in that county.
The monthly meeting allow resident of the county to voice their
concerns and suggestions about renewals or issuance of permits.

<p>
State excise officers are enforcement professionals trained and certified by the Indiana 
Law Enforcement Training Academy. They work closely with all law enforcement 
agencies in the State to offer assistance and coordinate efforts in monitoring the alcoholic 
beverage commission.
<p>
<h3>PUBLIC INFORMATION PROGRAM</h3>
<p>
The Indiana State Excise Police have launched a statewide public information program 
targeted to increase public and industry awareness about alcohol.  Officers utilize their 
expertise about alcohol and the alcoholic beverage industry to educate the public about the 
effects of alcohol and how it can be used responsibly and safely.
<p>
A large portion of the program is directed toward youth in an effort to combat alcohol 
abuse, hopefully before it begins.  Through films, brochures, and open discussion, officers 
educate  young people about alcohol and the effects of its use and abuse.  Because drunk 
driving is the number one cause of death for young adults, officers discuss the problem 
extensively.
<p>
The State Excise Police also work closely with the alcoholic beverage industry conducting 
training sessions to educate bartenders, waitresses, and servers of alcohol.  Servers are 
taught how to recognize when a customer has had too much to drink and how to 
creatively intervene.  Servers also learn about their legal responsibilities and liabilities.
<p>
The public information program is an example of the positive efforts of the State Excise 
Police to work cooperatively with the alcoholic beverage industry and the public an 
alternative to enforcement.  Officers are available to make presentations to any interested 
groups, schools and organizations at no cost.
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>Indiana State Excise Police</h3><br>
Chief Donald J. Okey<br>
