HREF=/search/home.html><AREA SHAPE=default
HREF=/home.html></MAP><!-- title map end --><!-- title image start --><img src="/graphics/title_banner.gif" align="bottom" border="0" usemap="#titlemap" >
<!-- title image end --><h1>Local Prevention Coalitions</h1>
<h2>A Web Section about Local Prevention Coalitions</h2>
<img src="bar3.gif" align="bottom" >

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="+1">Sample Direct Prevention Services Program Profile </font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><em><strong>Three-to-Six Club</em></strong>

<p align="center">an after-school program for targeted youth

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><pre>
<p><strong>Responsible Agency :</strong>          Westside Civic League (subcontractor)   
                              1234 Main Street
                              Hometown, IN 45678

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Program Supervisor:</strong>           John Prevention

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Volunteer Collaborating</strong>       St. Mark's Church 
<p><strong>Organizations:</strong>                
<p>                              Westside Christian Church

<p>                              Hoosier Area Food Bank

<p>                              Hometown Department of Parks and Recreation

<p>                              Hometown Transit Agency

<p>                              Metropolitan School District of Hometown

<p>                              Westside Middle School

<p>                              Northwest Elementary School

<p>                              Westside Elementary School

<p>                              Midwest Elementary School

<p>                              Southwest Elementary School

<p>                              Western Hills Elementary School
</pre>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Target Audience:</strong>   New 7th grade students at Westside       Middle School in Hometown, Indiana Western County)who are undergoing the transition from the more nurturing elementary school environment.  Approximately 600 students (100 each from 6 "feeder" elementary schools).  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Estimated number of participating students = 60 per year [10% of 
<p>target audience.  Note:  Program has space for 100 students (50 per semester), it will serveat least 30 "targeted youth" per semester based upon moderate risk status and family economic status -- it MAY serve up to 20 additional youth, but local funds will support non-targeted youth.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Requested DMH funding from Contractor:  $14,400 ($320 x [75% of 60])

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Based upon a local needs assessment, the Western County members of the Local Prevention Services Coalition determined that one important need in their community was to assist students who are "in transition" from the relatively nurturing environment of neighborhood elementary schools to the "large school" environment in their middle schools.  A secondary concern is to provide structured, supervised activities in the after-school hours for students who are at risk of substance involvement due to lack of adult supervision during those hours.  A consortium of youth-serving agencies on
the west side of Hometown propose to create a <em>"Three-to Six Club"</em> to provide a range of direct prevention services for new 7th grade students attending Westside Middle School.  The needs assessment revealed that the local school corporation's drug education curriculum does an adequate job of providing "facts about drugs" and teaching peer resistance skills, so the "focused prevention activities" will concentrate upon the identified local needs of (1) conflict resolution skills, (2) identifying and countering marketing of alcohol and tobacco to youth, and (3) teaching youth how to
plan social activities (as alternative activities) that are alcohol-,  tobacco-, and other drug-free.  All registered youth will participate in the focused prevention activities.  The club also will provide a range of supportive prevention activities that address certain risk and protective factors.  When youth register to participate in the club, the youth and parent/guardian will select two appropriate supportive prevention activities, based upon the individualized needs of the youth.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Westside Civic League will manage and coordinate the "<em><strong>Three-to-Six Club,"</em></strong> an after-school program for 7th grade youth who are in transition from an elementary school to a middle school environment.  The program consists of structured after-school activities two afternoons per week, from 3:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m. for ten weeks (20 days, 3 hours per day, for a total of 60 contact hours).  The program will serve two groups of approximately 25 youth participants during
the fall semester, and another two groups of approximately 25 youth participants during the spring semester.  The program will consist of four, 45-minute segments each afternoon: (1) structured recreational activities, (2) a focused prevention activity, (3) a free activity/nutritious snack break, and (4) an academic support activity ("homework help" or
"individualized tutoring").

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Focused Prevention Activities: </strong>(all students participate)

<p>6 day Conflict Resolution Education Program [6 45-minute sessions]

<p>6 day Identifying Youth-Oriented Marketing Program [6 45-minute sessions]

<p>8 day Planning ATOD-Free Social Events Program [8 45 minute sessions]

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Supportive Prevention Activities:</strong> (students choose, based upon individual needs & interests)
<p>
<p>Structured Recreational Activities (choose 2, 5 weeks each)

<p>Flag Football, Basketball, Volleyball, Slow Pitch   Softball,Chess Lessons, Arts and Crafts, Red Cross Certified Babysitting Course, Computer Skill Development, Model Shipbuilding, plus other student-suggested activities

<p>Academic Support Activities: (students choose, based upon   individual needs & interests)

<p>"Homework Help," "Individualized Tutoring," remedial skills development, academic enrichment activities, peer tutoring (gifted students may serve as
"cadet teachers" helping other students)

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Volunteer Collaborating Organizations:</strong>

<p><u>St. Mark's Church</u> has agreed to donate facilities to house one group of 25 participating youth Mondays and Wednesdays.

<p><u>Westside Christian Church</u> has agreed to donate facilities to house another group of 25 participating youth Tuesdays and
Thursdays.

<p><u>Hoosier Area Food Bank</u> has agree to donate food for nutritious snacks every program day (a small "per pound" handling
charge is assessed by the food bank)
<p><u>Hometown Department of Parks and Recreation</u> has agreed to waive user fees for participating youth to participate in six
"activity" field trips in parks facilities each semester.

<p><u>Hometown Transit Agency</u> has agreed to provide discounted bus passes to transport participating youth home from the
program.

<p><u>Metropolitan School District of Hometown</u> has agreed to assist in the marketing and recruitment of participating youth, to transport participating youth from their Middle School to the project site via existing school buses, and to collaborate with project staff in providing information needed to assist with the`"help with homework" and "individualized tutoring"
activities.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Staffing:</strong>  John Prevention, an existing professional staff member of the Westside Civic League will serve as Project Supervisor, as a 25% FTE assignment.  He will be the on-site coordinator every day.  He will be assisted by three high school students hired on an hourly basis, and community volunteers.  Collaborating agencies will also provide volunteers
for certain activities on an occasional basis.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong><u>Program Objectives:</strong></u>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><u>Process Objectives</u>:
<p>1. By June 30, 1998, this Direct Prevention Services Program shall implement the program as described in this profile,and shall enroll a minimum of 60 "targeted youth" in 4 program groups.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>2. By June 30, 1998, at least 75% of the participating youth registered for this Direct Prevention Services Program shall successfully complete the program.  Successful completion shall be defined as attending at least 80% of the scheduled program sessions, and completion of all survey forms and ending documentation for the program.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><u>Impact Objectives</u>:

<p>1. At the conclusion of this Direct Prevention Services Program, the prevalence of reported cigarette smoking in the previous month by participating youth shall not exceed 12%.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>2. At the conclusion of this Direct Prevention Services Program, the prevalence of reported alcohol use in the previous month by participating youth shall not exceed 15%.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>3. At the conclusion of  this Direct Prevention Services Program, the prevalence of reported inhalant use in the previous month by participating youth shall not exceed 5%.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>4. At the conclusion of  this Direct Prevention Services Program, the prevalence of reported marijuana use in the previous month by participating youth shall not exceed 5%.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><u>Outcome Objectives</u>:
<p>1. By the completion of this Services Program, at least 75% of participating youth will "pass" the standardized quiz included in the "Keep the Peace" educational package used by this program.
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>2. In the 4 month period following completion of this Services Program, the number of reports of alcohol use at Westside Middle School social events shall not exceed 20.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Proposed Budget:</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Targeted Participating Youth Successfully Completing the Program (TPYSCP) = 45

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Subcontract Reimbursement Rate of $320 per TPYSCP x 45 =$14,400.

<p>(DMH Funding provided by Contractor)

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Local and In-kind Contributions:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In-kind:

