<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><!-- title image end --><h1>Local Prevention Coalitions</h1>
<h2>A Web Section about Local Prevention Coalitions</h2>
<img src="bar3.gif" align="bottom" >

<p>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="+1">VII.  Minimum Requirements for Direct Prevention Services Programs</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">A <em><strong>"Direct Prevention Services Program" (or "Services Program")</em></strong> is a local program to provide direct prevention
services to a specified subset of the target population, usually defined by geographic boundaries or membership in a
particular group (ie. those living in a particular neighborhood or town, or those who are members of a particular
organization).  Each "Services Program" shall define its particular target audience and shall strive to serve at least 10% of
the targeted youth from that target audience in any particular contract year.</font>

<p><font size="-1">Each program of direct prevention services, whether provided by a subcontractor or by the primary contractor itself, shall
adhere to the following minimum requirements.</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">1.  A Direct Prevention Services Program shall consist of a structured series of activities providing continuing services to
targeted youth over a period of time sufficient to produce a predictable impact upon substance-using behavior.  This
should be operationally defined as providing at least 40 contact hours on at least 15 different days, over a time frame of at
least six weeks (programs providing longer or more contact hours are encouraged).  At least 10 hours of the programming
must be directly and easily identifiable as focused upon drug prevention (as described in "List 2-A - Focused Prevention
Activities" below), while the additional hours may be focused upon other activities that are related to prevention
objectives (as described in List "2-B - Supporting Prevention Activities" below).  Most of the "Focused Prevention
Activities" hours should be devoted to the "gateway drugs" of tobacco, alcohol, inhalants, and marijuana.  </font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">2.  Each Direct Prevention Services Program shall be designed based upon needs revealed in the Coalition's needs
assessment and shall provide a minimum of two "Focused Prevention Activities" from List 2-A below, in which <em><strong><u>all</em></strong></u>
participating youth shall enroll; and at least six "Supporting Prevention Activities" from List 2-B below, from which
participating youth may choose.  </font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong><font size="-1">LIST 2-A = "Focused Prevention Activities"</strong></font>

<p><font size="-1">(select two or more from this list; all participating youth   must complete those selected)</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">Provision of Factual Information about Drugs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Conflict Resolution</font>

<p><font size="-1">Refusal Skills/Resistance Training</font>

<p><font size="-1">Gang Prevention Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Violence Prevention Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Normative Education Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Awareness of Peer and Social Influences</font>

<p><font size="-1">Awareness of Advertising Pressures</font>

<p><font size="-1">Structuring Leisure Time to be Alcohol-, Tobacco-, and Other     Drug-Free</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong><font size="-1">LIST 2-B = "Supportive Prevention Activities"</strong></font>

<p><font size="-1">(select at least six, students must choose at least two from Service Program's list)</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">Remedial Tutoring</font>

<p><font size="-1">Help with Homework</font>

<p><font size="-1">Academic Skills Development</font>

<p><font size="-1">Adult Mentoring Programs (cross-generational)</font>

<p><font size="-1">Peer Mentoring Programs (intra-generational)</font>

<p><font size="-1">Natural Helpers Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Support Groups (non-users)</font>

<p><font size="-1">Structured Recreational Activities (various)</font>

<p><font size="-1">Positive Peer Organizations/Prevention Club</font>

<p><font size="-1">Community Service Programs (various)</font>

<p><font size="-1">Cadet Teaching or Tutoring</font>

<p><font size="-1">Non-Academic Classes (ie. art, crafts, dance, computer,  etc.) (various)</font>

<p><font size="-1">Rites of Passage</font>

<p><font size="-1">Cultural Competence Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Cultural Awareness Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Dropout Prevention Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Suicide Prevention Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Decision Making Skills Activities</font>

<p><font size="-1">Self Concept Development Activities</font>

<p><font size="-1">Leadership Development Activities</font>

<p><font size="-1">Generic Job Skills Development</font>

<p><font size="-1">Specific Job Skills Development</font>

<p><font size="-1">Social Etiquette Development</font>

<p><font size="-1">Goal Setting and Achievement Motivation Enhancement</font>

<p><font size="-1">Social Competence and Life Skills Development</font>

<p><font size="-1">Teamwork Development &amp; Interpersonal Skills</font>

<p><font size="-1">Development of Specific Skills (electronics, bicycle repair, etc.) (various)</font>

<p><font size="-1">Assertiveness Skills Development Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Communications Skills Development Programs</font>

<p><font size="-1">Stress Management Programs</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">3.  Each Direct Prevention Services Program shall include the following <strong><u>required</strong></u> components:</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">a) a registration process involving the youth and a parent/guardian that will include a signed parent/youth
consent/disclosure form; development of an individualized prevention plan for the youth, selecting optional supportive
prevention activities, in consultation with the youth and parent/guardian,  based upon individual needs and interests of the
youth; and a system for referral of youth to collaborating agencies for needed prevention services not provided by the
program.</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">b) completion of monthly report forms that include an attendance roster with youth's name and social security number. 
These reports will document progress at meeting the program's process objectives.</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">c) collection of data on the prevalence of alcohol, tobacco, and other drug use by participating youth, via an anonymous
confidential survey completed twice by participating youth: once at program enrollment, and again upon program
completion.  These data will document progress at meeting the program's impact objectives.</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">d) collection of needed data to document and evaluate progress at meeting the program's outcome objectives.</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">e) cooperation in DMH's satisfaction survey of a random sample of participating youth and their parents, by providing
names and addresses of 15 randomly selected participating youth who registered for the Services Program (10 who
completed the Services Program and 5 who did not complete it).</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">4.  Each program of direct prevention services shall be conducted under the direct supervision of a qualified prevention
professional ("Program Supervisor") who has attained at least "Level 2" status as a prevention professional in Indiana. 
Program supervisors who have not attained "Level 2" status at the date of hiring, but who hold an appropriate bachelor's
degree from an accredited institution of higher education, may be employed on an interim basis, but must immediately
begin the two courses required for "Level 2" status, and must obtain "Level 2" status within 120 days of employment (270
days of employment during the 1997-98 contract year).  Program supervisors are encouraged, but not required, to attain
"Level 1" status as a "Certified Prevention Professional."</font>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><font size="-1">5.  Each "Services Program" shall participate in the Coalition's evaluation plan, and shall adopt the two required process
objectives, the four required impact objectives, and two to four outcome objectives from the DMH-approved list of
outcome objectives provided below.  Each Services Program shall collect the necessary data required by the evaluation
plan and its staff shall tabulate the data needed for evaluating the outcome objectives and forward the data needed to
tabulate the process and impact objectives to the Indiana Prevention Resource Center for tabulation </font>
</body>
</html>
