<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Principles of Prevention Program Design</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>III. Principles of Prevention Program Design That
Must Be Incorporated into the Design of Each Coalition and Each
Services Program<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Prevention Programs funded by the Indiana Division
of Mental Health under this BAA must be based upon the following
principles:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>1.Successful drug prevention programs require the
interaction of the three most powerful institutions in the lives
of adolescents: family, school, and community. All programs funded
under this BAA must demonstrate that all three of these institutions
are involved in the planning and implementation of the proposed
programs.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>2.&quot;Stand alone&quot; programs implemented by
single agencies without the active collaboration of other community
organizations have historically been much less effective than
those implemented by coalitions of organizations that work together
for the benefit of their clients. All programs funded under this
BAA must be collaborative efforts planned by a true Local Coalition
and implemented by multiple agencies working together.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>3.In order for prevention programs to affect substance-use
behaviors, programs must be of sufficient intensity and duration
to provide an &quot;adequate dose&quot; of prevention activities.
Superficial programs of insufficient duration, programs that do
not attract the regular attendance of participants, and those
that are not focused have not been demonstrated to be effective.
All programs funded under this BAA must be of sufficient intensity
and duration to be expected to produce a measurable impact upon
future substance-using behaviors of the participants. This will
be operationally defined as requiring at least 40 contact hours,
on at least 15 different days, over a period of at least 6 weeks.
Participants should be expected to attend at least 80% of the
scheduled sessions.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>4.Over the past decade, enough research evidence
has been obtained to demonstrate that certain prevention strategies
can be predicted to reduce substance-using behaviors, and other
strategies are unlikely to reduce such behaviors. The purpose
of this BAA is to produce the greatest reduction in substance-using
behavior possible with the amount of funding available; it is
not intended to try new and unproven strategies. All programs
funded under this BAA must be based upon strategies that have
already been demonstrated to be effective in reducing adolescent
substance use, and must be included on the DMH list of approved
focused prevention activities or supportive prevention activities.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>5.The level of funding available cannot provide full
funding for meaningful prevention services for all eligible youth.
In order to assure that services are provided in all Indiana counties,
and to maximize the availability of prevention services, all programs
funded under this BAA will require significant local funding contributions.
All programs funded under this BAA must document the level of
local funding. The level of funding provided assumes that each
Contractor will utilize up to 20% of the total requested funds
for administrative costs, including the salary and benefits for
the program director, and other costs associated with administering
the project, and that the Services Programs will be funded only
for direct programming costs. It was assumed that subcontractor
overhead, indirect costs, and non-programming costs for Services
Programs would not be paid with DMH funds. Local contributions
would be used to provide these expenses. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>6.With the limited available funds, it is necessary
to establish funding priorities that are likely to result in the
greatest reduction in the prevalence of alcohol, tobacco, and
other drug problems in the future. Research evidence shows that
the greatest demonstrated effects from prevention programs have
come from those targeted toward 10- through 14-year old early
adolescents. All programs funded under this BAA must be targeted
solely toward direct services for 10- through 14-year old youth.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>7.With the limited available funds, it is necessary
to establish funding priorities that are likely to result in the
greatest reduction in the substance abuse prevalence per dollar
invested in prevention programs. Research evidence has shown the
greatest cost-benefit effect using &quot;prevention strategies&quot;
for programs targeted at populations that are at &quot;average
or moderate risk&quot; of developing future substance abuse problems.
Youth at &quot;low risk&quot; should be adequately served by school-based
programs, and those at &quot;highest risk&quot; should be served
with counseling, intervention, and treatment programs that are
better provided by managed care treatment professionals, rather
than prevention professionals.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>8.With the limited available funds, it is necessary
to establish funding priorities that eliminate or reduce program
overlaps and provide services that are not funded or required
to be funded by other sources. Indiana state law requires schools
to provide classroom instruction in drug prevention, and each
school corporation is eligible to receive funding from the Safe
and Drug-Free Schools Block Grant for school-based prevention
programs. All programs funded under this BAA must provide services
to targeted youth outside classroom settings and outside normal
school hours.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>9.Limited state funding should be reserved for providing
services to those in greatest need of financial assistance. The
funds allocated to each program funded under this BAA will be
based upon the number of targeted youth from households at or
below 200% of the federal poverty limits, which shall be operationally
defined as having total annual household incomes below $35,000.
Services should be made available to all youth in the target audience,
but DMH reimbursement will be limited to payment for &quot;targeted
youth&quot; completing each Services Program. Local funding or
user fees should pay for the participation of youth from households
with annual incomes in excess of $35,000. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>10.There is compelling research evidence that the
after-school hours present significant risk for the initiation
of substance-using behavior. Early adolescents who do not have
structured, adult-supervised activities in the after-school hours
are more than six times as likely to engage in substance-use as
those who have adult supervision. School vacation time also presents
significant risks. All programs funded under this BAA must address
the issue of adult-supervision of after-school activities.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>11.Although early adolescents have a need for both
focused and unfocused activities, and structured and unstructured
recreation, the sources of DMH funds restrict their use to drug
prevention programs. DMH has given absolute priority to programs
that are focused and structured and that have an easily-identifiable
drug prevention component. All programs funded under this BAA
must include at least ten hours of focused and structured drug
prevention activities. DMH funding may be used to provide additional
hours of supportive drug prevention activities, provided that
at least ten hours of focused prevention activities are included.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Contractors and subcontractors are encouraged to
provide additional, locally-funded programming for participating
youth that may be unfocused and unstructured. For example, the
DMH-funded program may provide focused, structured activities
two afternoons per week, and a locally-funded program (at the
same site and time) could provide an unfocused, unstructured &quot;drop-in
center&quot; the other three afternoons.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>12.Early adolescents are a heterogeneous group that
include members with differing needs. For example, some youth
may have low self esteem and may need programs to enhance their
self concept, while other youth may have inflated egos that need
a &quot;reality check;&quot; some youth may excel at academics,
while others need assistance. Effective prevention programs must
be designed to meet individual as well as group needs. All programs
funded under this BAA must provide for youth and parent (or guardian)
participation in the development of an individualized prevention
plan that allows for the selection of optional, supportive prevention
activities that meet the needs and interests of each participating
youth. At least some of the optional activities must be developed
in consultation with participating youth and their families.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>13.Effective community-based prevention programs
are designed to complement, and not to duplicate or compete with
school-based programs. All programs funded under this BAA must
be based upon a community needs assessment that examines existing
school- and community-based programs and that complements them.
At a minimum, it is expected that all Local Coalitions assess
the strengths and weaknesses of existing programs and select strategies
and activities that do not duplicate those that are already adequately
provided in the community. Each Contractor shall consult with
the designated Local Coordinating Council and the Step Ahead Council
in each county in its designated service area when developing
the local needs assessment.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>14.The federal enabling legislation that provides
the funds for this BAA requires that programs and services funded
supplement, and not supplant existing programs. This has been
interpreted to require that only new programs or services (or
significant capacity expansions of existing programs) can be funded.
Funding for existing programs may not be transferred to this BAA,
even if the funding for those programs is expiring. All programs
funded under this BAA must be new programs and/or services or
must provide significant expansions of the enrollment capacities
of existing programs, and must not supplant any program existing
as of the date on which this BAA was released.<BR>
<p>
<a href="contract.html">Next Section</a>
<a href="specs.html">Index</a>
</FONT>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
