<h3>Indiana Prevention Resource Center</h3>
<img src = "/graphics/publications/factline_banner.gif" alt = "Factline">
<h2>on Cocaine </h2>
<img align = right src = "/graphics/photographs/drugs/cokelow.jpg">
Copyright 1995, The Trustees of Indiana University. <br>
Permission granted for free distribution of copies for non-profit educational use.  All other 
rights reserved.
<p>
<p>
by William J. Bailey


<H3><A HREF="#Hydrochloride"><img align = center border = 0 src="/graphics/icons/tri.gif">Cocaine Hydrochloride</A></H3>

<H3><A HREF="#freebase"><img align = center border = 0 src="/graphics/icons/tri.gif">Freebase Cocaine</A></H3>

<H3><A HREF="#crack"><img align = center border = 0 src="/graphics/icons/tri.gif">Crack</A> </H3>

<H3><A HREF="#legal"><img align = center border = 0 src="/graphics/icons/tri.gif">Legal Issues</A> </H3>

<H3><A HREF="#other"><img align = center border = 0 src="/graphics/icons/tri.gif">Other Issues</A></H3>
<HR>



<P>
<B>COCAINE</B> is a powerful, stimulant drug drawn from the leaves
of the South American coca bush. It is an alkaloid, a member of
the chemical family that includes nicotine, caffeine and morphine.
Cocaine is made into a paste and its contents heated with hydrochloric
acid to produce cocaine hydrochloride, the most common, water
soluble form of cocaine, which can be snorted through the nasal
passages, intravenously injected or taken by mouth.
<P>
As it is produced in jungle labs in South America, <B><A NAME="Hydrochloride">COCAINE
HYDROCHLORIDE </b>is approximately 80 percent to 90 percent pure.
The impurities left over from the manufacturing process include
kerosene, benzene, leaded gasoline, powdered lime and a variety
of other substances. Between the jungle lab and the retail user,
cocaine passes through several distribution layers, such as exporters,
importers, drug kingpins and wholesalers who often &quot;cut&quot;
or &quot;step on&quot; the cocaine, diluting it with talcum powder,
amphetamines, local anesthetics and other substances. Today, street
cocaine averages less than 50 percent pure cocaine.</B>
<P>
<B><A NAME="freebase">FREEBASE COCAINE </b>is cocaine without
its water-soluble component or &quot;base.&quot; It is prepared
by dissolving cocaine hydrochloride with a strong alkali, and
drawing out the &quot;pure&quot; cocaine from many of the impurities.
Preparing freebase cocaine involves highly explosive solvents
and requires significant preparation time and equipment. Freebasing
originated in the mid-1970s as concern grew about the impurities
in cocaine hydrochloride. Because freebase cocaine is not water
soluble, it must be vaporized and inhaled to be absorbed. This
process is called &quot;smoking,&quot; though it does not involve
actual combustion of the cocaine.</B>
<P>
<B><A NAME="crack">
<img src="/graphics/photographs/drugs/crack.jpg" align=left>
Crack</a></b>is a new type of freebase cocaine
made by heating cocaine hydrochloride with baking soda or ammonia
in water. This process removes the hydrochloride base so the drug
can be &quot;smoked.&quot; Unlike regular freebase preparation,
crack manufacturing does not use explosive solvents. The result
is a hard paste that is cut into chunks resembling rock salt.
These ready-to-use portions allow users to quickly repeat doses
of the drug. Two or three chunks, sufficient for several doses
of the drug, typically sell for $5 to $20.</B>
<P>
The 1990 National Household Survey on Drug Abuse found that during
1990, 6.2 million persons had tried cocaine. Of that number, 662,000
used cocaine once a week or more and 336,000 used the drug daily
or almost daily. In 1990, 1.6 million North Americans reported
they had used cocaine in the past month; adolescents comprised
115,000 of that total, about 2.6 percent of the total adolescent
population. Of the 1.6 million persons who used cocaine during
the past month, approximately 500,000 had used crack.
<P>
The National High School Senior Survey found that annual use of
cocaine by high-school seniors at least once during their senior
year peaked in 1985 at 13.1 percent. By 1990, it had declined
to 5.3 percent. Use on a monthly basis by high-school seniors
also peaked in 1985 at 6.7 percent, and has declined steadily,
reaching 1.9 percent in 1990.
<P>
Cocaine stimulates the cells of the central nervous system and
the cardiovascular and sympathetic nervous systems. Cocaine is
also a local anesthetic that numbs the mucous membranes of the
mouth, vagina, rectum, and eye. The feeling of stimulation that
comes from cocaine is due to its activation of nerve cells in
the brain that release a chemical (dopamine), which is associated
with pleasure and a sense of alertness. Cocaine &quot;tricks&quot;
the brain into believing it has been furnished with pleasure,
such as food and sex.
<P>
Cocaine is one of the most &quot;reinforcing&quot; of all drugs.
People who use it experience a strong compulsion to continue taking
additional doses. Crack cocaine is especially dangerous because
of its high addiction potential. Because its vapors are inhaled
and go to the brain within seconds, the user experiences an intense
euphoria, while at the same time receiving a very high dose of
the drug. Tolerance to the euphoric effects builds quickly, so
after several doses the user must take more and more of the drug
to feel &quot;high.&quot; Because the euphoric effect lasts only
a few minutes, crack users feel compelled to take repeat doses
every few minutes. Users experience a vicious cycle of high followed
by depression followed by high.
<P>
Damage to body organs may occur as a result of using cocaine hydrochloride
or crack. Inhaling cocaine hydrochloride may cause damage to the
nasal cartilage. Rapid absorption of cocaine can trigger cardiac
irregularities, heart attack and cardiac arrest. Inhalation of
cocaine vapors can, over time, produce bronchitis and other respiratory
complications. Freebasing produces an especially strong immediate
rush, which may lead to convulsions and even death. Body burn-out,
malnutrition, and possible liver damage are also attributed to
crack use. Diseases of contamination, such as Hepatitis B, blood
stream infections and AIDS, may occur due to injection of cocaine
hydrochloride. Women who use cocaine are far more likely to have
miscarriages or spontaneous abortions. Risk of stroke and other
complications in pregnancy due to elevated blood pressure may
result from cocaine use. New research indicates a possible link
between birth defects and cocaine use in women. Studies show babies
born to cocaine addicts are more unresponsive and indifferent
than other newborns.
<P>
The use of cocaine may cause psychological changes in the user.
These effects may be a sense of increased self-esteem and confidence,
depression, intense anxiety, confusion, hallucinations, irritability,
repetition of tasks and a tendency to withdraw form normal activities.
Cocaine psychosis is paranoid behavior that occurs as a result
of overstimulation of the fright centers of the brain. Irrational
violence can occur at even the slightest provocation.<HR>

<P>
<a name="legal">
<B>LEGAL ISSUES:</B> 
<P>
Illegal use or distribution of any form of cocaine is a felony
under both state and federal law. Violators can be charged either
in state court or in federal court. Following is a summary of
Indiana laws on cocaine.
<P>
It is a Class A felony in Indiana to sell more than 3 grams of
cocaine to adults or to sell any amount to a person under 18 years
of age. The usual sentence for a Class A felony is 30 years, which
may range from 10 to 50 years, and carries a maximum $10,000 fine.
<P>
Possession with intent to deliver more than 3 grams, sales of
any amount or possession of 3 grams or more within 1,000 feet
of school property or on a school bus are Class A felonies.
<P>
Delivering up to 3 grams of cocaine to adults is a Class B felony,
as is possessing less than 3 grams of cocaine within 1,000 feet
of school property or on a school bus. The usual sentence for
a Class B felony is 10 years, which may range from 6 to 20 years,
and carries a maximum $10,000 fine.
<P>
Simple possession of 3 grams or more of cocaine is a Class C felony.
The usual sentence for a Class C felony is 5 years, which may
range from 2 to 8 years, and carries a maximum $10,000 fine.
<P>
Simple possession of up to 3 grams of cocaine is a Class D felony.
The usual sentence for a Class D is 2 years, which may range from
1 year to 4 years or be reduced to a Class A misdemeanor, and
carries a maximum $10,000 fine.
<P>
Note: Although suspension of all or part of prison sentences normally
is allowed under Indiana law, judges are required to impose a
minimum sentence that cannot be suspended on Class A felonies
and delivery of 3 grams or more of cocaine.<HR>

<P><a name = other>
<B>OTHER ISSUES: </B>
<P>
While the health consequences of using cocaine attract much attention,
cocaine use also leads to serious legal, social and economic problems.
<P>
It is estimated that more than half of all crimes against property
(burglary, larceny, etc.) committed in some major cities are related
to the use of crack cocaine and the addict's need for money to
buy the drug.
<P>
Crack addicts often develop a lifestyle based upon participating
in illegal activities to acquire the drug, such as stealing from
friends and family and employers, that results in job and career
problems due to the enormous cost of the habit. Involvement in
gangs and gang violence is often due to the influence of cocaine.
<P>
The U.S. Government Accounting Office has estimated that illegal
cocaine trafficking takes nearly $80 billion per year out of the
economy. Frequent news reports of hundred-million to billion-dollar
cocaine seizures by police attest to the economic impact of cocaine.
<P>
The excessive profit levels can serve as a corrupting influence
on citizens and law enforcement officials as well.
<P>
The huge profit potential tempts poor inner-city youth who can
support a family by selling cocaine, college students who can
make a year's tuition transporting it into the country, as well
as bankers who can make a fortune laundering cocaine profits.
Cocaine is an equal-opportunity corrupter.
<P>
In 1986, The Wall Street Journal reported that the cost of treatment
for cocaine addiction exceeded the cost of heart transplant surgery
in some East Coast hospitals. 
<p>


<!-- footer start -->
<hr>
<!-- footer end -->


