</MAP><!-- title map end -->

<!-- title image start -->
<center>
<img border = 0 src = "/graphics/title_banner.gif" usemap = "#titlemap">
<p>
</center>
<!-- title image end -->

<h3>Indiana Prevention Resource Center</h3>
<img src = "/graphics/publications/factline_banner.gif">
<h2>on Inhalants </h2>
<b>by William J. Bailey </b> <p>
Revised, December, 1996 <br>
Copyright 1997, The Trustees of Indiana University. <br>
Permission granted for free distribution of copies for non-profit educational
use.  All other rights reserved.<p>



<P>
<h3>INHALANTS</h3> 

Inhalants are gases or vapors that are inhaled to produce
psychoactive (mind-altering) drug effects. The drug category of "Inhalants" is 
characterized by the route or method by which the drugs enter the body, not by their
effects on the body.  There are three distinct categories of inhalants:
nitrous oxide, volatile nitrites, and petroleum distillates. 
  Many people do not think
of these products as harmful or deadly substances because many
are common items used for household and commercial use. Examples
of petroleum distillates include cleaning fluids, airplane glue, nail-polish
remover, hair sprays, paints and cooking sprays.
<P>
The inhaling of chemicals is not a new practice. Getting "high" 
by inhaling substances such as volatile hydrocarbons and anesthetics
was common in the 1800s in Europe, Great Britain and North America.
The use of ether and nitrous oxide also was not uncommon. In the
early 1900s, alcohol, ether and chloroform were inhalants of choice.
In the 1940s and 1950s, sniffing gasoline was prevalent. The 1960s
brought about additional abuses, which are still popular today,
including the sniffing of glues and acetone.<p><HR>

<P><a name="warning">
<h3>WARNING SIGNS OF USE: </h3>

Users of inhalants may exhibit the following characteristics:
<P>
Neglect of personal appearance; 
<P>
Lack of interest in school or work;
<P>
Withdrawal from family and/or friends; 
<P>
Retreat from athletic activities; 
<P>
Nonsensical talk; 
<P>
Loss of drive; 
<P>
Chemical odor on clothes or breath; 
<P>
Possesses paraphernalia (bags, discarded aerosol cans or rags).
<p>
<HR>


<P><a name = "common">
<h3>COMMON INHALANTS: </h3>

<B>NITROUS OXIDE </B>is a light anesthetic gas used as a painkiller in 
medicine and dentistry.  The drug also is used as a propellant
for whipping cream, and is used as a boosting agent to accelerate
combustion in auto racing.  Inhaling it creates
an intense, brief "high" that lasts for only a few minutes at
a time. 
<p>
Nitrous Oxide was discovered in the 1770s by Joseph Priestly.  It
has been used as an anesthetic since the mid-1800s.  It does not
completely block pain, but relieves a patient's anxiety and creates 
a dreamy or floating sensation.  Since it is not a complete pain 
killer, it is used in combination with other drugs in medicine and
dentistry.  In medicine, it is often mixed with halogenated gases, 
and with local anesthetics in dentistry.
<p>

<B>THE VOLATILE NITRITES</B> are stimulant drugs that produce powerful
heart stimulant effects.  <B>AMYL NITRITE</B> is a prescription drug for individuals
suffering from heart problems or asthma.  It is ususally dispensed 
in single dose glass ampoules, which are small glass vials covered with gauze.   
When used, the glass ampoule is crushed between the fingers and
and the vapors of the clear yellow liquid are inhaled.  The causes the blood vessels to 
dilate and the heart to beat faster.  Simultaneously, the amyl 
nitrite reduces the oxygen supply to the inner part of the brain 
and creates a sudden and intense weakness and dizziness. These effects can last 30 to
60 seconds.  
<B>BUTYL NITRITE </B>products are amyl nitrite substitues marketed 
as so-called room deodorizers in an attempt to avoid regulation as drugs.
They are packaged and available in small bottles and sold under names
such as &quot;LOCKER ROOM&quot; or &quot;RUSH.&quot; Butyl, unlike
amyl, is not legally classified as a prescription drug.  Consequently, these
chemicals often are available in bars and boutiques. Common effects
of this drug are identical to those of amyl nitrite and include a 
euphoric state that lasts from a few seconds to a few minutes. 
Individuals experience low blood pressure, followed by an increase in blood pressure, flushed face, dizziness and
headache. The &quot;rush&quot; occurs quickly and dissipates 
quickly so experienced users are inclined to maintain a &quot;high&quot;
by using increasing amounts of the inhalant. 
<p>
<B>PETROLEUM DISTILLATES</B> are gases or vapors of liquids that 
are made from petroleum.  They are used non-medically as powerful 
depressant intoxicant drugs.  The vapors of any common petroleum products 
are inhaled for their mind-altering effects, including <b>gasoline,
lighter fluid, kerosene, toulene, naptha, and model airplane glue.</b>  
Other petroleum distillate inhalants include aerosol gases used as a 
propellant in cooking sprays, spray paints, and cleaning supplies.  
Petroleum distillates are also found in such common household products 
as typewriter correction fluid and certain permanent magic markers.
 

<hr><p>
<P><a name = "effects">
<h3>EFFECTS OF INHALANT USE</h3>
<P><a name = "effects">
<B>ADVERSE EFFECTS: </B>
<P>
Some Inhalants are both physically and psychologically addictive, and
their effects depend on the type of inhalant used. In general, individuals
who use inhalants may risk these effects:
<P>
Depression and apathy
<P>
Nosebleeds
<P>
Headaches and eye pain
<P>
Kidney or liver damage
<P>
Chronic tired feeling
<P>
Heart failure
<P>
Slurred speech Anemia
<P>
Sores on mouth/nose
<p>
 Poor balance/coordination
<P>
Irritability
<P>
Personality changes 
<p>
Loss of muscle control
<P>
Bad breath and chemical odor
<P>
Severe nervous system and brain damage
<P>
Muscle/joint pain 
<P>
Death<HR>

<b>EFFECTS OF INHALANT INTOXICATION</b><br>
<font=-1>adapted from <i>Drug Use in American Society, 3rd ed.,</i> 
Burgess Publishing Co., 1993, &copy; Copyright 1993 William J. Bailey,
used with permission. </font><p>
<table border=3>
<tr><th colspan=2>Nitrous Oxide</th></tr>
<tr><td>General Effect:</td><td>Nitrous oxide produces a very intense euphoria.
The user appears to be delighted with life and unconcerned with things around him/her.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Eyes:</td><td>Usually wide open and a bit dilated.  The
intense euphoria may be "visible" in the eyes of the user.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Vital Signs:</td><td>Rapid pulse and somewhat elevated blood pressure.  
Deep inhalations may be related to method of administration. </td></tr>
<tr><td>Skin:</td><td>No Change.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Onservation:</td><td>It is obvious that the user is intoxicated
and use may be accompanied by laughter and boisterousness (thus the
name "laughing gas.")</td></tr>

<tr> <td colspan=2>   </td></tr>
<tr> <th colspan=2>Volatile Nitrites</th></tr>
<tr><td>General Effect</td><td>The volatile nitrites are stimulants that produce an intense
"rush."</td></tr>
<tr><td>Eyes:</td><td>No change.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Vital Signs:</td><td>Increase in heart rate and decrease in blood pressure, along 
with rapid and deep respirations.  Pulse may be bounding. </td></tr>
<tr><td>Skin:</td><td>Often flushed, often moist from persiration.</td><tr>
<tr><td>Observation:</td><td>Relaxation of smooth muscles.</td></tr>

<tr> <td colspan=2>   <td></tr>
<tr> <th colspan=2>Petroleum Distillates</th><tr>
<tr><td>General Effect:</td><td>Petroleum distillates are depressants that produce an 
intoxication similar to large doses of alcohol.  These drugs are 
sometimes called "deleriants," due to the creation of a delerious effect in the user.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Eyes:</td><td>Often glassy, the pupils may be constricted and 
may be slow to respond to light. </td></tr>
<tr><td>Vital Signs:</td><td>Slower pulse and respirations and lower blood pressure.  
Breathing may be shallow and somewhat labored. </td></tr>
<tr><td>Skin:</td><td>No change unless shock sets in, in which case it may be cool and clammy. </td></tr>
<tr><td>Observation:</td><td>The user appears to be "drunk" and may stumble 
when trying to walk.  A loss of coordination and ability to perform skilled tasks is common.  
The user may smell of the inhalant chemical and may continue to 
inhale it from a plastic bag or from a rag soaked in the liquid. </td></tr>
</table>



<P><a name = "alert">
<h3>PARENT/TEACHER ALERT: </h3>

Hazardous fumes and vapors are inhaled in a number of ways, often
as part of a group activity. Parents and teachers should be alert
for rags, cotton balls or tissues that are saturated with chemicals.
Users sometimes pour inhalants into soft-drink cans, which then
are held up to the face, or inhale from plastic bags.
<P>
Sniffing permanent-base magic markers or typewriter correction
fluid and spray paint also is common. Be alert for paint (especially
gold and silver), ink or correction fluid near the nostrils.
<P>
Inhaling from plastic bags is especially dangerous due to the
additional risk of asphyxiation.<p><HR>

<P><a name = legal>
<h3>LEGAL ISSUES: </h3>
<P>
Glue sniffing is a class B misdemeanor under Indiana law. A person
is guilty of glue sniffing if he or she inhales or ingests &quot;model
glue, or any substance containing toluene, acetone, benzene, N-butyl
nitrite, or any alphatic nitrite&quot; (not prescribed by a doctor)
to become intoxicated. The penalty for a class B misdemeanor in
Indiana is maximum imprisonment of 180 days and a maximum fine
of $1,000.
<P>
It is also a class B misdemeanor to distribute nitrous oxide for 
the purpose of producing intoxication.
<p>
Amyl nitrite and certain forms of nitrous oxide are &quot;legend&quot; drug under Indiana law. That
means only licensed practitioners (such as physicians, dentists
or pharmacists) may dispense them. Therefore, sale of a legend drug
 is illegal unless
it is dispensed by a pharmacist upon a prescription or drug order.
<P>
It is the crime of "maintaining a common nuisance" under Indiana law for any
person knowingly to maintain or visit a place (such as a store,
shop, warehouse, home or vehicle) used by that person or any other
person for unlawful use or sale of any legend drug.
<p>
<HR>
<h3>PATTERN OF USE </h3>
Unlike use of other drugs which continue to increase through 12th grade, 
inhalant use peaks in 8th or 9th grade.  In 1996, 8.0% of Indiana 8th graders 
reported using inhalants on a monthly or more frequent basis.  This compares
with 6.1% of 8th graders in a 1995 national survey.  In 1996, 18.3% of Indiana
9th graders reported using inhalants at least once in their lifetimes.
<p>
Anecdotal reports suggest that use of the petroleum distillate inhalants 
peaks at 8th grade and then declines each grade, but use of nitrous oxide 
and the volatile nitrites may continue to increase with each grade level.  Since 
most inhalant use involves the petroleum distillates, total inhalant use 
declines in the later grades.
<p>
<hr>
<!-- footer start -->
<!-- footer end -->

