<HEAD>

<TITLE>Are under-age students following "imaginary" peers?</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="William J. Bailey">
</HEAD>


<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">

<img src = "/graphics/newsline.gif" alt = "IPRC Newsline"><p>
Fall 1991
<p>
Are under-age students following &quot;imaginary&quot; peers?<!--Are under-age students following &quot;imaginary&quot; peers?-->

<P>
<I><B>A</B>ccording to Surgeon General Antonia Novello, more of
today's college students will die from alcohol-related illnesses
and injuries than will receive masters' degrees.</I> 
<P>
<I>More than 32 percent of this year's high-school seniors got
drunk at least once in the past two weeks, despite the fact that
nearly all of them are under the legal drinking age.</I> 
<P>
<I>More than one-third of Hoosier eighth-graders drink alcohol
at least once a month; more than half our 10th- and 11th-graders
do too.</I> 
<P>
<I>More than one-fourth of American high-school seniors report
that &quot;most or all&quot; of their friends get drunk at least
once a week.</I> 
<P>
<I>Alcohol related incidents kill more American teen-agers than
all other factors combined.</I> 
<P>
<I>Where do all these under-age youth get the idea it's all right
for them to drink? Whatever happened to the minimum drinking age?
What factors contribute to our current epidemic of under-age drinking?
Social acceptance? Lax law enforcement? Peer pressure? Who established
the social norms that seem to accept under-age drinking? Are the
norms set by community consensus, or are they the result of some
big misunderstanding?</I> 
<P>
<I>In this issue, Prevention Newsline focuses on under-age drinking.
In addition to the article that follows, articles on pages 3,
4 and 5 also consider use of alcohol by minors.</I> 
<P>
<B>Students overestimate drinking patterns of their peers</B>

<P>
<B>R</B>ecent research on college-student drinking norms sheds
some light on under-age drinking in general.
<P>
Although this article discusses how college-student drinking norms
are established, the findings are relevant to high-school and
junior high-school students as well. Numerous studies have shown
that students of all ages -- grade school through college -- greatly
overestimate peer use of alcohol and other drugs.
<P>
For many students, entering college is the first time to really
taste independence from parents and from many restrictions. The
pressure to adjust and conform is great. Making new friends and
following the crowd may be seen as essential to the transition
from high school to college, especially for freshmen.
<P>
College students have very definite perceptions regarding the
&quot;normal&quot; alcohol-related behaviors and attitudes of
other students, and these perceptions often influence their own
patterns of alcohol use. Yet studies conducted on a number of
college campuses reveal that students habitually <B>overestimate</B>
the extent to which their peers hold permissive attitudes or engage
in behaviors associated with abuse.
<P>
These misperceptions about peer behaviors in turn affect an individual's
own use of alcohol and other drugs. The result may be that one
&quot;imaginary peer&quot; is following OR leading another &quot;imaginary
peer&quot; down a path where neither truly desires to travel.
<P>
Research about norm misperceptions of students' alcohol and other
drug use by Alan Berkowitz, PhD. of Hobart and William Smith Colleges
in Geneva, NY, found the drinking behavior of most students was
more affected by peer influences than by family, personality,
ethnicity, or personal background characteristics.
<P>
&quot;This may be so because students spend a majority of their
time with other students and are strongly influenced in behaviors
by each other, sharing many similar values and beliefs,&quot;
Berkowitz wrote in a paper titled <I>Following Imaginary Peers:
How Norm Misperceptions Influence Student Substance Abuse.</I>

<P>
&quot;When these beliefs pertain to general standards of behavior
held by members of a group, they may be called norms. Norms exist
for how much students should drink, when and where they drink,
and how they behave when drinking. Norms are actual standards
of conduct and behaviors which are shared in common by members
of a group or culture. The college environment itself has been
referred to as a subculture with a unique set of norms for behavior
in general, and for drinking and other drug use in particular.&quot;
<P>
The extent of norm misperceptions may vary according to the type
of relationship involved, such as whether the relationship involves
a good friend, other residents of the same living unit, or fellow
students on campus. For example, while most students will overestimate
the alcohol and other drug attitudes of their friends and members
of their living unit, they do so even more when judging the overall
campus climate. In fact, the less familiar students are with individuals
or groups, the more likely it is they will be perceived inaccurately.
Students slightly misperceive their friends, have an exaggerated
sense of those in the living unit, and misperceive the overall
campus attitiude the most.
<P>
To illustrate, just imagine a student has a friend from home visiting
for the weekend. The two attend a large campus party, at which
a few individuals become obnoxiously drunk. Even though a majority
of the party guests do not display offensive behaviors, chances
are the campus visitor will perceive the whole college's population
to have the same attitudes as the rowdy few.
<P>
Berkowitz believes prevention education programs should try to
correct the misperceptions students hold about their peers' alcohol
and other drug use, possibly resulting in a reduction of alcohol
abuse or other associated behaviors. Therefore, students who are
more moderate may become comfortable declining a beer and socializing
with a cola in hand. They may feel more willing to let others
know when drinking behavior becomes inappropriate. The entire
campus community may become less tolerant of abusive use of alcohol
and other drugs.
<P>
Because peer influence is a significant factor in the drinking
behavior of students, changing the misperceptions students have
about other students' attitudes and behaviors associated with
alcohol and other drugs may be effective as a prevention strategy.
When they operate under misperceptions, many students ignore their
own better judgment because they fear disapproval or rejection
by their peers. By providing information and education to correct
the norm misperception of students' alcohol and drug use, we may
help free the students who already hold more responsible attitudes
to confront those who use alcohol and drugs destructively and
in ways that are unfair to others.
<P>
Berkowitz warns, however, that &quot;acknowledging the personal
expectancies regarding the use of alcohol does not negate the
fact that it has certain physiological effects.&quot; Alcohol
has well-documented effects on the central nervous system, it
impairs judgment, and it interferes with complex motor skills.
But it is important to also acknowledge how much of one's behaviors
and expectations associated with alcohol are socially conditioned
and can be changed if we examine our assumptions and correct them.
<P>
&quot;By making it less acceptable to use alcohol as an excuse
for our behavior and by learning more constructive ways to have
fun or relax, we can help reduce the problem use and abuse of
alcohol and other drugs among college students.&quot;
<P>
<B>References</B> 
<P>
1. Berkowitz, Alan, (1991). <I>Following Imaginary Peers: How
Norm Misperceptions Influence Student Substance Abuse.</I> Paper
developed for the Eta Sigma Gamma National Student Network Organization
Grant, PROJECT DIRECTION.
<P>
2. Perkins, Wesley H. and Berkowitz, Alan D. (1986). <I>Perceiving
the Community Norms of Alcohol Use Among Students: Some Research
Implications for Campus Alcohol Education Programming. <U>The
International Journal of Addictions,</U> 21(9/10), 961-976. </I>
<P>
<B>National minimum drinking age a myth</B> 
<P>
Sometimes good ideas are based upon faulty information. Many of
the principles that guide the development of alcohol and other
drug messages for youth are based upon the assumption that we
have a national minimum drinking age of 21, and that people under
that age cannot drink legally. We are told not to talk about &quot;responsible
use&quot; to minors, because minors are never allowed to drink.
<P>
As a Hoosier, that idea seemed logical to me. In Indiana there
is an absolute ban on minor consumption of alcoholic beverages.
Minors are not allowed to consume alcoholic beverages in Indiana
under any circumstances - never - there are no loopholes! I assumed
that, with the strong federal incentives tied to eligibility for
highway grants, all states had similar bans. I was wrong.
<P>
A recent court case in Monroe County raised my awareness of other
states' loopholes. An 18-year-old high-school senior was found
&quot;not guilty&quot; of minor consumption because the prosecutor
could not prove that the minor had not consumed the alcohol, legally,
in Ohio! It seems that one of his parents lived in Ohio, and Ohio
has a loophole in its minimum drinking-age law. Minors of any
age can legally consume alcohol in Ohio if the alcohol is furnished
by a parent in a private home.
<P>
That's a big loophole. Ten-year-olds could legally get drunk in
a private home! I thought that Ohio must be an anomaly. Surely
there weren't such loopholes in other state laws. I was wrong
again.
<P>
My non-lawyer's review of the laws of all 50 states and the District
of Columbia found loopholes in the laws of at least half the states.
A good lawyer might be able to find even more loopholes. Some
of the loopholes are big enough to drive a beer wagon through!
<P>
The most common loophole is &quot;parental permission.&quot; In
about half the states, it is legal for minors to drink alcohol,
in a private home, with the permission of their parent or legal
guardian. In some states, they may even drink in bars or restaurants
when in the presence of their parents.
<P>
Another common loophole is a &quot;public consumption ban.&quot;
In some states the law against minor consumption only applies
in public places. A minor can legally consume alcohol in private
in some states, sometimes even without parental permission. In
a few cases, college residence-hall rooms are considered private
places.
<P>
In Indiana, it is illegal for a minor to (1) consume, (2) possess,
or (3) transport an alcoholic beverage. In some states, the ban
is against possession only. This requires police to catch minors
with alcohol in their hands. Once the alcohol is in their system,
they are immune from arrest. That seems to promote rapid drinking.
<P>
A few states set the penalties for minor consumption so low that
law-enforcement officers may lose interest in enforcing the law.
In Iowa, 19- and 20-year-olds can be fined a maximum $15 for minor
possession. That's hardly much of a deterrent!
<P>
In Louisiana, private clubs are exempt places, and some courts
have interpreted that so broadly that college fraternities have
been immune from prosecution for serving high-school students.
<P>
Some states remain silent about certain situations. Sales to minors
or possession by minors may be banned, but consumption is not
specifically mentioned. Consumption in public may be banned, but
the law may be silent on private consumption.
<P>
In at least half our states, there are at least some circumstances
under which minors are allowed (or at least not forbidden) to
consume alcohol. Given our very mobile populations, even residents
of states with absolute bans, such as Indiana, cannot assume that
our high-school students may not encounter situations (on vacation,
for example), where they could legally consume alcoholic beverages.
<P>
We may need to rethink how we handle this issue in light of other
states' failure to enact and enforce meaningful minimum drinking-age
laws.
<P>
<B>- William J. Bailey</B> 
<P>
Make your community a drug-free zone<!--Make your community a drug-free zone-->

<P>
&quot;Drug Free Zones .... Taking Action&quot; is an exciting
new video available for loan from the Indiana Prevention Resource
Center. &quot;Drug Free Zones&quot; examines how a community can
become motivated and involved in the fight against alcohol and
other drug problems in schools, communities and housing developments.
<P>
This 27-minute video is hosted by Edward James Olmos and features
residents from New York to California -- real people who have
taken action against those promoting the use of alcohol and other
drugs to the youth and citizens of their communities.
<P>
The message of the video is that communities can take action,
and that there is hope of reclaiming a community that is being
overtaken by the use of alcohol and other drugs.
<P>
Viewers of the video are given practical ideas about things they
can do as individuals or groups to reduce the drug and alcohol
use by youth in their communities. These include filing claims
in small claims court, asking city officials to add street lights
and working with local law-enforcements officials to start a community
policing program. One example of a community's small, but important
step in reducing drug trafficking was a change in the time sprinklers
were turned on in the city park. Residents found that drugs were
being sold and used in the park at specific times of day. To curtail
this, the citizens' action group went to the city parks department
and asked that the lawn sprinklers be turned on during those times.
This simple action ended the use of the park for the selling and
using of drugs in that area.
<P>
A community action guide comes with the video. It gives suggestions
about on how to get started on the activities in the video. Ideas
about how to organize and lead the group and how to develop a
plan of action are provided. Several copies of &quot;Drug Free
Zones ... Taking Action&quot; are available for loan from the
PRC.
<P>
