<HEAD>

<TITLE>Learning from those who said "No"</TITLE>


<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="William J. Bailey">
</HEAD>


<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">
<img src = "/graphics/newsline.gif" alt = "IPRC Newsline"><p>
Winter 1991<p>

<H1><B>In this issue: </A></B></H1>

<H3><A HREF="#learning">Learning from those who said &quot;No&quot; </A>
</H3>

<H3><A HREF="#bibliography">A bibliography on resilience</A></H3>
<HR>

<A NAME="learning">
<H3><I><B>Learning from those who said &quot;No&quot;</B></I>
 </H3>

<H3>Resilience may be key to prevention </H3>

<P>
Should prevention programs be based upon positives or negatives?
Can we learn more from people who said &quot;Yes,&quot; or from
people who said &quot;No&quot;?
<P>
There is growing consensus in the drug-prevention field that effective
prevention programs need to be based upon knowledge gained from
the study of those who successfully avoided alcohol and other
drug problems -- not those who used and abused.
<P>
During the 1980s, much of the attention of drug professionals
focused on &quot;what went wrong&quot; in youth and adults who
developed alcohol and other drug problems. Little attention was
focused on &quot;what went right&quot; in those who managed to
avoid problems.
<P>
Recently, attention has shifted to studying why some so-called
&quot;high-risk youth&quot; are successful in staying free of
alcohol and other drugs. These &quot;resilient&quot; youth may
have had ample opportunity and predisposition to use chemical
substances, but were able to overcome their risk factors through
reliance upon protective factors that helped them avoid problems.
<P>
For example, while children of alcoholics are at greater risk
than others of developing alcohol and coping problems, the vast
majority of children of alcoholics do not develop alcoholism or
serious coping problems. Some researchers estimate that only one
in five develop such problems. Prevention programs based upon
the resilient children of alcoholics should be more effective
than those based upon the &quot;casualties.&quot;
<P>
&quot;The concept of risk factors ... is only one component necessary
to understanding the range of youth drug-related behaviors,&quot;
noted Kevin McIntyre, Douglas White and Richard Yoast in their
monograph, <I>Resilience among High Risk Youth</I>, published
recently by the Wisconsin Clearinghouse. &quot;A second component,
'protective factors,' or those aspects of a person's biology,
psychology, and environment which serve to mediate or mitigate
against substance abuse, are at least as important.&quot;
<P>
In an extensive review of the literature, Hawkins, Lishner, Catalano,
and Howard (1985) identified several potential protective factors
that seemed to reduce the likelihood of adolescent involvement
with alcohol and other drugs. They noted that adolescents with
positive relationships, involvement and bonding within families,
strong role models, educational successes, good school bonding,
and focused aspirations seemed much less likely to develop alcohol
and drug problems. Easy temperaments seemed to enable children
and adolescents to adapt to stresses and adopt more positive attitudes,
and both of these attributes seem to be powerful protective factors.
<P>
In 1986, the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism
commissioned another literature review, which was prepared by
Macro Systems, Inc. This review noted three additional categories
of potential protective factors against alcohol abuse: parental,
peer and environmental. Parental factors included &quot;parental
disapproval of alcohol use by youth, setting clear expectations
for nonuse, and ... strong family relationships and social competencies.&quot;
Peer factors included accurate perceptions of norms of use and
nonuse by peers, and skills to resist pressures to use. Environmental
factors included such things as availability and accessibility
of alcohol in the community, and the ability to critically examine
alcohol advertising.
<P>
Among the &quot;protective factors&quot; Hawkins and his associates
described was a strong commitment to education. Adolescents committed
to education, even if they were otherwise high risk, were much
less likely to use drugs than their peers. This suggests that
programs to increase student interest in education, such as Indiana's
new 21st Century Scholars Program, can foster resilience in participating
students. (See article on page 4.)
<P>
Those who have developed social competence and possess the skills
to resist unwanted peer pressure also exhibit resilience. A model
program is Project SMART (Self Management And Resistance Training),
developed at the Institute for Health Promotion and Disease Prevention
Research at the University of Southern California. Beginning in
the early 1980s, the USC project team developed strategies and
techniques to enhance resistance to peer pressure via classroom-based
activities. The same team helped build Kansas City's Project STAR
(Students Taught Awareness and Resistance) and Indiana's Project
I-STAR (Indiana Students Taught Awareness and Resistance). These
projects recently were commended by the U.S. secretary of health
and human services as models of proven effectiveness.
<P>
Another model to enhance resilience is the Life Skills Training
curriculum developed by Botvin and his associates. LST combines
factual information about alcohol and other drugs with information
about social pressures to use, and techniques for resisting the
pressure. Participants learn and practice skills to think critically,
make informed decisions, and control anxieties and pressures.
The program also develops communication skills, assertiveness
and skills in handling male/female relationships. A rigorous evaluation
has demonstrated its effectiveness in reducing alcohol, tobacco
and other drug use among students who complete LST.
<P>
The latest twist on resilience applies the idea of developing
skills and competence -- &quot;empowerment&quot; -- to communities.
Just as individuals can reduce the risk of developing alcohol
and other drug problems by avoiding risk factors and enhancing
protective factors, communities can reduce collective risks by
avoiding factors that expose the community to risk and enhancing
factors that protect the community from problems.
<P>
Communities can develop collective skills and community networks
to enhance their abilities to resist social pressures that promote
alcohol and other drug abuse. Hansen and his associates, who developed
Project SMART to enhance individual resilience, are developing
a &quot;social ecology model&quot; to enhance community resilience.
The model describes how community environments increase or decrease
exposure to drug problems for residents and considers the impact
on community acceptance or rejection of drug use of such factors
as alcoholic beverage licensing, law-enforcement priorities, prosecution
and adjudication strategies, parent networks to supervise adolescent
social activities, media support and community values.
<P>
Schools and communities can enhance resilience by adopting and
implementing policies and norms that promote nonuse of alcohol
and other drugs. Communities can influence public policy on advertising
and promotion of alcohol and tobacco, reporting of drug-law violations,
enforcement of regulations on sale and serving of alcohol and
tobacco to minors, and taxation and pricing policies.
<P>
Prevention strategies that build resilience often are perceived
as &quot;positive&quot; and therefore more attractive to community
support. The next issue of <I>Prevention Newsline</I> will highlight
successful programs that build resilience and discuss ideas for
gaining community support.
<P>
<B>--William J. Bailey</B> <HR>

<a name="bibliography">
<H3><B>Read more about it:<I> </I>a bibliography on resilience</B>
</H3>

<P>
<B>Anthony</B>, E.J. (1987a). Risk vulnerability, and resistance.
In E.J. Anthony and B.J. Cohler (Eds.), The Invulnerable Child,
(pp. 3-48). New York: Guilford.
<P>
<B>Anthony</B>, E.J. (1987b). Children at high risk for psychosis
growing up successfully. In E.J. Anthony and B.J. Cohler (Eds).
The Invulnerable Child, (pp. 147-184). New York: Guilford Press.
<P>
<B>Bernard</B>, B. (1987, March). Protective factor research:
what we can learn from resilient children. Prevention Forum, 7(3),
3-10. (Available from AHTDS Prevention Resource Center, 901 S.
Second Street, Springfield, IL, 67204).
<P>
<B>Botvin</B>, G.J. (1983). Prevention of adolescent substance
abuse through the development of personal and social competence,
in T.J. Lynn, C.G. Leukefield, and J. P. Ludford (Eds), Preventing
Adolescent Drug Abuse: Intervention Strategies (NIDA Research
Monograph 47, pp. 115-140. DHHS Publication No. ADM 86-1280).
Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office.
<P>
<B>Botvin</B>, G.J. and Wills, T.A. (1985). Personal and social
skills training: cognitive-behavioral approaches to substance
abuse prevention, in C.S. Bell and R. Battjes (Eds), Prevention
Adolescent Drug Abuse Among Children and Adolescents (NIDA Research
Monograph 63, pp. 8-49. DHHS Publication No. ADMA 85-1334). Washington,
DC: U.S. Government Printing Office.
<P>
<B>Felsman</B>, J.K. and Vaillant, G.E. (1987). Resilient children
as adults: a 40-year study. In E.J. Anthony and B.J. Cohler (Eds),
The Invulnerable Child (pp. 211-228). New York: Guilford Press.
<P>
<B>Fisher</B>, L., Kokes, R.F., Cole, R.E., Perkins, P.M., and
Wynne, L.C. (1987). Competent children at risk: a study of well-functioning
offspring of disturbed parents. In E.J. Anthony and B.J. Cohler
(Eds), The Invulnerable Child (pp. 211-228). New York: Guilford
Press.
<P>
<B>Garmezy</B>, N. (1971). Vulnerability research and the issue
of primary prevention,American Journal of Orthopsychiatry, 41,
101-116.
<P>
<B>Garmezy</B>, N. and Newuchtrelein, K. (1972). Invulnerable
children: the fact and fiction of competence and disadvantage,
American Journal of Orthopsychiatry, 42(2), 328-329.
<P>
<B>Hansen</B>, W.B. (1988, March). Theory and Implementation of
the Social Influence Model of Primary Prevention. Paper presented
at the First National Conference on Prevention Research Findings:
Implications for Alcohol and Drug Abuse Program Planning, National
Prevention Network, Kansas City, MO.
<P>
<B>Hansen</B>, W.B., Johnson, C.A., Flay, B.R., Grahman, J.W.,
and Sobel, J. (1988). Affective and social influences approaches
to the prevention of multiple substance abuse among seventh grade
students: results from Project SMART, Prevention Medicine, 17(2),
135-154.
<P>
<B>Hawkins</B>, J.D., Lishner, D.M., Catalano, R.F., Jr. and Howard,
M.O. (1985). Childhood predictors of adolescent substance abuse:
toward an empirically grounded theory, Journal of Children in
Comptemporary Society, 18(1/2), 11-48.
<P>
<B>Kaufman</B>, C., Grunebaum, H., Cohler, B., and Gamer, E. (1979).
Superkids: competent children of psychotic mothers, American Journal
of Psychiatry, 136(11), 1398-1402.
<P>
<B>Kumpfer</B>, K.L. (1987). Special populations: etiology and
prevention of vulnerability to chemical dependency in children
of substance abusers, in B.S. Brown and A.R. Mills (Eds), Youth
at High Risk for Substance Abuse, (DHHS Publication No. ADM 87-1537,
pp. 1-72). Rockville, MD: National Institute on Drug Abuse.
<P>
<B>Macro Systems</B>, Inc. (1986). Literature Review on Alcohol
and Youth. Washington, DC: National Institute on Alcohol Abuse
and Alcoholism.
<P>
<B>McIntyre</B>, K., White, D., and Yost, R. (1990). Resilience
Among High Risk Youth. Madison, WI: University of Wisconsin, Dean
of Students Office, Wisconsin Clearinghouse.
<P>
<B>Murphy</B>, L.B. (1987). Further reflections on resilience.
In E.J. Anthony and B. J. Cohler (Eds), The Invulnerable Child(pp.
84-105). New York: Guilford Press.
<P>
<B>Quinton</B>, D. and Rutter, M. (1988). Parenting Breakdown:
The Making and Breaking of Inter-generational Links, Aldershot,
England: Avebury.
<P>
<B>Rutter</B>, M. (1979). Protective factors in children's responses
to stress and disadvantages. In M.W. Kent and J.E. Rolf (Eds),
Primary Prevention of Psychopathology: Vol. III. Social Competence
in Children (pp 49-74). Hanover, NH: University Press of New England.
<P>
<B>Rutter</B>, M. (1985). Resilience in the face of adversity:
some issues and some questions, Journal of Child Psychology and
Psychiatry, 147, 598-611.
<P>
<B>Wallack</B>, L. (1985). Mass media, youth and the prevention
of substance abuse: towards an integrated approach, Journal of
Children in Contemporary Society, 18(1/2), 153-180.
<P>
<B>Werner</B>, E.E. (1986). Resilient offspring of alcoholics:
a longitudinal study from birth to age 18, Journal of Studies
on Alcohol, 47(1), 34-40. 
