<HEAD>

<TITLE>Alcohol, tobacco campaigns frequently aim at women, children, minorities 
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="William J. Bailey">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">

<img src = "/graphics/newsline.gif" alt = "IPRC Newsline"><p>
Spring 1992<p>


<H1><B><A NAME="campaign">In this Issue:</A> </B></H1>

<H3><A HREF="#campaign">Alcohol, tobacco campaigns frequently aimed at women, children and minorities</A>
</H3>

<H3><A HREF="#campaign">Tips for taking aim at the targeters</A>
</H3>

<H3><A HREF="#indiana">ASSIST</A></H3>
<HR>

<H3>Alcohol, tobacco campaigns frequently aim at women, children,
minorities </H3>

<H4>Marketers target 'vulnerable' consumers</H4>

<P>
<I><B>Since his 1988 debut, Old Joe Camel has become a ubiquitous
presence on billboards, phone booths and magazine pages. Whether
he's on the beach or in the bar, straddling his chopper or jamming
on the bandstand, the macho dromedary is often surrounded by adoring
babes. Sometimes Joe offers Camel buyers coupons that can be redeemed
for T-shirts and baseball caps. He also mugs for promotional events
such as the Camel &quot;Mud &amp; Monster&quot; series, a stadium
show in which trucks with giant wheels drive over piles of empty
cars.</B></I> 
<P>
<I><B>Who is this multimillion-dollar campaign directed at?</B></I>

<P>
--<I>Newsweek</I>, Dec. 23, 1991.
<P>
<I><B>Name the TV program on which Anheuser-Busch premiered its
latest ad campaign for Michelob beer: a) </B></I><B>Monday Night
Football<I> b)</I> American Gladiators <I>c)</I> Danielle Steel's
Fine Things<I>.</I></B> 
<P>
<I><B>The answer is &quot;c.&quot; See? Things do change in beer
marketing. In its attempts to revive its Michelob brand, Anheuser-Busch
is targeting women.</B></I> 
<P>
<I>--USA Today</I>, Feb. 3, 1992
<P>
<B>M</B>arketers spend innumerable hours and dollars finding new
ways to sell their products. This includes researching audiences,
their perceived needs, perceptions, attitudes and behaviors. The
resulting marketing campaigns create an atmosphere of acceptability
and necessity for products.
<P>
Part of marketing is targeting a particular population based on
audience characteristics such as gender, age or ethnicity, and
advertisers strategically place their campaigns where they want
the target population to see them. As traditional market segments
shrink and new groups command more buying power, marketers turn
their attention to those markets. Hence, we see alcohol advertisements
appearing in &quot;youth-oriented&quot; publications, and tobacco
ads saturating billboards in ethnic communities.
<P>
Concern is increasing over the targeting of &quot;vulnerable&quot;
consumers. A great deal of recent concern has focused on RJ Reynolds'
Joe Camel cigarette campaign, after studies published in December
in the <I>Journal of the American Medical Association</I> indicated
the cartoon-like camel strongly attracts children and adolescents
to smoking.
<P>
For various reasons, four specific populations have emerged as
target audiences for alcohol and tobacco marketers: African Americans,
Hispanics, children and women.
<P>
Collectively, these populations have one thing in common -- they
are especially vulnerable to the messages promoted by these industries.
<P>
African Americans have disproportionately high rates of poverty
and poor education, and also suffer from higher rates of death,
disease and injury from alcohol and tobacco. Specifically, African-American
males are at higher risk than white males for heart disease, liver
disease and esophageal cancer, all of which are tied to cigarettes
and/or alcohol. High rates of homicide, motor-vehicle crashes,
and criminal behavior also have been linked to alcohol misuse.
<P>
Cigarette and tobacco advertising that promotes the use of these
drugs as typical of sophistication and success is concentrated
in low-income urban neighborhoods, where susceptible individuals
and groups may reside.
<P>
Individuals in inner-city neighborhoods often have little health
education, and may be less aware of the dangers of smoking and
drinking. As a group, African Americans are affected by inadequate
health care and the aggravating effects of social and economic
factors. Herein lies the vulnerability of this population.
<P>
It is no accident that research studies have found more cigarette
and alcohol billboards in predominantly black neighborhoods than
predominantly white ones.
<P>
Increased marketing of alcohol and tobacco to Hispanics can be
attributed to the changing demographics of Hispanic communities.
This population is growing rapidly, is youthful (median age =
25.5 years), diverse, and can be targeted in two different languages.
Cigarette and alcohol companies have responded with multi-million
dollar advertising campaigns promoting increased consumption,
especially among women and young people, who typically have exhibited
low rates of drinking and smoking behavior.
<P>
Although many Hispanic groups have experienced lower rates of
major chronic illnesses such as cancer and heart disease than
whites, the acculturation of Hispanics is resulting in a rise
in the prevalence of drinking and smoking.
<P>
Consequently, researchers anticipate increases in alcohol- and
tobacco-related illnesses among this group.
<P>
Women are a favorite target for many advertisers. Changes in society
have provided women with more independence and purchasing power
than in years past, and today they are bombarded with advertising
that will help them &quot;improve&quot; their independent image.
Virtually every product, from shampoo to &quot;Slim Fast,&quot;
promises women they will become more attractive, sophisticated,
desirable and physically fit.
<P>
Consistent with this market ing strategy, alcohol and tobacco
ads also promote these images, promising pleasure, fun and freedom
to the woman who smokes the right kind of cigarette or drinks
the right kind of beer.
<P>
Women comprise the fastest growing group of smokers, and lung
cancer has surpassed breast cancer as the leading cause of death
from cancer in women.
<P>
Tobacco and alcohol companies realize most consumers are aware
of the risks associated with their products. Thus, advertisements
must be
<P>
psychologically appealing to perpetuate both the company's and
the consumer's denial of potential consequences of smoking and
drinking.
<P>
Advertisements targeted to women skillfully exhibit this denial.
An example of this denial mechanism was found by psychologist
Carol Moog, who reports:
<P>
&quot;Newport Stripes offers a stunning example of this kind of
psychological sleight-of-hand in an ad which has as its centerpiece
two hysterically laughing, nearly identical blonde women cuddling
big, fat, jolly snow &quot;babies&quot; on their laps. They're
little-girl-women-mommies, in exuberant good health (a glow heightened
by the intensely hot pink color of the surrounding page). Their
cigarettes are &quot;smooth and delicate&quot; (like a baby's
skin) and they are &quot;light, refreshing&quot; and (harmless)
as the candy features on their &quot;babies.&quot; Why do so many
young women smoke? For one thing, their mothers do. The messages
in this ad insidiously support continuing the habit in the next
generation by showing these delightful young mothers who enjoy
&quot;the latest in pleasure&quot; and have fine chubby children
(to whom they will pass on their addictions).&quot;
<P>
Modifications of alcohol and tobacco products and their packaging
help make smoking and drinking more &quot;female-friendly.&quot;
<P>
Companies have developed &quot;ultra light&quot; and &quot;ultra
slim&quot; cigarettes, and brands such as &quot;Eve&quot; and
&quot;Misty&quot; cigarettes have emerged. Alcohol companies have
created &quot;light beer,&quot; fruit-flavored wine coolers for
people who do not like the taste of hard liquor, and most recently,
reduced-calorie wine coolers. These products are designed to appeal
to the calorie-conscious woman. She can still drink <I>and </I>watch
her figure.
<P>
Children are the most vulnerable audience targeted by alcohol
and cigarette marketers. To maintain business growth, tobacco
companies need to initiate thousands of new smokers every day.
Hence, children frequently are exposed to tobacco ads in stores,
on billboards and incertain sports, entertainment and teen-oriented
magazines. The exposure to alcohol advertising is similar, with
the addition of television and radio exposures.
<P>
A study that examined the effects of children's exposure to TV
beer commercials found that 88 percent of fifth- and sixth-grade
students surveyed could not only identify &quot;Spuds MacKenzie,&quot;
but they also could correctly link him with Bud Light. The recent
widely publicized studies of children's recognition of Joe Camel
reiterates the fact that advertising is reaching young people.
<P>
Finding these examples is easy, but changing alcohol and tobacco
marketing strategies is comparatively difficult.
<P>
Mass media and advertising influence and sustain certain lifestyles
as much as medical technology, cultural norms and family system
values.
<P>
To combat targeted marketing of alcohol and tobacco, public concern
and awareness must be accompanied by strategies that communicate
health promotion and risk reduction messages.
<P>
Communication efforts must be comprehensive and should come from
a variety of sources, including schools, families, community organizations,
and print and broadcast media.
<P>
<B>--Sarah M. Greene</B> 
<P>
<B>References</B> 
<P>
<I>OSAP Prevention Monograph-5. Communicating about Alcohol and
Other Drugs: Strategies for Reaching Populations at Risk</I>.
(1990).
<P>
<I>OSAP Prevention Monograph-6. Youth and Drugs: Society's Mixed
Messages</I>. (1990).
<P>
<I>Marketing Booze to Blacks</I>. (1987). George A. Hacker, Ronald
Collins and Michael Jacobson.
<P>
<I>Marketing Disease to Hispanics</I> (1989). Bruce Maxwell and
Michael Jacobson.
<P>
<I>The Booze Merchants - The Inebriating of America</I>. (1983).
Michael Jacobson, Robert Atkins and George Hacker.
<P>
<I>Media &amp; Values</I>. Spring/Summer 1991, Number 54-55.<HR>

<H3>Tips for taking aim at the targeters: </H3>

<P>
While targeted alcohol and tobacco marketing has a pervasive influence,
effective strategies can be designed to counteract this influence.
Measures can be initiated by government agencies, community organizations,
state and local educators, businesses and church groups. Possible
strategies include:
<P>
1. Become aware of local and state advertising regulations by
contacting local zoning offices.
<P>
2. Enact and enforce zoning laws that control distribution and
operation of new alcohol and tobacco vendors in Hispanic and African-American
neighborhoods, or near schools, parks and churches.
<P>
3. Implement legislation that restricts billboards promoting alcohol
or tobacco, especially near schools or areas with high concentrations
of &quot;vulnerable&quot; populations.
<P>
4. Encourage local businesses to increase advertising to limit
the time and space available to alcohol and tobacco marketers.
<P>
5. Work with law-enforcement agencies to enforce laws prohibiting
alcohol and tobacco sales to persons not of legal purchasing age.
<P>
6. Ask community officials to enact city &quot;clean-up&quot;
and &quot;beautification&quot; acts, including elimination of
alcohol and tobacco billboards and local radio advertising of
alcohol products.
<P>
7. Lobby for removal of tobacco and alcohol advertising from sports
stadiums and mass-transit systems.
<P>
8. Involve individuals from a variety of groups (business, churches,
preservation groups, neighborhood organizations, etc.) in a coalition
against tobacco and alcohol marketing.
<P>
9. Petition outdoor advertising companies to donate billboard
space to charitable groups and voluntary health agencies for public-service
announcements.
<P>
10. Encourage local health-care providers and voluntary health
agencies to disseminate messages to the public about the risks
associated with smoking and drinking.
<P>
11. Contact local advertising agencies to initiate a counter-advertising
program that spotlights negative aspects and images of smoking
and drinking.<HR>

<H3><A NAME="indiana">Indiana one of 17 states in national anti-smoking
program</A></H3>

<P>
Indiana is one of 17 states taking part over the next seven years
in a comprehensive multi-strategy prevention initiative to reduce
the use of tobacco. The project is titled ASSIST (American Stop
Smoking Intervention Study for Cancer Prevention), a joint project
of the National Cancer Institute and the American Cancer Society.
<P>
Project ASSIST, the United States' largest organized effort to
combat the use of tobacco, is a result of 20 years of tobacco-related
research and intervention studies.
<P>
Peter Greenwald, director of the National Cancer Institute's Division
of Cancer Prevention and Control, says, &quot;From more than 60
large intervention studies, we have learned which strategies and
approaches are most effective in controlling tobacco use. It is
time we apply these techniques as broadly as possible to prevent
smoking-related lung cancers and other diseases.&quot;
<P>
The National Cancer Institute will provide $114 million in program
support and $20 million for training, technical assistance and
evaluation. The American Cancer Society will provide $25 million
to $30 million to provide state and local coalition with staff
members, training, and materials. Additionally, the American Cancer
Society will provide access to its network of volunteers. It is
estimated more than 800,000 volunteers will be involved in Project
ASSIST.
<P>
The overall goal of ASSIST is to reduce the occurrence of cancer
and smoking-related deaths. This will be achieved by concentrating
on tobacco use, which is the greatest modifiable risk factor among
the top three leading causes of death.
<P>
Reduction of smoking prevalence among adults from 28 percent to
15 percent nationally is a specific goal of ASSIST, which also
has four main objectives: 1) To reach 91 million people (including
18 million smokers) with its messages about tobacco use; 2) To
help more than 4.5 million adults stop smoking; 3) To help 2 million
young people never start smoking; and 4) To prevent 1.2 million
people from dying prematurely as a result of smoking-related diseases.
<P>
To achieve these goals, populations at greatest risk for tobacco
use will be targeted. This includes adolescents, women, African
Americans, Hispanics, blue-collar workers, the poor and the undereducated.
<P>
Though efforts in Indiana will be statewide, most will be targeted
to four counties that give the best access to these target populations:
Allen, Lake, Marion and Vanderburgh.
<P>
Indiana Project ASSIST is a collaborative effort of the American
Cancer Society, Indiana Division, and the Indiana State Department
of Health.
<P>
Each state that has received funding will be free to design programs
and plans that work specifically in that state. For example, Indiana
is not a large tobacco-producing state, while in North Carolina,
another Project ASSIST state, tobacco is a $3 billion-a-year business
and the sole source of income for many residents. These unique
qualities will be considered as long-range plans are made.
<P>
A statewide planning coalition has been organized in Indiana.
It includes representatives from community agencies, state and
local government, schools, voluntary health organizations, hospitals
and media organizations. Each targeted local area also will form
a coalition of community leaders. The state coalition will help
with statewide plans and provide assistance to the local coalitions.
<P>
Project ASSIST will be conducted in two phases. Phase I, from
now until 1993, will focus on establishing the coalitions, which
will identify the state's high-risk smoking populations and determine
the best approach for reaching them.
<P>
In addition, the following committees will be formed: schools,
communities, worksites and health-care settings.
<P>
Each committee will work to promote tobacco-free environments
in each setting and will assess current tobacco-control strategies.
Results of these assessments will be used to develop the state's
comprehensive tobacco control plan.
<P>
Phase II will involve implementation of strategies developed in
Phase I, and will run from 1993 to 1998.
<P>
A variety of intervention strategies will be used. In the health-care
setting, providers will be given information on smoking-related
issues and trained to offer smoking-cessation courses.
<P>
Community leaders will be educated on the benefits of developing
tobacco-related public policies. These policies include such things
as restricting smoking in the workplace and schools, limiting
minors' access to cigarette vending machines, restricting smoking
in restaurants and public areas, and placing restrictions on tobacco
promotions targeting youth.
<P>
The coalitions will help establish smoking-cessation classes in
the schools and community, and work with employers to offer smoking-cessation
classes at workplaces.
<P>
Coalitions also will conduct public-service and educational campaigns
designed specifically for the targeted population in their areas.
<P>
For more information call the Indiana State Department of Health.

</BODY>

</HTML>

