<HEAD>
<TITLE>Conflict-resolution curriculum teaches adolescents to 'win' without violence 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">
<img src = "/graphics/newsline.gif" alt = "IPRC Newsline"><p>
Spring 1993<br>
<H1><B><A NAME="conflict">In this issue:</A> </B></H1>

<H3><A HREF="#conflict">Conflict Resolution Curriculum - Win without Violence</A>
</H3>
<HR>

<H3>Conflict-resolution curriculum teaches adolescents to 'win'
without violence</H3>

<P>
<I><B>Young man killed for &quot;cutting in&quot; check-out line</B></I>

<P>
<I><B>Teenager shot in back after walking away from argument</B></I>

<P>
<I><B>Young man shot after asking group to be quiet while he made
a phone call</B></I> 
<P>
Do any of these stories sound familiar? Episodes like these are
no longer isolated cases, but everyday occurrences in our society.
<P>
Over the last few years, Americans increasingly have turned to
violence to resolve arguments and interpersonal disputes. People
seem not to be interested in working out problems; instead, they
are turning to guns and weapons to &quot;win&quot; their fights.
<P>
This type of violence is occurring at an alarming rate in many
African-American communities, where murder is the No. 1 cause
of death for African-American males and females between the ages
of 15 and 34, according to <I>The Washington Post</I> While some
of these incidents may be labeled gang- or crime-related, the
fact is many of these youth are killing and being killed because
they lack basic communication and problem-solving skills.
<P>
Because of the escalating violence among this population, schools
and other organizations are adding conflict-resolution courses
to their curricula. &quot;Dealing with Anger. Givin' It, Takin'
It, and Workin' It Out&quot; is one such conflict-resolution curriculum,
and it is available from the Indiana Prevention Resource Center.
<P>
&quot;Dealing with Anger. Givin' It, Takin' It, and Workin' It
Out,&quot; produced by Norman Baxley and Associates, Inc. and
distributed by Research Press, is a videotape curriculum designed
to teach conflict-resolution skills to African-American youth.
<P>
The curriculum is divided into three parts, each of which runs
between 15 and 20 minutes. The first part, &quot;Givin' It,&quot;
is designed to teach adolescents to express their feelings to
someone without provoking an argument or fight. The second part,
&quot;Takin' It,&quot; shows youth how to take criticism and respect
the opinions of others, while maintaining self-composure and dignity
-- or in the vernacular of many adolescents, allowing them to
&quot;save face.&quot; The third part, &quot;Workin' It Out,&quot;
teaches adolescents to compromise when no other alternative is
available -- and still come out of situations as winners.
<P>
The curriculum's three skills -- giving out anger, taking anger
and working out anger -- are taught through the use of vignettes.
For each technique, the first vignette shows a typical everyday
conflict (such as someone confronting another about a rumor),
and how such a confrontation easily can turn into a heated argument
or fight.
<P>
The second vignette shows how the person can use the conflict-resolution
skill or technique in the same situation to resolve the conflict
and avoid further disputes.
<P>
In addition to vignettes, each tape shows a group of African-American
adolescent males who have watched the tapes and are practicing
the techniques. In these segments, the young men role play and
practice conflict-resolution skills using their personal experiences.
They also receive feedback from each other on how well they used
the skills and how they could improve.
<P>
These segments are useful because they show teachers how to teach
the skills in their classrooms, as well as show students how they
can apply the techniques to their everyday lives.
<P>
In addition to the videotapes, the curriculum includes a lesson
plan for teachers and group leaders.
<P>
&quot;Dealing with Anger. Givin' It, Takin' It, and Workin' It
Out&quot; is a good curriculum because it is realistic and specifically
designed to meet the needs of African-American youth. Unlike some
&quot;culturally sensitive&quot; educational materials that end
up stereotyping an entire culture and insulting their audiences,
this series uses a variety of vignettes to show ordinary people
in everyday situations that any audience is comfortable relating
to.
<P>
One important group of skills that could have been included in
this series are skills to weigh the benefits and costs of becoming
involved in certain conflicts --skills to determine which battles
are worth fighting, and which ones are not. These skills should
be addressed in this series and in all
<P>
conflict-resolution courses. Today, adolescents must be able to
make immediate decisions and answer questions such as: Is hitting
this person worth going to jail? Is this argument worth getting
shot? Is it better for me to walk away from a fight, or be kicked
out of school? Combining these quick decision-making skills with
the conflict-resolution skills presented in the videotapes would
give adolescents additional tools to avoid violent confrontations.
<P>
The most valuable lesson adolescents can learn from conflict-resolution
courses is that controlling their behavior is more important than
controlling the actions of others. Most often, the one who can
maintain his or her behavior can control the situation without
resorting to violence. Adolescents need to understand that the
&quot;winner&quot; is not always the one who has the gun, but
the one who can sense a bad situation and leave before the gun
goes off.
<P>
In addition, youth need to understand that life is important and
that saving their lives is far more important than &quot;saving
face.&quot; Adolescents must know they have the ability and right
to choose many situations they are in, and that they have the
power to turn a negative, volatile situation into nonviolent one.<I>
</I>
<P>
Conflict-resolution courses not only can be taught in schools,
but also can be used by other organizations. For example, churches,
boys' and girls' clubs, big brother/big sister organizations and
other community-based programs can incorporate conflict-resolution
skills development into their programming. National Black fraternities
and sororities that are known for their educational and skills
development efforts among African-Americans also can use these
courses to better serve their communities.
<P>
&quot;Dealing with Anger. Givin' It, Takin'It, and Workin' It
Out&quot; and other conflict-resolution courses are good first
steps to developing and improving good communication skills among
adolescents, particularly African-American youth. However, we
must remember behaviors and skills take time and practice to develop.
One course is not enough. To decrease this surge in violence,
communities and schools must make communication and problem-solving
skills an integral part of school and other organizational curricula.
By making these skills a normal and expected part of adolescent
behavior, we can see this pattern of violence end.
<P>
Call the Indiana Prevention Resource Center at (800) 346-3077
to borrow a copy of &quot;Dealing with Anger. Givin' It, Taken'
It and Workin' It Out&quot; or for more information.
<P>
<B>-- Karen E. Rice</B> 
<P>
<B>References</B> 
<P>
Baxley, Norman and Associates. <U>Dealing with Anger. Givin' It,
Takin' It, and Workin'It Out.</U> Research Press, Champaign, IL
1991.
<P>
Squitieri, Tom and Jack Kelley.<I> </I>&quot;Bias slaying 'disregard
for life.' &quot;
<P>
<I>USA Today</I>, Dec. 6, 1990, p. 26
<P>
Will, George F. <I>&quot;</I>The Disease of Violence<I>.&quot;</I>
<I>The Washington Post</I>, November 29, 1992, p. 26. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
