<HEAD>

<TITLE>Reorganization aimed at improving federal prevention and treatment efforts 
</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="William J. Bailey">
</HEAD>


<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">

<img src = "/graphics/newsline.gif" alt = "IPRC Newsline"><p>
Winter 1993<br>

<H1><B><A NAME="reorganization">In this issue:</A> </B></H1>

<H3><A HREF="#reorganization">Reorganization aimed at improving federal prevention and treatment efforts</A>
</H3>

<H3><A HREF="#funding">Primer on prevention funding</A></H3>
<HR>

<H3>Reorganization aimed at improving federal prevention and treatment
efforts </H3>

<H3>Federal AOD agencies reorganized</H3>

<P>
The alphabet soup of acronyms for federal alcohol and other drug
prevention and treatment agencies has been rearranged. Forget
ADAMHA and OSAP and OTI, and learn SAMHSA, CSAT, CSAP, and CMHS
instead. On October 1, 1992, federal agencies that deal with alcohol
and other drug issues were reorganized as part of the federal
government's effort to strengthen prevention and treatment of
addictive and mental disorders.
<P>
The <B>Alcohol, Drug Abuse and Mental Health Administration</B>
(ADAMHA) was reorganized into a new health-service agency called
the <B>Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration</B>
(SAMHSA) within the U.S. Public Health Service of the U.S. Department
of Health and Human Services (DHHS).
<P>
The SAMHSA mission is to reduce the incidence and prevalence of
alcohol and other drug use and mental disorders, improve treatment
outcomes for persons suffering from these disorders, and diminish
consequences for their families and communities.
<P>
As mandated by the ADAMHA Reorganization Act of 1992, SAMHSA will
consist of three centers: the Center for Substance Abuse Treatment
(CSAT), the Center for Substance Abuse Prevention (CSAP) and the
Center for Mental Health Services (CMHS). Coordination will be
provided by the Office of the Administrator.
<P>
Three research institutes that were part of ADAMHA when it was
created in 1974 have been transferred to the National Institutes
of Health. These institutes are the National Institute of Mental
Health (NIMH), National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism
(NIAAA), and National Institute of Drug Abuse (NIDA).
<P>
<B>The new centers</B> 
<P>
The Center for Substance Abuse Treatment (CSAT) will administer
the block grant for the prevention and treatment of alcohol and
other drug use, and will continue to administer other treatment
programs begun by its predecessor organization, the ADAMHA Office
for Treatment Improvement (OTI), which aimed at enhancing the
quality of alcohol and other drugs treatment systems nationwide.
<P>
The Center for Mental Health Services (CMHS)- an entirely new
entity-has been established to create a focus for increased federal
attention on issues related to mental health services across the
United States. The Center's overall objective is to assist the
States in providing access to treatment, prevention and rehabilitation
services while reducing the impact of these devastating illnesses
on families and communities.
<P>
The Center for Substance Abuse Prevention (CSAP) replaces the
Office for Substance Abuse Prevention (OSAP) and will administer
several of the programs previously run by OSAP, including the
two major funding programs -- the Community Partnership and the
High Risk Youth grant programs. The new legislation also authorizes
CSAP to help small business employers who cannot afford Employee
Assistance Programs to establish them.
<P>
The mission of the Center for Substance Abuse Prevention (CSAP)
is to support, advocate and promote the continued development
of community, state, national and international comprehensive
prevention systems. CSAP connects people and resources with innovative
ideas, strategies and programs designed to encourage creative
and effective efforts aimed at reducing and eliminating alcohol,
tobacco and other drug problems in our society. CSAP also provides
federal leadership to support, stimulate and create partnerships
at all levels and with all sectors of the society to create a
holistic prevention agenda designed to strengthen the nation's
capacity to foster healthy individuals, families, organizations,
institutions and communities, especially among those at risk.
<P>
<B>CSAP will administer several programs including:</B> 
<P>
--the existing Community Partnership Demonstration program, which
is given authorization by the new law;
<P>
--the existing High Risk Youth Prevention Demonstration Program;
<P>
--the existing Substance Abuse Preventions Conference Grant Program;
<P>
--newly authorized Employee Assistance Programs;
<P>
--a new national data base on prevention, including the National
Clearinghouse for Alcohol and other Drug Information (NCADI)
<P>
--the existing Communications Cooperative Agreement Program; and
<P>
--prevention components of its previous training initiative.
<P>
<B>CSAP is also required to:</B> 
<P>
1. Sponsor regional workshops on the prevention of drug and alcohol
abuse;
<P>
2. Coordinate the findings of research sponsored by Public Health
Service Agencies on drug and alcohol abuse prevention;
<P>
3. Establish effective drug and alcohol abuse prevention literature;
<P>
4. Disseminate prevention materials to states, localities and
school systems, in conjunction with the Department of Education;
<P>
5. Support clinical training programs for alcohol and other drugs
counselors and health professionals serving in the drug abuse
education and prevention fields;
<P>
6. Create educational materials to reduce alcohol and other drug
users' risks of acquiring HIV, in coordination with the Centers
for Disease Control;
<P>
7. Carry out training, technical assistance, data collection and
evaluation of Drug-Free Schools and Communities Act programs;
<P>
8. Strengthen the development of innovative, community-based model
programs to prevent alcohol and other drug use and abuse among
youth;
<P>
9. Develop and distribute documentary films and public-service
announcements for television and radio to educate the general
public about the dangers of drugs;
<P>
10. Establish and fund demonstration grants to identify and discourage
the improper use or abuse of anabolic steroids by students, particular
high school students.
<P>
Additionally, CSAP has been charged with the mission of developing
a national data base on alcohol and other drugs prevention programs.
The data base will be developed from information currently held
by the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information
(NCADI). CSAP will also continue to design,
<P>
implement and evaluate innovative knowledge transfer and communication
strategies. This will include the continued operation of a national
clearinghouse for alcohol and drug information.
<P>
CSAP will administer two major grant programs carried over from
the former office for Substance Abuse Prevention. These are the
<I> Community Partnership Program</I> and the <I>High Risk Youth
Program</I>.
<P>
<I>The Community Partnership Program</I> assists community coalitions
to develop partnerships of agencies and organizations to take
a systematic approach to the prevention of alcohol and other drug
abuse. An appropriation of up to $120 million is authorized for
fiscal year 1993.
<P>
<I>The High Risk Youth Prevention Demonstration Grant Program</I>
is targeted at youth who are at risk of alcohol or other drug
use. It is reauthorized with a new requirement that grantees focus
on reducing tobacco, as well as illegal alcohol and other drug
use, among high risk youth. Up to $70 million is authorized for
fiscal year 1993.
<P>
A new provision authorizes CSAP to help Employee Assistance Programs
(EAPs) through grants to public and private nonprofit groups to
aid small business employers who are without EAPs to establish
them. Special consideration will be given to businesses with 50
or fewer employees. Up to $3 million is authorized for fiscal
year 1993.
<P>
<B>New special interest offices</B> 
<P>
Two new offices have been established to track special issues:
<I>The Office of Applied Science</I> and <I>The Office for Women's
Services.</I> <I>The Office of Applied Studies</I> (OAS), in the
Office of the Administration, was formed to serve as the focal
point for SAMSHA's data gathering analysis and dissemination activities.
<P>
Among its important functions, the Office will oversee key agency
alcohol and other drug use surveys, with the specific responsibility
for the annual <I>National Household Survey on Drug Abuse</I>,
and the <I>DAWN (Drug Abuse Warning Network) Survey</I>, both
previously administered under the National Institute on Drug Abuse.
<P>
<I>DAWN</I> is a national system in which data are collected on
drug abuse episodes from emergency rooms and medical examiner
facilities across the country. <I>DAWN</I> data are available
quarterly.
<P>
<I>The National Household Survey on Drug Abuse</I> is an annual
prevalence survey that includes people 12 years of age in the
United States.
<P>
OAS will evaluate the relevance of the findings of those and other
major national surveys to the activities of SAMHSA components,
the Department of Health and Humans Services and the White House
Office of National Drug Control Policy, and will interpret them
for the public.
<P>
Another vital function of this new office is the coordination
of all Agency evaluation programs. OAS will work with SAMHSA components
to develop evaluation goals and facilitate development of agency
evaluation efforts.
<P>
The special needs of women will be the focus of activity of a
new SAMHSA <I>Office for Women's Services</I> (OWS). Under the
direction of an Associate Administrator, the office will lead
agency efforts to address issues involved in providing alcohol
and other drugs and mental health services for women-medical care,
psychological treatment, social services, an establishment of
necessary links to jobs, housing and transportation.
<P>
The primary care needs of substance-abusing mothers and their
children also will be addressed, as well as the unique needs of
minority women, including Native American, Hispanic, African American
and Asian women.
<P>
The office will enhance the collection of data on women's health
by developing standardized data-collection programs and assuring
that data are made accessible to health providers, researchers
and the public. The office also will ensure the establishment
of an information program on women's alcohol and other drugs and
mental health services.
<P>
In addition, working with an Agency Coordination Committee, the
new women's services office will identify program gaps, recommend
policy, and coordinate and promote collaboration among the three
SAMSHSA Centers, and with other U.S. Public Health Service components.
<P>
<I>This article was compiled from the following sources: RADAR's
Electronic Communication System, ADAMHA News, and Federal Funding
Oppourtunities Under the ADAMHA Reorganization Act, which is a
publication of Government Information Services.</I> <HR>

<a name="funding">
<H3>PRIMER ON PREVENTION FUNDING: PART I</H3>

<H3>Develop strategies for funding drug prevention programs </H3>

<P>
<I>&quot;Do you know what makes these birds [America's first spacecraft]
fly? Funding makes these birds fly! No bucks, no Buck Rogers!&quot;</I>

<P>
<I>-</I>Mercury astronauts speaking to the rocket
<P>
scientists in the movie <I>The Right Stuff</I> 
<P>
The <I>Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986</I>, and other federal and
state initiatives, helped to stimulate interest in preventing
alcohol and other drug problems. Over the past five years, tens
of thousands of drug prevention programs have emerged in communities
across the country. As these programs mature, and as new programs
develop, many prevention practitioners have shifted their attention
to generating adequate funding to operate these programs.
<P>
Unfortunately, just like the spacecraft referred to by the Mercury
astronauts, it takes funding to make most drug prevention programs
&quot;fly.&quot; Many prevention practitioners have little experience
in locating and raising the funding they need to keep their programs
going.
<P>
This is the first of a series of three &quot;On Prevention&quot;
columns in <I>Prevention Newsline</I> that will focus on funding
drug prevention activities.
<P>
One of the biggest mistakes that prevention practitioners make
in developing a funding strategy is to <B>overestimate</B> their
chances of receiving funding from federal and state sources and
to <B>underestimate</B> their chances of receiving funding from
local sources in their own community. As a general rule, the chances
for successful funding are better the closer the funding source
is to their home community.
<P>
While the lure of large federal budgets may entice many people
to apply for federal grants, most of these programs fund fewer
than 5% of all applications they receive.
<P>
<B>Federal funding</B> for drug prevention activities falls into
two general categories: block grants to states, and competitive
grants to individual programs. The largest share of federal funding
is distributed through block grants to states. In most federal
agencies, competitive grants account for less than 10% of their
total prevention funding.
<P>
<B>Federal block grants</B> are distributed through designated
state agencies. Each federal agency utilizes a parallel state
agency to distribute its block grants in a given state. For example,
the Alcohol, Drug Abuse, and Mental Health block grants are administered
in Indiana by the Indiana Family and Social Services Administration
- Division of Mental Health.
<P>
Block grants are intended to provide funding assistance for general
operating expenses of local programs that do not involve a &quot;compelling
federal interest.&quot; Only programs that involve a compelling
federal interest are eligible for most competitive grant programs.
<P>
In some cases, federal laws or regulations establish a formula
for the distribution of block grant funds. About 70% of the Drug-Free
Schools block grant funds for the state of Indiana are distributed
to local school districts according to a formula based upon census
data. School corporations that comply with the minimum requirements
for funding receive their share of the block grant funds as an
&quot;entitlement.&quot; Only qualifying local education agencies
(school corporations) are entitled to apply for these funds, and
the Indiana Department of Education distributes application information
directly to all eligible school corporations.
<P>
The balance of the Drug-Free Schools block grant is awarded to
local projects via several different programs - some coordinated
by the Indiana Department of Education, and some by the Division
of Mental Health. In some cases, federal law restricts eligibility
to receive funding to local education agencies, while in other
cases, a wide range of community agencies are eligible to apply.
<P>
In Indiana, all applications for federal block grant money to
fund alcohol and other drug programs that is not distributed as
an entitlement require review by the appropriate <B>Local Coordinating
Council (LCC)</B> of the Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free
Indiana. Since some of these programs provide a multi-year funding
commitment to successful applicants, not all programs receive
applications every year.
<P>
The best source of information about available block grant funding
is your <B>Regional Coordinating Office (RCO)</B> of the Governor's
Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana. To have any realistic chance
of receiving these funds, you must work through their Local Coordinating
Councils. Each RCO will receive information about all of the current
block grant programs that are accepting applications.
<P>
<B>Federal competitive grants</B> (sometimes called &quot;discretionary
grants&quot;) generally are restricted to programs that address
some problem of &quot;compelling federal interest.&quot; Examples
of such interest include: &quot;research projects&quot; that are
designed to develop new strategies for preventing alcohol and
other drug problems, &quot;demonstration projects&quot; that apply
the findings from research and demonstrate the effectiveness (or
lack thereof) of new strategies, projects that target groups of
special interest to the federal government (such as Native Americans,
&quot;high risk youth,&quot; etc.), projects that serve nationwide
populations, and programs that address emerging or special priority
issues (such as AIDS/drug prevention).
<P>
A very few federal programs (such as the ACTION Drug Alliance
program, and the FIPSE institution wide program for colleges and
universities) provide one-time start-up funds for routine local
programs.
<P>
All of the competitive federal grants require very detailed applications,
are highly competitive, must be based upon solid prevention theory,
and must have elaborate evaluation plans. For most local prevention
programs, the type of evaluation required would require hiring
an outside evaluation consultant.
<P>
Most federal drug prevention grant awards are in the $100,000+
range. With the exception of the ACTION Drug Alliance Grants,
very few awards are for less than $50,000. Smaller grant requests
often are referred to block grant programs.
<P>
A few federal programs accept applications for review year-round
(although the reviews occur only three times per year), but most
have one application deadline per year. Application deadlines
are strictly enforced.
<P>
Federal grants usually require audited financial statements and
strict fiscal controls. Often, local prevention programs must
apply using a local government agency as the official applicant,
since most non-profit agencies do not have the level of financial
control required for federal grants.
<P>
Preparation of a federal grant proposal may take a first-time
applicant six to nine months of work. Since applications often
are accepted only once per year, a 12 to 18 month lead time from
starting the application to the time of the award would not be
unusual.
<P>
The Indiana Prevention Resource Center now provides intensive
grantwriting assistance to help local prevention programs prepare
applications for federal grants.
<P>
Most <B>state funding</B> for drug prevention activities involve
either state awards of federal block grant funding, or funds provided
under the <B>Drug-Free Indiana</B> program.
<P>
The <B>Drug-Free Indiana</B> grants are funded from fees collected
from defendants convicted of alcohol or drunk driving offenses.
Each person convicted is assessed a fee of $200, $90 of which
goes into a state-level fund and $90 of which goes into a local
fund. Each of these funds makes awards to local alcohol and other
drug programs in prevention and education, treatment, and law
enforcement.
<P>
All applications for Drug-Free Indiana funding must be reviewed
and prioritized by the appropriate Local Coordinating Council
(LCC) for each community being served. Local awards are made by
county governments based upon LCC recommendations. State-level
awards are made by the Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free Indiana,
in cooperation with other state agencies involved in alcohol and
other drug issues, based upon LCC and state-level review committee
recommendations. Some state awards are funded by the <B>Hoosier
Alliance Against Drugs</B>, again using the LCC review process
as the starting point.
<P>
Applicants seeking state grants should contact their Regional
Coordinating Office (RCO) of the Governor's Commission for a Drug-Free
Indiana for further information.
<P>
The Indiana Prevention Resource Center can provide some basic
assistance in locating state funding, but our intensive grantwriting
assistance program is limited to federal and foundation grant
applications.
<P>
In the next issue of <I>Prevention Newsline</I>, &quot;On Prevention&quot;
will focus on private sector funding.
<P>
<B>- William J. Bailey</B> 
</BODY>

