<HEAD>

<TITLE>Planning a "social" marketing campaign involves six steps 
</TITLE>


<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="William J. Bailey">
</HEAD>


<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">
<img src = "/graphics/newsline.gif" alt = "IPRC Newsline"><p>
Winter 1992<p>

<H1><B>In this issue:</A></B> </H1>

<H3><A HREF="#planning">Planning a &quot;social&quot; marketing campaign involves six steps</A>
</H3>

<H3><A HREF="#communication">Planning key to good communication research</A>
</H3>
<HR>

<a name="planning">
<H3>Planning a &quot;social&quot; marketing campaign involves
six steps </H3>

<H3>Prevention can learn from business</H3>

<P>
The Swedish Bikini Team, Spuds Mackenzie, Old Joe, &quot;Give
Me a Light&quot; or &quot;Tastes Great: Less Filling&quot; are
all familiar and powerful communication tools used to market legal
drugs -- alcohol and tobacco -- in the United States. The success
represented by these marketing campaigns depends on strategic
planning and research.
<P>
While such planning and research is routine in the marketing of
products and services by the private sector, only recently have
marketing concepts been applied to health and other social issues.
That application is referred to as &quot;social&quot; marketing,
which the United States Public Health Service began to use in
the 1980s when developing and reviewing campaigns for alcohol
and other drug prevention programs and messages. Social marketing
is now part of the technical assistance trainings and consultations
offered by the Office for Substance Abuse Prevention to communities
and agencies working in the alcohol and other drug use prevention
field.
<P>
When planning programs or awareness campaigns, it is essential
that an emphasis is placed on the audience's needs. Just as commercial
marketers take the time to know the audience so they can sell
beer or cigarettes, so must those in the alcohol and other drug
field get to know the audience. Programs and messages then can
be targeted specifically to the intended audience, and impact
of the programs or messages not only will be greater, but will
have a greater likelihood of having the desired impact.
<P>
To market alcohol and other drug prevention programs, the planner
should borrow the the four P's used by marketers: <B>product</B>,
<B>price</B>, <B>place </B>and <B>promotion</B>.
<P>
In health communications, these concepts take on the following
meanings:
<P>
<B>PRODUCT </B>is knowledge, attitudes or behavior you want the
audience to adopt.
<P>
<B>PRICE, </B>unlike in commercial marketing, is not monetary.
Instead price in health communication is what audience members
must give up to receive the program's benefits.
<P>
<B>PROMOTION </B>is the means for persuading the target audience
that the product is worth the price.
<P>
<B>PLACE </B>refers to how the message is disseminated, such as
through electronic or print media, billboards or community programs.
<P>
For example, the <B>product</B> a prevention program wants its
teen audience to adopt could be refusing to drink with peers.
The <B>price</B> for adopting that product could be the risk of
not fitting in with one's peers. <B>Promotion</B> could stress
that not drinking is &quot;smart&quot; behavior, and <B>place</B>
could be a mass media campaign.
<P>
Planning alcohol and other drug communication programs can be
broken down into six stages.
<P>
<B>STAGE 1: PLANNING AND SELECTING STRATEGY </B>
<P>
This stage provides the foundation for the entire social marketing
process. An assessment of the problem, the target<B> </B>audience
and the available resources is conducted before moving ahead.
During this planning process, the target audience should become
increasingly segmented. This segmentation will aid in the development
of appropriate messages. Goals and objectives for the program
will be developed at this time. These will shape the program as
planners progress through the stages.
<P>
<B>STAGE 2: SELECTING CHANNELS AND MATERIALS</B> 
<P>
Channels are how the message will be delivered, whether it be
face-to-face, group, mass media, community activities or a combination
of channels. The more channels selected, the more the target audience
will be exposed to the message. Determining the channel prior
to producing materials is important because different materials
work in different channels.
<P>
Material selection involves using what you have learned about
your target audience to your advantage. Time and money can be
saved by selecting materials that are specific to the audience
you are trying to reach. You would no more use coloring sheets
for adults than you would use a 10-page booklet filled with technical
terms for second graders.
<P>
When selecting materials, choose things that can be reproduced
within your budget in the needed quantity. A booklet with four-color
photographs might be terrific, but can you get out the same message
using two-color drawings?
<P>
Not all materials have to be developed from scratch; many free
materials are available to communities from a variety of organizations.
<P>
The Indiana Prevention Resource Center can serve as an excellent
source for prevention materials. In addition to the PRC's library
of print and audio-visual materials, the PRC serves as the state
RADAR site for Indiana. Bulk quantities of most materials produced
by the government are available in stock or can be ordered.
<P>
<B>STAGE 3: DEVELOPING MATERIALS AND PRETESTING</B> 
<P>
Begin by developing a draft of materials, then pretest them with
your target audience. Determine if materials get the intended
results, or revise them accordingly. This process should be repeated
until all involved are satisfied with the end product.
<P>
It is important to determine the number of times materials will
be pretested before being produced as final products, because
pretesting does add time to the project and does require some
expenses. It can, however, save money in the long run, helping
avoid the pitfalls of programs that spend their entire materials
budget on one great idea and produce materials, only to find that
the target audience does not understand the point of the materials.
<P>
<B>STAGE 4: IMPLEMENTING THE PROGRAM</B> 
<P>
All materials for the communication program should be ready and
available in sufficient quantities before the start of the program.
A method for tracking and evaluating the program should be in
place before the kick-off.
<P>
The tracking method will allow you not only to see where your
<P>
program is succeeding, but allow you to identify areas where changes
are needed. The most successful programs are always being updated
with current information about the program and about the target
audience.
<P>
The appropriate evaluation type to use is process evaluation,
which requires looking at the steps involved with the program,
such as the number of times a public-service announcement is aired,
the use of clipping services or an inventory of the materials
on hand.
<P>
It is during the implementation stage that the use of intermediaries
is effective. Intermediaries are those people who have contact
with and influence on your target audience, and can serve as spokespersons
for your program. The best intermediary will change with each
program and target audience, but intermediaries are generally
from outside your agency. If intermediaries' views are so different
from that of the program developer that despite their standing
with the target group, they will be detrimental to the goals of
the program, they probably should not be used.
<P>
<B>STAGE 5: ASSESSING EFFECTIVENESS</B> 
<P>
Assessment of the effectiveness of the program in this stage goes
beyond the process evaluation of the previous stage. Here, how
the program is affecting beliefs, attitudes and/or behaviors of
the target audience is measured. It is important to note that
<P>
evaluation of the program should be conceived during the initial
stage, although not conducted until this stage. The type of evaluation
conducted at this stage will depend upon several factors, including:
money, time, policies regarding the ability to gather information,
the level of support for evaluation and the overall design of
the program.
<P>
Four types of evaluation generally are used in health communications:
formative, process, outcome and impact.
<P>
<B>FORMATIVE EVALUATION </B>includes pretesting of materials and
is designed to test the strengths and weaknesses of a program
before it is ready for implementation. It is used in stages one
through three.
<P>
<B>PROCESS EVALUATION </B>basically reviews the tasks of implementing
the program.
<P>
<B>OUTCOME EVALUATION </B>is used to gather descriptive information.
It gathers information about knowledge and attitude changes, expressed
intentions of the target audience and the initiation of policy
changes.
<P>
<B>IMPACT EVALUATION</B>, which is the most comprehensive of the
four types of evaluation, focuses on the long-term outcomes of
the program. It measures such things as changes in morbidity and
mortality, long-term maintenance of behavior change and changes
in absenteeism from work or school. Impact evaluations are seldom
done for communication programs because of such factors as their
cost and/or the time it takes to conduct them. Impact evaluation
most often is used in a multi-faceted health-education program
that includes awareness, education, training and communication
programs.
<P>
<B>STAGE 6: REFINING THROUGH FEEDBACK</B> 
<P>
If the program is to be continued, revisions of the program should
be undertaken. If this is the end of the program, documentation
of what was learned should be made so as to assist others who
may undertake a similar project in the future. Whether the program
continues or ends, an evaluation report should be prepared. The
report may be formal and contain charts, graphs and materials
samples, or it may be as simple as a letter to the board or peers
in similar situations. The report can be used to secure funding
to continue the program, assist others conducting similar activities,
or help document that you have the ability to conduct programs.
<P>
The use of the six stages of health communication can be used
to break a large program into small manageable parts.
<P>
For a program to succeed and have an effect on alcohol and other
drug issues in a community, it must be planned for the target
audience, just as the tobacco and alcoholic beverage companies
plan their advertising programs around their target audiences.
<P>
If beer sales declined during campaigns featuring the Swedish
Bikini Team, Stroh Brewery Co. would not spend millions of dollars
a year researching and developing campaigns around the concept.
Therefore, it is important that those working to prevent illegal
alcohol and other drug use learn the lesson being taught by the
experts and use the same weapons: know your audience, identify
your product, determine the price, find a place and promote the
product.
<P>
<I>This article was compiled from materials provided by the Office
for Substance Abuse Presention Communications Training Team.</I>

<P>
<I>Seeking feedback an important part of communication</I> <HR>

<a name="communication">
<H3>Planning key to good communication research </H3>

<P>
Communication is <B>not</B> a one-way process. That's why communicating
prevention messages about illegal alcohol and other drug use must
involve more than simply sending messages. You -- the <B>sender</B>
-- must insure that your audience -- the <B>receiver</B> -- accurately
understands your message. You must pay attention to that part
of the communication process known as <B>feedback</B>. In other
words, you may need to do some research.
<P>
Research can range from informal chats with your program's patrons
to the kind of formal and systematic research program that is
favored by the corporate and academic worlds.
<P>
Successful businesses, in fact, spend millions of dollars to employ
their own research professionals or hire outside research firms
and consultants to monitor all aspects of business communications,
whether they be the messages sent by television commercials, highway
billboards, company letterhead or corporate news releases.
<P>
Although most prevention programs won't have the money or the
expertise to engage in the kind of systematic research used in
the corporate and academic realms, there are some research techniques
that can be borrowed successfully by prevention professionals.
And prevention programs should not overlook community resources
that can help with a communications research effort. Many college
business and communications faculty, for example, look for small
organizations that can provide real-world marketing research projects
for students.
<P>
However you obtain research, it's helpful to be informed about
the basics. What follows is a quick look at the research process,
and it is crucial to view research as a process involving several
steps, not as a quick fix. Four steps in marketing research are
outlined by authorities Philip Kotler, who is Harold T. Martin
Professor of Marketing at the Kellogg Graduate School of Management
at Chicago's Northwestern University, and Gary Armstrong, professor
of marketing in the School of Business Administration at the University
of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. Kotler and Armstrong's four
steps are:
<P>
<B>1. Defining the problem and research objectives.</B> 
<P>
<B>2. Developing the research plan.</B> 
<P>
<B>3. Implementing the research plan, collecting and analyzing
information.</B> 
<P>
<B>4. Interpreting and reporting the findings.</B> 
<P>
<B>DEFINE THE PROBLEM AND RESEARCH OBJECTIVES</B> 
<P>
This may be the hardest aspect of marketing research, but it's
also the most important. For instance, if you've tried several
new techniques to promote the services of your program but find
the use of those services is decreasing, you should decide what
you want to know before you spend time and/or money on research.
<P>
Do you want to explore whether your program might better serve
a different clientele? Do you want to describe the clientele your
program currently serves? Or do you want to learn what techniques
-- newspaper, radio, word-of-mouth, for example -- are best suited
for reaching your clientele? Defining your problem and the objectives
you want to achieve through re-
<P>
search will help insure the suc-
<P>
cess of that research, and ultimately the success of the messages
you communicate.
<P>
<B>DEVELOP THE</B> <B>RESEARCH PLAN</B> 
<P>
This is the point at which you identify what information is needed
to achieve your objectives and determine how it can be collected.
<P>
<B>1. Determine the specific information you need.</B> 
<P>
For instance, if your goal is to find out if your after-school
program is best serving elementary-school students in your community
who are at risk for alcohol and drug use, you may need several
kinds of information, such as: Where are the students who aren't
in your program currently going after school? Are their parents
interested in after-school programming for their children? How
could you reach those parents? What kinds of messages should you
be sending teachers and school administrators?
<P>
The answers you give to these questions will dictate the kind
of information you need to seek.
<P>
<B>2. Look for previously collected, or secondary, information
that will meet your needs.</B> 
<P>
Secondary information -- whether you find your organization already
has it or you have to search for it externally -- could include
government publications such as census and statistical reports,
or periodicals and books relevant to your topic.
<P>
The advantage of secondary information is its ability to provide
information you could not collect on your own because time, technique
or expense would make collecting the information a prohibitive
task for you.
<P>
One external source of secondary information not to overlook is
the Indiana Prevention Resource Center. We have useful materials
in our library, or our professional prevention staff members can
refer you to other sources of information.
<P>
<B>3. Plan to collect any additional, or primary, information
you need, using a single technique or a combination of technique,
including:</B> 
<P>
<B>a. Observation.</B> 
<P>
To use this research technique, identify the people, actions and
situations that are germane to your task and observe them. That
may mean observing the flow of traffic through the neighborhoods
where you plan to post billboards, counting the number of fliers
picked up by students who visit your booth at a school health
fair, or listening to the laughter or groans of an audience gathered
to watch a videotape.
<P>
Keep in mind that while observation can be relatively quick and
easy, it does not lend itself to all situations. Some things,
like attitudes or long-term response, can't be observed. Realize,
too, that the presence of an observer can affect the behavior
of people being observed.
<P>
<B>b. Mail, telephone or in-person surveys.</B> 
<P>
These can be structured mail surveys that pose formal lists of
questions or unstructured personal surveys that probe for issues
related to the research topic. Whatever form they take, surveys
are familiar to us all; they're the most frequently employed means
of gathering research information. Check the PRC library or your
local public or college library for the many books that can help
you assess such issues as the cost of different types of surveys
or the merits of using one type of question over another.
<P>
<B>c. Focus groups.</B> 
<P>
These are small gatherings of people who meet with a trained moderator
to share what they think about program themes, messages and products.
(To learn more about conducting focus groups, see the article
on page 6.)
<P>
<B>4. Present your plan to others for evaluation.</B> 
<P>
Discussing your proposed plan with others certainly will increase
the chance that you won't waste time and/or money on collecting
information that turns out to be inappropriate.
<P>
<B>IMPLEMENT THE RESEARCH PLAN, COLLECTING AND ANALYZING INFORMATION</B>

<P>
When you've prepared a plan and you know what information you
need, it's time to put your plan into action.
<P>
Because the actual collection of information can be the most expensive
phase of research, particularly if your research effort were to
involve a technique such as telephone interviews conducted by
an outside research firm, it's important that you monitor the
collection of information.
<P>
Analysis of information can be expensive, as well as time-consuming.
For example, analysis might involve coding and keying questionnaire
answers into a computer program that will allow the researcher
to tabulate and analyze results. Even if significant time and
money are not involved in the analysis phase, it's important that
analysis be done carefully.
<P>
<B>INTERPRET AND REPORT THE FINDINGS</B> 
<P>
At this point, you're ready to interpret what you've found and
draw conclusions. To guard against any of your own biases creeping
into your interpretations and conclusions, it's important that
you check your judgments with others. Checking your research with
others also can ensure you haven't overlooked key details in the
information you've collected.
<P>
Carefully planned research, whether low-budget efforts done by
volunteers or high-dollar systematic programs carried out by professionals,
will help you insure the effectiveness of the prevention messages
you communicate about illegal alcohol and other drug use.
<P>
<I>Information for this article was drawn from </I>Marketing:
An Introduction<I> by Philip Kotler and Gary Armstrong (1987,
Prentice-Hall, Inc.).</I> 
</BODY>

</HTML>

