<HEAD>

<TITLE>Resilience in action</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="William J. Bailey">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">

<img src = "/graphics/newsline.gif"><p>

Spring 1991<p>
<H1><B>In this issue: </A></B></H1>

<H3><A HREF="#resilience">Reilience in Action</A> </H3>

<H3><A HREF="#focus">Focus on Gateway Drugs</A> </H3>
<HR>

<a name="resilience">
<H3>Resilience in action </H3>

<P>
Resistance training builds resilience in youth
<P>
Resilient children are like the watches in the old Timex commercials
- &quot;they take a licking and keep on ticking.&quot;
<P>
We can build resilience - the ability to avoid problems despite
exposure to overwhelming &quot;risk factors&quot; - by exposing
youth to programs that emphasize &quot;protective factors.&quot;
Protective factors may include strong role models, educational
success, family bonds, and skills to resist peer and social pressures.
<P>
Teaching specific social skills about how to resist peer and social
pressures to use alcohol and other drugs is an important resilience-
building strategy. Youth need to learn how to &quot;say no&quot;
without losing friends and how to avoid being influenced by social
pressures such as those exerted by the advertising, news media
and entertainment industries. Curricula that develop resilience
through protective factors are in place in several Indiana schools.
<P>
In Indiana, <B>PROJECT I-STAR</B> and <B>D.A.R.E.</B> are two
such programs that develop personal and social skills to help
children cope with pressures to use alcohol and other drugs. Both
PROJECT I-STAR (Indiana Students Taught Awareness and Resistance)
and D.A.R.E. (Drug Abuse Resistance Education) target children
making the transition from elementary school to junior-high school.
D.A.R.E. is presented to students in fifth and/or sixth grade
who will enter junior high the following year, while I-STAR is
presented in the first two years of junior high, generally grades
seven and eight.
<P>
<B>Project I-STAR</B>, modeled after California's <B>Project SMART</B>,
was developed by the University of California's Institute for
Health Promotion and Disease Prevention Research to provide a
school and community approach in the prevention of alcohol and
other drug abuse among youth. In 1987, working cooperatively with
Lilly Endowment, Inc., Marion County Public Schools established
Project I-STAR, which began as the <B>Project STAR</B> curriculum
Kansas City schools patterned after California's Project SMART.
<P>
In 1990, Project I-Star received the United States Secretary of
Health and Human Services Excellence in Prevention Award and the
American Medical Association's Adolescent Health Congress Award.
<P>
I-STAR is a school-based program designed to involve an entire
community. The program encourages involvement of local media,
businesses, religious groups, youth agencies, government, medical
institutions and parent groups. A parents' committee is established
in each I-STAR school to support the program's goals. Through
these committees, prevention messages from the curriculum are
passed on to other parents and community members. Parental involvement
also is solicited through student homework assignments in the
I-STAR curriculum. Assignments are designed for parent and child
to work on together, and when an assignment is completed, both
parent and child sign it before it is turned in at school.
<P>
The I-STAR curriculum can be integrated into most subject areas,
including science, health, social studies or language arts. A
special supplement is available to teachers who work with special-needs
students.
<P>
Regular classroom teachers, who attend a training workshop before
teaching the program, present the curriculum to students in two
parts. Part I is<B> </B>presented in the first year and consists
of 13 sessions, including sessions such as &quot;Techniques to
Say 'No,'&quot; &quot;Peer Pressure Resistance,&quot; &quot;Advertising
Influences&quot; and &quot;Developing Friendships.&quot; Part
II is presented the following year. After a review of the previous
year is conducted, Part II sessions focus on such topics as &quot;Problem
Solving,&quot; &quot;Refusal Skills&quot; and &quot;Family Interaction
Skills.&quot;
<P>
Before the beginning of each session, students from each class
are chosen to participate in skill leaders training and serve
as leaders for their classes. As skill leaders, students assist
their teachers in demonstrating skills being addressed in each
session. In addition, because one of the most powerful influences
on anyone, especially youth, is the behavior and attitudes of
peers, the positive attitudes and actions of Skill Leaders expose
students in I-STAR classes to positive peer pressure.
<P>
Evaluation of Projects I-STAR and STAR has been extensive, and
is funded by a multi-million dollar federal research grant.
<P>
Project I-STAR currently is being conducted in 93 schools in the
Indianapolis metropolitan area. Every public and private school
in Marion County and most parochial schools offer I-STAR as part
of a drug-education curriculum. I-STAR also is operating in several
schools in counties surrounding Indianapolis and is available
to any school in Indiana. For more information, contact Project
I-STAR at 5559 W. 73rd St., Indianapolis, IN 46268.
<P>
<B>D.A.R.E., </B>which also evolved from Project SMART, traces
much of its success to the use of uniformed law-enforcement officers
in the classroom. The D.A.R.E. curriculum is taught by veteran
officers who have completed 80 hours of intensive training. The
officers are assisted by classroom teachers, who remain in the
classroom and help with activities.
<P>
The program's curriculum and training resulted from a cooperative
effort of the Los Angeles Police Department and the Los Angeles
Unified School District. The program now has spread across the
United States and currently has five regional training sites.
It is expected that more sites will be established over the next
few years. In Indiana, 50 law-enforcement agencies currently provide
D.A.R.E. programs.
<P>
The D.A.R.E. curriculum is targeted to the fifth and/or sixth
graders who will enter junior high the following year and includes
17 45- to 50-minute lessons, which are highly structured and build
upon one another. Lesson topics include &quot;Practices for Personal
Safety,&quot; &quot;Resistance Techniques,&quot; &quot;Building
Self-Esteem,&quot; &quot;Media Influences,&quot; &quot;Role Modeling&quot;
and &quot;Ways to Deal with Pressures from Gangs.&quot;
<P>
Lessons in the D.A.R.E. program are designed to teach students
the social skills necessary to recognize and resist influences
and other pressures experienced when making personal choices.
While building refusal skills is integral to the program, developing
self-esteem, decision-making skills, critical thinking and communication
skills also are emphasized.
<P>
The same officer conducts all D.A.R.E. sessions in a particular
class. In addition to the time spent with the class during lesson
time, the officer also spends time with students during lunch
and recess. This way, the officer is able to relate to students
in a non-threatening situation, and when students see the officer
outside school they are able to relate to him or her as a respected
authority figure they know personally, not just as another person
enforcing rules.
<P>
D.A.R.E. ends with a schoolwide assembly in which all students
participating in the program receive a certificate of completion.
<P>
Program activities include the use of student leaders from area
high schools. These students, who do not use drugs, have been
identified by teachers and fellow students as being admired and
respected. The high-school students serve as role models for students
in the D.A.R.E. program.
<P>
An advisory group has been formed in Indiana to examine the how
best to coordinate D.A.R.E. throughout the state. Representatives
from local, county and state law-enforcement agencies, education
and business are included in the group. For more information about
starting a D.A.R.E. program, contact local law-enforcement agencies.
<P>
The 4th Indiana Prevention Conference - &quot;STRONG FENCES: Building
Resilience in Youth and Communities&quot; - will feature workshop
sessions about both programs.
<P>
<B>Some information for this article was taken from &quot;Resilience
Among High Risk Youth&quot; by Kevin McIntyre, Douglas White and
Richard Yoast. Wisconsin Clearinghouse. 1990.</B> <HR>

<a name="focus">
<H3>Focus on &quot;gateway drugs&quot; Non-smoking youth better
resist other drugs</H3>

<P>
Cigarette smoke contains hundreds of harmful chemicals, but none
of them cause smokers to try other drugs. It isn't the chemicals
that make tobacco a &quot;gateway drug,&quot; it's worse!
<P>
Gateway drugs are drugs that serve as almost essential precursors
to use of other drugs, such as marijuana, heroin and cocaine.
In other words, use of gateway drugs serves as the &quot;gate&quot;
or path that almost always precedes the use of the other drugs
and leads to the drug-using lifestyle. Heroin addicts rarely,
if ever, start out using heroin - they start with gateway drugs
and then move on to the heroin.
<P>
But the link between the gateway drug and the other drug is not
biochemical. The gateway drugs serve as social and psychological
precursors to the use of other drugs. The decisions to use the
tobacco or other gateway drugs set up <B>patterns of behavior</B>
that make it easier for a user to go on to the other drugs. It
is the series of decisions made by the smoker that make decisions
to use other drugs easier. Social psychologists refer to this
phenomenon as a &quot;developmental progression.&quot; Students
who decide to accept the risks of smoking later find it much easier
to accept the risks of using other drugs.
<P>
On the other hand, students who make conscious decisions to avoid
smoking tobacco because of the health risks are very unlikely
to make a decision to smoke marijuana, because accepting the health
risks of marijuana smoking would be psychologically inconsistent.
<P>
While the link is not biochemical, it is powerful nonetheless.
How powerful is the influence of a gateway drug? In 1987, a research
team at the University of Michigan's Institute for Social Research
found that among high-school seniors, daily cigarette smokers
were <B>10 times more likely to use cocaine</B> regularly than
were seniors who never had smoked regularly! Students who never
smoked were much less likely to experiment with controlled substances
and very unlikely to use them regularly. Nearly one-fourth of
the seniors who smoked cigarettes daily had used cocaine in the
month before the survey! (Johnston, <U>et al.</U>, 1987)
<P>
The Michigan study examined five different levels of smoking history
and use of 15 different drugs. The evidence was overwhelming that
cigarette-smoking high-school seniors were much more likely to
use controlled substances (but only slightly more likely to use
alcohol) than were non-smoking students.
<P>
The link is dose-related - the more cigarettes a student smoked,
the more likely he or she was to use marijuana and cocaine. For
example, while less than 4 percent of the high-school seniors
who never had smoked tried cocaine one or more times during their
senior year of high school, more than 40 percent of the seniors
who smoked a pack a day or more had tried cocaine during the year.
Only 7.2 percent of non-smoking seniors used marijuana during
the month before the survey, as compared with 59 percent of the
pack-a-day smokers. (More detailed data is provided in the charts
that accompany this article.)
<P>
Unlike in the 1960s and 1970s, when older teens and adults sometimes
took up smoking, virtually all new smokers in the 1990s begin
experimenting with tobacco in the late elementary grades and progressively
acquire the addiction before age 16. It has been suggested that
if a child doesn't experiment with tobacco before age 13, he or
she is unlikely ever to try it.
<P>
According to U.S. Secretary of Health and Human Services Louis
Sullivan, the tobacco industry must gain 5,000 new smokers every
day just to maintain a level number of customers, because about
1,300 of its best customers die each day from smoking, another
200 die from other causes, and about 3,500 smokers quit. Because
the only &quot;new&quot; smokers are children, the industry must
entice at least 5,000 additional pre-teens to try its product
every single day.
<P>
If the only risk to these pre-teens was addiction to tobacco and
the resulting health consequences, that would be bad enough. But
if one-half of those kids go on to try cocaine -- and one-third
will use illegal drugs every month by the time they are seniors
in high school -- the results of that enticement are even more
unconscionable.
<P>
Prevention of controlled substance use begins with prevention
of tobacco and other gateway drug use.
<P>
If we hope to reduce the use of marijuana and cocaine in the next
decade's high- school students, we must reduce the use of tobacco
in this decade's elementary-school students. A tobacco-free lifestyle
serves as a powerful protective factor against abuse of controlled
substances.
<P>
It is essential that today's elementary-school students learn
the risks of tobacco use and skills for avoiding the peer and
social pressures that encourage them to experiment.
<P>
<B>--William J. Bailey</B> 
<P>
<U><B>Reference</B></U> 
<P>
Johnston, L.D., O'Malley, P.M., and Bachman, J.G., <U>National
Trends in Drug Use and Related Factors Among American High School
Students and Young Adults, 1975-1986,</U> National Institute on
Drug Abuse, DHHS Pub. No. (ADM) 87-1535, Washington: USGPO, 1987.

</BODY>

