<HTML>
<title>IPRC - Alcohol, Disinhibition, Sexual Arousal, and Deviant...
</title>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h3><i>Re-posted by the Indiana Prevention Resource Center at Indiana University</i><br>
Indiana's <b>RADAR Network</b> State Center<br></h3>

<HR>
<IMG SRC = "a1.gif">

<H2>Alcohol, Disinhibition, Sexual Arousal, and Deviant Sexual Behavior</H2>reprinted from <b><i>Alcohol, Health and Research World</i></b>
<I>
<H3>William H. George, Ph.D., and Jeanette Norris, Ph.D. </H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>William H. George Ph.D., is an associate professor, State University of New York at Buffalo, New York.<BR>
Jeannette Norris, Ph.D., is a research scientist at the Alcohol and Drug Abuse Institute, University of Washington, Seattle, Washington.</I></BLOCKQUOTE>

<HR>
<P><B>The relationship between a person's consumption of alcohol and subsequent disinhibition of sexual behavior is strong, although not well understood.  Studies have found that for men, the mere expectancy that drinking has occurred can enhance arousal and disinhibition.</B></P>
<HR>

<P>In settings ranging from candlelight dinners to drunken debaucheries, alcohol has been depicted as a solvent of sexual inhibitions.  Studies of beliefs and experiences have attested to the pervasiveness of the view that alcohol provokes and heightens sexual responsiveness (Athanasiou et al. 1970; Brown et al. 1980).  Yet the relationship between drinking and sexuality is far more complex than that defined by this simple formula:<BR><BR>
<CENTER><B>Alcohol input  ---&#62;  sexual output.</B></CENTER>
<P>And this complexity is found in the relationship between alcohol consumption and sexual responsiveness to both deviant and nondeviant sexual materials.</P>

<P>The relationship between alcohol consumption and responses to deviant erotica is of particular interest and is the main topic of this article.  Much research has demonstrated an association between the reading or viewing of violent pornography and rape-supportive attitudes and behaviors in normal males (Malamuth and Donnerstein 1984).  However, controversy surrounds this issue because the exact nature of the relationship has not been established.  The connection between alcohol and deviant sexual material may be important because of alcohol's strong link to sexual responding.</P>

<HR>
<H3> ALCOHOL AND SEXUAL AROUSAL</H3>

<P>The relationship between alcohol and sex is complex in part because the individual's responses to alcohol and to sexual stimuli involve complex psychological and physiological processes.  Alcohol seems to have the paradoxical effects of enhancing and suppressing sexual responses, with the two effects reflecting the two processes.</P>

<P>There is an inverse relationship between the amount of alcohol consumed and the level of physical sexual arousal; that is, as the concentration of alcohol in the blood increases, sexual arousal diminishes.  Several studies have shown that penile response decreases with increases in blood alcohol concentration (BAC) in a linear fashion (Briddell and Wilson 1976; Farkas and Rosen 1976).  Also, the time required for men to achieve orgasm during masturbation increases as BAC increases (Malatesta et al. 1979).  Exceptions to the pattern of suppression of penile response have been observed at low BACs. </P>

<P>With women, a similar pattern emerges: increases in BAC have been associated with diminishing vaginal arousal (Wilson and Lawson 1978) and increases in the time required to attain orgasm (Malatesta et al. 1982).  That acute alcohol consumption suppresses the physical sexual response of both men and women is the clearest and most robust finding in alcohol-sex research.</P>

<P>On the other hand, subjective sexual arousal is affected not only by blood alcohol concentration but also by a person's beliefs about the effects of alcohol.  That is, expectancies about the relationship between alcohol and sex generated by the culture influence how a person believes he or she will respond to sexual stimuli.</P>

<P>A methodological technique known as the balanced placebo design (BPD) has been helpful in elucidating the psychology of drinking.  The BPD compares the independent and interactive influences of alcohol's physiological and psychological effects.  The technique manipulates two factors in drinking:  perceived alcohol content, which is known as the expectancy set, and actual alcohol content.  Participants in BPD studies are led to expect that they will be given either alcoholic or nonalcoholic drinks;  then within those two groups, half again either receive alcohol or do not (Figure 1).  Thus, the BPD creates four groups:  subjects who expect alcohol and receive alcohol, subjects who expect alcohol and do not receive it, subjects who do not expect alcohol and who do not receive it, and subjects who do not expect alcohol yet do receive it.  An important shortcoming of the BPD is that it necessarily limits the alcohol dosage to relatively low levels.  Despite this and other shortcomings, BPD studies have divulged much about alcohol's effects on men (Knight et al. 1986; Collins and Searles 1988).</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="graph1.gif">
<H5>Figure 1<BR>
In experiments involving the balanced placebo design, four<BR>different groups of subjects are tested.  This allows researchers<BR>to judge the effects of expectancies about alcohol in addition<BR>to actual effects of alcohol.</BLOCKQUOTE></H5>

<P>In these studies, the men expecting to receive alcohol -- irrespective of whether or not they did receive it -- have exhibited greater penile responses (Wilson and Lawson 1976; Briddell et al. 1978) and subjective arousal (Lang et al. 1980; George and Marlatt 1986).  Men who expect alcohol also have chosen to spend more time watching erotic slides (George and Marlatt 1986) 0and waiting to be shown erotic films (Abrams and Wilson 1983).  In one study, the expectancy set increased the length of time subjects chose to view erotica, but only for subjects who had a high degree of guilt about sex (Lang et al. 1980).  Such enhancements of sexual responsiveness based on the expectancy set have not been duplicated in studies employing erotic materials with low arousal potential (McCarty et al, 1982) and studies in which exposure to erotica was accompanied by competing processes such as divided attention tasks or instruction that counter arousal (Lansky and Wilson 1981; Wilson and Niaura 1984; Wilson et al. 1985).  In sum, the expectation that one has consumed low dosages of alcohol has been found to enhance, in men, penile tumescence, subjective arousal, and the tendency to read or view pornography.</P>

<P>BPD studies of women have been less revealing.  Only a few studies have employed female subjects, and these have produced confusing results.  Wilson and Lawson (1978) found that the expectancy set did not affect vaginal arousal, while alcohol content reduced arousal.  However, subjective arousal in women did correlate positively with the level of intoxication.  Although both women and men are known to expect that alcohol heightens sexual response, women's responses in BPD studies have borne this out less well than have men's responses.</P>

<P>One explanation for the difference in the responses of the genders has been suggested by studies of social anxiety.  These BPD studies involve cross-gender social processes that have an indirect bearing on the link between alcohol and sexuality.  To induce anxiety in subjects, researchers tell them that they will have to impress judges of the opposite sex who will evaluate their attractiveness.  Under such conditions, the alcohol expectancy set reduced anxiety (Wilson and Abrams 1977) and increased self-disclosure (Caudill et al. 1987) in men, but had opposite effects on women (Abrams and Wilson 1979; Caudill et al. 1987).  Exit interviews revealed that women who expected to receive alcohol worried that men might misinterpret their actions.  This concern agrees with the timeless warning for women to exercise more care when drinking with men so as to guard against undesired sexual advances.  It would have made them more anxious and less self-disclosing.  An implication of this interpretation is that men and women differ in their sexual responses to the alcohol expectancy set partly because they experience different degrees of inhibition (Lang 1985; Crowe and George 1989).  In addition to inhibitory concerns that might weigh against a drinking man's sexual expression (for example, sexually transmitted diseases),  concerns such as contraception, social stigmatization, and sexual and nonsexual victimization exist for a drinking woman (Fillmore 1985; also see the article by Blume, pp. 139-146).  Thus, the alcohol expectancy set should create less sexual enhancement for women than for men.</P>

<P>Men's responses in BPD studies have agreed with the belief that alcohol enhances sexual behavior.  And the responses seem consistent with the idea that men have learned to view men and women drinking together as a potential sexual situation in which men have an exploitable advantage.  Women's behavior in BPD studies suggests, on the surface, that they have learned to view men and women drinking together as a potentially disadvantageous situation, that is, as a possible prelude to undesired sexual advances.</P>

<P>To summarize, alcohol has been found to have paradoxical effects on sexual arousal.  Increasing doses of alcohol suppress physiological signs of arousal for both men and women.  On the other hand, the alcohol expectancy set enhances physical and subjective signs of arousal in men but not in women.  Therefore, culturally transmitted beliefs and expectations can exert a powerful influence over sexuality in drinking situations.  These cultural processes become more important with respect to disinhibition of deviant sexual behavior.<P>

<HR>
<H3>DISINHIBITION AND DEVIANT SEXUAL BEHAVIOR</H3>

<P>Does alcohol disinhibit deviant sexual behavior?  Gossip, crime and news stories, and fictional accounts would indicate that an affirmative answer to this question is a foregone conclusion.  Scientific research has yielded ambiguous conclusions.</P>

<P>Even the definitions of deviance and disinhibition are unclear.  Obviously, that which is judged to be deviant varies across cultures.  Similarly, disinhibition is interpreted differently in different cultures.  Inhibitions typically are considered standards for acceptable behavior which are transmitted by the culture and internalized by the individual.  Because the adequacy of such transmission and internalization is never known precisely and because the mechanics of disinhibition are not visible, the judgment that disinhibition has occurred requires a fair degree of inference and subjectivity.  The grayness of such judgments, coupled with expectations about alcohol's powers, yields a wide berth for blaming sexual misbehaviors on alcohol rather than the person.  It is accordingly not surprising that perpetrators of illegal sexual acts such as rape and incest later blame alcohol (Scully and Marolla 1984; Williams and Finkelhor 1990).</P>

<P>Cultural processes shape the definitions of deviance, the inhibitions that alcohol presumably loosens, and the judgements that disinhibition has occurred.  In a blow to the intuitive wisdom that alcohol disinhibits deviant behavior solely by virtue of its drug action, MacAndrew and Edgerton (1969) argued that alcohol's effects across and within cultures are too variable to be completely explained by pharmacology.  Likewise, there is high variability across and within individuals.  Therefore, any general rule or theory attempting to link alcohol with deviance must also assign importance to situational and predispositional factors as well as cultural factors.  The cumulative weight of these factors is significant and will forever argue against any simplistic alcohol-causes-deviance assertion.</P>

<P>Nevertheless, careful experimentation has been applied to investigating the role of alcohol in the disinhibition of deviant sexual behavior in men.  In one of the aforementioned BPD studies, it was found that heterosexual men who expected to receive alcohol became more aroused by films of explicit heterosexual activity than did men who expected no alcohol (Wilson and Lawson 1976).  This study also found that the expectancy-set effect occurred and was even more pronounced when the subjects were shown films of homosexual activities.  Although there is no inherent deviance in homosexual activity, genital arousal in heterosexual men shown portrayals of homosexual activity might be construed as out of character.  The results led the researchers to speculate that the expectancy set provided subjects with an excuse for sexual arousal that might otherwise be judged unacceptable by the self and by others.  This apparent exploitation of alcohol's excuse value under laboratory conditions agrees with excuse seeking by sexual deviates such as rapists (Scully and Marolla 1984).</P>

<P>Briddell and co-workers (1978) performed a study in which subjects listened to audiotapes depiciting consenting heterosexual intercourse and forcible rape.  Despite some shortcomings (Barbaree 1990), the study revealed that the alcohol expectancy set increased penile responses.  The effect was more pronounced during exposure to depicitions of rape than during exposure to depicitions of intercourse.  Presumably, the deviant nature of the rape created a greater need for alcohol's excuse-conferring properties.</P>

<P>Because deviance is in the eye of the beholder, the alcohol excuse should also have greater utility for some people than for others.  Lang and co-workers (1980) investigated whether men who are more inclined to feel guilty about sexuality would be affected more by the alcohol expectancy set than would others.  The researchers instructed subjects in the use of a slide projector and then allowed the subjects to watch and rate a series of erotic slides on their own.  Unbeknown to the subjects, the slide exposure times were measured and considered as a behavioral index of the subjects' interest in erotica.  The alcohol expectancy set was found to have no effect on subjects with low or moderate guilt about sexuality.  However, among subjects with high degrees of guilt about sexuality, the men with the expectancy set viewed erotic longer than did the men who did not expect alcohol.  This effect of the expectancy set with high-guilt men became more pronounced as the pornographic content of the slides increased.  Because the level of sex guilt or inhibition was determined prior to the experiment, this study provides the best evidence for a process of disinhibition.  And again, the disinhibitory agent was the alcohol expectancy set, not alcohol.</P>

<P>In a study in which subjects were not preselected based on guilt about sexuality, George and Marlatt (1986) measured interest in viewing violence, erotic, and violent erotica.  Men expecting to receive alcohol chose to view more of the material than did men not expecting alcohol.  Again, this expectancy-set effect became more pronounced with the viewing of more deviant erotica.  Also, for men shown slides of violent erotica, the expectancy-set effect was greatest with the most deviant subset of those slides.</P>

<P>In a recent extension of this work, men were allowed to view erotica at the same time that an unseen and unknown partner viewed it (George et al. 1990).  The subject and partner were both served drinks that ostensibly could contain alcohol, although no alcohol was actually served.  Under these conditions, the expectancy set about the partner's drinking was most influential in determining the subject's behavior.  Subjects spent more time viewing erotica when they thought the other person had consumed alcohol.  Moreover, this expectancy-set effect concerning the other person increased as the explicitness and deviance of the viewed material increased.  That is, the difference between the amount of erotica viewed with drinking versus with nondrinking partners widened with more deviant erotica.</P>

<P>These experiments convey a distinct impression:  men behave as though alcohol excuses deviant sexual indulgence.  Futhermore, the use of alcohol as an alibi becomes more apparent when the usefulness of the alcohol excuse is heightened either by virtue of the person's standards or by virtue of the deviance of the indulgence.  Not all studies have fit these patterns (Barbaree et al. 1983); nevertheless, the consistency in the five studies mentioned here is striking when considered alongside the ambiguity inherent in the area of alcohol, disinhibition, and deviance.</P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="graph2.gif">
<IMG SRC="graph3.gif">
</CENTER>
<H5><BLOCKQUOTE>In controlled studies of the effcts of alcohol on sexuality, subjects' responses are determined by self-reports (above) or by instruments that measure physiological arousal.  Photographs courtesy of G.A. Marlatt.</BLOCKQUOTE></H5>

<HR>
<H3>DISCUSSION</H3>

<P>Again, does alcohol disinhibit deviant sexual behavior?  Research based on the balanced placebo design suggests that there is a relationship between learned associations about alcohol's effects and disinhibition of deviant and nondeviant sexual behavior in men.  However, this relationship is so fraught with complexities and qualifying circumstances that it is difficult to decipher its true nature.  Is it causal, correlational, or coincidental?  That is, does alcohol cause disinhibition to occur or does it just look that way because (a) people who engage in deviant sex drink more in general, (b) deviance and drinking are both caused by a third variable such as a personality or dispositional factor, or (c) both are caused by social (for example, permissiveness) or environmental features common to the settings where drinking and deviance occur?  Perhaps some combination of these scenarios exists. </P>

<P>Within the smaller scope of data from experiments in which it is assumed that a casual relationship exists, information has been gained.  At low dosages of alcohol, the belief that alcohol has been consumed promotes indulgence in deviant sexual behavior for men.  According to a number of researchers, this effect seems due to a "discriminative disengagement of self-evaluative processes"  (Marlatt and Rohsenow 1980; Wilson 1981; Lang 1985; Hull and Bond 1986; Crowe and George 1989).  Men behave as though they have an internal censor that normally guards against deviant sexual expression.  Consequently, this censorship becomes muted when men are convinced that they have been drinking.</P>

<P>This alcohol-as-excuse explanation of a casual link between alcohol and deviant sexual behavior has intuitive appeal, but is not fully satisfying for several reasons.  First, it is based on data from only male subjects.  This is partly defensible  because men are most often the perpetrators of sex crimes.  However, from a scientific perspective, overreliance on male data restricts and potentially distorts construction of a theory.</P>

<P>Second, the best support is from BPD data, in which the alcohol dosage is restricted to low levels.  Events such as sex crimes, which involve using alcohol as an excuse, typically also involve greater consumption of alcohol.  An explanation of disinhibition that does not incorporate the full range of alcohol dosages is therefore incomplete.</P>

<P>Third, the excuse explanation rests on some underlying assumptions that have not been confirmed.  It assumes that men consider alcohol consumption to be a viable excuse for deviant sexual indulgence, and that once drinking commences, this expectancy influences their behavior.  While questionnaires have established that people generally believe alcohol enhances or disinhibits sexuality (Brown et al. 1980), studies have not established that people endorse alcohol's excuse-conferring properties.  In addition, there is only modest support for the idea that a previously held expectancy about alcohol can affect behavior after drinking (George et al. 1989).</P>

<P>Finally, the excuse explanation implies that there exists a motivation to drink prior to an opportunity to indulge in deviant sexual behavior.  In such circumstances, a person wishing to indulge will drink in order to excuse later disinhibition.  Anecdotal reports support this idea.  However, when tested experimentally, this hypothesis has received modest support or no support (George et al. 1988; Skinner and George 1988 <I>a,b;</I> Skinner unpublished data 1991).</P>

<HR>
<H3>ALCOHOL MYOPIA</H3>

<P>In an alternative explanation of alcohol's contribution to disinhibition, Steele and colleagues emphasize the importance of alcohol's physiological effects (Steele and Southwick 1985; Steele and Josephs 1990).  Their theory is based on evidence that alcohol impairs attention, cognition, and information processing.  It proposes that a person is more likely to exhibit a socially "excessive" behavior when intoxicated, if the behavior ordinarily is one that presents a conflict.  By decreasing the person's ability to process information, alcohol eliminates the conflict the person would experience related to the behavior.  This is referred to as alcohol myopia, and, supposedly, greater intoxication leads to greater myopia which leads to greater disinhibition.  A clear advantage of this alcohol-myopia explanation is that it extends to situations involving higher dosages of alcohol -- the most problematic episodes of alcohol-related disinhibition involve high dosages.</P>

<P>Combining the alcohol-myopia model with the excuse explanation may yield a more satisfying account of sexual disinhibition following drinking.  It is conveivable that when alcohol is consumed in low dosages, a person exploits the alcohol excuse to lead to sexual disinhibition.  When alcohol is consumed in higher dosages (although not so high as to suppress sexual arousal completely), alcohol myopia becomes alcohol's main contribution to sexual disinhibition.</P>

<HR>
<H3>CONCLUSIONS</H3>

<P>Alcohol and sexuality are closely linked in this culture.  A casual description of this link is that alcohol has powerful aphrodisiac properties that can be used wittingly or unwittingly to encourage the reluctant mate or to unleash deviant sexual desires.  Studies have revealed that the relationship between alcohol and sexuality is very complex.  Alcohol can influence the expression of deviant and nondeviant sexual behavior; however, this influence is shaped by numerous qualifying conditions, such as dosage, gender, and expectancy.</P>

<HR>
