<BLOCKQUOTE>This quarterly newsletter highlights issues concerning gays and lesbians and ATOD.  Upcoming conferences and events for people in the field; articles about health issues, including addiction and HIV; and book reviews are included in each issue.  Each issue ends with stories of ATOD professionals who are making a difference in the gay and lesbian communities.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Getting Sober, Getting Well:  A Treatment for Caregivers Who Work with Women</B><BR>
Date:  1990<BR>
Format:  Book<BR>
Length:  633 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Intervention and Treatment<BR>
Target Audience:  Alcohol and Other Drug Treatment Professionals and Health Care Providers<BR>
Setting:  Community Organization and Health Care<BR>
Readability:  Difficult<BR>
Availability:  Women's Alcoholism Program of CASPER, 6 Camelia Avenue, Cambridge, MA 02139 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This book is a guide for training caregivers for treating substance-abusing women.  It is divided into two sections:  getting sober and getting well.  The first section contains 10 sessions on topics, such as physiology concerns, barriers to treatment, and prescription drug abuse.  Section two has 17 sessions covering violence against straight, lesbian, and homeless women.  Each session consists of an overview of the situation, staff training activities, client treatment activities, resources, and handouts.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lesbian and Gay Issues in Early Recovery</B><BR>
Year:  1987<BR>
Format:  Pamphlet<BR>
Length:  26 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Gays and Lesbians and Alcohol and Other Drugs<BR>
Target Audience:  Gays and Lesbians<BR>
Setting:  Prevention and Treatment Professionals, Gays, and Lesbians<BR>
Readability:  Difficult<BR>
Availability:  Hazelden Foundation, Pleasant Valley Road, Box 176, Center City, MN 55012-0176, 800-328-9000
<BLOCKQUOTE>Gays and lesbians with alcohol and other drug problems face two major issues:  recovery from a chronic disease and society's homophobia.  This pamphlet identifies and discusses issues related to gays and lesbians in treatment and early recovery.  It also helps those who are AOD-dependent recognize that, although they can be negatively affected by societal attitudes, as recovering people they can claim personal power by initiating healthy changes in their lives.  Resources for more information are listed.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Gay and Lesbian Alcoholics:  AA's Message of Hope</B><BR>
Year:  1980<BR>
Format:  Pamphlet<BR>
Length:  13 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Gays and Lesbians and Alcohol and Other Drugs<BR>
Target Audience:  Gays and Lesbians<BR>
Setting:  Community and Health Care<BR>
Readability:  Difficult<BR>
Availability:  Hazelden Foundation, Pleasant Valley Road, Box 176, Center City, MN 55012-0176, 800-328-9000
<BLOCKQUOTE>Many lesbians and gays in AA feel they are a &quotminority inside a minority.&quot They need the fellowship and example of men and women who have achieved good, healthy, gay sobriety.  They feel complete acceptance only where their lifestyle can be affirmed in all honesty and openness.  The pamphlet answers questions about AA groups for gays and lesbians and lists AA's 12 Steps.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>I Wish We Had Listened:  A Gay Man's Story about AIDS</B><BR>
Year:  1993<BR>
Format:  Booklet<BR>
Length:  7 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  Sr. High Youth, Young Adults, and Gays<BR>
