<IMG SRC="lgbsl.gif"><BR><A NAME="Sec2"> <H2>ATOD Resource Guide: Lesbians, Gay Men, and Bisexuals<BR> Section 2 -- Studies, Articles, & Reports </H2></A>
<H3>Government Publications and Journal Articles </H3></BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Violence Toward Homosexuals:  Experts Recommend Research on Consequences of <BR>
<I>Sargent, M. </I></B><BR>
<I>ADAMHA News </I>August 1989, pp. 9-10
<BLOCKQUOTE>Homosexuals who are victims of violence are said to suffer from &quotPost Traumatic Stress Disorder Plus&quot (PTSD+).  The disorder is manifested by symptoms, such as an inability to concentrate, loss of trust in others, startle reactions, depression, anxiety, nightmares, and eating and sleeping problems.  Homosexuals who have been victims of violence appear to be at a high risk for alcoholism, drug abuse, and suicide -- all ways to escape pain.  Recommendations include studies to decide the prevalence of anti-homosexual violence, its risk factors, the types of mental health consequences experienced by victims, their coping skills, and services needs.  Studies are suggested also on the training needs and characteristics of service providers in the mental health and criminal justice fields.  Preventive efforts, such as educational programs for potential perpetrators of violence, including teenagers and family members, are recommended also.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Stress, Expectancies, and Vulnerability to Substance Abuse:  Test of a Model among Homosexual Men<BR>
<I>McKirnan, D.J., and Peterson, P.L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Abnormal Psychology </I>97(4):461-466, 1988<BR>
(Available from David J. McKirnan, Department of Psychology m/c 285, Box 4348, University of Illinois at Chicago, Chicago, IL 60680.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Researchers hypothesize that specific attitudes or expectancies make people vulnerable to responding to stress with alcohol or other drugs.  This &quotstress-vulnerability&quot model was tested among homosexual men who show elevated rates of substance abuse and have culturally specific stressors and vulnerability.  Tension reduction expectancies of alcohol effects had a substantial effect on alcohol and marijuana/drug abuse, as did the use of bars as a social resource.  Two stress variables -- negative affectivity and discrimination attributable to sexual orientation -- also had significant, though more moderate effects.  Interactions of the vulnerability measures with the stress variables had significant effects on substance abuse beyond the main effects, supporting the central hypothesis.  In a second analysis both simple consumption levels and high-risk styles of alcohol or other drug use predicted alcohol or other drug problems better among vulnerable than among nonvulnerable respondents.  These findings strongly supported a general stress-vulnerability model of substance abuse and illustrated several important risk factors in homosexual culture.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Data Missing for in-the-Closet Gay Drinkers<BR>
<I>Zimmerman, R.</I></B><BR>
<I>U.S. Journal of Drug and Alcohol Dependence </I>June 1989
<BLOCKQUOTE>The author suggests that the widely quoted statistic that 30 to 35 percent of the gay population has alcohol or other drug problems may be understated because it is based on evidence from people who have acknowledged their homosexuality.  Research subjects are suggested to get a better understanding of the true epidemiology of this problem and, in turn, provide the necessary data for more appropriate, effective prevention and treatment strategies.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Chemical Dependency in Gay and Lesbian Youth</B><BR>
<I>Shifrin, F., and Solis, M.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>5(1):67-76, 1992<BR>
(Available from Haworth Press, 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Issues underlying chemical use by gay youths are outlined.  These include:  decreasing the stigma felt in developing a homosexual or gay identity by medicating the concomitant anxiety; helping discharge sexual impulses more comfortably; decreasing depression and dissonance generated by the adolescent's discovery of his or her sexual identity; escaping the pain of exclusion, ridicule, and rejection of the family and peer group; gaining a sense of power; and gaining a sense of identity.  A discussion of treatment issues includes:  prevention; gay youth in a straight treatment setting; the role of the family in treatment; and other factors, such as denial and family pathologies.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Double Trouble:  Lesbians Emerging from Alcoholic Families <BR>
<I>Rothberg, B.P., and Kidder, D.M.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>5(1):77-92, 1992<BR>
(Available from Haworth Press, 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>A young woman emerging as a lesbian in an alcoholic family system faces a dual set of problems.  She knows the life and shame of being an adult child of an alcoholic (ACOA), while she has all the stresses all lesbians face in a society that renders them deviant and invisible.  The process of identity formation is inexorably linked with growing up in a shame-based family system where there is already a high level of stress and intolerance for upsetting the balance at any time.  Successful relationships depend on the development of intimacy, which depends on each individual's ability to share and reveal the true self or the deep, emotional self.  Ideally, the formation of a couple's relationship should be the result of a process of emotional bonding accompanied by a healthy dose of self-individuation.  A beginning relationship for an emerging lesbian can be fraught with anxiety producing stimuli.  Once developed, however, a relationship with another woman can provide the possibilities of growth for an ACOA lesbian by providing her with an atmosphere of nurturance, support, and validation.  Conversely, a relationship initiated by fear, alienation, and loneliness, or by the desire to escape family of origin, can become a stumbling block to development.  Stages of therapeutic intervention for the lesbian ACOA are discussed.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lesbians' and Gay Men's Experiences of Discrimination and Harassment in a University Community<BR>
<I>D'Augelli, A.P.</I></B><BR>
<I>American Journal of Community Psychology </I>17(3):317-321, 1989
<BLOCKQUOTE>A survey of 125 lesbians and gay men in a university community was conducted to determine the incidence of discrimination, harassment, and violence.  Nearly three-fourths had experienced verbal abuse; 26 percent were threatened with violence; and 17 percent had personal property damaged.  Students and roommates were most often responsible.  Most incidents were not reported to authorities, and many made changes in their daily routines to avoid harm.  Over half of the sample feared for their personal safety; their fear was related to the amount of harassment and previous property damage.  Men were more often victimized than women.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Recreational Drugs and Sexual Behavior in the Chicago MACS/CCS Cohort of Homosexually Active Men<BR>
<I>Ostrow, D.G.; Beltran, E.D.; Joseph, J.G.; DiFranceisco, W.; Wesch, J.; and Chmiel, J.S.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Substance Abuse </I>5:311-325, 1993<BR>
(Available from David Ostrow, Medical College of Wisconsin, Community Health Behavior Program, 1201 North Prospect Avenue, Milwaukee, WI 53202.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Since initial reports emerged of an association between recreational drug use and high-risk sexual behaviors in gay men, there has been interest in studying this relationship for its relevance to behavioral interventions. This study reports the longitudinal patterns of alcohol and other drug use of gay men in the Chicago Multicenter AIDS Cohort Study (MACS) Coping and Change Study (CCS).  A pattern of decreasing drug use over 6 years was observed that paralleled a decline in high-risk sexual behavior (i.e., unprotected anal intercourse).  In contrast, alcohol consumption tended to be more stable over time and to show no relationship to sexual behavior change.  Men who combined volatile nitrite (popper) use with other recreational drugs were at high risk both behaviorally and in terms of immunodeficiency virus-1 (HIV) seroconversion throughout the study.  Popper use also was associated independently with lapse from safer sexual behaviors (failure to use a condom during receptive anal sex).  Use of other recreational substances showed no relationship to sexual behavior change patterns, and stopping use was unrelated to improvement in safer sexual behavior.  When popper use and lapse from safer sex were reanalyzed, controlling for primary relationship status, popper use was associated with failure to use condoms during receptive anal sex among nonmonogamous men only.  These findings suggest an association between popper use and high-risk sexual behavior among members of the Chicago MACS/CCS cohort that has relevance to HIV prevention intervention efforts.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lesbian Alcohol and Substance Abuse<BR>
<I>Mosbacher, D.</I></B><BR>
<I>Psychiatric Annals </I>18(1):47-50, January 1988<BR>
(Available from Dee Mosbacher, M.D., Ph.D., P.O. Box 60840, Santa Barbara, CA 93111.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Health professionals treating lesbian alcohol and other drug abusers are often handicapped by a scarcity of accurate information on the topic.  The author reviews the literature on lesbian alcohol and other drug abuse and discusses issues pertaining to treatment and topics for future investigation.  To provide sensitive care to lesbian alcohol and other drug abusers, additional studies are needed about the effect of homophobia on diagnosis, course, prognosis, and treatment.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Spirituality in Everyday Life:  Experiences of Gay Men of Alcoholics Anonymous<BR>
<I>Kus, R.J.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>5(1):49-66, 1992<BR>
(Available from The Haworth Press, Inc., 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY, 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>To learn how gay men of AA use spirituality in everyday life, 50 gay American men were interviewed in depth.  The findings of this study are presented here so that clinicians can teach their gay male clients how other gay men recovering from chemical dependency go about practicing spirituality.  In everyday life, the men in this study practiced spirituality by maintaining sobriety, ridding themselves of internalized homophobia, communicating with their Higher Power (who was defined as God by the overwhelming majority of the study's participants), turning their lives and wills over to the care of God as they understood Him, performing good works (both corporal and spiritual works of mercy), meeting adult social roles, engaging in self-examination, applying AA slogans to everyday life, sharing themselves with others, attending AA meetings, seeking forgiveness, reading positive gay, alcoholic, and other literature, engaging in rituals, engaging in sacrifice and discipline, and doing everyday tasks as well as they possibly could.  Tips on how clinicians may use this knowledge for their gay male clients are provided.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lesbians and Alcohol:  Patterns and Paradoxes in Medical Notions and Lesbians' Beliefs<BR>
<I>Hall, J.M.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Psychoactive Drugs </I>25(2):109-119, 1993<BR>
(Available from Joanne M. Hall, Ph.D., 1612 Noriega Street, San Francisco, CA 94112.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>There is growing awareness in the lesbian community about the prevalence of alcohol problems and the meanings and values attached to alcohol use are currently undergoing change.  Little research has focused on lesbians' life experiences and alcohol use practices, although in earlier decades a number of medical theories linked lesbianism with alcohol problems as copathologies.  More recent theories from the social sciences also linked lesbianism with alcohol problems, but on the basis of sociocultural dynamics and consequent negative self-images.  This article compares and contrasts medical theories about lesbians and alcohol, with lesbians' own ideas about alcohol use and alcohol problems.  Mutually reinforcing themes in medical views and lesbians' experiences are identified.  The analysis clarifies what is at stake in the current debates about alcohol, alcohol problems, and recovery experiences in the lesbian community, and offers suggestions for research, theory, and practice regarding this significant health issue.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Knowledge and Opinions of Alcohol Intervention Workers in Ontario, Canada, Regarding Issues Affecting Male Gays and Lesbians:  Parts I and II<BR>
<I>Israelstam, M.A.</I></B><BR>
<I>International Journal of the Addictions </I>23(3):227-252, 1988<BR>
(Available from S. Lambert, Social Policy Research, Prevention Studies, Addiction Research Foundation, 33 Russell Street, Toronto, Ontario, Canada M5S 2S1.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Complex societies, such as those in Canada, include people from a variety of special populations.  It has been observed that drinking problems within these subpopulations tend to be specific to such groups.  Identification of the special problems of subpopulations is seen as important in intervention issues.  The Task Group on Homosexuality, established by the American Sociological Association, found that the stigma associated with homosexuality discouraged researchers from studying this group.  Thus, a questionnaire was designed to reflect the controversies in the literature concerning homosexuals and their alcohol use to find out what is known and thought by alcohol intervention workers.  Questionnaires were mailed to respondents who filled them out anonymously.  Three follow ups were used to ensure a solid response rate.  The age of respondents ranged from 25 to 63 years, with a median age of 40 years.  Education, occupation, partner status, and size of workplace are listed in tabular form.  Respondents generally felt that heavy drinking is more prevalent in the gay community than in the general population, and that intervention efforts should take sexual orientation into account.  They also believed that intervention protocol does not encourage gays to seek treatment.  Results indicate an overall lack of knowledge about lesbian-male gay differences.  It is concluded that Ontario agencies and any other agencies dealing with alcohol problems need to decide whether their programs are relevant or can benefit homosexuals.  42 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcoholism and Non-Acceptance of Gay Self:  The Critical Link<BR>
<I>Kus, R.J.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Homosexuality </I>15(1-2):25-41, 1988
<BLOCKQUOTE>Research was conducted to investigate the etiology of alcoholism among gay American men and to explore any relationship between etiology and gay bars or nonacceptance of gay self or both.  The study was part of a larger project aimed at generating grounded theory on the nature of sobriety among gay people.  Twenty gay men recovering from alcoholism were interviewed in depth in Seattle, Iowa City, Chicago, and Oklahoma City; each of the men had been sober at least 1 year.  The following conclusions were made from the results:  (1) the disease etiology of the informants was totally unrelated to gay bars, but most of the men thought the gay bar ethnotheory could explain the high incidence of alcoholism in the gay community; (2) before they were sober, none of the men viewed being gay as a positive thing, yet many did not realize until they were sober that they were nonaccepting; (3) only after choosing and living sobriety did the men accept being gay as a positive aspect of self; and (4) the etiology and high incidence of alcoholism among American gay men may be explained by nonacceptance of being gay as a positive aspect.  14 Ref.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Homosexuals Who Indulge in Excessive Use of Alcohol and Drugs:  Psychosocial Factors to be Taken into Account by Community and Intervention Workers <BR>
<I>Israelstam, S., and Lambert, S.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Alcohol and Drug Education </I>34(3):54-69, 1989
<BLOCKQUOTE>The secluded nature of the gay bar and its importance as a social center is just one example of how lifestyle may contribute to alcohol and other drug problems of homosexuals.  This article describes what aspects of lifestyle and social control must be taken into account when intervening into such problems.  The paper discusses issues that have a direct bearing on chemical use by homosexuals and need to be considered when related intervention or research is undertaken.  Most of the articles in this paper refer to alcohol use.  63 Ref.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Support Choices and Abstinence in Gay/Lesbian and Heterosexual Alcoholics<BR>
<I>Holleran, P.R., and Novak, A.H.</I></B><BR>
<I>Alcoholism Treatment Quarterly </I>6(2):71-83, 1989<BR>
(Available from The Haworth Press, Inc., 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The purpose of this study was to examine the therapeutic support choices made by gay, lesbian and heterosexual alcoholics in their pursuit of abstinence.  Subjects were 652 males and females served by a private residential alcohol treatment facility in New York State.  Data was analyzed to determine how gay and lesbian participants differed from their heterosexual counterparts by sex, abstinence, and chosen support system.  6 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Psychosocial and Cultural Factors in Alcohol and Drug Abuse:  Analysis of a Homosexual Community<BR>
<I>McKirnan, D.J., and Peterson, P.L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Addictive Behaviors </I>14(5):555-563, 1989<BR>
(Available from David J. McKirnan, University of Illinois - Chicago, Department of Psychology, Box 4348 (m/c 285), Chicago, IL 60680.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Homosexual men and women may be at risk for alcohol and other drug abuse due to psychosocial variables, such as drinking styles, stress, or the cultural importance of bars.  The study of psychosocial variables in homosexual culture may help us understand how they operate generally.  This paper describes the findings of a large (n=3,400) survey of homosexual population.  The core hypothesis was that stress and other psychosocial variables have their primary effects among people made vulnerable to substance abuse by individual expectancies and/or cultural values.  Tension reduction expectancies of alcohol effects had substantial effects on alcohol and other drug abuse, as did the use of bars as a social resource, a vulnerability variable more specific to urban homosexual culture.  Further, stress affected alcohol and other drug problems only among people who were vulnerable via expectancies and values.  Both high-risk styles of substance use and simple consumption levels had much stronger effects on problems among vulnerable respondents, thus supporting the stress-vulnerability perspective.  Individual differences in social role status were related to alcohol and other drug problems and may explain differences between homosexual and general populations.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>The Research Symposium on Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention among Lesbians and Gay Men</B><BR>
Proceedings, Sacramento, CA:  California Department of Alcohol and Drug Programs, October 1992<BR>
(Available from California Department of Alcohol and Drug Programs, 1700 K Street, Sacramento CA 95814.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This symposium was a forum for researchers, policy makers, and prevention practitioners on AOD problems and needs of lesbians, gay men, and bisexual men and women.  These proceedings give an overview of important themes of the symposium:  (1) the politics of research on and services to gay men and lesbians influence how research questions are formulated and findings are interpreted; (2) gay men and lesbians are not a monolithic entity, diversity abounds; (3) bisexuals do exist; and (4) understanding gay and lesbian AOD use patterns provides the key to effective prevention approaches.  The proceedings summarize three panels on people of color, youth, and environmental risk reduction; lists presenters and participants; and gives four papers presented by researchers.  (The four papers presented are abstracted below.) </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Drug Use among Lesbian and Gay People:  Findings, Research, Design, Insights, and Policy Issues from the Trilogy Project<BR>
<I>Skinner, W., and Otis, M.D.</I></B><BR>
Proceedings, The Research Symposium on Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention among Lesbians and Gay Men, October 1992<BR>
(Available from EMT Group, Inc., 3090 Fite Circle, Suite 201, Sacramento, CA 95827.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This paper presents findings from the Trilogy Project, a study on alcohol and other drug use among gay men and lesbians in two metropolitan communities in a southern State.  The study investigated social issues, such as victimization, discrimination, stress, social support, AIDS testing, sexual practices, and psychological well-being.  It focused on the epidemiology and etiology of licit and illicit drug use.  The goals of the Trilogy Project were to (1) examine the prevalence and frequency of using 11 licit and illicit drugs by a large sample of self-defined gay men and lesbians; (2) compare the prevalence rates of AOD use of gay men and lesbians to that of respondents from the 1988 National Household Survey on Drug Use; and (3) examine the etiology of substance use among gay men and lesbians by elaborating, refining, and testing causal models derived from the literature on stress, social supports, and personal well-being.  This paper contains data for goals (1) and (2).  The study concluded that the prevalence of problematic alcohol use among gay men and lesbians is not higher than that occurring in the general population.  Programs must be specially designed to meet the needs of the lesbian and gay population.  These programs need to recognize both the differences and similarities between gay and lesbian substance abusers and their nongay/lesbian counterparts.  The author contends that the gay and lesbian communities are interested in learning more about themselves, and that researchers and practitioners need to design studies, programs, and policies that make their participation nonthreatening, safe, and worthwhile.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>An Exploration of Lesbians Images of Recovery from Alcohol Problems<BR>
<I>Hall, J.M.</I></B><BR>
Proceedings, The Research Symposium on Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention among Lesbians and Gay Men, October 1992<BR>
(Available from EMT Group, Inc., 3090 Fite Circle, Suite 201, Sacramento, CA 95827.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The author explores the images lesbians used to describe their recovery from alcohol problems and the implications for health care.  Lesbians' experiences in recovery are particularly significant because of growing concerns about the prevalence of alcohol problems among lesbians, the vulnerability of lesbians as an aggregate, and the cultural trend away from substance use in lesbian communities.  Images of recovery are the descriptions that people offer about their healing from alcohol problems.  They are the framework by which problem drinkers interpret the meanings of their experiences and determine which aspects of their lives are most pertinent to their recovery efforts.  The images persons use to represent their progress and the difficulties they encounter in recovery also provide important bases for developing relevant resources, therapeutic techniques, and social support.  Excerpts from an ongoing ethnographic interview study about the recovery experiences of lesbians with alcohol problems illustrate the diversity of recovery images characteristic of this population. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Changes in Drug and Alcohol Use Patterns among Gay Men in San Francisco:  The San Francisco Mens Health Study <BR>
<I>Stall, R.; Barrett, D.; and Paul, J.</I></B><BR>
Proceedings, The Research Symposium on Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention among Lesbians and Gay Men, October 1992<BR>
(Available from EMT Group, Inc., 3090 Fite Circle, Suite 201, Sacramento, CA 95827.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The San Francisco Men's Health Study (SFMHS) is a longitudinal study of gay and bisexual men selected through a random household sampling technique of the 19 census tracts in San Francisco with the highest cumulative incidence of AIDS as of 1984.  Follow-up of the HIV seropositive men allows ascertainment of the long-term effects of HIV infection within a cohort of gay men.  Measures of drug and alcohol use were included at baseline and were repeated throughout the course of the study.  The findings presented in this paper show substantial declines for the prevalence of marijuana, cocaine, LSD, downers, opiates, uppers, and any drug use during the course of the 1980s.  The authors also note increases in abstention over time, as well as declines in heavy/frequent use.  These declines over time were for both HIV positives and negatives, although the positives tended to report higher levels of AOD use on intake.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol and Drug Use Among Homosexual Men and Women:  Epidemiology and Population Characteristics<BR>
<I>McKirnan, D.J., and Peterson, P.L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Addictive Behaviors </I>14(5):545-553, 1989<BR>
(Available from David J. McKirnan, University of Illinois-Chicago, Department of Psychology, Box 4348 (m/c 285), Chicago, IL 60680.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Homosexual men and women have been described as being at high risk for alcohol and other drug abuse due to psychosocial variables, such as stress levels or the cultural importance of bar settings.  However, there are few actual data in this regard.  This paper presents the finding of a large (n=3,400) survey of a homosexual population regarding population characteristics and patterns of alcohol and other drug use.  Psychosocial variables that may account for substance use patterns both generally and in this population are discussed in an accompanying paper.  Substantially higher proportions of the homosexual sample used alcohol, marijuana, or cocaine than was the case in the general population.  Contrary to other reports, this was not accompanied by higher rates of heavy use, although homosexuals did show higher rates of alcohol problems.  In the general population women consume less drugs and alcohol than do men, and substance use substantially declines with age.  Neither of these patterns were found for the homosexual sample, thus creating overall higher rates of substance abuse.  This may reflect differences between homosexuals and the general population in their adherence to sex-role stereotypes and age-related social role changes, as well as culturally specific stressors and vulnerability.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Homosexuality and Illegal Residency Status in Relation to Substance Abuse and Personality Traits among Mexican Nationals<BR>
<I>Tori, C.D.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Clinical Psychology </I>45(5):814-821, 1989<BR>
(Available from Christopher D. Tori, California School of Professional Psychology, 1005 Atlantic, Alameda, CA 94501.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Maladaptive behavioral and personality reactions to severe stressors among Mexican homosexual men were assessed by comparing substance abuse and Rorschach data obtained from three samples:  (1) homosexuals residing illegally in the United States (n=40), (2) homosexuals living in Mexico (n=21), and (3) heterosexuals living illegally in the United States (n=25).  The results of <BR>
orthogonal contrasts showed very similar personality structure and substance abuse patterns among the participants in the two homosexual groups.  As predicted, these men were found to be using alcohol or other drugs to a greater extent than the heterosexual controls.  Rorschach findings indicated that the homosexual subjects were experiencing dysphoric moods and distorted perceptions; they were also having significant difficulties coping with an environment that was discerned as increasingly dangerous.  These results are relevant to the stress reduction hypothesis of addiction and provide quantitative information regarding the extent of psychopathology in this underserved Hispanic population.  32 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Treatment of Homosexual Alcoholics in Government- Funded Agencies:  Provider Training and Attitudes<BR>
<I>Hellman, R.E.; Stanton, M.; Lee, J.; Tytun, A.; and Vachon, R.</I></B><BR>
<I>Hospital and Community Psychiatry </I>40(11):1163-1168, 1989
<BLOCKQUOTE>Treatment of homosexual alcoholics in government-funded agencies was evaluated, with a focus on 36 agencies in the New York City area.  They were surveyed for information about training and attitudes toward the treatment of homosexual patients.  Approximately 160 responses were obtained that indicated limited knowledge about the evaluation and/or treatment of homosexual alcoholics.  Providers often did not discuss sexual matters, even when it was considered of importance.  About half of the providers believed that treatment programs would benefit from the presence of gay staff members.  However, as a rule, the development of homosexual-oriented programs was of low priority.  25 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Issues Relating to the Treatment of Adolescent Lesbians and Homosexuals<BR>
<I>Teague, J.B.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Mental Health Counseling </I>14(4)422-439, October 1992
<BLOCKQUOTE>Homosexuality as a lifestyle can be many things to many people.  For the gay or lesbian adolescent, it can lead to confusion, isolation, or a number of other serious problems, such as <BR>
attempted suicide.  These teens may seek out a mental health professional for support and accurate information.  This article reviews the current theoretical literature with respect to a number of key issues that can help mental health counselors be more aware and more effective in their delivery of services to this population.  Etiological, developmental, treatment, and resource issues are highlighted, and suggestions for future research are provided.  According to the author, mental health counselors can help gay men and lesbians develop innovative and satisfying ways to grow as gay people by (1) becoming more active and visible in reducing the public stigma of homosexuality; (2) making the investigation of suicide among gay and lesbian youths a priority; and (3) using gay and lesbian adolescents and adults who are comfortable with their lifestyle to work with those who have not been as successful in their attempts to cope.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Treatment of the Gay or Lesbian Alcoholic<BR>
<I>Lewis, G.R., and Jordan, S.M.</I></B><BR>
In:  G. W. Lawson and A.W. Lawson (eds.) <I>Alcoholism and Substance Abuse in Special Populations. </I>Rockville, MD:  Aspen Publishers, Inc., 1989. 370 pp.
<BLOCKQUOTE>Some research seems to indicate a significantly higher percentage of lesbian and gay alcoholism than in the general population.  For counselors to treat these patients in a constructive and effective manner, they must be able to focus on the alcoholism and ignore the client's sexuality unless and until it becomes a problem for the client.  Gays and lesbians learn to be homophobic from a very early age -- often as young as 5 or 6 years of age.  Internalized homophobia creates many problems and is almost certainly a factor in a gay client's substance abuse.  Counselors need to see sexuality as a part, not the total, of the personality.  Being gay or lesbian must not be seen as pathological.  It is necessary to accept homosexuality as within the sexual norm and within the natural order.  The genital act of homosexuality is not of itself immoral.  Counselors need to be aware of the many stresses on the gay or lesbian client that arise from society at large, from the gay society, and from within the client because of the homosexuality and the alcoholism.  The relevant dynamics in treating gays and lesbians are discussed.  75 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Family Treatment with Chemically Dependent Gay Men and Lesbians<BR>
<I>Shernoff, M., and Finnegan, D.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>4(1):121-135, 1991<BR>
(Available from Michael Shernoff, 80 Eighth Avenue, Suite 1305, New York, NY 10011.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This article examines three issues:  (1) the context within which family treatment of chemically dependent gay men and lesbians takes place; (2) the concepts that underlie any understanding of how to provide quality treatment to them; and (3) examples of practical approaches to providing such treatment.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Dual Diagnosis Issues with Homosexual Persons<BR>
<I>Hellman, R.E.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>5(1):105-117, 1992<BR>
(Available from Haworth Press, 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The ways in which a dual diagnosis of both substance abuse and psychiatric disorders impact homosexual individuals are explored, as are the ways a homosexual orientation may affect those with dual diagnoses.  A clinical approach is outlined to give treatment providers some context and method for better evaluation and understanding of these issues.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lesbian Recovering Alcoholics:  A Qualitative Study of Identity Transformation. A Report on Research and Applications to Treatment<BR>
<I>McNally, E.B., and Finnegan, D.G.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>5(1):93-103, 1992<BR>
(Available from Haworth Press, 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This qualitative study describes the identity transformation of lesbian recovering alcoholics in Alcoholics Anonymous (AA).  Open-ended interviews with the women provide the primary data for analyzing the process of transforming the stigmatized identity of lesbian recovering alcoholics (LRA).  This analysis examines the dynamic interaction between sexual identity and drinking, alcoholism recovery, and on-going sobriety.  Eight women who identified themselves as lesbian recovering alcoholics were chosen as participants in this study.  They were white, middle class, employed women between the ages of 30 and 45, from a large urban area, and were both lesbian and recovering alcoholics for at least 2 years.  Symbolic interactionism and some of the stage models of alcoholic and lesbian identity transformation provided the theoretical framework that guided the researcher.  The distinctions about and patterns of identity transformation that emerged from an analysis of the data are presented in eight profiles and five themes.  The five themes are:  (1) &quotI was different, alone, and afraid&quot; (2) &quotI drank to cope with being a lesbian, but ended up being an alcoholic&quot; (3) &quotI became a recovering alcoholic:  sobriety saved my life&quot; (4) &quotI accepted my lesbian identity in sobriety&quot; and (5) &quotI am a lesbian recovering alcoholic.&quot Finally, this study offers a stage model of lesbian recovering alcoholic identity transformation.  This model describes the process by which the women accept and integrate the two sub-identities of lesbian and alcoholic into the single, distinct identity of lesbian recovering alcoholic.  The model provides a basis for recommendations for further research and for clinical practice.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Planning an Experiential Weekend Workshop for Lesbians and Gay Males in Recovery<BR>
<I>Picucci, M.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>5(1):119-139, 1992<BR>
(Available from Haworth Press, 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Gay men and lesbians in stage II recovery can realize profound curative benefits from an experiential weekend workshop.  The mechanics of planning such a workshop while providing a framework for understanding the benefits of experiential process and the parameters of stage II recovery are presented.  The design of this workshop creates an opportunity for support with their evolving sexual identity and difference while modeling the concept of self-parenting to heal and care for one's own wounded inner child.  To go back to one's developmental years using supportive therapeutic technique and group dynamics touches and begins to heal unconscious hurts and limitations.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Application of Family Therapy Concepts in the Treatment of Lesbians and Gay Men<BR>
<I>Weinstein, D.L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>5(1):141-155, 1992<BR>
(Available from Haworth Press, 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>There is a need to incorporate three-generational family thinking into the discussion of treatment of lesbians and gay men, specifically those struggling with addictions.  The genogram is a method of diagramming family members.  Creating the genogram in the counseling session is a clinical intervention in and of itself.  It organizes the client's family history as the client provides the information.  A case example is provided illustrating that an expanded view of a client's family history and connections facilitates treatment.  It allows for the assessment of a presenting problem in context.  The fuller the assessment, the more opportunity for clinical interventions of reframing, recognizing themes, or restraining change.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Model for the Treatment of Lesbian and Gay Alcohol Abusers<BR>
<I>Ratner, E.</I></B><BR>
<I>Alcoholism Treatment Quarterly </I>5(1/2):25-46, 1988<BR>
(Available from The Haworth Press, Inc., 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY, 13904-1580.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This article describes a holistic model for treating lesbian and gay people who are addicted to alcohol or other drugs.  The model was developed at Pride Institute, a 36-bed facility established in March 1986 near Minneapolis, Minnesota.  The author points out that a larger percentage of alcoholism is found among homosexuals than in the American population as a whole, then discusses some of the similarities and differences between homosexual and heterosexual alcoholics.  The treatment model, outlined in the final section, consists of three phases (assessment, clinical, and aftercare) plus a weekend family program for family members and other concerned people.  The treatment phase includes individual and group therapy, issue-oriented group meetings, relaxation training, meditation or prayer, instructional sessions, exercise and recreation, 12-step recovery meetings, and a homophobia program.  It is concluded that the internal and environmental stressors that affect all lesbians and gay men must be dealt with in an effective treatment program for that population.  36 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Differences in Assessment and Treatment Approaches for Homosexual Clients<BR>
<I>MacEwan, I.</I></B><BR>
<I>Drug and Alcohol Review </I>13(1):57-62, 1994<BR>
(Available from Ian MacEwan, MA, Advisory Council of New Zealand, P.O. Box 5023, Wellington, New Zealand.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This study was undertaken to discover both the similarities and differences in assessment and treatment approaches for heterosexual and homosexual clients.  The purpose of the study was to investigate to what extent sexual orientation is incorporated into treatment plans and what effect this had for treatment outcomes.  Responses to nine questions were obtained from 50 self-reporting heterosexual and 50 self-reporting homosexual clients of a range of treatment providers.  Differences were found at each stage of the assessment and treatment process.  There was evidence of sexual orientation not being used as a treatment factor.  For both groups there was evidence of inadequate significant-other involvement in treatment and post-treatment planning.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Heterosexual Therapists Treating Homosexual Addicted Clients<BR>
<I>Ubell, V., and Sumberg, D.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>5(1):19-33, 1992<BR>
(Available from The Haworth Press, Inc., 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Many therapists may intellectually accept homosexuality, while remaining homophobic in their emotional belief systems.  Suggestions are offered to therapists working with lesbian and gay addicted clients for coping with their countertransferential and homophobic reactions.  The therapist's acceptance of homosexuality becomes crucial in helping the addicted client recover from his or her disease in which self-denial and self-hate are such significant factors.  It is detrimental to the recovery process when the therapist begins treatment with a client with an agenda to change the client's sexual orientation, or to define it as pathological, or to explore how it evolved.  In addition to low self-esteem, poor self-image, difficulty in relating, intense anxiety, and deep feelings of shame experienced by many clients who are in recovery, the homosexual client also may feel internalized homophobia resulting from the accumulated negative messages he or she has received from family, friends, and society.  Suggestions are made to help heterosexual therapists raise their levels of consciousness, gaining more knowledge about and a sense of ease with homosexuality.  Knowledge of addiction and its treatment is the other crucial factor in dealing with homosexual addicted clients.  It is suggested that maintaining a consistent and primary focus on physical and emotional sobriety is a critical factor in the addicts recovery regardless of whether the addict is heterosexual or homosexual.  Case examples illustrate the importance of focusing on sobriety ahead of sexual issues with recovering substance abusers and their significant others.  Once sobriety has been achieved, it is important for the therapist to accept any homosexual feelings the client may have; this is essential for the maintenance of sobriety and the emerging self.  Family of origin issues may arise during recovery, as well; it is important for the therapist to understand both the role of addiction in the extended family and the family's acceptance of homosexuality.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Other Publications </H3>
<B>Presentation/Workshop Summaries & References/ Bibliographies:  10% of Those We Serve Annual Conference</B><BR>
Proceedings, 10% of Those We Serve Annual Conference.  New York, NY:  April 29, 1988. 41 pp.<BR>
(Available from 10% Conference - GLAS, P.O. Box 1141, Cooper Station, New York, NY 10276.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The particular issues of lesbians and gay men affected by alcoholism and other addictions are addressed.  Topics include disability coupled with addiction, dealing with the grief of death, adolescent sexual identity development, homosexual incest survivors, battering and abuse, gay priests and lesbian nuns, aging and alcoholism, and recovery issues.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Multiple Treatment Issues:  Lesbian/Gay/Alcoholic/Incest Survivor<BR>
<I>Breckinridge, M., and Samuels, C.</I></B><BR>
Conference Paper, 10% of Those We Serve Annual Conference. New York, NY:  April 29, 1988. 41 pp.<BR>
(Available from 10% Conference - GLAS, P.O. Box 1141, Cooper Station, New York, NY 10276.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Areas of concern in treating the lesbian and gay alcoholic incest survivor are outlined.  These include defensive structures and strategies, shame, and self-abuse, transference/countertransference, psychosocial issues, homophobia, other addictions, power relationships, sexual/relationship behavior, and recommended interventions.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcoholic Recovery of Gay Priests and Lesbian Nuns:  Questions and Issues <BR>
<I>Godden, R.</I></B><BR>
Conference Paper, 10% of Those We Serve Annual Conference. New York, NY:  April 29, 1988. 41 pp.<BR>
(Available from 10% Conference - GLAS, P.O. Box 1141, Cooper Station, New York, NY 10276.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Shame and guilt play a big part in blocking the recovery of chemically dependent homosexual priests and nuns.  To deal with this shame and guilt, this population would probably best be served with the general public.  Such a solution would help to break their isolation and alleviate any depression.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Straight Providers:  Lesbian/Gay Clients<BR>
<I>Wallman, G., and Peck, I.</I></B><BR>
Conference Paper, 10% of Those We Serve Annual Conference.  New York, NY:  April 29, 1988.  41 pp.<BR>
(Available from Gerry Wallman, 70 West 95th Street, New York, NY 10025.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The authors say that heterosexual service providers need to be trained in treating homosexual clients.  Many issues need to be understood and addressed, including sexual identity, family history, growing up processes, relationship issues, discrimination, isolation, and issues of addiction.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Behind Closed Doors:  Battering & Abuse in the Lives of Lesbians & Gay Men <BR>
<I>Walber, E.</I></B><BR>
Conference Paper, 10% of Those We Serve Annual Conference.  New York, NY:  April 29, 1988. 41 pp.<BR>
(Available from Elizabeth Walber, New York City Gay and Lesbian Anti-Violence Project, 208 West 13th Street, New York, NY 10011.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Battering and abuse in the lives of lesbians and gays are defined.  Forms of battering and abuse are outlined; community denial and community response are examined; and the myths surrounding the issues are also examined.  Implications for lesbian and gay service providers and information resources are also identified.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Something New in Continuing Education:  Training Mental Health Professionals to Work with Lesbian and Gay <BR>
<I>Nichols, M., and Shernoff, M.</I></B><BR>
New York, NY:  National Association of Gay Alcoholism Professionals, 11 pp.
<BLOCKQUOTE>In this paper, the authors describe essential issues of style and substance to be used in training mental health professionals and alcoholism and drug addiction counselors to work with lesbian and gay men.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Ties That Bind:  Strategies for Counseling the Gay Male Co-Alcoholic <BR>
<I>Whitney, S. </I></B><BR>
New York, NY:  National Association of Gay Alcoholism Professionals, 10 pp.
<BLOCKQUOTE>It is stated that little specialized clinical work is being done with gay male alcoholics and still less is known about working with their co-alcoholic lovers, a person in the alcoholic's life who intervenes in such a way as to prevent the alcoholic from facing the consequences of his actions.  In this paper, some common co-alcoholic issues are described and strategies for treating co-alcoholics, specifically in groups, are discussed.  It is concluded that treatment personnel must look closely at the social system supporting the addictions of their gay male clients.  Also, it is important that those who serve in a co-alcoholic role within that system be contacted and, if possible, brought into treatment.  Since working in small groups that emphasize alcohol education, stress management, communication skills, and increased socialization within the gay community has proved effective in an outpatient setting, clients should be encouraged to involve themselves in Al-Anon to deepen their knowledge of co-addiction and to strengthen their support system.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Accepting Ourselves:  Twelve-Step Journey of Recovery from Addiction for Gay Men and Lesbians<BR>
<I>Kominars, S.B.</I></B><BR>
New York:  Harper & Row, 1989. 186 pp.<BR>
(Available from Harper & Row, 10 East 53rd Street, New York, NY 10022.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This book applies the Twelve-Step recovery process used by Alcoholics Anonymous to the special concerns of homosexual substance abusers.  Substance addiction affects homosexual Americans at two to three times the rate of the general population.  The author describes a double bind faced by some chemically addicted homosexuals -- denying both their addiction and their sexuality.  The author contends that the first step on the road to recovery is acceptance of one's addiction and one's sexual orientation.  He draws on the experience of his own recovery as he presents and examines each of the Twelve Steps, relating each to the particular needs of the homosexual addict.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lonely Journey:  Lesbians and Gay Men Who Are Co-Dependent<BR>
<I>Finnegan, D.G., and McNally, E.B.</I></B><BR>
In:  B. Carruth and W. Mendenhall (eds.) <I>Co-dependency:  Issues in Treatment and Recovery. </I>Binghamton, NY:  Haworth Press, Inc., 1989. 167 pp.
<BLOCKQUOTE>Co-dependence can be defined as a disorder of the relationship of the self to the self and to others.  The denial of self in order to feel connected to others is at the heart of co-dependence.  People create a false self in order to be who they think others want them to be because they cannot tolerate the fear of being alone or abandoned.  Society's homophobic teachings merge with and intensify its teachings about co-dependence and make gay men and lesbians and those with sexual identity issues especially vulnerable to becoming co-dependent.  The implications for treatment for gay men and lesbian co-dependents are that skilled counselors need to be knowledgeable about issues and problems specific to lesbians and gay men and take a creative approach to working with a non-traditional population.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Gay Men of Alcoholics Anonymous:  First-Hand Accounts<BR>
<I>Kus, R.J.</I></B><BR>
North Liberty, IA:  WinterStar Press, 1990. 217 pp.<BR>
(Available from WinterStar Press, P.O. Box 199, North Liberty, IA 52317.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>A collection of the life stories of 27 gay men in Alcoholics Anonymous (AA) is presented.  These stories describe what life was like before sobriety and what life is like in sobriety.  Unlike traditional AA stories, these address the critical gay issues the men deal with in their quest for full mental, spiritual, and physical health.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Double Duty:  Raised in Alcoholic/Dysfunctional Family and Gay/Lesbian<BR>
<I>Black, C.</I></B><BR>
Denver, CO:  MAC Publishing, 1990. 79 pp.<BR>
(Available from MAC Publishing, Claudja Inc., 5005 East 39th Avenue, Denver, CO 80207.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This publication is excerpted from the book Double Duty.  The author examines the stories of two gay men and three lesbians and how their dual identity had affected their lives and their recoveries.  Double duty is defined as the experience of adult children of alcoholics who deal with the family dysfunction along with an additional set of circumstances.  The two aspects of the problem are synergistic, causing difficulty for the individual attempting to change his or her circumstances.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Tailoring Treatment for Lesbians and Gay Men</B><BR>
<I>Addiction Letter </I>December 1991<BR>
(Available from Fraelean Curtis, 264 Beacon Street, Boston, MA 02116.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Lesbians and gay men who are addicted to alcohol or other drugs present unique treatment challenges.  This population suffers stigmatization and discrimination in a society that believes heterosexuality is normal and homosexuality is abnormal, and a society that fears and dreads homosexuals.  For them, recovery from addictions must include recovery from their own internalized homophobia and heterosexism.  Lesbians and gay men must transform two stigmatized identities, that of lesbian and gay men and that of the addict, into positive, affirming identities if they are to become clean and sober.  A five-state model of recovery from internalized homophobia and heterosexism is described, including pre-encounter, encounter, immersion and emergence, internalization, and synthesis/commitment.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Serving Lesbian & Gay Youth<BR>
<I>McManus, M.C.</I></B><BR>
<I>Focal Point </I>Spring/Summer 1991<BR>
(Available from Marilyn C. McManus, J.D., Research and Training Center, Portland State University, Portland, OR 97207-0751.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Although lesbian and gay youth receive services from multiple systems, including mental health, education, child welfare, juvenile justice, and health, historically these service providers have neither identified nor addressed the special needs of this population.  Most gay and lesbian youths emerge as healthy adults from the struggles associated with adjusting to a stigmatized minority status.  Estimates on the prevalence of homosexuality among adolescents vary widely; however, within gay and lesbian communities it is widely believed that approximately 10 percent of the population is homosexual.  Lesbian and gay youth of color live within at least three communities:  (1) their ethnic minority community; (2) the gay and lesbian community; and (3) the majority community.  Some gay and lesbian youths are at significant risk for serious depression and suicide.  Lesbian and gay youth are particularly vulnerable to alcohol and other drug abuse, as they seek to cope with the isolation, 
rejection, and stressors they experience.  Homosexuals are probably the most frequent victims of hate violence.  Group homes, emergency shelters, residential facilities, and juvenile detention facilities can be dangerous places for gay and lesbian youth, since they may be blamed by administrators when sexual or other assaults take place.  Pregnancy among teenage lesbians is not uncommon, since for some youth pregnancy is a method of concealing their sexual orientation.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Recovery Needs of Lesbian Alcoholics in Treatment<BR>
<I>Underhill, B.L.</I></B><BR>
In:  N. Van Den Bergh (ed.) <I>Feminist Perspectives on Addictions. </I> New York:  Springer Publishing Company, 1991. pp. 73-86<BR>
(Available from Springer Publishing Co., Inc., 536 Broadway, New York, NY 10012-3955.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>An overview is presented of the specific needs of lesbian alcoholics in treatment and recovery.  The underlying premise presented is that the barriers to effective treatment for the lesbian woman with alcohol problems are cultural and external, as well as intrapsychic and interpersonal.  Lesbians, as women, must recover from the physical effects of alcoholism and the social diseases of sexism and homophobia.  A feminist perspective on alcoholism is based on the understanding that an individual lesbian alcoholic must surrender to her powerlessness over alcohol and other mood-altering drugs while at the same time reclaiming her power as a woman and a lesbian.  The design and delivery of services to this segment of the population must address all of these factors if services are to be effective.  39 Ref.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Chemical Dependency Treatment for Lesbians and Their Families:  The Feminist Challenge<BR>
<I>Bushway, D.J.</I></B><BR>
In:  C. Bepko (ed.) <I>Feminism and Addiction. </I> Binghamton, NY:  Haworth Press, 1991. 224 pp.<BR>
(Available from Haworth Press, 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The field of chemical dependency has recently begun to come to terms with the particular issues of lesbians and gay men who are addicted.  The challenges of providing service to this community and their families are complex.  Some of these complexities are reviewed in this article.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Psycho-Therapy Techniques with Lesbian Clients<BR>
<I>Hughes, P., and Davis, B.L.</I></B><BR>
<I>The Counselor </I>November/December 1993. pp. 25-27<BR>
(Available from National Association of Alcoholism & Drug Abuse Counselors, 3717 Columbia Pike, Suite 300, Arlington, VA 22204-4254.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>For the lesbian dealing with a dual stigmatized identity of chemical dependency and sexual orientation, treatment styles must be tailored to address the complex levels of anonymity of each individual.  As with any other population, chemical dependency in the lesbian population must be dealt with first; however, the key to ensuring ongoing recovery for the lesbian woman is to simultaneously address internalized homophobia.  Treatment professionals must be aware that when working with this population, a didactic approach is vital where the degree of non-acceptance is of primary concern.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcoholism, Chemical Dependency and the Lesbian Client <BR>
<I>Glaus, K.O.</I></B><BR>
<I>Women & Therapy </I>8(1/2):131-144, 1989<BR>
(Available from Kathleen O'Halleran Glaus, Associate Professor of Professional Psychology, Wright State University, Dayton, OH 45431.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The problems of women doubly stigmatized by society for being lesbian, as well as alcoholic or chemically dependent, are discussed.  Topics covered by this review include greater risk of alcoholism among lesbians because of higher than expected frequency of alcoholism among their families, heavy reliance on drinking environments as social meeting places, and ambivalence or conflict about sexual orientation.  Other topics include clinical assessment and treatment issues for alcohol or drug dependent lesbians; special issues that affect this group of women, including the role of self-help groups, denial and rationalization, negative affect, internalized homophobia, sexuality issues, involvement of the partner and extended &quotfamily&quot in the treatment process; and matters that therapists need to be aware of in treating lesbians for alcohol or other drug abuse, including facing up to their own homophobia, which, when it exists, may be expressed subtly and without awareness.  46 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lesbianism as a Model of a Positive Lifestyle for Women<BR>
<I>Rothblum, E.D.</I></B><BR>
<I>Women & Therapy </I>8(1/2):  1-12, 1989<BR>
(Available from The Haworth Press, Inc., 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The article describes the legal status of lesbianism in the United States and other nations.  In the U.S., the legality of lesbianism is determined on a State-by-State basis.  It also discusses the psychiatric history of lesbianism and research on the prevalence and positive mental health of lesbians.  According to the author, nontraditional roles of lesbians can serve as a model of positive mental health for women in general.  Mental health statistics show that being single is psychologically healthier, possibly because married women often face a combination of employment plus full responsibility for housework and child care.  Lesbians have more long-term relationships, with emphasis on emotional closeness, love, and security.  Lesbian relationships include little risk of sexually transmitted disease.  Lesbian mothers lose 80 percent of all custody battles in lower courts and face other issues, such as homophobic remarks by others to the children, lesbian partners relating to the children, rearing male children, and coming out to children.  Lesbian feminists have been in the vanguard of social change, initiating alternative health care, feminist therapy collectives, women's shelters, and grassroots political organizations.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Sobriety, Friends, and Gay Men<BR>
<I>Kus, R.J.</I></B><BR>
<I>Archives of Psychiatric Nursing </I>5(3):171-177, 1991<BR>
(Available from Robert J. Kus, RN, Ph.D., 110 Hackberry Street, North Liberty, IA 52317.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>A study to learn how sobriety affects friendships in gay recovering alcoholic men is described.  The research sample included 20 gay recovering alcoholic males, each of whom had been sober for at least 1 year, who were interviewed.  The results of the study indicated that most of the subjects had lost friends, had many heavily drinking acquaintances, and were having difficulty meeting the responsibilities of friendships.  When sobriety had been achieved, the men were able to expand their friendship circles to others who were abstainers as well as to normal drinkers.  Nursing strategies for care of recovering gay alcoholics are discussed.  13 Ref.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Perceived Acceptance and Social Isolation among Recovering Homosexual Alcoholics<BR>
<I>Milliger, C., and Young, M.</I></B><BR>
<I>International Journal of the Addictions </I>25(8):947-955, 1990<BR>
(Available from Marcel Dekker, Inc., 270 Madison Avenue, New York, NY 10016.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The purpose of the study was to identify variables that might be associated with perceived acceptance and social isolation among recovering homosexual alcoholics.  Participants (n=126) completed a questionnaire that included the Gay Perceived Acceptance and Social Isolation Scale (PASI).  Data were analyzed using stepwise multiple regression.  This procedure resulted in the selection of four independent variables which, as a set, accounted for more than 50 percent of the variation in PASI scores.  Three of the four terms related to sexuality:  perception that sexuality was a major cause of subject's alcoholism; perception that sexuality had nothing to do with alcoholism; and family awareness of the subject's homosexuality.  The fourth factor was the presence of alcoholism in the subject's biological family.  The overall results indicate that resolution of conflict concerning sexuality could lead to higher PASI scores and may increase the prospects of long-term recovery from alcoholism.  18 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Social Supports and Lesbian Alcoholics<BR>
<I>Schilit, R.; Clark.W.M.; and Shallenberger, E.A.</I></B><BR>
<I>Affilia, </I>3(2):27-40, 1988
<BLOCKQUOTE>The relationship between social support and alcoholism among lesbians is described.  The study sample included 15 lesbian alcoholics and 15 lesbian nonalcoholics who responded to a questionnaire covering childhood and adolescence, social support systems, drinking history, and demographic information.  While the current support systems of alcoholic lesbians were not as disrupted as had been expected, these alcoholic women reported a less supportive childhood and adolescence, conflict with family adults, and at least one parent with a drinking problem.  44 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Substance Use as a Correlate of Violence in Intimate Lesbian Relationships<BR>
<I>Schilit, R., and Lie, G.Y.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Homosexuality </I>19(3):51-65, 1990
<BLOCKQUOTE>The relationship between substance use and violence in lesbian relationships is discussed.  The study sample included 104 lesbians who responded to a 70-item questionnaire.  The survey results indicated that 39 subjects reported an abusive relationship, either past or present, and 64 percent reported the use of alcohol or drugs prior to or during abuse.  Frequency of drinking was directly and significantly related to the commission of abuse, as well as with being the victim of abuse.  It is concluded that increased efforts should be made to improve delivery of human and social services, including substance abuse services, to this population.  41 Ref.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Pain of Invisibility:  Issues for Lesbians<BR>
<I>Underhill, B.L., and Ostermann, S.E.</I></B><BR>
In:  P. Roth (ed.) <I>Alcohol and Drugs Are Women's Issues:  Volume One. A Review of Issues</I>, pp. 71-77. Metuchen, NJ:  Scarecrow Press, 1991. 192 pp.
<BLOCKQUOTE>The authors examine some of the ways in which the dominant culture transmits its anti-lesbian messages to individuals.  Focus is on factors, such as stigma, denial, alienation, and discrimination, which place lesbians at high risk to develop problems with alcohol and other drugs.  Some of the important issues pertaining to lesbians are discussed:  (1) family of origin as a source of stress; (2) extended family of the lesbians; (3) legality of lesbian partnerships; (4) &quotcoming out&quot process as a source of stress; (5) lack of visible mainstream models; and (6) lack of meeting places other than the bar.  Some suggestions for guidelines in working with lesbians and incorporating their needs into any project or program are presented, along with some of the available resources.  22 Ref.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol Consumption and Unsafe Sex:  A Comparison of Heterosexuals and Homosexual Men<BR>
<I>Trocki, K.F., and Leigh, B.C.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndromes </I>4(10):981-986, 1991<BR>
(Available from Dr. K.F. Trocki, Alcohol Research Group, 2000 Hearts Street, Berkeley, CA 94709.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The relationship between alcohol consumption and unsafe sexual practices was studied.  The research sample included 844 responses to a mailed 20-page questionnaire.  Of the sample, which ranged in age from 18-76 years, 80 percent were white, 52 percent were male, 76 percent were heterosexual, and 70 percent were college graduates.  The questionnaire specifically addressed the circumstances of sexual encounters that took place in conjunction with alcohol consumption.  The study results indicated that alcohol intoxication was related to unsafe sexual practices by homosexual men and heterosexual women but not by heterosexual men.  Respondents whose sexual partners were met in pickup locations were more likely to adhere to safe sexual practices.  It is suggested that the Combination of alcohol and sex may be significantly affected by the setting in which both occur.  30 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lesbian Women<BR>
<I>Finnegan, D.G., and McNally, E.B.</I></B><BR>
In:  R.C. Engs (ed.) <I>Women:  Alcohol and Other Drugs</I>, pp. 149-156. Dubuque, IA:  Kendall/Hunt Publishing Company, 1990. 173 p.
<BLOCKQUOTE>Alcohol consumption and drug usage by lesbian women are discussed in this review of the literature.  Headings within this book chapter include:  (1) the severity of the problems; (2) incidence; (3) triple stigmas; (4) what needs to be done; (5) prevention; and (6) treatment.  The incidence of gay men and lesbians at risk for alcoholism is usually cited as between 28 and 32 percent.  Most lesbian women alcoholics drink in order to cope with their internalized homophobia, their fear, and their shame.  The great majority of lesbian alcoholics will not willingly risk the price of self disclosure, passing as heterosexual in order to survive in a homophobic atmosphere.  They may feel isolated, shamed, and lonely; if they survive treatment, they are likely to be at risk for relapse.  The alcoholism field must help lesbians or women with sexual identity concerns recover from their addictions.  Prevention programs should address alcohol problems in high risk groups, including adolescent girls and women in their early 20's.  Professionals must commit to training, examining, and changing their attitudes, exploring their own sexual identity issues, and providing non-sexist, non-homophobic help to all women.  22 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Preventing Alcohol Abuse in the Gay Community:  Toward a Theory and Model <BR>
<I>Mongeon, J.E., and Ziebold, T.O.</I></B><BR>
In:  J. Ziebold and J. Mongeon (eds.) <I>Alcoholism and Homosexuality</I>, pp. 89-100. New York:  Haworth Press, 1982. 107 pp.
<BLOCKQUOTE>Major components of a prevention model for the gay community are described.  The approach is grounded in the belief that, for an alcohol abuse prevention program to be successful with a particular community, it must be sensitive to the values and norms of that community, be conducted by trusted and visible community members, involve a broad spectrum of the community leaders and opinion makers in its planning and implementation, and be integrated into the existing institutions and service delivery networks within that community.  An early intervention and outreach program for gay men and women identified as at risk with beverage alcohol is proposed.  The intervention component consists of an intensive, experimental group process that will encourage participants to develop more constructive alternative behaviors in their lives.  It is proposed that this intervention effort be accompanied by a public education and/or outreach campaign.  Using the formal and informal communications networks of the gay community and involving broad community representation can heighten gay awareness of the destructive consequences of alcohol misuse and develop additional alternative outlets exclusive of &quotbar and brunch&quot activities.  12 Ref.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Breaking the Silence:  Creating Safe Schools for Gay Youth<BR>
<I>Anderson, J.D.</I></B><BR>
<I>Student Assistance Journal </I>March/April 1994, pp. 21-23
<BLOCKQUOTE>An estimated 10 percent of school students are gay or lesbian.  Although the American Psychiatric Association and other organizations recognized the gay lifestyle 20 years ago, educators today do little to support gay and lesbian adolescents.  As a result of fear of discovery and lack of role models, gay and lesbian adolescents have a suicide rate two to three times higher than heterosexual youths.  Homophobia is worse among people who have never knowingly met a homosexual.  Therefore, the simplest solution, according to the author, is for more and more gays and lesbians to come out.  To make the school environment better for gay youth and staff, the Connecticut State Board of Education through its Equity Newsletter urged giving attention to inclusive language; challenging antigay epithets; designating resource people in the schools for gay, lesbian, and bisexual students; making resources and materials visible and accessible; educating staff on homophobia; supporting gay and lesbian colleagues and using them as role models; and referring self-identified gay and lesbian students to appropriate services.  In 1993, the Massachusetts Governors Commission on Gay and Lesbian Youth recommended several areas of concentration, including:  school policies protecting gay and lesbian students from harassment, violence, and discrimination; training teachers, counselors, and school staff in crisis intervention; school-based support groups for gay students; information in school libraries for gay adolescents; and curriculum that includes gay issues.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Suicide and Sexual Orientation:  A Critical Summary of Recent Research and Directions for Future Research<BR>
<I>Muehrer, P.</I></B><BR>
Address, American Association of Suicidology Convention, New York, April 8, 1994
<BLOCKQUOTE>Research on the relationship between sexual orientation and suicide is limited both in quantity and quality.  The percentage of overall adolescent suicides committed by gay and lesbian youth is unknown.  Scientific data on the effectiveness and safety of suicide prevention programs is lacking; however, recent evaluations suggest that they are ineffective and may actually have unintended negative effects.  This review summarizes the literature on completed and attempted suicides among gay and lesbian youth, as well as the small scientific literature on programs aimed at preventing suicide among youth in general.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Gay Parents in Addictions Treatment<BR>
<I>Segal, J.</I></B><BR>
<I>The Counselor </I>January/February 1994.  pp. 26-27
<BLOCKQUOTE>Gay and lesbian parents have unique needs; the normal rigors of parenting are greatly increased by being gay or lesbian.  Internalized homophobia and the shame developed by internalizing the negative attitudes towards gays and lesbians perpetuated by a homophobic society impact on self, parenting, and relationships.  It is necessary to address issues related to sexual orientation during recovery from addictions.  A number of effects of internalized homophobia on parenting that must be acknowledged in treatment are listed.  Clients may be self-conscious about their appearance and behavior.  They will avoid public and professional activities.  They may use their children to pass as heterosexual in the outside world.  Clients also may fear that their children will be gay or lesbian.  On the other hand, the client may be overly zealous in expressing his or her sexuality.  The process of coming out is a lifelong process, but it begins with coming out to oneself.  Clients must learn to accept who they are and be proud of the fact.  When dealing with children, clients must realize that coming out sends a clear message that honesty and integrity are values important to family relationships.  Professionals should consider bringing the children into treatment, so that accepting the parents sexual orientation becomes a family-oriented task.  While children of gay men and lesbians question their own sexuality at an earlier age, they are no more likely to be gay or lesbian than their peers.  The parent who has a healthy identity as a gay or lesbian is better prepared to explore strategies with his or her children to respond to homophobia attacks than the parent who personalizes situations and experiences guilt and shame.  On the positive side, children who grow up with gay or lesbian parents learn to accept and have a higher tolerance for differences in both themselves and in others, and they have greater exposure to new viewpoints and so are better able to expand their own thinking.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Dual Identities:  Counseling Chemically Dependent Gay Men and Lesbians<BR>
<I>Finnegan, D.  G., and McNally, E.  B.</I></B><BR>
Center City, Minnesota:  Hazelden Educational Materials, 1987, 128 pp.<BR>
(Available from Hazelden Foundation, Pleasant Valley Road, Box 176, Center City, MN 55012-0176.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Society's homophobia creates magnified feelings of low self-worth, guilt, and shame in chemically dependent lesbians and gay men.  To cope, they adopt a defense system where denial of addiction swirls together with the fear of disclosing homosexuality.  Professionals in the chemical dependency field can break through this double barrier to recovery by increasing their knowledge about homosexuality.  The book describes counseling techniques to deal with the special needs and issues of gay and lesbian alcoholics.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Creating Visibility:  Providing Lesbian-Sensitive and Lesbian-Specific Alcoholism Recovery Services<BR>
<I>Underhill, B.  L.</I></B><BR>
Los Angeles, CA:  Alcoholism Center for Women, 1993, 63 pp.<BR>
(Available from Alcoholism Center for Women, 1147 South Alvarado Street, Los Angeles, CA 90006.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Data suggest that as many as 25 to 30 percent of lesbians have serious problems with alcohol and other drugs.  Due to the societal oppression that lesbians confront and the invisibility that results from that oppression, the problem goes largely unaddressed in most alcohol and other drug abuse recovery programs.  The stresses of dealing with ongoing and systematic oppression may manifest as low self-esteem, isolation, alienation, and despair within an individual.  The needs of lesbian alcoholics are discussed to raise awareness of these needs among service providers.  Delivery of meaningful recovery services to lesbians requires a thorough understanding of the lesbian lifestyle and the issues that impact it, including lesbian family units, lesbian mothers, survival of incest, a high incidence of adult children of alcoholics, and a significant number of relationships involving domestic violence.  This population, particularly during adolescence, is at extremely high risk for alcohol and other drug abuse; it is also a population with a very high suicide rate.  Strategies are offered for more successful recovery for these women, including strategies in the area of outreach (promotional materials, advertising and public relations, and community relations), administration (policies, procedures, and personnel), and programmatic concerns (staff training, program design and implementation, and followup care).  Additional resources are listed for further study.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Preventing Alcohol and Other Drug Problems in the Lesbian and Gay Community<BR>
<I>Kelly, J.</I></B><BR>
Sacramento, CA:  California Department of Alcohol and Drug Programs, March 1994<BR>
(Available from California Department of Alcohol and Drug Programs, 1700 K Street, Sacramento, California 95814.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>People who identify as lesbian or gay constitute a population that requires AOD problem prevention strategies consistent with their cultural experiences.  This handbook combines research and program experience knowledge.  It bridges the gap between academia and the field in understanding the AOD problems of gay men and lesbians.  The handbook is divided into six sections:  The first two sections provide background theory and research information.  Section one presents an overview of research-based knowledge of lesbian and gay AOD use patterns.  Because of a lack of funding, early studies of AOD abuse by gay men and lesbians were conducted on easily accessible subjects, such as bar patrons, mental health clients, and prisoners.  Random sampling techniques are difficult for such surveys because one must be willing to identify oneself as gay or lesbian to participate in these studies.  Also, not much is known about gay men and lesbians of color and gay and lesbian youth.   The author highlights seven key findings derived from research presented at the Research Symposium on Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention among Lesbians and Gay Men in October 1992.  [Note:  Proceedings of the symposium are abstracted in this resource guide.]  The key findings are:  (1) the incidence of heavy use of AOD is about the same among lesbians and gay men as it is among their heterosexual counterparts; (2) fewer lesbians and gay men abstain from AOD than do their counterparts; (3) lesbians alcohol use patterns are more similar to those of gay and heterosexual men (that is, a higher rate of use) than to patterns of heterosexual women; (4) although there is little evidence that addiction rates are higher among lesbians and gay men, some studies find that lesbians and gay men report higher rates of AOD-related problems; (5) gay men and lesbians appear to use other drugs at substantially higher rates than their heterosexual counterparts; however, alcohol is clearly the drug of choice; (6) as people get older, their AOD use tens decrease.  Among gay men and lesbians, this decrease appears to be not as substantial as among the general population; (7) the rate of AOD use among gay men and lesbians may be declining.  Section two discusses the concepts of prevention, risk, and resiliency.  Examples of risk factors in the gay and lesbian communities include alienation, isolation, and low self-esteem; lack of connectedness to a supporting, caring community; a belief that AOD use is necessary to one's identity; and a reliance on AOD to reduce inhibitions to engage in sex.  A strong resiliency factor is connection to and identification with a lesbian and gay community.  Key prevention principles are listed.  The last four sections describe specific prevention approaches.  Section three discusses the Lapis Program of the Alcoholism Center for Women, which uses alternative activities, topical support groups and workshops, and community outreach to reach African-American and Latino lesbians.  Section four describes the LYRIC Program and Project Ten, which provide a parallel social and recreational network for adolescent gays and lesbians who are barred from full participation in normal teenage activities.  Section five discusses the environmental approach to AOD prevention.  It describes the Stepping Stone, an alcohol treatment and recovery program serving primarily lesbians and gay men.  Section six looks at the link between HIV and AOD and the need for HIV and AOD prevention fields to work together to develop effective strategies.  A list of resources and a bibliography are included.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Counseling Lesbian, Gay and Bisexual Persons with Alcohol and Drug Abuse Problems.<BR>
<I>Neisen, J.</I></B><BR>
Arlington, VA:  NAADAC Education and Research Foundation, 1994
<BLOCKQUOTE>This monograph provides an overview of the salient issues in counseling lesbians, gay men, and bisexuals with substance abuse problems.  It reviews the literature on the prevalence of substance abuse in the gay population and points to recent sociological approaches that emphasize the role of cultural victimization in explaining heavy drinking and drugging in the gay community.  Heterosexism and homophobia are defined and case examples are presented that indicate how cultural victimization contributes to substance abuse.  The coming out process for lesbians and gays is discussed to help alcoholism and drug abuse counselors recognize the particular risks for heavy drinking and drug use at various stages of the coming out process.  Issues of counselor sensitivity are presented as well as guidelines to improve counselor proficiency in facilitating the stages of healing for lesbians and gays with substance abuse problems.  Guidelines are identified for working with lesbians and gays and their families.  This includes information on working with both the family of origin and family of choice.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol and Other Drug Abuse in a Gay/Lesbian Population:  Related to Victimization? <BR>
<I>Neisen, J., and Sandall, H.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Psychology and Human Sexuality </I>3(1), 151-168, 1990
<BLOCKQUOTE>The authors address possible connections between alcohol and drug addiction, homosexuality, and child sexual abuse.  They review the literature on homosexuality and alcoholism and point to (1) the lack of empirical studies on this issue; (2) changing perspectives on both alcoholism and homosexuality in the last two decaded; and (3) past psychoanalytic literature that assumed a causal relationship between homosexuality and alcoholism in contrast to more recent sociological explanations that suggest gays and lesbians may be liable to turn to drinking and drugging as a response to the cultural prejudice they face.  The authors conducted a retrospective clinical case study on 201 gay and lesbian individuals at Pride Institute, an inpatient alcohol and drug treatment program specifically designed to meet the needs of gays and lesbians, to provide information regarding the prevalence of sexual abuse among chemically dependent gays and lesbians.  They found a large number of clients reporting a history of sexual abuse.  The researchers attributed three factors to these reports of abuse:  (1) the safe, supportive environment provided at Pride Institute was conducive to disclosure to sensitive information, (2) Pride Institute staff routinely and thoroughly assess for histories of sexual victimization, and (3) assessment of sexual abuse continues beyond the evaluation stage of treatment and into primary treatment, including workshops on abuse, group therapy, and individual therapy with the clients primary therapist, staff psychologist, and staff psychiatrist.  This study discusses the importance of addressing sexual abuse issues in chemical dependency treatment and the importance of recognizing how cultural victimization and sexual victimization contribute to drinking and drugging.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Black, Gay, and Alcoholic Men:  Their Character and Treatment<BR>
<I>Icard, L., and Traunstein, D.M.</I></B><BR>
<I>Social Casework</I>, 68(5), 267-272, 1987
<BLOCKQUOTE>The authors focus on normative factors of the black and the gay communities and show how these factors converge to affect the character (abuse and dependence) and treatment of black, gay alcoholic men.  Assuming that black men are proportionally represented among homosexual men, as many as 1.3 million black men may be homosexual, according to the authors.  They also estimate that the rate of alcohol abuse among black gays is similar to white gays--one out of three.  Gay black men are a double minority, subject to harsh social treatment by racist and antihomosexual attitudes.  Moreover, they are often stigmatized by both the black and gay communities.  The sharp cultural differences between the black and gay communities often force the black, gay person to choose between being black or being gay.  This alienation often contributes to the individuals abusive drinking behavior.  In treating the black, gay alcoholic, attention should be focused on (1) the persons drinking behavior, (2) black cultural influences; (3) the persons gay self-concept; and (4) his reference groups in the black and the gay communities.  The black, gay alcoholic may be mistrustful of mental health services and not seek services as readily as white, gay alcoholics.  In successful treatment, the client must (1) control his drinking; (2) gain a better understanding of himself; and (3) recognize the range of choices available to him as a sober, recovering, functioning, emotionally healthy black, gay male.  He has to develop skills of assertiveness, communication, positive self-appraisal, and development of a positive support system.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Working with Lesbian Alcoholics<BR>
<I>Anderson, S.C., and Henderson, D.C.</I></B><BR>
<I>Social Work </I>30(6), 518-525, 1985
<BLOCKQUOTE>The authors describe the myths and realities of lesbian experience, review the literature, and discuss the need to overcome homophobia among social workers and in agencies.  Lesbian alcoholics experience a triple burden of social stigma.  In treating lesbian alcoholics, attention must be focused on drinking behavior, low self-esteem, coming out, role expectations, and parenting.  There is little systematic research on the relative effectiveness of treatment modalities with lesbian alcoholics; most reports are anecdotal and involve small samples.  The authors review individual, couples, family, and group therapy and AA and suggest treatment strategies that address the special problems and needs of lesbian alcoholics.  It is critical, say the authors, that traditional alcohol treatment programs and other social service settings begin a dialogue with their respective homosexual communities, hire lesbian staff, or provide their nongay staff with opportunities for education and attitudinal change.  There is an urgent need for research on alcoholism among lesbians; large samples and longitudinal designs are particularly needed.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Transexuality, Identity, and Empowerment:  A View from the Front Lines<BR>
<I>Warren, B.E.</I></B><BR>
<I>SIECUS Report</I>, February/March 1993, pp. 14-16.
<BLOCKQUOTE>Transexuals are people who find their gender identity (the inner sense of self as male or female) in conflict with their sexual anatomy, says the author.  Manifestations range from occasional cross-dressing, to living full- or part-time in the gender opposite of ones sexual anatomy, to taking hormone therapy, and ultimately to undergoing sex reassignment surgery.  The author reports on the support groups of the Gender Identity Project (GIP) of New York Citys Lesbian and Gay Community Services Center.  After sex reassignment surgery, the person is technically no longer transexual; however, many continue to use the term to describe their unique experience.  Approximately 50 percent of male-to-female transexual women who participate in the Centers GIP report an attraction to women; these transexuals describe themselves as lesbians.  Male-to-female transexual women attracted to men describe themselves as heterosexual women.  Female-to-male transexual men who are attracted to men describe themselves as gay men.  Female-to male transexual men who are attracted to women identify as heterosexual men.  GIPs mission is to enable transexuals to develop a positive, affirmed identity in an environment of support and self-acceptance.  The authors report the controversies about proper diagnosis upon which to base treatment decisions and the reluctance of physicians and mental health professionals to treat transexuals.  The authors conclude there is a need for a non-judgmental, educated, affirming and community-based response to the needs of people who are experiencing gender identity conflict.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Misconceptions about Womens Sexuality:  Understanding the Influence of Alcoholism<BR>
<I>Covington, S.S.</I></B><BR>
<I>Focus on Family and Chemical Dependency </I>9(2):6-7, 44, 1986
<BLOCKQUOTE>Throughout history, alcohol has been viewed as an aphrodisiac for women.  Data, however, suggest a social learning explanation of how drinking affects sexual behavior; due to psychological factors, a woman's experience of arousal may be totally opposite of her measured physiological arousal response.  The author reviews data on women's sexuality and chemical dependency.  Looking at data from Hite and Masters and Johnson, there was a marked shift in choice of sexual partners before, during, and after phases of alcoholism.  Before alcoholism, 74 percent of the women reported they were exclusively heterosexual; 20 percent bisexual; 6 percent lesbian; and 3 percent no information.  During the alcoholism period, 57 percent reported they were exclusively heterosexual; 37 percent bisexual; and 6 percent lesbian.  In sobriety, 66 percent reported they were heterosexual; 17 percent bisexual; and 17 percent lesbian.  The author concludes that alcohol can be an important survival mechanism in a society hostile and nonsupporting of lesbian relationships, as it helps a woman to deny her sexual identity.  The author concludes that treatment providers must look at themselves and their attitudes, values, and knowledge about alcohol and other drug use, and acknowledge that sexuality and chemical dependency are intertwined in women's lives.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>The Prevalence and Demographic Predictors of Illicit/Licit Drug Use Among Lesbians and Gay Men:  The Trilogy Project <BR>
<I>Skinner, W.F.</I></B><BR>
<I>American Journal of Public Health </I>84 (8)1307-1310, 1994,<BR>
(Available from William F. Skinner, Ph.D., Department of Sociology, University of Kentucky, Lexington, KY 40506-0027.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Studies on illicit/licit drug use among gay men and lesbians have focused primarily on gay men, employed limited drug measures, and have been conducted in cities known for large gay and lesbian populations.  This paper examines (1) the prevalence of 12 illicit/licit drugs by gender and age group and (2) the demographic predictors of past year frequency of marijuana, alcohol, and cigarettes.  Self-report data were collected on 455 gay men and lesbians living in a southern state, using organizations mailing lists.  Differences were found between gay men and lesbians in the use of specific substances and the demographic predictors of drug use.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Assessing Risk in the Absence of Information:  HIV Risk among Women Injection-Drug Users Who Have Sex with Women<BR>
<I>Young, R.M.; Weissman, G.; and Cohen, J.B.</I></B><BR>
<I>AIDS & Public Policy Journal </I>7(3):175-183, Fall 1992
<BLOCKQUOTE>Lesbian/bisexual injection drug users (IDUs) are ignored, confused, mistreated, and miseducated by the majority of AIDS research, education, and service programs, say the authors.  Lesbian/bisexual IDUs are at risk for HIV not only because of their sexual and injection behaviors, but also because they believe they are at low risk.  Scientific information about woman-to-woman sexual transmission is badly lacking.  Institutional denial of the possibility of lesbian risk by researchers, policy makers, and drug treatment, as well as HIV program staff has resulted in a failure to provide appropriate risk reduction education to this group.  Since lesbians are assumed (mistakenly) neither to be mothers nor to have sex with men, HIV research on lesbians in unlikely to be done.  Researchers tend to study and describe not simply &quotwomen&quot but &quotwomen of reproductive age&quot; this suggests that concern for women among many epidemiologists and policy makers is not based on concern for womens health but rather on concern for protecting men and infants.  The authors review the limited evidence on risky drug use and sexual behaviors of lesbians/bisexual IDUs.  HIV infection risk may differ according to both the gender of sexual partners and self-reported sexual identity.  Six recommendations to provide this population with information to reduce their HIV risks are provided.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Chemical Dependency and Relapse in Gay Men with HIV Infection:  Issues and Treatment<BR>
<I>Green, D., and Faltz, B. </I></B><BR>
In <I>Counseling Chemically Dependent People with HIV Illness. </I> The Haworth Press, Inc. 1991, pp. 79-90.<BR>
(Available from Triangle Treatment, Robinson Institute, 1841 Broadway, New York, NY 10023.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Chemically dependent gay men with HIV infection need counseling services because (1) substance use may exacerbate their already compromised immune system; (2) substance use may cause disinhibition and noncompliance with risk reduction behaviors, resulting in reinfection or infection of others; and (3) substance use may result in progressive deterioration of quality of life.  To assist counselors in providing services specific to the needs of gay men with HIV who are chemically dependent, the authors discuss relapse prevention and intervention strategies and present a case illustration.  The conditions of distress that may lead to relapse in gay men who are HIV positive must be appreciated by the counselor to provide effective treatment.  These concerns include HIV-associated distress; internalized homophobia; external homophobia; socialization in gay bars; disrupted social and intimate relationships; vocational functioning, finance, and physical health; or use of substances to control moods, thought processes, or behavior.  Treatment programs and individual providers must do more than not assume all men in recovery are heterosexual or HIV negative; they must offer a safe and supportive atmosphere for all clients to explore their unique concerns about maintaining abstinence.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Gay and Alcoholic Epidemiologic and Clinical Issues <BR>
<I>Paul, J.P.; Stall, R.; and Bloomfield, K.A.</I></B><BR>
<I>Alcohol Health & Research World </I>15(2), 1991
<BLOCKQUOTE>The authors review the literature on the prevalence of alcoholism among gay men and lesbians, as well as the risk factors for alcohol abuse in the gay and lesbian communities.  They also review recommendations from the treatment literature on clinical interventions for gay and lesbian alcoholics.  The article is organized around questions crucial to understanding alcohol abuse and alcoholism in the gay and lesbian community:  (1) Do elevated rates of alcoholism exist in the gay community? (2) Are rates of alcohol abuse in the gay community changing? (3) What are the risk factors for alcohol abuse in the gay community? (4) Is there a need for gay-sensitive alcoholism treatment programs? (5) How can existing treatment programs respond to the needs of gay alcoholics? and (6) How can gay alcoholics obtain the social support necessary to maintain sobriety?  Early studies that oversampled bar patrons estimated that one out of three gay men and lesbians abused alcohol and other drugs (AOD).  Later studies based on sampling techniques designed to approximate community-wide samples of gay men found considerably lower rates of AOD abuse among gay men.  Several gaps exist in the epidemiologic literature concerning AOD use by gay men and lesbians.  First, no effort has been made to approximate a community-based sample of lesbians.  Second, most of the research on gay men and lesbians has relied on samples that are white and middle class.  Third, nearly all of the literature on gay and lesbian drinking practices has come from the largest urban centers.  Formal training in treatment issues specific to gay alcoholics and knowledge of the gay community is needed among alcoholism professionals.  Gay alcoholics have difficulties seeking treatment at many mainstream treatment settings and may encounter prejudicial attitudes and nonacceptance from heterosexual staff.  As a result of the AIDS epidemic, major changes have occurred over the last decade in how gay men and women approach the health care system and in their expectionthat service providers be responsive to their needs.  Alcohol and other drug abuse treatment providers may face increasing pressure to become familiar with and to accommodate the specialized needs of their gay, lesbian, and bisexual clients.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Being Gay<BR>
<I>Struve, J.</I></B><BR>
Talk given by Jim Struve at Decatur Hospital, Georgia, on November 12, 1993.
<BLOCKQUOTE>This speech was given at the opening of the Common Steps treatment program at Decatur Hospital in Georgia.  The author begins by presenting his personal history of struggle as a gay man.  Treatment programs must address an additional level of dysfunction that, if ignored, will leave clients at increased risk for relapse.  For gay men and lesbians, daily living in our society imposes all the trappings of a dysfunctional system.  The author lists five essential areas of functioning within any system:  authority and leadership who use their roles to nurture rather than control members; open and spontaneous expression, rather than constricted and controlled communication; flexible norms and rules that adapt to special circumstances, rather than rigid rules enforced by external controls; respect for healthy differences between people, rather than intolerance for nonconforming behavior; and communication and mutual respect used to resolve conflicts, rather than coercion.  Treatment programs must assist clients in discovering alternative coping strategies for living in a world that discriminates against gay men and lesbians.  Treatment providers need to move beyond a clinical focus and address political issues, as well.  To be supportive, they must actively promote alternatives to the underground culture of bars, so gay men and lesbians have safe and healthy ways to meet and socialize.  Gay and lesbian clients must be encouraged to learn about their cultural heritage, and positive role models must be made available.  Finally, according to the author, treatment programs must deal directly with the homophobic forces of organized religions that portray gay men and lesbians with an evil vengeance.   </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Specific Approaches and Techniques in the Treatment of Gay Male Alcohol Abusers<BR>
<I>Smith, T.M.</I></B><BR>
In <I>Alcoholism and Homosexuality</I>, pp. 53-69. Binghamton, NY:  The Haworth Press, 1982<BR>
(Available from Haworth Press, 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The author presents an extended discussion of specific therapeutic approaches and techniques with homosexual male alcohol abusers, including dealing with low self-esteem, sober sex, getting high, getting &quotfar out&quot sexually, double lives, second rate relationships, social bonding, and aging.  In this paper, the bias of treatment approaches is toward individualized, interpersonal, holistic eclecticism:  a combination of responsibility building therapy, awareness therapy, medical and neurophysiological approaches, strategic therapy, use of altered states of consciousness, and attitudinal change therapy.  Knowledge of the gay subculture, of the various surroundings in which the gay alcoholic lives, and of the varying attitudes within the gay world, is essential in helping the therapist to understand the client and his problems and to formulate an appropriate treatment plan.  The therapist needs to be aware of the many stresses upon the client that arise from society, from the gay subculture, and from the clients psyche, not only because of gayness, but also because of the alcoholism.  Many gay male alcoholics are oppressed in several different ways by assaults on different aspects of their personality and constitution.  Since the client often does not describe these pressures, the therapist must be attuned to what the client might be experiencing and must then confirm and affirm these presumptions by discussions with the client.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lesbian and Gay Psychology:  Theory, Research, and Clinical Applications<BR>
<I>Greene, B., and Herek, G.M. (eds.)</I></B><BR>
Thousand Oaks, CA:  SAGE Publications, Inc., 1994
<BLOCKQUOTE>This is the first of a series of planned annual publications sponsored by the Society for the Psychological Study of Lesbian and Gay Issues of the American Psychological Association.  Its aim is to provide a forum for the dissemination of contemporary lesbian and gay affirmative perspectives that are distinctively psychological.  It is no longer sufficient simply to acknowledge that gay and lesbian sexual orientations are within the realm of psychological normalcy.  Mental health professionals are challenged to explore the complexities and subtleties of lesbian and gay sexual orientations; the unique developmental tasks and stressors among lesbians and gay men; the special nuances and dynamics of same-gender relationships; and the treatment of lesbian and gay clients from diverse racial, ethnic, and class backgrounds.  They are called upon to design programs of research and to include material relevant to these issues in the training of psychologists in the broadest sense.  This volume includes empirical studies on the children of lesbians, internalized homophobia, lesbian and gay male development, and aspects of relationship quality in cohabiting couples.  Theoretical analyses of the relationship between the feminist political movement and choice in sexual orientation, sexual pride and shame in lesbians, and lesbians and physical appearance are also included.  The role of individual differences in reactions to lesbians and gay men and empirical research with the Attitudes toward Lesbians and Gay Men (ATLG) Scale are reviewed, as well as a discussion of appropriate therapeutic boundaries when lesbian therapists treat clients within the lesbian community.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>MMPI-Derived Prevalence Estimates of Homosexuality among Drug-Dependent Patients<BR>
<I>Craig, R.J.</I></B><BR>
<I>The International Journal of the Addictions </I>22(11), 1139-1145, 1987
<BLOCKQUOTE>Based on the best MMPI index available (Question 69, &quotI am very strongly attracted to members of my own sex,&quot answered &quottrue&quot; and Question 430, &quotI am attracted to members of the opposite sex,&quot answered &quotfalse&quot), prevalence estimates of homosexuality among 225 drug-abusing clients in treatment were placed at 11 percent.  The rate among black cocaine freebasers was 17 percent, and among black opiate users the rate was 10 percent.  These rates are two to three times the rate of homosexuality among the general population.  They may be an underestimation because of our inability to detect hidden homosexuality among those persons wishing to remain undetected in gender orientation.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Lesbian Health Comes Out of the Closet<BR>
<I>Gallagher, J.</I></B><BR>
<I>Agenda</I>, November 30, 1993
<BLOCKQUOTE>The National Institutes of Health (NIH) includes questions about sexual orientation and sexual behavior in the Womens Health Initiative, the largest study of women's health ever conducted by the Federal Government.  It is a $600 million study that will survey and track 160,000 women ages 50 to 79 about their health.  Data is expected to be available in 1996.  The study has three components:  an observational trial will track the health of 100,000 women for 9 years; clinical trials will determine the effect of prevention and early intervention on 60,000 women; and a test will gauge the effectiveness of educational messages about health care on women who have traditionally been underserved by the Nations health care system.  Researchers hope the study will tell medicine how to end the alienation of lesbians from health care.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Changes in Levels of Alcohol Consumption:  United States, 1983-1988 <BR>
<I>Williams, G.D., and Debakey, S.F.</I></B><BR>
<I>British Journal of Addiction </I>87, 643-648, 1992
<BLOCKQUOTE>Using data from the 1983 and 1988 National Health Interview Surveys, this study examines changes both in the prevalence of abstention and the prevalence of heavier drinking among drinkers in the United States.  Changes are examined separately by gender and according to other sociodemographic characteristics often associated with different levels of alcohol consumption.  Results suggest an increase in abstention and a decrease in heavier drinking between 1983 and 1988.  For women, decreases in heavier drinking were found among those 18 to 44 years of age, among those employed, and among those divorced, separated, or never married.  For men, decreases in heavier drinking were found among those employed, among those with family income of $25,000 or more, and among those married, divorced, or separated.  Changes both in abstention and heavier drinking were found to vary considerably by geographical region.  These findings do not support results from other general population survey studies on alcohol use that suggest a stability in drinking levels, or even a slight increase in heavier drinking among men.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>A Comparison of Alcohol Consumption between Lesbians and Heterosexual Women in an Urban Population<BR>
<I>Bloomfield, K.</I></B><BR>
<I>Drug and Alcohol Dependence </I>33, 257-269, 1993
<BLOCKQUOTE>An elevated rate of alcohol problems is believed to exist in the gay and lesbian community.  However, prevalence estimates suggesting this have generally been based on convenience samples that have over-represented bar patrons and clinical sources.  Recent epidemiological studies examining risk factors for AIDS have gathered information on alcohol consumption, as well as sexual orientation.  Data based on improved sampling methods are now available for estimating drinking rates of lesbians and gay men.  This study compares the drinking patterns of heterosexual women and lesbian/bisexual women who were recruited through a random sampling design in San Francisco.  Contrary to previous research, no statistically significant differences in alcohol consumption and drinking patterns between these two groups were found.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol Abuse among Lesbians:  A Descriptive Study<BR>
<I>Diamong, D.L., and Wilsnak, S.C.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Homosexuality </I>4:123-142, 1978
<BLOCKQUOTE>Intensive interviews with 10 lesbian alcohol abusers revealed dependency needs, low self-esteem, and a high incidence of depression.  Decreased drinking increased power-related behaviors, enhanced self-esteem, and for many subjects increased feelings of depression.  The findings suggest that lesbians with alcohol problems need therapists who will accept their sexual orientation and treatment that will help them increase their sense of power and esteem without alcohol.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Dual Diagnosis Issues with Homosexual Persons<BR>
<I>Hellman, R.E.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Chemical Dependency Treatment </I>5(1):105-117, 1992<BR>
(Available from Haworth Press, 10 Alice Street, Binghamton, NY 13904-1580.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The ways in which a dual diagnosis of both substance abuse and psychiatric disorders impact homosexual individuals are explored, as are the ways a homosexual orientation may affect those with dual diagnoses.  A clinical approach is outlined to give treatment providers some context and method for better evaluation and understanding of these issues.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Counseling Gay and Lesbian Native Americans<BR>
<I>Tafoya, T., and Rowell, R.</I></B><BR>
In <I>Gay and Lesbian Health Care Resources</I>, M. Shernott, ed., Gay and Lesbian Professional Health Care Association, 1988
<BLOCKQUOTE>Native American gay men and lesbians combine elements of common gay experiences with their own unique culture.  Historically, some tribes gave gays special gender status, even believing they represented elements of the sacred.  The authors report that depression is diagnosed among Native Americans at a rate four to six times higher than with whites and suggests that alcohol may be seen as self-medication to deal with the depression.  In traditional cultures, Native Americans sought assistance from a medicine person or healer.  The healers treatment approach might have included therapeutic metaphor, rituals, change of status, involvement of the family network, and self-mastery.  Little emphasis was put on insight.  As a result, family therapy is often the treatment of choice for Native Americans.  If the family has had difficulty with accepting the individuals sexual orientation, the family therapy could provide the means of re-integrating the individual into the family.  The authors remind therapists that words have different associations and nuances among different cultures.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Sexual Diversity in Alcohol and Other Drug Abuse Prevention<BR>
<I>Eversole, T.</I></B><BR>
<I>New Designs for Youth Development </I>11(2), 1994.  Multiple Strategies for Multiple Issues, Module 2
<BLOCKQUOTE>Lesbian, gay, and bisexual Americans are at increased risk for alcohol and other drug abuse. Substance abuse programs have not addressed the prevention needs of sexual minorities, citizens who comprise greater than 10 percent of the people at risk.  The author looks at sexual minorities and prevention and offers suggestions for addressing this critical need.  Lesbian, gay, and bisexual communities are typified by their own history, customs, and values, as well as social and behavioral norms.  There are clearly identified cultural festivals, holidays, rituals, symbols, heroes, language, art, music, songs, and literature.  Certain risk factors are more prevalent for sexual minority youth than for other young people:  (1) history of family addiction; (2) physical, sexual, or psychological abuse and victimization; (3) school dropout; (4) attempted suicide; (5) low self-esteem/efficacy; (6) inadequate social services; (7) homelessness; (8) pro-use norms in the community; and (9) lack of healthy role models.  The author outlines program strategies for prevention that can be undertaken within an entire community to increase resiliency factors and decrease risk factors facing sexual minority youth.  These include outreach and inservice training programs for service providers, mentors, and foster parents; programs to change community attitudes; alcohol and other drug free events for gay and lesbian youth; programs that increase the visibility of healthy, nonabusing, adult role models for lesbian and gay youth; AOD prevention programs by straight parents on behalf of their gay and lesbian children; family advocacy programs that address the issues of homophobia, cultural consciousness, communication, and substance abuse; inservice education of educators; peer support groups; alternative activities; and a hotline with information services to lesbians, gay men, bisexuals and their families.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol Problems in Several Midwestern Homosexual Communities<BR>
<I>Lohrenz, L.J.; Connelly, J.C.; Coyne, L.; and Spare, K.E.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Studies on Alcohol </I>39(11)1959-1963, 1978
<BLOCKQUOTE>The authors focused on the extent and nature of alcohol problems in homosexual communities in the midwest and on the attitudes of homosexual alcoholics toward traditional mental health <BR>
resources and Alcoholics Anonymous.  According to their scores on the Michigan Alcoholism Screening Test, close to one-third of the homosexual men surveyed in four urban areas of Kansas were alcoholics.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Suicidal Behavior in Adolescent and Young Adult Gay Men<BR>
<I>Schneider, S.G.; Farberow, N.L.; and Kruks, G.N.</I></B><BR>
<I>Suicide and Life-Threatening Behavior</I>, 19(4), 381-394, 1989
<BLOCKQUOTE>The relationship of homosexuality to suicidal behavior was explored by questionnaire responses from 52 men in gay and lesbian college organizations and 56 men in gay rap groups.  A family background of alcoholism and physical abuse, social supports perceived as rejecting of homosexuality, and no religious affiliation were associated with a history of suicidal ideation, reported by 55 percent of the participants.  Racial/ethnic minorities tended to be overrepresented among suicidal, as compared to nonsuicidal gay men.  Suicide attempts reported by 20 percent of the sample were most often associated with intrapersonal distress and occurred most often while individuals were closeted and/or in the context of recent rejection for being homosexual.  Nearly all attempters were aware of their homosexual feelings, but had not yet established a &quotpositive gay identity&quot at the time of their first suicide attempt.  Suicidal behavior in gay youths may be the product both of familial factors that predispose youths to suicidal behavior and of social and intrapersonal stressors involved in coming to terms with an emerging homosexual identity.</BLOCKQUOTE>
