<BLOCKQUOTE>This article provides an overview of employee assistance programs (EAPs), presents research data on aspects of their operation in relation to employee alcohol problems, and outlines some of the problems of and prospects for EAPs in dealing with alcohol problems in the work force. Headings within this article include:  (1) the emergence and growth of EAPs; (2) referrals and program utilization for alcohol-related problems; (3) EAP administration; (4) supervisory and managerial involvement; (5) issues for the future; and (6) alternative approaches. Suggested alternative approaches include alcohol education, alcohol control policies, and wellness programs at the workplace.  However, it is clear that EAPs are making substantial contributions to dealing with the national alcohol problems and are doing so in a context of voluntary action without public subsidy.  17 Ref. </BLOCKQUOTE>
