</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>

<IMG SRC="injuryl.gif"><BR><A NAME="Sec1"> <H2>ATOD Resource Guide:  Injury Control <BR> Section 1 -- Prevention Material</H2></A>
<BR>

<B>Just When You Thought It Was Safe...Poster</B><BR>
Year:  1988<BR>
Format:  Poster <BR>
Context:  Stands Alone and Part of a Packet/Program <BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention <BR>
Target Audience:  General Public <BR>
Setting:  Recreation/Sports <BR>
Readability:  Easy <BR>
Current Scope:  Michigan<BR>
Availability:  Michigan Substance Abuse & Traffic Safety Information Center, 2409 E. Michigan Avenue, Lansing, MI 48912-4019; 517-482-9902
<BLOCKQUOTE>This 11 x 17 in. poster shows a capsized boat, life jackets, and an ice chest, and states that &quotZero Alcohol = Safe Boating.&quot  The message encourages all individuals who drive that are under the age of 21, pregnant, or chemically dependent to refrain from drinking any alcohol.  The Enjoy Michigan Safely Coalition is listed as a resource for more information.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Just When You Thought It Was Safe...Brochure</B><BR>
Year:  1988<BR>
Format:  Brochure <BR>
Length:  8 Pages<BR>
Context:  Stands Alone and Part of a Packet/Program <BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention  <BR>
Target Audience:  General Public <BR>
Setting:  Recreation/Sports <BR>
Readability:  Easy <BR>
Current Scope:  Michigan<BR>
Availability:  Michigan Substance Abuse & Traffic Safety, 2409 E. Michigan Avenue, Lansing, MI 48912-4019; 517-482-9902
<BLOCKQUOTE>This colorful brochure encourages readers to enjoy the summer months and to remember that alcohol and boating don't mix.  The brochure states that alcohol affects skills that may impair boating abilities and make it more difficult to swim to safety if necessary.  Michigan laws regarding alcohol and boating are mentioned, and the Enjoy Michigan Safely Coalition is listed as a resource.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Snowmobilers Check This Out!</B><BR>
Year:  1988<BR>
Format:  Poster <BR>
Context:  Stands Alone and Part of a Packet/Program <BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention  <BR>
Target Audience:  General Public <BR>
Setting:  Recreation/Sports <BR>
Readability:  Easy <BR>
Current Scope:  Michigan<BR>
Availability:  Michigan Substance Abuse & Traffic Safety, 2409 E. Michigan Avenue, Lansing, MI 48912-4019; 517-482-9902
<BLOCKQUOTE>This 11 x 17 in. poster warns snow-mobilers that two of every three snowmobile fatalities are alcohol related, and that intoxicated snowmobile operators are subject to jail and/or fines.  The poster states that alcohol and other drugs impair driving ability, and that &quotzero&quot alcohol is the safest choice.  The Enjoy Michigan Safely Coalition is listed as a resource for more information.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>American Red Cross Basic Aid Training Instructor's Manual</B><BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  Curriculum<BR>
Length:  12 Sessions<BR>
Context:  Part of a Packet/Program and Has Training Component <BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention  <BR>
Mode of Delivery:  Instructor-led <BR>
Target Audience:  Elementary Youth <BR>
Setting:  Community Organization and School <BR>
Readability:  Average <BR>
Availability:  American National Red Cross Headquarters; 1-800-969-8890
<BLOCKQUOTE>The Basic Aid Training Program provides instructors with discussion points, practice sessions, and activity sheets to instill in students the skills necessary to respond to and prevent injuries.  The program is designed for children 8 to 10 years old, includes 12 lesson plans, and incorporates alcohol and other drug prevention into the curriculum.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>FYI:  Alcohol, Accidents, and Crime</B><BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  Brochure <BR>
Length:  2 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  Community Service Groups, Educators, and General Public <BR>
Setting:  Community Organization and School <BR>
Readability:  Average <BR>
Current Scope:  Minnesota<BR>
Availability:  Minnesota Prevention Resource Center, 2829 Verndale Avenue, Anoka, MN 55303; 612-427-5310 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This publication looks at the correlation between alcohol, accidents, and crime.  It provides information on alcohol-related injuries and states that alcohol may contribute to criminal behavior, such as murder and rape.  Falls, fire fatalities, and boating deaths are mentioned as a few correlates of alcohol abuse.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Substances & Safety </B><BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  Brochure <BR>
Length:  8 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  Employees and Employers <BR>
Setting:  Worksite <BR>
Readability:  Average <BR>
Availability:  Do It Now Foundation, P.O. Box 27568, Tempe, AZ 85285-7568; 602-491-0393
<BLOCKQUOTE>This pamphlet looks at the dangers of using alcohol and other drugs (AOD) on the job, stating that employees who use AOD at work are 3.6 times as likely to be involved in an accident.  The pamphlet points out the effects and risks associated with several drugs and lists ways for employers to respond to a drug problem at work.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Spinning the Bottle</B><BR>
Organization:  Injury Prevention Network Newsletter, Center For Injury Prevention, Building One, Room 311, San Francisco General Hospital, San Francisco, CA 94110; 415-821-8209<BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  Newsletter <BR>
Length:  16 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention  <BR>
Target Audience:  AOD Prevention Professionals and College Students<BR>
Setting:  Health Care and School <BR>
Readability:  Average<BR>
Inventory No.:  LQ012<BR>
Availability:  National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD  20847-2345; 1-800-729-6686
<BLOCKQUOTE>This newsletter contains several articles on the role of alcohol in injuries not caused by car crashes.  Authors look at how alcohol is a factor in boating, surfing, and drowning injuries; falls; and injuries in the home.  Examples of how advertisements promote drinking within dangerous settings are given.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcoholism and Alcohol-Related Problems</B><BR>
Year:  1990<BR>
Format:  Fact Sheet<BR>
Length:  4 Pages<BR>
