Setting:  School and Home <BR>
Readability:  Average <BR>
Availability:  The Rosen Publishing Group, Inc., 29 East 21st Street, New York, NY  10010; 212-777-3017
<BLOCKQUOTE>This book looks at the connection between drug use and teen suicide and states that many youth attempt suicide while under the influence of alcohol or other drugs.  Common questions about suicide are answered, and warning signs are discussed.  A list of support groups and other helpful resources is included.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Safe Winter</B><BR>
Organization:  Snow Country Coalition on Alcohol and Substance Abuse, Lewis County Council on Alcoholism and Substance Abuse (Coalition Member) <BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  Brochure <BR>
Length:  6 Pages (with 2-page insert)<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention  <BR>
Target Audience:  Hunters and Fishers<BR>
Setting:  Recreation/Sports <BR>
Readability:  Average <BR>
Current Scope:  North Country (Snow Country), New York<BR>
Availability:  Snow Country Coalition on Alcohol and Substance Abuse, Lewis County Council on Alcoholism and Substance Abuse (Coalition Member), P.O. Box 13, Lowville, NY 13367; 315-376-2321
<BLOCKQUOTE>This brochure looks at how the body is affected by alcohol intake during the coldest winter months.  Trivia questions and a windchill factor chart point out the risks associated with alcohol and outdoor recreational activities, such as skiing, hunting, and snowmobiling in extremely frigid weather.  &quotWhat Are the Signs of Alcoholism?&quot and &quotTen Winter Don'ts&quot are two sections of the brochure.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Drinking Stories</B><BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  VHS Video<BR>
Length:  14 Minutes<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention  <BR>
Mode of Delivery:  Mass Media <BR>
Target Audience:  College Students and Sr. High Youth <BR>
Setting:  School and Community Organization <BR>
Availability:  Churchill Media (Churchill Films, Inc.), 12210 Nebraska Avenue, Los Angeles, CA 90025-3600; 800-334-7830
<BLOCKQUOTE>College students relay personal &quotdrinking stories&quot in which alcohol clouded their judgment and led to injuries and crimes, such as date rape and vehicular homicide.  Students share the emotional consequences of their behavior and express intense regret and guilt.  These stories are interspersed with the tales of other students who boast about their drinking prowess and think it's all just innocent fun.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Missing Persons (The Drunk Driving Holocaust)</B><BR>
Year:  1992<BR>
Format:  VHS Video<BR>
Length:  35 Minutes<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drugs and Injury Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  Sr. and Jr. High Youth <BR>
Setting:  School <BR>
Availability:  Cambridge Educational, P.O. Box 2153, Charleston, WV 25328; 800-468-4227
<BLOCKQUOTE>This video unites bereaved parents and friends, permanently disabled victims, and young inmates convicted of vehicular homicide in an attempt to educate students about the direct connection between alcohol, automobile crashes, and death.  The video also dispels common myths, provides information on blood alcohol concentration, and brings the real-life consequences of mixing alcohol with driving into the classroom.</BLOCKQUOTE>
