<IMG SRC="injuryl.gif"><BR><A NAME="Sec2"> <H2>ATOD Resource Guide:  Injury Control <BR> Section 2 -- Studies, Articles, & Reports </H2></A>
<H3> Government Publications and Journal Articles </H3> 
<B>What Emergency Room Studies Reveal About Alcohol Involvement in Violence-Related Injuries</B><BR>
<I>Alcohol Health & Research World </I>17(2):162-166, 1993
<BLOCKQUOTE>Representative emergency room studies provide the best evidence linking alcohol use with violent injuries. The available data on alcohol's association with violent injuries are reviewed, with emphasis on findings from emergency room studies.  Problems inherent in the study methods and an interpretation of results are explored.  24 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Prevention of Alcohol-Impaired Driving</B><BR>
<I>Alcohol Health and Research World </I>17(1):28-34, 1993
<BLOCKQUOTE>The extent of the drinking and driving problems in the United States is explored.  Major initiatives of the past decade aimed at the prevention of drinking and driving are discussed.  A variety of laws are identified that have reduced drunk driving fatalities, such as reduced legal BACs, raising the minimum legal drinking age, and criminal and administrative per se laws.  In addition, heightened police enforcement and use of driver sobriety checks deterred alcohol impaired driving.  Some potential interventions to further reduce injury and fatalities from alcohol-impaired driving are examined.  43 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Illicit Drugs Take Still Another Toll ¾ Death or Injury from Vehicle-Associated Trauma</B><BR>
<I>JAMA:  Journal of the American Medical Association </I>263(23):3122, 3125, 1990
<BLOCKQUOTE>Each year approximately 46,000 people die on U.S.  highways and 300,000 to 500,000 more suffer serious injuries.  While studies have shown that alcohol plays a significant role in at least 60 percent of these traumas, there are few data to show how much the use of marijuana, cocaine, amphetamines, and other illicit drugs adds to the toll.  This article cites recent data from theNational Study Center for Trauma and Emergency Medical Services showing that 7.1 percent of injured drivers admitted to the institute tested positive for cocaine, and 4 percent tested positive for phencyclidine.  Among motorcycle drivers, 10 percent had tested positive for cocaine and 10 percent were positive for phencyclidine.  The article points to the need for further investigation of the role of drugs, other than alcohol, in the causation or trauma experienced in vehicle injuries.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Community-Based Alcohol and Injury Prevention Project:  Reflections from Three U.S. Communities<BR>
<I>Schatz, I.; Schember, C.; Parsons, J.; Rodriguez, J.; Young, C.; and Holder, H.D.</I></B><BR>
In:  <I>Experiences With Community Action Projects:  New Research in the Prevention of Alcohol and Other Drug Problems, CSAP Prevention Monograph-14,</I> T. K. Greenfield, R. Zimmerman, Eds., pp. 138-145. Rockville, MD:  Center for Substance Abuse Prevention, 1993<BR>
(Available from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD  20847-2345. Inventory Code:  BKD87.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The Prevention Research Center (PRC) is implementing a 5-year community prevention trial to reduce alcohol-involved unintentional injuries and fatalities¾resulting from traffic collisions, falls, drownings, and burns¾through the application of environmental strategies (Holder and Saltz 1988).  Five interacting and supporting components provide the framework for the set of comprehensive community-based interventions developed for this project.  These five components are the following:  (1) community knowledge, values, and mobilization; (2) responsible beverage service; (3) reduction of underage drinking; (4) risk of drinking and driving; and (5) access to alcohol.  This report provides information on the role of the coalition, structures to provide real community input, benefits and advantages of research-oriented projects, disadvantages and deterrents of research-driven projects, contributions to the project only the community can make, political realities that must be addressed, and working with multicultural groups.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Methodological Issues in Community-Based Alcohol-Related Injury Prevention Projects:  Attribution of Program Effects<BR>
<I>Putnam, S.L.; Rockett, I.R.H.; and Campbell, M.K.</I></B><BR>
In:  <I>Experiences with Community Action Projects:  New Research in the Prevention of Alcohol and Other Drug Problems, CSAP Prevention Monograph-14, </I>T. K. Greenfield, R. Zimmerman, Eds., pp. 32-42. Rockville, MD:  Center for Substance Abuse Prevention, 1993<BR>
(Available from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD  20847-2345. Inventory Code:  BKD87.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This report looks at the Rhode Island Community Alcohol Abuse/Injury Prevention Project (RICAAIPP), an epidemiologic research project with a prevention intervention component.  The project's goals were to establish a model/demonstration project to conduct an indepth epidemiologic study of selected risk factors for adverse, health-related outcomes of alcohol use in each of two communities in a State.  The alcohol-related health outcomes to be influenced were confined to injuries, specifically assault injuries and motor vehicle crash injuries.  Results showed increases in intervention community arrest rates, as a result of increased police enforcement.  There also were decreases in intervention community emergency room injury rates, especially assault and motor vehicle crash injury rates, along with decreased head injury visit rates, which were probable program effects.  The report concludes that injury reduction can be accomplished through primary and secondary prevention related to server training and police training, technical assistance, and enforcement programs.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Position Papers from the Third National Injury Control Conference:  Setting the National Agenda for Injury Control in the 1990s</B><BR>
U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health Service, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 1992
<BLOCKQUOTE>The concern and interest of the American public, policy makers, and public health professionals have increasingly focused on the problem of injury, including the high number of deaths and disabilities and the enormous costs, both human and financial, to our country.  As part of this increased focus, the Committee on Trauma Research and the Institute of Medicine, in the Injury in America report, and subsequently, the Secretary's Advisory Committee for Injury Prevention and Control called for a national plan to control injuries.  As the first step in developing such a plan, the National Center for Environmental Health and Injury Control and the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) have spent more than a year facilitating the development of the position papers in this book.  The plan will help shape the future of injury control research, programs, and policies for this decade.  The seven position papers serve to (a) define the field of injury control; (b) assess the current status of injury control research and programs; (c) help CDC, other Federal agencies, and nongovernmental organizations clearly define directions and priorities in a coordinated way; (d) identify what interventions should be evaluated and disseminated; (e) plan for the development of injury control program capacity in State and local health departments and other agencies; and (f) identify organizations and opportunities for carrying out various research and programmatic recommendations.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Office of Inspector General:  General Reports on Youth and Alcohol<BR>
Report, U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, 1991</B><BR>
(Available from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD  20847-2345.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This report provides the results of three surveys presented to the U.S. Surgeon General on youth and alcohol.  The first survey, Youth and Alcohol:  A National Survey.  Drinking Habits, Access, Attitudes, and Knowledge, surveyed junior and senior high school students (grades 7 to 12) to determine how they obtain, view, and consume alcohol.  The second survey, Youth and Alcohol:  A National Survey.  Do They Know What They're Drinking?, surveyed the same age group to determine their knowledge about alcoholic and non-alcoholic beverages.  The third survey, Youth and Alcohol:  Laws and Enforcement.  Is the 21-Year-Old Drinking Age a Myth?, examined current State laws and regulations governing youth access to alcohol and how these laws are enforced.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Injury Prevention:  Meeting the Challenge.  National Committee for Injury Prevention and Control</B><BR>
New York:  Oxford University Press, 1989<BR>
(Available from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD 20847-2345. Inventory Code:  BK156.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This book focuses on current knowledge about and strategies for preventing injuries.  The content of the book was provided by the 31-member National Committee for Injury Prevention and Control.  The book is divided into three parts.  The first part is a primer on identifying, strengthening, and using existing resources.  Part two is a report on the state-of-the-art and knowledge in regard to major determinants of injuries.  Part three describes the community response to persons who are severely injured.  Among the topics covered are traffic, residential, recreational, and occupational injuries; child abuse; domestic violence; elder abuse; rape and sexual assault; suicide; and firearm injuries.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Effect of Legal Drinking Age on Fatal Injuries of Adolescents and Young Adults<BR>
<I>Jones, N.E.; Pieper, C.F.; and Robertson, L.S.</I></B><BR>
American Journal of Public Health </I>82(1):112-115, 1991<BR>
(Available from Nancy E. Jones, Hunter College, Hunter-Bellevue School of Nursing, 425 East 25th Street, New York, NY 10010.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This study examined the effect of legal drinking age (LDA) on fatal injuries in persons ages 15 to 24 years in the United States between 1979 and 1984.  Effects on pre-LDA teens, adolescents targeted by LDA, initiation at LDA, and post-LDA drinking experience were assessed.  A higher LDA was also associated with reduced death rates for motor vehicle drivers, pedestrians, unintentional injuries excluding motor vehicle injuries, and suicide.  An initiation effect on homicides was identified.  Reductions in injury deaths related to drinking experience were not found.  In general, a higher LDA reduced deaths among adolescents and young adults for various categories of violent death.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol and Attempted Suicide<BR>
<I>Merrill, J.; Milner, G.; Owens, J.; and Vale, A.</I></B><BR>
<I>British Journal of Addiction </I>87(1):83-89, 1992<BR>
(Available from Dr. John Merrill, Consultant in Drug Dependence, Prestwich Hospital, Regional Drug Dependence Service, Bury New Road, Prestwich, Manchester M25 7BL United Kingdom.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This study investigates the prevalence of excessive drinking and alcohol-related problems among suicide attempts.  It also compares the characteristics of attempted suicide by alcohol consumption groups.  Drinking histories were taken on 250 consecutive attempted suicides admitted to the West Midlands Poison Unit.  Fifty-one percent of the men and 31 percent of the women drank more than the weekly limits recommended by the Health Education Council.  Of the men, 22.5 percent drank more than 50 units of alcohol a week, and 9.5 percent of the women drank more than 35 units of alcohol a week.  Alcohol-related problems (social problems, alcohol dependence, or physical illness) were present in 34 percent of men and 15.5 percent of women.  These results show a greater incidence of alcohol misuse than previous studies on attempted suicide.  This is probably because detailed alcohol histories were taken on all patients.  Alcohol misuse is best treated before major alcohol-related problems develop.  Those responsible for assessing cases of attempted suicide should be adept at detecting alcohol misuse and instituting appropriate management.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Parental Alcohol Use, Problem Drinking and Children's Injuries<BR>
<I>Bijur, P.E.; Kurzon, M.; Overpeck, M.D.; and Scheidt, P.C.</I></B><BR>
<I>JAMA:  Journal of the American Medical Association </I>267(23):3166-3171, 1992
<BLOCKQUOTE>Millions of U.S.  children are exposed to parents who are problem drinkers, yet there is little evidence about the effect of parental alcohol consumption on children's health.  The aim of this study was to assess the association between children's injuries and parental drinking.  Data for this study was collected through a nationally representative sample of the U.S. population by household interview.  The participants were 12,360 children and parents from single-family households, with data from the Alcohol and Child Health supplements to the 1988 National Health Interview Survey.  Serious injuries ¾ injuries resulting in hospitalization, surgical treatment, any time missed from school, or one half day or more in bed ¾ were used as the major outcome for this study.  Children of mothers categorized as problem drinkers had 2.1 times the risk of serious injury as children of mothers who were nondrinkers (95 percent CI, 1.3 to 3.5).  Other measures of mothers' alcohol consumption (i.e., average, maximum, and self-rated consumption) were unrelated to child injuries, as were all measures of fathers' drinking.  Children of women who were problem drinkers married to men rated as moderate or heavy drinkers had a relative risk of serious injury of 2.7 (95 percent CI, 0.8 to 8.6) compared with children of nondrinkers.  Children of women who are problem drinkers have an elevated injury risk; children with two parents who are problem drinkers are at higher risk.  Further research is needed on potential mechanisms and interventions.  Primary prevention might be enhanced if physicians elicited information about parental drinking, helped secure appropriate treatment, and participated in public health efforts to reduce the deleterious effects of alcohol.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Position Papers from the Third National Injury Control Conference:  Setting the National Agenda for Injury Control in the 1990s. Prevention of Violence and Injuries Due to Violence</B><BR>
Conference Paper, U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health Service, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, National Center for Environmental Health and Injury Control, Division of Injury Control, Denver, CO, April 22 - 25, 1991. pp. 161-254
<BLOCKQUOTE>An agenda is presented for reducing injuries and death due to interpersonal violence and suicidal behavior.  The dimensions of the health problem due to self-directed and interpersonal violence are reviewed.  The complexity of the etiology of injuries due to violence is discussed.  The potential for progress, through the application of public health perspectives and principles, to the prevention of intentional injuries is examined.  There is a need for a coordinated approach and structure for planning and implementing a comprehensive violence prevention effort.  Four areas of emphasis are discussed:  (1) injuries from firearm violence; (2) alcohol and other drug use and violence; (3) early childhood experiences that affect the risk of future violent behavior or victimization; and (4) treatable mental disorders associated with an increased risk of suicide.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Homicide:  Drinking by the Victim<BR>
<I>Welte, J.W., and Abel, E.L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Studies on Alcohol </I>50(3):197-201, 1989
<BLOCKQUOTE>A comparison was made between homicides in which the victim had either been drinking or had not been drinking.  Medical examiner records for 792 homicides in Erie County, New York from 1972 through 1984 were used.  A logistic regression found that in a significantly higher proportion of certain types of homicides there was alcohol in the victim's blood:  male victims, victims ages 30-49, homicides that occur in the warmer months and in the evening or at night, homicides not related to another crime, stabbings, and homicides that take place in bars and restaurants.  Some circumstances associated with a very high likelihood of alcohol in the victim's blood were:  men killed at night, men killed by women, African-American male victims, and all killings on Saturday or Sunday nights.  These results suggest that a high likelihood of alcohol in victims is associated with circumstances that make drinking more likely (e.g., male victims, homicide at night), but also alcohol is more likely to be present in homicides that arise spontaneously from personal disputes.  It was also found that there is a higher likelihood of alcohol in the victim for homicides that occur during time periods when there are more homicides.  It is suggested that in some cases the alcohol may be a causal factor in the homicide.  10 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol Use and Homicide Victimization:  An Examination of Racial/Ethnic Differences<BR>
<I>Goodman, R.A.; Mercy, J.A.; and Rosenberg, M.L.</I></B><BR>
In:  <I>Alcohol Use Among U.S. Ethnic Minorities Research Monograph No. 18.</I> D. Spiegler, D. Tate, Aitken, S., Christian, C. (Eds.), pp. 191-204. Rockville, MD:  NIAAA, Department of Health and Human Services, 1989<BR>
(Available from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD 20847-2345.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Alcohol use may play an important causal role in homicide.  However, information characterizing the association between alcohol use and homicide victimization within specific racial/ethnic groups is limited.  To characterize the relationship, data from the Los Angeles City Police Department and the Los Angeles Medical Examiner's Office were used to study victims of criminal homicides in Los Angeles during the period 1970-1979.  Alcohol was detected in the blood of 1,733 (49 percent) of the 3,551 victims ages 15 to 64 who were tested.  In 32 percent of those cases tested, the blood alcohol level was equal to or more than 100 mg/100 ml, the level of legal intoxication in most States.  Blood alcohol was present in 39 percent of Whites, 49 percent of Blacks, and 59 percent of Hispanic victims of homicide.  The presence of blood alcohol among racial and ethnic groups also differed, according to situational variables, including the day of the week the homicide occurred and the relationship between the victim and the offender.  These variations emphasize the need to examine situational, socioeconomic, and cultural factors in explaining racial and ethnic differences in alcohol use patterns among homicide victims.  44 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<H3> Other Journals </H3> 
<B>Alcohol and Injuries:  Problems and Responses</B><BR>
<I>Prevention File </I>7(5):2-5, 1992
<BLOCKQUOTE>Injuries cause about 150,000 deaths per year in the United States.  About one-third are from motor vehicle or traffic related injuries, one-third are from intentional injuries, such as homicide and suicide, and one-third are from other unintentional injuries.  For each death, there are hundreds of injuries requiring medical attention.  This article looks at the correlation between alcohol and injuries and states that alcohol is associated with a substantial percentage of car crashes, falls, fires, occupational deaths, assaults, rapes, and attempted suicides.  Several injury prevention proposals are suggested, including strategic ideas, criminal justice recommendations, and policy changes.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Violence and Homicide:  Another Facet of Substance Abuse <BR>
<I>Mendez, G.; Shabazz, W.; Wood, N.P.; Spurlock, J.; and Sutton, R.</I></B><BR>
In:  <I>Proceedings of a National Conference on Preventing Alcohol and Drug Abuse in Black Communities, </I>pp. 111-125. Washington, DC, May 22-24, 1990. 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This article considers violence and homicide as another facet of substance abuse looked at from an Afrocentric view of the world.  In the past, African American people came together to solve their problems collectively, but because this problem-solving technique has been abandoned, African Americans are now experiencing even more problems.  The authors believe that the African-American people need to go back to collectively helping themselves and not depend on the Federal Government or anyone else.  The theme discussed is:  Crime is not part of our African-American heritage.  African-American people are not criminals by tradition, but 10 percent of the people in the African-American community commit 100 percent of the crime.  Traditionally, the African-American community is very religious and hard-working, having to work harder in order to come from slavery to dignity.  In the program described here, successful African-American males who represent positive role models are put in the high-crime areas to share their experiences.  (Programmers also take hard-working men that have dirt under their fingernails back to work with young males.)  These are positive role models that are needed in the African-American communities.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Workplace Drug Abuse Leads to Injuries and Other Job Problems</B><BR>
<I>Narcotics Demand Reduction Digest, </I>December 1990, pp. 7-8
<BLOCKQUOTE>This article reports that while employees who tested positive for marijuana or cocaine use had higher rates of injury in the workplace, the problems may not be as great as previously believed.  A study of 2,537 applicants for postal workers' jobs showed that those who tested positive for marijuana had 55 percent more accidents, 85 percent more injuries, and 56 percent more turnover.  Those who tested positive for cocaine had 59 percent more accidents, 85 percent more injuries, and 15 percent more turnover.  A brief overview of literature discussing the prediction of outcome from drug screening is included.  The study lacked information about the relationship of alcohol use to job injuries and accidents.  Several statistics about accidents, absenteeism, injury, and turnover are cited, compared, and discussed.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Adolescent Suicide and Drugs <BR>
<I>Gold, M.S.</I></B><BR>
<I>Addiction and Recovery, </I>March/April 1991, p. 15
<BLOCKQUOTE>The author notes that one-third of all suicide victims have a history of substance abuse, and that the percentage is higher among teenage suicides.  The author contends that many of the fatal, alcohol-related automobile crashes and deaths caused by drowning, fire, and homicide are actually teenage suicides.  Alcohol-related crashes are the leading killer of youths ages 15 to 24 and about half of the other deaths are alcohol- or other drug-related.  The author explains that youth often view substance use as a way of being accepted when, in reality, alcohol and drugs increase a sense of isolation.  Statistics about teenage use are cited from a Parent's Resource Institute for Drug Education (PRIDE) survey.  Strategies to lower the risk of suicide and drug use are described via PRIDE surveys taken before and after a media campaign.  Exposure to anti-drug messages consistently affected people's attitudes in a year, with the greatest change in college students.  A prevention program implemented by the National Institute on Drug Abuse in a Kansas City high school also had a great impact on teenage drug use.  The author suggests that suicide prevention programs take the same tactics of educating and helping youth in avoiding negative outcomes.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol-Related Relative Risk of Fatal Driver Injuries in Relation to Driver Age and Sex<BR>
<I>Zador, P.L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Studies on Alcohol </I>52(4):302-310, 1991<BR>
(Available from Paul L. Zador, Ph.D., Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, 1005 North Glebe Road, Arlington, VA 22201.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>The relative risks of fatal crash involvement at various blood alcohol concentrations (BACs) were examined using data on fatal driver injuries from the Fatal Accident Reporting System in conjunction with driver exposure data from the second national roadside breath-testing survey.  Based on driver fatalities in single-vehicle crashes, it was estimated that each 0.02 percentage increase in the BAC of a driver with non-zero BAC nearly doubles the risk of being in a fatal crash.  Crash risk was found to increase with increasing BAC among all of the six age and sex groups studied.  At BACs in the 0.05-0.09 percent range, the likelihood of a crash was at least nine times greater than at zero BAC for all age groups.  Younger drivers with BACs in the 0.05-0.09 range had higher relative risks than older drivers, and females had higher relative risks than males.  At very high BACs (at or above 0.15 percent), the risk of crashing was 300 to 600 times the risk at zero or near-zero BACs.  These relative risk estimates are considerably higher than estimated in other studies, but other studies have based their estimates on all crashes rather than single-vehicle crashes only.  In this study, relative risks were also lower when based on driver fatalities in all crashes.  However, when plausible assumptions were made about the BAC distributions of other participants in multiple-vehicle crashes (whose actual BAC is often unknown), the relative risks based on the maximum BAC of the crash participants were nearly as high as those estimated in single-vehicle crashes.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol-Related Injuries:  State-of-the-Art in Interventions<BR>
<I>Cohen, S.</I></B><BR>
Conference Paper, Education Development Center, Inc., Center for Health Promotion and Education, Washington, DC, March 23 - 25, 1992<BR>
(Available from Stu Cohen, Education Development Center Inc., Center for Health Promotion and Education, 55 Chapel Street, Newton, MA.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Despite the roles that medicine and criminal justice play in responding to alcohol-related injuries, they cannot solve the problem of isolation.  Reducing the toll of mortality and morbidity is classically a public health problem, requiring a multidisciplinary solution.  Prevention must rely upon a comprehensive array of interventions, drawing upon legislation and enforcement, education and behavior change, and engineering and environmental approaches.  Necessarily, a reduction must be made in alcohol-related motor vehicle crashes and in annual alcohol consumption to reduce the injury caused by drunk drivers.  Many approaches to alcohol-related problems are based upon a theory of availability, which is grounded in an understanding that alcohol is a risk factor for many health problems.  Changes in consumption of alcohol will be accompanied by a change in the prevalence of mortality and morbidity.  Therefore, measures designed to affect overall consumption will have a broad, preventive effect.  Many of these interventions are described, including minimum drinking age laws, alcohol excise tax increases, and dram shop laws.  These are the most promising since they are designed to broadly affect consumption.  113 Ref.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>The Significant 'Other':  Car Crashes Aren't the Only Way Drinking Leads to Injury</B><BR>
<I>Prevention File:  Alcohol, Tobacco and Other Drugs </I>1992, pp. 18-20<BR>
(Available from Alcohol, Tobacco & Other Drug Studies, UCSD Extension, 0176, University of California - San Diego, 9500 Gilman Drive, La Jolla, CA 92093-0176.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>More Americans die from alcohol-related injuries in falls, fires, drownings, shootings, and cases of child abuse, battering, rape, and suicide, than in alcohol-related traffic crashes.  Approximately 23,830 alcohol-related trauma deaths annually have causes other than motor vehicle crashes.  Alcohol involvement in trauma cases is hard to measure, however, and therefore often is overlooked.  Policies vary from one emergency room to another on whether patients are tested for alcohol.  Evidence from a number of studies does exist to support the enormity of this problem.  Some of these study results include:  heavy drinking doubles the risk of fatal injury; 41 percent of deaths resulting from unintentional falls in a Minnesota study involved alcohol; a Maryland study found that alcohol was involved in 47 percent of drownings of persons ages 15 and older; Maryland researchers studying 398 fatal fires found that 40 percent of fire victims had positive blood alcohol concentrations and 85 percent were legally intoxicated; a study in upstate New York reported positive blood alcohol concentrations in 33 percent of persons committing suicide, which suggests that alcohol contributes to impulsive suicides; at a trauma center in Orange County, California, 52 percent of the people injured in fights and 49 percent of those treated for stab wounds had positive blood alcohol concentrations; one study found that more than half of convicted rapists had been drinking at the time of their offense; and there is ample evidence to suggest that alcohol is a significant factor in cases of battering.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Political Approaches to Injury Control at the State Level<BR>
<I>Bergman, A.B. (Ed.)</I></B><BR>
Seattle, WA:  University of Washington Press, 1992, 113 p.
<BLOCKQUOTE>Injuries destroy the health, lives, and livelihoods of millions of people, yet they receive little attention, compared with diseases and other hazards.  Many approaches to control this modern epidemic have been employed, but none have been as efficient or effective as legislation and regulation.  In the traffic safety field, for example, countless lives have been saved by laws mandating the safer design of cars and highways, wearing of seat belts, and swift and certain punishment of drunk drivers.  A diverse group of experts from the fields of law, medicine, insurance, and State government discuss:  (1) defining the most significant injury problems (in terms of morbidity and mortality) amenable to approach through legislation, regulation, and or legal means at the State level, and (2) developing practical implementation strategies and useful data that could be employed at the State level.  Among the legislative issues explored are:  drunk driving; compulsory motorcycle helmets; alcohol taxes and advertising; burn prevention; drowning; and handgun control.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Role of Alcohol in Nonfatal Bicycle Injuries<BR>
<I>Olkkonen, S., and Honkanen, R.</I></B><BR>
<I>Accident Analysis and Prevention </I>22(1):89-96, 1990
<BLOCKQUOTE>To assess the risk of nonfatal bicycle injury related to blood alcohol concentration (BAC) an unmatched case-control study was conducted in Helsinki in 1986.  Eligible cases included 140 adults injured either in motor vehicle or other bicycle crashes that occurred between 3 p.m.  and 10 p.m., who arrived at the hospital within 6 hours of injury.  Seven hundred bicyclists from the street were randomly selected as controls.  BAC was measured with a breathalyzer.  A major difference in alcohol involvement was found between cases (24.1 percent) and control (4.0 percent).  The injury risk estimate (odds ratio) of an inebriated bicyclist was at least 10-fold at BACs above 100 mg/dl compared to a sober bicyclist.  Alcohol increased the bicyclist's risk of injury from falling more than from collision.  As an unprotected road user, an inebriated bicyclist greatly increases personal risk of injury but seldom causes danger to other road users.  28 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Bringing &quotBooze&quot Back In:  Alcohol and Theories of Homicide<BR>
<I>Parker, R.N.</I></B><BR>
Walnut Creek, CA:  Prevention Research Center, 1989, 44 pp.
<BLOCKQUOTE>The relationship between alcohol consumption and homicide is discussed.  Headings within this review of the literature include:  (1) what possible role alcohol plays in the genesis of homicide; (2) economic deprivation, homicide, and alcohol; (3) what role alcohol consumption plays in the deprivation/homicide relationship; (4) subcultures of violence, (5) capital punishment and deterrence; (6) lifestyle and routine activities; and (7) data requirements for testing alcohol integrated theories of homicide.  62 Ref.<BR>
Alcohol's role in causing death and injury was the backdrop of the first Secretary's National Conference on Alcohol-Related Injuries in March 1992.  The conference served as a forum for planning strategies to achieve the objectives regarding alcohol-related injuries contained in Healthy People 2000.  The three papers that follow were among those presented at the conference.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Cost of Alcohol-Related Highway Crashes:  Presentation, Secretary's National Conference on Alcohol-Related Injuries<BR>
<I>Miller, T.</I></B><BR>
Conference Paper, Urban Institute, Washington, DC, March 23-25, 1992<BR>
(Available from Dr. Ted Miller, The Urban Institute 2100 M Street, NW, Washington, DC  20037.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Statistical information is presented in the form of charts and graphs concerning the costs of alcohol-related highway crashes in terms of number of deaths, nonfatal injuries, number of innocent victims, numbers of the partially and totally disabled, number of lost years of life and functioning, amount of medical and property damages, costs to the public, costs to employers, and completed and attempted crimes.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol and Injuries:  Epidemiology and Control<BR>
<I>Wagenaar, A.C.</I></B><BR>
Conference Paper, Healthy People/Healthy Environments:  The Secretary's National Conference on Alcohol-Related Injuries, Washington, DC, March 23 - 25, 1992<BR>
(Available from Alexander C. Wagenaar, Ph.D., School of Public Health, Division of Epidemiology, 1300 South Second Street, Suite 300, Minneapolis, MN  55454-1015.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>There is little question that consumption of alcohol impairs human performance on many tasks and increases the risk of unintentional injury.  The evidence also is clear that drinking increases the chances for interpersonal violence and intentional injury.  Recent literature is reviewed on the rate of involvement of alcohol in diverse injury situations.  Strategies are identified for preventing injuries derived from the field of injury control.  Injury prevention strategies also are identified from the field of criminal justice.  Recent research on selected strategies for preventing injuries from the field of alcohol control are reviewed.  35 Ref.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Relationship of Price, Alcohol Consumption and Injury<BR>
<I>Grossman, M.</I></B><BR>
Conference Paper, Healthy People/Healthy Environments:  The Secretary's National Conference on Alcohol-Related Injuries, Washington, DC, March 23 - 25, 1992<BR>
(Available from Michael Grossman, City University of New York Graduate School, New York, NY  10003.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>If reductions in excessive alcohol consumption and alcohol-related injuries and deaths are desired, an increase in Federal excise tax rates on alcoholic beverages is an effective policy to accomplish this goal.  To justify an excise tax hike of a particular magnitude two things must be considered:  (1) the welfare costs imposed on all segments of the population by excise tax hikes and (2) the costs and benefits of excise tax hikes compared to alternative policies, such as those that increase the probability of punishment for drunken driving and the fine for this offense.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
