<A NAME="Sec1"> <H2>ATOD Resource Guide:  Faith Communities <BR> Section 1 -- Prevention Materials</H2></A>
<BR>

<B>The Circle of Wholeness, Church</B><BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  Book <BR>
Length:  35 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention <BR>
Target Audience:  Community Service Groups and Churches<BR>
Setting:  Religious <BR>
Readability:  Average <BR>
Availability:  $3 plus shipping and handling; The Presbyterian Distribution Management Service; 800-524-2612.<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This curriculum includes six ATOD prevention lessons framed within a Christian context. Lessons focus on addiction, self image, the family, and other related topics.  Four appendixes, which contain additional information and resources, are also included.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Substance Abuse Agency Resources Guide</B><BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  Booklet <BR>
Length:  74 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention <BR>
Target Audience:  Catholics<BR>
Setting:  Religious <BR>
Readability:  Average <BR>
Availability:  $15; Carol Peck, Catholic Charities, USA, 1731 King Street, Suite 200, Alexandria, VA  22314; 703-549-1390 ext. 29<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This guide contains a list of resources designed to help agencies start ATOD prevention programs in their parishes. Catholic and nondenominational resources are listed by agency and category, and an extensive appendix includes assorted fact sheets and promotional items from Catholic resources throughout the country.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol and Other Drugs:  A Planning Guide for Congregations</B><BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  Minnesota Department of Human Services<BR>
Format:  Planning Guide<BR>
Length:  46 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention <BR>
Target Audience:  AOD Prevention Professionals and Congregations<BR>
Setting:  Religious <BR>
Readability:  Average <BR>
Availability:  $7.50 plus $2 shipping and handling; Minnesota Prevention Resource Center, 2829 Verndale Avenue, Anoka, MN  55503; 612-427-5310<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This planning guide is designed to help spiritual and religious organizations address the problem of alcohol and other drug use within their congregations.  Chapters look at ways in which congregations can plan effective AOD prevention programs, and examine model prevention efforts.  Worksheets and checklists are included for assistance.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Technical Assistance and Resource Bulletin:  National Anti-Drug Campaign</B><BR>
Format:  Newsletter <BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention <BR>
Target Audience:  Clergy, Community Service Groups, and Blacks <BR>
Setting:  Religious <BR>
Readability:  Average <BR>
Availability:  Free; The Congress of National Black Churches, Inc., 1225 Eye Street, NW, Suite 750, Washington, DC  20005-3914; 202-371-1091<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This bimonthly newsletter, produced by the Congress of National Black Churches, Inc., keeps readers abreast of current news, events, and resources within CNBC's National Anti-Drug Campaign.  Grant information and prevention articles are included.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Revival of Hope</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  United Methodist Church<BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  Kit includes:  Video, Viewers Guide, Manual, Booklet, Catalog<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  General Public, Religious Communities<BR>
Setting:  Religious Community<BR>
Availability:  $19.95 plus shipping and handling; Cokesbury, United Methodist Publishing House, 201 8th Avenue South, P.O. Box 801, Nashville, TN 37202; 800-672-1789<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This training kit is designed to help congregations and task groups interested in confronting the alcohol and other drug problem within their community. The material provides reasons why the church should get involved in AOD prevention and treatment efforts and offers examples of model church programs.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>When Someone You Love Drinks Too Much:  A Christian Guide to Addiction, Codependence and Recovery</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  Nondenominational<BR>
Year:  1990<BR>
Format:  Book<BR>
Length:  159 Pages<BR>
Context:  Stands Alone<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Mode of Delivery:  Self-Instructional<BR>
Target Audience:  Women, General Public, and Christians<BR>
Availability:  $9 plus $2.75 shipping and handling; Harper Collins Publishing, P.O. Box 588, Dumare, PA  18512; 800-331-3761<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This book provides extensive information for those affected by a loved one's drinking. Feelings of denial, anger, guilt, and depression are explored, and suggestions are offered on ways of improving one's codependent situation. All information is framed in a Christian context, with frequent mentions of Jesus Christ and the New Testament.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Turning Awareness Into Action:  What Your Community Can Do About Drug Use in America</B><BR>
Organization:  Center for Substance Abuse Prevention<BR>
Year:  1989<BR>
Format:  Book<BR>
Length:  68 Pages<BR>
Context:  Stands Alone<BR>
Topic:  Prevention in the Community<BR>
Target Audience:  Community Service Groups, Educators, and Parents<BR>
Setting:  Community<BR>
Language:  English and Spanish<BR>
Inventory no.:  PHD519<BR>
Availability:  Free; National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD  20847; 800-729-6686<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This booklet gives examples of community-based drug prevention programs, and offers suggestions on what groups and individuals can do to make their neighborhoods drug-free. Specific guidelines are presented for businesses, religious communities, health care systems, civic groups, and others. Government and private resources are also listed for additional help and information.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Is There an Elephant in Your Sanctuary?</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  Presbyterian Church<BR>
Format:  VHS Video<BR>
Length:  16 Minutes<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug and Prevention/Faith Community<BR>
Target Audience:  Faith Community Service Groups<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Availability:  $19.95 plus $2.90 shipping and handling; Office of Health Ministries, Social Justice and Peacemaking Ministry Unit, 100 Witherspoon Street, Room 3060, Louisville, KY  40202; 502-569-5793<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This video uses a pink elephant amidst the congregation as a metaphor for the alcoholic church-goer.  It instructs the clergy to recognize and address the problem of AOD abuse within their congregation, and demonstrates how churches can come together to help alleviate the problem within their communities. The 12-Step program is presented as an effective model.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>The Bible and Alcohol</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  Nondenominational<BR>
Format:  Fact Sheet<BR>
Length:  4 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  General Public<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Readability:  Fairly Difficult<BR>
Availability:  Free; Alabama Citizens Action Program, 2376 Lakeside Drive, Birmingham, AL  35244; 205-985-9062<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The cover of this small pamphlet shows a sword cutting through an alcohol bottle, and reads, &quot;The Word of God speaks with striking forcefulness against the evil of drinking.  The truth concerning this evil cannot be ignored or escaped.&quot;  Inside, 47 biblical admonitions against the use of alcohol are listed.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>AIDS:  A Catholic Educational Approach</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  National Catholic Educational Association<BR>
Year:  1992<BR>
Format:  Teacher's Manual<BR>
Length:  165 Pages<BR>
Context:  Stands Alone and Part of a Packet/Program<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  Educators<BR>
Setting:  School, Religious <BR>
Readability:  Fairly Difficult<BR>
Availability:  $12.50; National Catholic Educational Association, 1077 30th Street, NW, Washington, DC  20007-3852; 202-337-6232<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This teacher's manual is designed to provide AIDS education within a Catholic context.  Developmentally appropriate lessons include information on prevention, transmission, and symptoms of HIV and AIDS. Children are also encouraged to treat those who are already HIV-positive with compassion and care.  The manual is accompanied by a leader's guide.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol Use and Abuse:  The Social and Health Effects</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  Presbyterian Church<BR>
Year:  1986<BR>
Format:  Booklet<BR>
Length:  68 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  Alcohol/Drug Prevention Professionals and Parents<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Readability:  Average<BR>
Availability:  $2.50 plus $1 shipping and handling; Office of Health Ministries, Social Justice and Peacemaking Ministry Unit, 100 Witherspoon Street, Room 3060, Louisville, KY  40202; 502-569-5793<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This booklet contains two reports:  &quot;Report and Recommendations on the Social and Health Effects of Alcohol Use and Abuse&quot; submitted by the Presbyterian Church's Advisory Council on Church and Society, and &quot;Implementation of an Expanded Church-wide Address to Alcohol Related Problems,&quot; a joint report of the General Assembly Mission Board and the Program Agency of the Presbyterian Church.  Presbyterian attitudes about alcohol, alcohol and public policy, and the effects of alcohol on the body are addressed.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>The Congregation:  A Community of Care and Healing</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  Presbyterian Church<BR>
Year:  1990<BR>
Format:  Booklet<BR>
Length:  24 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  General Public and Congregation<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Readability:  Average<BR>
Availability:  $2.50 plus $1 shipping and handling; Office of Health Ministries, Social Justice and Peacemaking Unit, 100 Witherspoon Street, Room 3060, Louisville, KY  40202; 502-569-5793<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This booklet features several articles that address ways in which the Presbyterian Church can assist in the prevention and treatment of alcohol and other drug use among its congregants.  The role of Alcoholics Anonymous, a needs assessment survey, and a listing of symptoms that may indicate an AOD problem are among the articles included.  The 12 steps of AA and the Serenity Prayer are also mentioned.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Get'em Talking:  104 Great Discussion Starters for Youth Groups</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  Nondenominational<BR>
Year:  1989<BR>
Format:  Book<BR>
Length:  160 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Mode of Delivery:  Instructor-led<BR>
Target Audience:  Sr. High Youth<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Readability:  Easy<BR>
Availability:  $10.95 plus shipping and handling; Youth Specialties, 1224 Greenfield Drive, El Cajon, CA  92021; 800-776-8008<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This training manual for discussion leaders provides step-by-step instructions for engaging youth in Christian-based group conversations. Topics include alcohol and other drugs, conformity, goals, decision-making, morals, peer approval, personal problems, and self worth.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Option Plays:  Sixty Creative Dilemmas to Help Your Kids Learn Effective Decision Making</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  Nondenominational<BR>
Year:  1990<BR>
Format:  Book<BR>
Length:  116 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Mode of Delivery:  Instructor-led<BR>
Target Audience:  Sr. High Youth and Educators<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Readability:  Easy<BR>
Availability:  $10.95 plus $4 shipping and handling; Youth Specialties, 1224 Greenfield Drive, El Cajon, CA  92021; 800-776-8008<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This book provides kids with real life scenarios that replicate experiences that they have either already gone through or may face sometime in their future.  Each scenario focuses on one or more of a wide range of issues, including alcohol or other drugs, impaired driving, and peer pressure.  Discussion leaders may present any of the 60 dilemmas and the youth group is encouraged to discuss and explore the options that they feel most appropriate.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Talksheet:  Fifty Creative Discussions for Junior High Youth Groups</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  Nondenominational<BR>
Year:  1988<BR>
Format:  Book<BR>
Length:  112 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  Educators and Jr. High Youth<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Readability:  Easy<BR>
Availability:  $10.95 plus $4 shipping and handling; Youth Specialties, 1224 Greenfield Drive, El Cajon, CA 92021; 800-776-8008<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This publication serves as a discussion guide for youth group leaders. Each talksheet includes discussion starters that can also be used as curriculum. Issues addressed include alcohol and other drugs, self-esteem, peer pressure, temptation, advertising, decision-making, values and behavior, stress, and suicide. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Ten for Today</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  B'nai B'rith Commission on Community Volunteer Services<BR>
Year:  1990<BR>
Format:  Brochure<BR>
Length:  8 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  General Public<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Readability:  Easy<BR>
Availability:  Free; B'nai B'rith Commission on Community Volunteer Services (CVS), 1640 Rhode Island Avenue, NW, Washington, DC,  20036; 202-857-6582<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This brochure describes 10 community service projects in which B'nai B'rith volunteers are involved.  One such activity is working to help prevent AOD abuse across the country.  The pamphlet states that, &quot;Many Americans consider drug and alcohol abuse to be the Number One problem in our society today,&quot; and it encourages everyone to get involved in this preventive effort.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Parent Power:  Keeping Our Kids Drug Free</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  B'nai B'rith International<BR>
Format:  Booklet<BR>
Length:  17 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  General Public and Parents of children ages 12-19<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Readability:  Easy<BR>
Availability:  $1; B'nai B'rith International, 1640 Rhode Island Avenue, NW, Washington, DC  20036; 202-857-6582<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This manual provides parents with facts, skills, and tips to help keep their children off drugs.  Beating peer pressure, signs of alcohol and other drug use, and what to do if you suspect substance abuse are all among the topics addressed.  A description of similar material available from other resources, a 12-step program designed for parents, and a listing of State organizations and national hotlines are also included.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Religion and Health</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  The Church of Jesus Christ Latter-day Saints<BR>
Year:  1990<BR>
Format:  Audio Tape<BR>
Length:  30 Minutes<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  General Public<BR>
Setting:  Religious and Home<BR>
Availability:  $1 (plus $2 phone charge if ordered by phone); Salt Lake Distribution Center, 1999 West 1700 South, Salt Lake City, UT 84104; 800-537-5950<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This audiocassette discusses the link between religious practice and bodily health.  Because many religions believe the body is sacred, effort is taken to keep it healthy and fit.  Several religions are mentioned, including Seventh-day Adventists, Mormons, Buddhists, Jews, and Christians.  Diet, exercise, and AOD use are discussed in terms of the religious-health connection.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>On Line with Jesus Christ</B><BR>
Sponsor/Endorser:  United Methodist Church<BR>
Year:  1991<BR>
Format:  Booklet<BR>
Length:  64 Pages<BR>
Topic:  Alcohol and Other Drug Problem Prevention<BR>
Target Audience:  Educators, Youth Age 11 to 14, and Ministers<BR>
Setting:  Religious<BR>
Readability:  Fairly Difficult<BR>
Availability:  Free; The United Methodist Publishing House, 201 8th Avenue South, PO Box 801, Nashville, TN 37202; 800-672-1789; 615-749-6068<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This booklet contains excerpts from three publications that make up the &quot;On Line with Jesus Christ&quot; program. The program is targeted to 11 to 14 year olds and is designed to help prevent or stop at-risk behavior. The model connects faith with skills and relationships to address some of the practical needs of adolescents. Activities focus on building confidence, God's role in one's life, decisions and feelings, families, friendships, service, and goals for the future.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<IMG SRC="faithl.gif">
<A NAME="Sec2"> <H2>ATOD Resource Guide:  Faith Communities <BR> Section 2 -- Studies, Articles, and Reports </H2></A>
<BR>

<H3>Government Publications and Journal Articles</H3>

<B>Alcohol, Drug, and Mental Health Problems among Jewish and Christian Men at a University<BR>
<I>Monteiro, M.G., and Schuckit, M.A.</I></B><BR>
<I>American Journal of Drug and Alcohol Abuse</I> 15(4):403-412, 1989<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Data from a questionnaire sent to 704 male university students and nonacademic staff were re-analyzed to compare self-reports of drug and alcohol intake patterns and problems as well as family histories of psychiatric disorders for Jewish (N=110, Group 1) and Christian men (N=594, Group 2). Although the two groups did not differ significantly on the quantity and frequency of alcohol intake, men in Group 2 were more likely to report at least one episode of heavy drinking and alcohol-related problems, and their responses indicated a higher rate of a family history of alcoholism.  There were no differences across the groups on the proportion of lifetime drug use and related difficulties, or on the family histories of other psychiatric disorders.  The results are consistent with previous studies demonstrating a lower prevalence of heavy drinking and related problems among Jews.  44 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Effects of Religiosity on Adolescent Self-Reported Frequency of Drug and Alcohol Use<BR>
<I>Cochran, J. K.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Drug Issues</I> 22(1):91-104, 1991<BR>
(Available from Dr. John K. Cochran, Department of Sociology, Norman, OK 73019.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Homogeneous effects cumulative logistic regression is used to examine the effects of personal religiosity on adolescent self-reported frequency of drug and alcohol use.  Survey data from a sample of 3,065 male and female adolescents in grades 7 through 12 in three midwestern States are employed. While the existence of an inverse religiosity-substance use relationship is well documented, questions still exist concerning the nature of these relationships.  A review of the literature reveals three rival hypotheses concerning variation in the strength of these relationships across drug types:  the Anti-Asceticism hypothesis, which predicts stronger relationships among the &quot;softer&quot; drug types; the moral condemnated hypothesis which predicts stronger relationships among the &quot;harder&quot; drugs; and the Hellfire hypothesis, which predicts stable effects across drug types. These data provide strong support for the more general Hellfire hypothesis, with equivalent parameter estimates for the effects of religiosity observed for each drug type.  However, slightly weaker effects are observed for adolescent use of alcohol.  29 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Religion and Drug Use<BR>
<I>Hawks, R. D., and Bahr, S. H.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Drug Education</I> 22(1):1-8, 1992<BR>
(Available from R.D. Hawks, Weber Co. Substance Abuse, 2650 Lincoln Avenue, Ogden, UT 84401.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This study is a secondary analysis of data gathered under the sponsorship of the Utah State Division of Alcoholism and Drugs in 1989.  The researchers concluded that there is a difference in frequency of alcohol use, source of alcohol, and age of first alcohol use among Latter Day Saints (LDS), Other Religions and No Religions subgroups.  There is no significant difference found among the various religious subgroups for age of first marijuana use and quantity of alcohol use.  For all religions except Jewish, a lower percentage of Utahns used alcohol than their national counterparts.  A theoretical model for LDS drug use is presented.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Prevention Models for Black Youth at High Risk:  Family and Religion<BR>
<I>Rashid, H.; Brock, R.; Key, A.; Amuleru-Marshall, O.; and Meehan, S.</I></B><BR>
In <I>Ecology of Alcohol and Other Drug Use:  Helping Black High Risk Youth, OSAP Prevention Monograph No. 7,</I> U. J. Oyemade, D. Brandon-Monye, Eds., pp. 134-150. Rockville, MD:  Office for Substance Abuse Prevention, 1990<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This panel discussion addressed the role in which the family, specifically parents, and the church can play in the prevention of alcohol and other drug use among Black youth. Participants discussed programs developed by parent groups and congregations, and highlighted successes that have resulted.  PARADE--Parents Rally Against the Drug Epidemic¾is one such Washington, DC, based parents' organization which has brought concerned parents together in hopes of eradicating drug use in their neighborhoods.  The Neighborhood Action Coalition for Substance Abuse Prevention, based in Baltimore, is another parent-run organization which, in its 3-year existence, cut the number of community delinquencies from 113 children to 53 children.  Participants stressed the significant role the church has played and can continue to play in this prevention effort for its African American youth.  The Black church serves as a powerful voice in social, religious, advocacy, and spiritual circles.  Influential clergy can serve as organizers for various causes, and the church can sponsor prevention, intervention, and treatment programs for its at  risk and addicted population.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Drinking Habits of Sikh, Hindu, Muslim and White Men in the West Midlands:  Community Survey<BR>
<I>Cochrane, R., and Bal, S.</I></B><BR>
<I>British Journal of Addiction</I> 85(6):759-769, 1990<BR>
(Available from Raymond Cochrane, School of Psychology, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham  B15 2TT, United Kingdom.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Men born in India but living in Britain have higher than expected treatment rates for alcohol-related disorders.  A community survey of random samples of 200 each of Sikh, Hindu, and Muslim men and 200 White English-born men, matched for age, were interviewed using a structural questionnaire containing a retrospective drinking diary. Sikhs were most likely to be regular drinkers, followed by Whites and Hindus.  The very few Muslim men who drank consumed the most alcohol on average.  The frequently reported pattern of an inverse relationship between drinking and age was found for White men but not among Sikhs and Hindus.  In both these groups older men reported consuming more alcohol than younger men.  However, age was confounded with generation:  heavier levels of consumption were reported by Sikhs and Hindus born in India than by Sikhs and Hindus born in Britain.  Among regular drinkers Sikhs had higher average Alcohol Problem Scale Scores than did White men or Hindus.  The highest average scores were recorded for the (few) Muslim regular drinkers (who also consumed the most alcohol).  A clear association with religious observance was found for all three Asian groups and for the White men.  No actively practicing Muslims drank at all, and a relatively small proportion of the other groups who were regular church/temple/mosque attenders drank regularly.  15 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Chemical Dependency in the Jewish Community<BR>
<I>Teller, B.</I></B><BR>
<I>The Counselor</I> May/June 1989<BR>
(Available from <I>The Counselor</I>, 3717 Columbia Pike, Suite 300, Arlington, VA  22204.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The rate of alcohol and other drug abuse (AOD) among Jews is near that of the general population. Contrary to the myth that being Jewish bestows immunity to addictions, AOD abuse is an issue among every segment of the population. This not only encompasses all age groups, but also affects those who maintain various levels of religious observation. Jewish youth are statistically among the most vulnerable to middle class drug abuse (with alcohol as the most popular drug). Jewish families tend to emphasize high achievement and excellence which may result in denial that teens use alcohol or other drugs. Parents may inadvertently encourage alcohol consumption because they fear exposure to illegal drugs. In addition, there are special problems for observant Jews who are alcoholics in that non-Jewish treatment facilities often seem unfamiliar and unfriendly settings and do not provide kosher food.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Jewish Drinking Practices:  Implications for Prevention<BR>
<I>Gressard, C.F., and Bainwol, S.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Alcohol and Drug Education</I> 33(2):67-75, 1988<BR>
(Available from Charles F. Gressard, Department of Counselor Education, University of Virginia, Charlottesville, VA  22903.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Jews have long been recognized for their moderate drinking practices and for their low rates of alcohol problems. It is the purpose of this article to review the body of literature on Jewish drinking, extract the factors that appear to provide Jews with their &quot;immunity,&quot; and discuss how these factors may be applied to prevention programs. 17 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<H3>Other Publications</H3>

<B>No Hiding Place:  Empowerment and Recovery for Our Troubled Communities<BR>
<I>Williams, C.</I></B><BR>
New York:  Harper Collins Publishers, 1992<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Reverend Cecil Williams tells the story of the efforts and successes of his Glide Memorial Church in San Francisco.  Seeking to improve the drug-infested lives of Tenderloin district residents, and decrying the drug trade as an agent of genocide for African Americans, Williams developed an innovative recovery program which shows how Black history and spiritual, religious, and cultural values provide vital tools for resisting and overcoming the slavery of drugs.  The result is a community in recovery where crack addicts are giving up their pipes, where abused women are coming to heal their pain, and abusive men are letting go of their rage.  Williams demonstrates how other communities can model his endeavors, and likewise eradicate the drug trade from their neighborhoods.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Beyond Hellfire:  Exploration of the Variable Effects of Religiosity on Adolescent Marijuana and Alcohol Use<BR>
<I>Cochran, J.K., and Akers, R.L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Research in Crime and Delinquency</I> 26(3):198-225, 1989<BR>
(Available from Dr. John K. Cochran, Department of Sociology, University of Oklahoma, Norman, OK  73019.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Since its original formulation in 1969 by Hirschi and Stark, the Hellfire hypothesis has undergone several significant revisions. This hypothesis asserts that involvement in deviant behavior is inversely related to religiosity. Early revisions of this hypothesis stressed the importance of religiosity on violations of ascetic norms over violations of secular norms. More recent revisions have stressed the interactive effects of religiosity and contextual factors such as denominational norms and aggregate religiosity. Each of these respecifications of the original Hellfire hypothesis is evaluated here with survey data on self-reported alcohol and marijuana use from a sample of 3,065 male and female adolescents in grades 7 through 12 in three midwestern states. Results suggest that most of these revisions are only marginally more useful than the original formulation for explaining adolescent alcohol consumption and are largely irrelevant with regard to marijuana use. We find that the more parsimonious proposition of a direct religiosity effect alone does about as well in explaining alcohol and marijuana use among adolescents as the more complex contextual propositions. 68 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Our Overlooked Resource<BR>
<I>Smith, D.</I></B><BR>
<I>Alcoholism and Addiction</I>, November 1989<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This article discusses the role that the clergy can play in education and referral for their congregations. The spiritual aspects of chemical dependency have frequently been dismissed by the lay public as unimportant or even non-existent. However, the clergy have also faced the natural reluctance of parishioners to reveal the existence of substance abuse within their families. Therefore, clergy have been overlooked as a resource in the battle against alcohol and other drug abuse. Currently, perceptions are changing both inside and outside the church and religious and civic leaders have begun to recognize the value of working together to seek solutions to this problem. A survey of 101 clergy found that the majority agreed to help in this area; however, they all requested more information to help them recognize substance abuse problems. The clergy stated that they see the results of substance abuse when ministering to broken families, troubled youth and the homeless. The response of this study provided the framework for the Interfaith Council's first clergy outreach program, a day-long conference titled:  &quot;The Clergy and Substance Abuse:  Ministering to Your Congregation and Community&quot; The program was tailored to meet the needs expressed by the clergy in the study.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcoholics & Their Families:  Guide for Clergy & Congregations<BR>
<I>Keller, J.E.</I></B><BR>
New York:  Harper Collins Publishers, 1991<BR>
(Available from Harper Collins Publishers, 10 East 53rd Street, New York, NY  10022.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The author examines the following issues:  what the clergy need to know about alcoholics and their families; the most common misconceptions about alcoholism; how to distinguish between social drinking and problem drinking; alcoholism as a moral weakness versus alcoholism as a disease; and Alcoholics Anonymous -- its effectiveness and how it works. The author also discusses the key issues facing pastors and church members, including:  identifying alcoholism's progressive symptoms, counseling for alcoholics and family members, treatment programs, intervention, and aftercare. He introduces the idea of a Support Team Ministry within the congregation, a church-connected network that raises awareness through education and that can help provide vital information on treatment programs. Tips are offered on how to begin such a group locally staffed with volunteers.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Creating a Safe Place:  Christians Healing from the Hurt of Dysfunctional Families<BR>
<I>Grayson, C., and Johnson, J.</I></B><BR>
San Francisco:  Harper Collins Publishers, 1991<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The classic symptoms of dysfunctional families are examined. Ways in which dysfunction permeates a family and breaks down communication and leaves family members feeling isolated and anxious are illustrated. Dysfunctional families are characterized by three rules of denial:  don't talk, don't trust, and don't feel. This denial often fuels the problem and keeps the cycle going. Ironically, children who grow up in dysfunctional families often repeat the patterns they learned as children, creating an unhealthy cycle. Ways in which Christians can help to heal themselves, breaking free from past problems and finding their inner child, are outlined. Recovery groups and church-sponsored programs are advocated for fostering recovery. Guidelines are presented for fostering recovery and starting a support group for adult children of dysfunctional families.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Binding the Wounds:  Religious Response to Teenage Drug/Alcohol Abuse<BR>
<I>Black, H.</I></B><BR>
<I>Adolescent Counselor</I> 1(3):27-28, 45-46, 1988<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The alcohol and other drug problem among adolescents has become so critical that churches and synagogues throughout the United States have adopted successful programs to deal with this problem among young people, as well as adults. Many others are still seeking answers to this dilemma of substance abuse among the faithful. Among those groups who have established successful programs are the Assemblies of God, Youth for Christ, and the Texas Conference of Churches.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Church, Youth, Alcohol and Education Programs and Youth Substance Use<BR>
<I>Lorch, B.R., and Hughes, R.H.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Alcohol and Drug Education</I> 33(2):14-26, 1988<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>A questionnaire survey was administered to 237 church pastors and leaders in a western city to determine church attitudes and policies concerning alcohol and other drug (AOD) use and the extent and nature of their church alcohol and other drug education programs.  The results indicate that fundamentalist religious groups were the greatest deterrent to youth substance use. The substance use education programs reflect negative attitudes toward alcohol and other drugs and forbid their use.  Religious groups at the liberal end of the fundamentalism-liberalism scale, were the most effective in preventing <I>heavy</I> substance use. Their substance abuse education programs are more accepting of alcohol and other drugs and tend to provide guidelines for their use.  The results appear to indicate that although forbidding young people to use alcohol or other drugs may be a satisfactory deterrent for substance use, having guidelines for use of AOD may help prevent young people from becoming <I>heavy</I> users.  It is suggested that prevention of substance use and abuse could be more successfully achieved by the church if more churches provided substance use education programs.  23 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Minister Equipped for Facilitating Alcoholism Recovery in and through a Christian Church:  A Journey<BR>
<I>Scarem, R.H. Jr.</I></B><BR>
<I>Dissertation Abstracts International</I> 49(9):2693-A<BR>
(Available from UMI, 300 North Zeeb Road, Ann Arbor, MI 48106.   Refer to #DA8825363.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The purpose of this dissertation is to set forth the problems of alcoholism recovery in the context of the family. Discussion is framed around the author's experience as a semi-recovered alcoholic and through studies in Pastoral Care Concentration in the Doctor of Ministry Program at the Fuller Theological Seminary.  The minister understands alcoholism and alcoholism recovery and can pave the way for alcoholic families to find a climate of acceptance and understanding within the local congregation.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Religious Involvement and Practices Concerning the Use of Alcohol among Black Adolescents<BR>
<I>Neal, A.A.</I></B><BR>
<I>Dissertation Abstracts International</I> 49(10):4256-B - 4257-B, 1989<BR>
(Available from UMI, 300 North Zeeb Road, Ann Arbor, MI 48106.  Refer to #DA8828041.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The purpose of the study was to investigate the relationship between the Black male adolescent's use of alcohol and (1) his own church involvement, and (2) the church involvement of significant others. The subjects of the investigation were 139 Black male adolescents age 12 to 15 in a southeastern State. All came from families meeting Federal guidelines for low income families, and all claimed membership in or affiliation with the Baptist denomination.  More than half of the subjects (60.5 percent) reported attending church once a week or more and 63.3 percent reported that they never drank alcoholic beverages.  The survey instrument used was a self-report questionnaire (Neal's Alcohol Attitudes Questionnaire) administered to the subjects.  Items were designed to measure the adolescent's alcohol use; father's, mother's, and best friend's church attendance; and attitudes toward religion, father, mother, and alcohol.  The findings were discussed in the light of previous research, including Fishbein's model of behavioral intentions, and were found to be consistent with that research. The importance of the father as a role model for adolescent sons in Black families versus the mother was verified. The findings also indicate that the adolescent's own church attendance influences his/her decision regarding alcohol use more than the church attendance of parents or best friends.  </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Buddhist, Hindu and Islamic Influence on Alcohol<BR>
<I>Samarasinghe, D.S.</I></B><BR>
In <I>Alcohol in Developing Countries:  Proceedings from a Meeting in Oslo, Norway, August 7-9, 1988</I>, J. Maula, M. Lindblad, C. Tigerstedt, L. Green-Rutanen, Eds. pp. 231-233. Helsinki, Finland:  Nordic Council for Alcohol and Drug Research, 1990 <BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The Buddhist, Hindu, and Islamic influences on alcohol consumption are discussed.  The study included a survey of 7,600 persons.  Alcohol dependence was highest among the Buddhists and the Christians, with an incidence of 14 per 1,000 and 10 per 1,000, respectively.  Although Buddhist, Hindu, and Islamic faiths all condemn alcohol use, the Buddhist faith alone appears to have had no effect on reducing alcohol abuse and dependence.  While all Hindus and Moslems, including those who consume alcoholic beverages, appear to understand that their religion prohibits the consumption of alcohol, Buddhists who consume alcohol report that alcohol was not prohibited. It is suggested that these differences should be considered when prevention strategies are developed.  3 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Religion and Substance Use<BR>
<I>Benson, Peter L.</I></B><BR>
In Schumacker, J. (Ed.) <I>Religion and Mental Health</I>. New York:  John Wiley and Son, In press.<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This report offers a review of a significant volume of research on alcohol, marijuana, tobacco, and other drug use in conjunction with religious practice. The author describes in detail how the apparent inhibiting role of religion generalizes to multiple, demographic subgroups and across multiple measures of religion and substance use. Attention is given to documenting the strength of the negative relationship between religion and substance use, with religion compared in predictive power to various social and psychological constructs. The author evaluates the research which is aimed at explaining the religion-substance use association, and offers suggestions for guiding further research.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Adventist Adolescents and Addiction:  Substance Use/Abuse in an Adventist Population and its Relationship to Religion, Family, Self-Perception, and Deviant Behavior<BR>
<I>Daily, S.G.</I></B><BR>
<I>Dissertation Abstracts International</I>, 52B(6):3315B-3316B, 1991<BR>
(Available from UMI, 300 North Zeeb Road, Ann Arbor, MI 48106.  Refer to #DA9128455.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This study was designed to measure the relative impact of four independent variables (religion, family, self-perception, and deviant behavior) on Seventh-day Adventist adolescent substance users. It also analyzed how the Adventist teaching of total abstinence impacts substance use patterns among the church's adolescents, and compared these findings with parallel research conducted with adolescents in six other Protestant denominations, and in the general population. Thirteen thousand eight hundred and eighteen subjects were administered a 465-item questionnaire in carefully controlled group settings. For testing of hypotheses, substance abusers were defined as those who:  smoked tobacco, or drank alcohol more than once a day, used illegal drugs more than once a week, used any of these substances 40 or more times in the last 12 months, or who engaged in binge drinking. As predicted, Adventist adolescents scored significantly lower on reported rates of substance use, and even lower on substance abuse, than adolescents in other Protestant churches. Deviant behavior, religious orientation, family environment, and self-perception all proved to have strong correlations with Adventist adolescent substance use, with religion being even stronger than predicted, and self-perception being weaker than predicted. Contrary to prediction, Hispanic ethnicity was linked to higher reported rates of Adventist adolescent substance use, and geographical location did prove to be a significant factor correlating with varying levels of substance use. Also, contrary to prediction, abstainers scored significantly better than experimenters or moderate users on measures of religion, family, self-perception and deviance. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>1990 Adventist Youth to Youth Conferences:  A Comprehensive Evaluation Report<BR>
<I>Mutch, P. B., and Slikkers, T.</I></B><BR>
Report, Andrews University, 1991<BR>
(Available from Andrews University, Institute of Alcoholism and Drug Dependency, Berrien Springs, MI  49104.) <BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Five 1990 union-wide conferences were evaluated for conference success and effectiveness of outcomes at the local level.  The most impressive finding on conference success, which was high in each case, is the consistency of the response youth make to the program.  The use of identical feeling words to describe overall attitudes and family group experiences is remarkable.  Participants believed their knowledge about drugs had increased and their readiness to become active at the local level as leaders or members increased 2.5 to 5 times over involvement prior to attending.  Participants also believed they were spiritually enriched in spite of the lack of overt religious format.  Evaluation of local club activity 2 to 4 months post-conference in a sample of academies showed that two-thirds of the schools had good to excellent functioning clubs with a wide range of activity.  This suggests that the conferences not only motivate and encourage commitment, but have a continued impact on youth leadership and prevention involvement.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Substance Use and Correlates among Adult Seventh-Day Adventists in North America</B><BR>
<I>McBride, D. C.; Mutch, P. B.; Dudley, R. L.; and Julian, A. G.</I></B><BR>
Report, Andrews University, 1989<BR>
(Available from Andrews University, Institute of Alcoholism and Drug Dependency, Berrien Springs, MI, 49104.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Since the founding of the church, Seventh-Day Adventists have believed in abstinence from alcohol and drug use.  Adventists, however, have begun to discover that their church is not completely immune to general societal changes in accepting, even promoting, the use of alcohol and drugs.  This study was designed to explore whether these changes were widespread among the church membership or limited to symptoms of youthful &quot;wild oats.&quot;  A simple random sample of 5,053 households was selected from the mailing list of the North American monthly edition of the <I>Adventist Review</I>.  Data showed that, except for caffeine, most Adventists (from 64-95 percent) have never used any addictive drug.  However, the data also showed that a small, but significant minority, are current users of drugs.  Of particular concern was the trend towards increased drinking among younger members.  While findings confirm that Adventists are much more likely than the general public to be abstinent, the data strongly suggests the need for the church to vigorously revitalize its theological position on abstinence and to strengthen its prevention programs.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Religious Factors and Drug Usage among Seventh-Day Adventist Youth in North America<BR>
<I>Dudley, R. L.; Mutch, P. B.; and Cruise, R. J.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal for the Scientific Study of Religion</I> 26(2):218-223, 1987<BR>
(Available from Andrews University, Department of Christian Ministry, Berrien Springs, MI 49104.)<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>In an attempt to identify factors that predict frequency of drug use by youth within a conservative denomination, a sample of 801 young people between the ages of 12 and 24 from 71 churches in North America were chosen.  The youth were questioned on the frequency of use of 10 drug categories as well as reasons for not using drugs, a variety of religious attitudes and behaviors, and educational and membership practices.  As a reason for not using drugs, &quot;My commitment to Christ&quot; was the strongest predictor of abstinence from alcohol, tobacco, and all drugs combined.  Other factors of nearly equal strength were &quot;I want to be in control of my life&quot; and &quot;Concern for my health.&quot;  As to religious practices, regular participation in family worship was most highly related to abstinence over all categories with attendance at Sabbath School first for alcohol and personal prayer first for tobacco.  Watching R-rated movies and listening to hard rock music (both strongly discouraged by the church) were both predictive of more frequent use, while intending to remain in the church and believing that God wants us to take care of our bodies were both associated with less frequency.  While membership status of youth, mother, or father or years of parochial education had little effect on frequency of usage, joining the church at a younger age had a weak protective effect.</BLOCKQUOTE>
