<IMG SRC="womenl.gif"><BR>
<A NAME="Sec1"> <H2>ATOD Resource Guide:  Women<BR> Section 1 -- Prevention Material</H2></A>
<BR>
<B>Women and AIDS</B><BR>
Year: 1990<BR>
Format: Brochure<BR>
Length: 10 Pages<BR>
Topic: Injected Drugs and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience: General Public, Women, and Young Adults<BR>
Setting: Community and Health Care Organizations<BR>
Readability: Fairly Difficult<BR>
Availability: American College Health Association, P.O. Box 28937, Baltimore, MD 21240-8937; 410-859-1500
<BLOCKQUOTE>This brochure discusses women and AIDS and looks at the various ways HIV can be transmitted. It mentions several ways to reduce the risk of infection from AIDS, including remaining sexually abstinent, engaging in safe sex, and maintaining monogamous relationships. The brochure provides information for lesbian and bisexual women, offers 10 tips for effective condom use, and lists several hotline phone numbers for additional information.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>The Fact Is...Education Can Help Prevent AIDS and Drug Abuse Among Women</B><BR>
Year: 1990<BR>
Format: Fact Sheet<BR>
Length: 7 Pages<BR>
Topic: AIDS and Alcohol and Other Drug Prevention, Intervention, and Treatment <BR>
Target Audience: Prevention Professionals, Health Care Providers, and Women<BR>
Setting: Community and Health Care Organizations<BR>
Language: English and Spanish<BR>
Readability: Fairly Difficult<BR>
Inventory No.: MS395<BR>
Availability: National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD 20847; 1-800-729-6686
<BLOCKQUOTE>This fact sheet looks at the problem of AIDS within the female population. It provides definitions and abbreviations for HIV/AIDS-related terms and lists several statistics on AIDS and women, including several figures specific to African American and Hispanic women. An extensive resource list citing relevant organizations and publications is also included.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Women of Substance</B><BR>
Organization: Video/Action Fund and American Academy of Pediatrics
Year: 1992<BR>
Format: VHS Video<BR>
Length: 10 Minutes<BR>
Topic: Alcohol and Other Drugs Prevention, Intervention, and Treatment<BR>
Target Audience: OB/GYNs and Health Care Providers<BR>
Setting: Community and Health Care Organizations<BR>
Availability: Video/Action Fund, 3034 Q Street, NW, Washington, DC 20007; 202-338-3346
<BLOCKQUOTE>This 10-minute advocacy video focuses on the problems encountered by pregnant and parenting addicts seeking alcohol or other drug treatment. The video highlights several innovative programs that successfully address the problems faced by pregnant addicts. Through personal stories and experiences, Women of Substance looks beyond the statistics and reveals the human aspect of the problem.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Sex Under the Influence: For Women Only</B><BR>
Organization: BACCHUS<BR>
Format: Booklet<BR>
Length: 6 Pages<BR>
Topic: Alcohol and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience: Students and Women<BR>
Setting: Home and School<BR>
Availability:Gamma Peer Education Network, P.O. Box 100430, Denver, CO 80250; 303-871-3068

<BLOCKQUOTE>This booklet warns female college students about the risks of combining alcohol with sexual activity. It encourages women to consider how they will feel the &quotmorning after&quot before having sex with someone and highlights issues such as body language, date rape, and condom use. The booklet states that both men and women are responsible for safer sex and urges readers to avoid letting alcohol be their guide regarding sex. A cartoon depicting how to use a condom effectively is also included. (Note: BACCHUS is a national, nonprofit organization dedicated to encouraging the responsible use of alcohol by post-secondary students.)</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Impact: A Newsletter of Chemical Health in Minnesota</B><BR>
(Special Issue, Volume 10, Number 3, Spring, 1992) &quotWomen: Reflections on Women and Chemical Health Issues&quot<BR>
Year: 1992<BR>
Format: Newsletter<BR>
Length: 12 Pages<BR>
Topic: Alcohol and Other Drugs and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience: Women and Employees <BR>
Setting: Community Organizations and Home<BR>
Readability: Fairly Difficult<BR>
Availability: The Minnesota Prevention Resource Center, 2829 Verndale Avenue, Anoka, MN 55303; 612-427-5310
<BLOCKQUOTE>This newsletter discusses alcohol, tobacco, and other drug issues as they affect teenage and adult women. The issue contains statistics on chemical dependency and women and looks at several prevention and intervention programs targeted specifically toward females. Alcohol-related sexual assault is discussed, and issues to be considered when planning adolescent prevention programs are highlighted.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Facts on Women and Alcohol</B><BR>
Year: 1991<BR>
Format: Fact Sheet<BR>
Length: 2 Pages<BR>
Topic: Alcohol and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience: Women<BR>
Setting: Health Care and Community Organizations<BR>
Readability: Average<BR>
Availability: New Jersey Alcohol and Drug Resource Center and Clearinghouse, Rutgers University, Center of Alcohol Studies, Piscataway, NJ 08855-0969; 908-932-0787
<BLOCKQUOTE>This fact sheet focuses on women and alcohol and explains some of the sociological, psychological, and biological factors that are unique to women. The fact sheet looks at several gender differences regarding alcohol problems and lists some barriers women face when seeking treatment. A collection of references and a listing of suggested readings is also included.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>So Sad, So Sorry, So What</B><BR>
Format: VHS Video<BR>
Length: 27 Minutes<BR>
Topic: Alcohol and Other Drugs and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience: Inmates<BR>
Setting: Community Organizations and Prison <BR>
Availability: Fanlight Productions, 47 Halifax Street, Boston, MA 02130; 617-524-0980

<BLOCKQUOTE>JoAnne, a 28-year-old recovering drug addict, tells her story in this emotional video about women, drugs, AIDS, and prison. JoAnne discusses her drug addiction and explains how her drug use led to other &quotrisky business.&quot The young woman shares her fears and hopes as she works toward recovery and battles the disease of AIDS. The video takes an intimate look into JoAnne's life through photographs, songs, and personal narrative.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Women: Coming Out of the Shadows</B><BR>
Organization: Fanlight Productions 
Year: 1991<BR>
Format: VHS Video<BR>
Length: 27 Minutes<BR>
Topic: Alcohol and Other Drugs Prevention, Intervention, and Treatment<BR>
Target Audience: AOD Prevention and Treatment Professionals <BR>
Setting: Community and Health Care Organizations<BR>
Availability: Fanlight Productions, 47 Halifax Street, Boston, MA 02130; 617-524-0980 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Ten female alcoholics share their personal stories of addiction and recovery in this video hosted by Mariette Hartley.  The stories provide an excellent overview of the disease, a detailed examination of how alcoholism affects women in particular, and an emotional look at some childhood issues that alcoholism may bury. The women encourage viewers to seek help for themselves or a friend and state that &quotcoming out of the shadows&quot is the best decision they ever made.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Photo-Talk About Tobacco: Look Who's Getting Burned</B><BR>
Year: 1992<BR>
Format: Brochure<BR>
Length: 8 Pages<BR>
Topic: Tobacco and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience: Sr. High Youth and Women<BR>
Setting: Community Organizations and Schools<BR> 
Language: English and Spanish<BR>
Readability: Average<BR>
Availability: Tobacco Education Clearinghouse of California ETR Associates, P.O. Box 1830, Santa Cruz, CA 95061-1830; 1-800-321-4407 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This photo-novella takes place in a beauty school where three women examine the deceptive advertising techniques of cigarette companies. The women discuss ways in which tobacco advertisers specifically target women and offer several ideas on how to boycott tobacco ads and avoid cigarettes altogether. The adverse health consequences of smoking are also discussed.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Women, Sex, and HIV</B><BR>
Organization: American Red Cross<BR> 
Year: 1992<BR>
Format: Brochure<BR>
Length: 14 Pages<BR>
Topic: Alcohol and Other Drugs and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience: Public, Women, and College Students <BR>
Setting: Health Care and Community Organizations<BR>
Readability: Average<BR>
Availability: Prices vary, contact your local American Red Cross Chapter or call 202-973-6000 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This brochure looks at issues surrounding HIV/AIDS with an emphasis on concerns specific to women. The brochure explains how the virus is transmitted and urges women to discuss HIV with their partner before beginning a sexual relationship. Information on AIDS and pregnancy is presented and resources for additional information are included. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Is Drinking Becoming a Problem? Older Women and Alcohol</B><BR>
Year: 1991<BR>
Format: Brochure<BR>
Length: 8 Pages<BR>
Topic: Alcohol and Other Drugs Prevention, Intervention, and Treatment<BR>
Target Audience: Women<BR>
Setting: Health Care and Community Organizations<BR>
Readability: Average<BR>
Availability: Single copies free; American Association of Retired Persons, 601 E Street, NW, Washington, DC 20049

<BLOCKQUOTE>This brochure is designed for older women and lists several warning signs that may indicate a drinking problem. It urges readers to seek help, stating that &quotit is never too late for recovery.&quot The brochure offers steps to assist in locating help and lists resources for further information.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>How to Talk to a Woman Who Has Problems with Alcohol or Other Drugs</B><BR>
Format: Brochure<BR>
Length: 14 Pages<BR>
Topic: Alcohol and Other Drugs and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience: Women<BR>
Setting: Health Care and Community Organizations<BR>
Readability: Average<BR>
Availability: Single copies free; Hazelden, P.O. Box 11, Center City, MN 55012-0011; 1-800-257-7800 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This pamphlet addresses the &quotresponsibility of friendship,&quot and provides specific suggestions on how to help a close female friend with an alcohol or other drug problem. Topics include how to tell if your friend has a problem, how to talk to your friend, and what to do if your friend isn't ready for help. Suggestions on how to help a casual friend and how to help a coworker are also given.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Babies-in-Waiting</B><BR>
Organization: Family Care Communications, Inc.<BR>
Year: 1992<BR>
Format: Booklet<BR>
Length: 21 Pages<BR>
Topic: Alcohol/Drugs and Prevention<BR>
Target Audience: Educators, A/D Prevention Professionals, Health Care Providers, OB/GYNs, Schools, and Community Organization<BR>
Readability: Easy<BR>
Availability: Family Care Communications, Inc., 9226 Amsden Way, Eden Praire, MN  55344; 612-944-5350. 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This discussion guide to the video, &quotBabies-in-Waiting,&quot contains a video overview; pre- and post viewing activities, discussion questions, AOD statistics, and a list of resources for prevention information.  The video portrays three pregnant women that are endangering their own health, as well as their unborn child's, by abusing alcohol, tobacco, marijuana, or crack/cocaine.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<IMG SRC="womenl.gif"><BR><A NAME="Sec2"> <H2>ATOD Resource Guide:  Women<BR> Section 2 -- Studies, Articles, and Reports</H2></A>
<BR>
<H3>Government Publications and Journal Articles</H3>
<B>High Rates of Alcohol Use and History of Physical and Sexual Abuse among Women Outpatients
<I>Swett, C.; Cohen, C.; Surrey, J.; Compaine, A.; and Chavez, R. </I></B> <BR> 
<I>American Journal of Drug Alcohol Abuse </I>17(1): 49-60, 1991<BR>
(Available from Chester Swett Jr., Brattleboro Retreat, 75 Linden Street, Brattleboro, VT 05301.)

<BLOCKQUOTE>A total of 189 consecutive new women patients were surveyed at an adult psychiatric outpatient clinic that did not have a specific program for the treatment of alcoholics. Twenty-seven patients (14 percent) reported a history of heavy alcohol consumption measured by scores of 10 or more on the Michigan Alcoholism Screening Test (MAST), but only 16 had a diagnosis of alcohol abuse or alcohol dependence made by a clinician. Those with a self-reported history of physical and/or sexual abuse had significantly higher scores on the MAST than those with no such history. When the first abuse occurred before the age of 18 years and there was no recent reported abuse, the association of abuse and high MAST scores persisted, suggesting that early physical or sexual abuse may be associated with current levels of alcohol use.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Adapting the Traditional EAP Model to Effectively Serve Battered Women in the Workplace<BR>
<I>Bryant, V.; Eliach, J.; and Green, S. L.<BR></I></B>
<I>Employee Assistance Quarterly </I>6(2): 1-10, 1990<BR>
(Available from Valerie Bryant, 290 Carlton Avenue, Brooklyn, NY 11205.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>While domestic violence is frequently correlated with chemical dependency, EAP professionals have been slow to identify and address this widespread social problem. The authors believe it is crucial for EAP professionals to recognize the numerous disguised ways domestic violence presents itself both in the workplace and in the EAP assessment interview. They suggest that an alternative to the traditional assessment and referral model is indicated to effectively serve this population. A new model of clinical EAP practice with this population is introduced.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Women, Alcohol and Incest: Analytical Review<BR>
<I>Hurley, D. L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Studies on Alcohol </I>52(3): 253-268, 1991<BR>
(Available from Dorothy L. Hurley, Training and Organizational Development, University of Medicine & Dentistry of New Jersey, 45 Knightsbridge Road, Piscataway, NJ 08854.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This study examines the historical treatment of two phenomena that negatively affect the lives of millions of women_incest and alcoholism. It explores the similarities in characteristics of alcoholic women and women with histories of incest. Before the early 1980s, incest histories were rarely mentioned in the literature on alcohol. Similarly, the literature on incest makes only passing references to alcohol abuse among adolescent and adult survivors. Hence, formal research comparisons between the alcoholic woman and the incest-surviving woman are lacking. The purpose of this study is not merely to illustrate the similarities between the alcoholic woman and the incest-surviving woman, but also to present a persuasive argument that multidisciplinary research efforts are essential to promote the identification, diagnosis, and treatment of women who suffer both alcoholism and incest. To accomplish these goals, this study presents parallel reviews of (1) women and alcohol and (2) women and incest. It then develops a comparative profile of the alcoholic woman and the incest-surviving woman. Additionally, the sparse information on the alcoholic incest-surviving woman is reviewed. This study points to the need for further research to address the compelling question that emerges: Why do some incest-surviving women become alcoholic while others do not?</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Influence of Substance Use among Adult Female Inmates<BR>
<I>Blount, W. R.; Danner, T. A.; Vega, M.; and Silverman, I. J.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Drug Issues </I>21(2): 449-467, 1991<BR>
(Available from William R. Blount, University of South Florida, Department of Criminology, Tampa, FL 33620.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Using a 90-percent sample (1,076) of the women incarcerated in August 1985 in Florida prisons and a &quotnon-use, casual/recreational use, problem use&quot typology, the extent of substance abuse was found to be inversely related to age at first arrest as an adult, age at incarceration, and employment at time of arrest. Extent of substance use was directly related to number and percent of prior offenses and incarcerations, broken parental home, and criminality in the family of origin. Though non-users were more likely to be convicted of homicide, casual/recreational users were the most violent. No evidence was found for an increase in substance use/abuse between 1975 and 1985.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Biobehavioral Research on Nicotine Use in Women<BR>
<I>Pomerleau, C. S.; Pomerleau, O. F.; and Garcia, A. W.</I></B><BR>
<I>British Journal of Addiction </I>86(5): 527-531, 1991<BR>
(Available from Cynthia S. Pomerleau, University of Michigan, Department of Psychiatry, Behavioral Medicine Program, Riverview Medical Building, 900 Wall Street, Ann Arbor, MI 48105.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>More American women are taking up smoking than men and fewer are quitting; if current trends continue, rates for women will surpass those for men by the mid-1990s. Ironically, much of what is known about the biobehavioral aspects of smoking is based on research using male subjects. The paper reviews evidence suggesting that: (1) women may differ from men with regard to nicotine intake and/or effects; (2) nicotine intake and effects may be influenced by menstrual cycle phase; (3) oral contraceptive use and estrogen replacement therapy may affect intake and effects of nicotine; (4) the effects of chronic nicotine use on female reproductive endocrinology may have implications for the reinforcement of smoking; and (5) pharmacological agents used to treat smoking may have different effects in women than in men. Guidelines and suggestions are presented by future biobehavioral research in women, including standardization of assessment procedures, attention to the use of appropriate controls, and use of pharmacological probes.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Some Special Considerations for Treatment of Drug Abuse and Dependence in Women<BR>
<I>Mendelson, J. H.; Weiss, R.; Griffin, M.; Mirin, S. M.; Teoh, S. K.; Mello, N. K.; and Lex, B. W.</I></B><BR>
<I>Improving Drug Abuse Treatment: NIDA Monograph No. 106</I>, R.W. Pickens and C.G. Leukefeld, Eds., pp. 313-327. Rockville, MD: National Institute on Drug Abuse, 1991<BR>
(Available from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD 20847.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>Though treatment programs for women may be similar or identical to those developed for male substance abusers, gender related factors merit special attention. This chapter focuses on three important areas for substance abuse treatment programs developed for women. These areas include special considerations for pharmacy-therapeutic treatment of drug abuse and dependence for women and development of new medications for women who abuse drugs; polydrug abuse in association with alcohol abuse by women and their unique needs; and new findings on gender-related differences that are both antecedent to and consequent on cocaine abuse. 44 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>AIDS Prevention for Women at Risk: Experience from a National Demonstration Research Program<BR>
<I>Weissman, G.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Primary Prevention </I>12(1): 49-63, 1991<BR>
(Available from Gloria Weissman, National Institute on Drug Abuse, 5600 Fishers Lane, Room 9A42, Rockville, MD 20857.)
<BLOCKQUOTE>This paper discusses data from a national research program working with large numbers of women at risk for HIV. Important similarities between injection-drug-using (IDU) women and the non-injecting partners of IDU men have been shown. High levels of non-injection drug use are common to both groups, as are crack use and the trading of sex for crack. Despite considerable knowledge about AIDS, risky sex and drug injection behaviors are the rule. Many important principles for outreach and intervention with women have also emerged, including the need for simultaneously aggressive and sensitive outreach strategies and for interventions that consider the full context of these women's lives.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>AIDS Knowledge, Perception of Risk, and Behaviors among Female Sex Partners of Injection Drug Users<BR>
<I>Corby, N. H.; Wolitski, R. J.; Thornton-Johnson, S.; and Tanner, W. M.</I></B><BR>
<I>AIDS Education and Prevention </I>3(4): 353-366, 1991<BR>
(Available from Nancy H. Corby, Ph.D., Long Beach Department of Health and Human Services, 2655 Pine Avenue, Long Beach, CA 90806.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Interviews were conducted with 137 female sex partners of male injection drug users to provide quantitative and qualitative information regarding their AIDS knowledge, attitudes, and specific risk behaviors. Levels of knowledge regarding HIV transmission and prevention were high, with an average of 81.8 percent correct on a 16-item test. Most women (87.5 percent) believed that there was at least some chance they would become HIV infected. Substance abuse was prevalent; 67.2 percent used non-injection drugs (44.5 percent used crack cocaine), and 32.1 percent reported prior use of injection drugs. One-fifth had engaged in prostitution. Although AIDS knowledge was high, almost all (94.9 percent) reported engaging in unprotected vaginal intercourse during the previous 6 months, and 6.6 percent reported anal intercourse without a condom. Among women who did not report consistent condom use, the most frequently stated reasons for non-use of condoms were dislike by their male partner (26.9 percent) and/or personal dislike of condoms (23.1 percent). A disturbing pattern of increased risk was observed among African-American interviewees, who were more likely than Latinos or Whites to have contracted syphilis, have multiple sex partners, engage in prostitution, use crack cocaine, and drink alcohol daily.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Eating Disorders and Alcohol Abuse in Women<BR>
<I>Goldbloom, D. S.; Naranjo, C. A.; Bremner, K. E.; and Hicks, L. K.</I></B><BR>
<I>British Journal of Addiction </I>87(6): 913-920, 1992<BR>
(Available from David S. Goldbloom, Eaton 8N-219, The Toronto Hospital, 200 Elizabeth Street, Toronto, Ontario, Canada M5G 2C4.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Theory and empirical evidence support a relationship between eating disorders (anorexia nervosa and bulimia nervosa) and alcoholism. This study examines the coprevalence and characteristics of these disorders among two populations of adult women: those presenting for treatment of alcoholism and those referred to a specialized eating disorders program. Twenty-two of 73 females (30.1 percent) with alcohol problems met psychometric cutoff scores for eating disorder, while 25 of the 96 eating disorder females (26.9 percent) gave psychometric evidence of alcohol dependence. These rates exceed general population norms. While certain clinical and psychometric features distinguish subgroups with both disorders, the basis for coprevalence and the implications for treatment are unknown.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Acculturation and Changes in Drinking Patterns among Mexican-American Women<BR>
<I>Gilbert, M. J.</I></B><BR>
<I>Alcohol Health and Research World </I>15(3): 234-238, 1991
<BLOCKQUOTE>Over the last decade, researchers have developed extensive data on the epidemiology of alcohol use and alcohol problems among Latino populations. Research has established several consistent findings: Latinas are more likely to be abstainers or very light drinkers than their male counterparts; Latinas, more than Latino men, show a linear acculturation change with more women drinking in each generation beyond immigration status; and Mexican-American women report heavy drinking and problems related to alcohol more often than Cuban-American and Puerto Rican women. This article 
looks at the patterns of alcohol use associated with acculturation among Latinas, with special attention to findings from studies of Mexican-American women. The researchers confirm an increase in alcohol consumption by Mexican-American women with each successive generation following immigration to the United States. Changes in drinking patterns are thought to be part of an acculturation process in which these women adopt the behaviors and attitudes of women in the general population. Implications for prevention are discussed. 26 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Substance Use/Misuse among Female Prostitutes and Female Arrestees<BR>
<I>Kuhns, J. B.; Heide, K. M.; and Silverman, I.</I></B><BR>
<I>International Journal of Addictions </I>27(11): 1283-1292, 1992 
<BLOCKQUOTE>The literature has documented the correlation between prostitution and drug use/misuse. This study probed demographics, drug use experimentation and frequency, age of first drug use, and drug use treatment among 53 female prostitutes and 47 female arrestees. The results showed that: (1) prostitutes were likely to drop out of school; (2) significantly more prostitutes had tried drugs, had used drugs with greater frequency, and had begun drug/alcohol use at younger ages. These results imply that: early drug/alcohol use and withdrawal from school could make young women vulnerable and at higher risk of becoming involved in prostitution; and drug use treatment and intervention need to begin at younger ages. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Why We Are Concerned: An Overview of Women and Alcohol<BR>
<I>Blume, S.</I></B><BR>
<I>The Counselor</I>, January-February: 14, 20, 1989
<BLOCKQUOTE>The effects of alcohol consumption on women are discussed. It is noted that most studies on alcohol and alcohol-related problems are based on the responses of men, and that the results are very different when repeated with women. Physically, physiologically, and psychologically, women respond differently to alcohol than do men. In addition, most treatment programs were initially designed for men, while women remain underrepresented. Three intervention approaches developed for alcoholism are better at reaching men than women: (1) the drinking driver program, (2) the public inebriate program, and (3) the employee assistance program. Screening and outreach for women should be developed in medical and family service settings. The facts presented here emphasize the need for prevention, diagnosis, and treatment for women suffering from the disease of alcoholism. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Spousal Violence among Alcoholic Women as Compared to a Random Household Sample of Women<BR>
<I>Miller, B. A.; Downs, W. R.; and Gondoli, D. M.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Studies on Alcohol </I>50(6): 533-540, 1989 
<BLOCKQUOTE>The purpose of this study is to examine the relationship between spousal violence and women's alcoholism problems. This study compares two samples: (1) 45 alcoholic women selected from local treatment agencies and Alcoholics Anonymous groups; and (2) 40 nonalcoholic women selected randomly from households. Two-hour interview schedules were administered to both samples. The Conflict Tactics Scale was used to assess spouse-to-woman violence. Alcoholic women were found to have higher levels of spouse-to-woman negative verbal interaction, moderate violence, and severe violence as compared to the household women. Multivariate analyses revealed that spouse violence scores were strong predictors of type of sample. This was true even after controlling for presence of alcohol problems in the spouse, income, parental violence, parental alcohol problems, and changes in parental family. These findings suggest that alcoholism treatment programs should screen for spousal violence among women alcoholics, and that victims of spousal violence should be screened for alcohol-related problems. 30 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Gender Differences in Drinking Patterns among College Students:  A Review of the Literature<BR>
<I>Engs, R. C., and Hanson, D. J.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Alcohol and Drug Education </I>35(2): 36-47, 1990 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Studies on gender variations in drinking patterns and problems among college students are reviewed. Most studies report a higher percentage of drinkers among male than among female collegians, although some studies have found no gender differences and others have reported a higher percentage of female than male drinkers. Higher drinking frequencies and consumption levels in male college students have been consistently reported for decades. Several reasons have been suggested for the different drinking patterns of males and females, including a traditional belief that alcohol use and abuse is a male prerogative, the expectation of conventionality for females, and economic dependence of women on men. It appears, however, that changes in women's roles are accompanied by increased drinking among women. Although differences between the sexes on frequency and volume of drinking are narrowing, males continue to experience more alcohol problems and have different attitudes and motivations for drinking. Gender differences have also been reported in beverage preference and drinking locations. It is recommended that college alcohol policies and programs reflect these continuing gender differences.  74 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol and Women</B><BR>
<I>Alcohol Alert </I>10: 1-4, 1990 I<BR>
(Available from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, P.O. Box 2345, Rockville, MD 20847.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This issue of Alcohol Alerts deals with alcohol consumption by women. There are demographic differences in drinking among women and it may vary in different races and ethnic groups. Women have diminished first-pass metabolism of alcohol and are more susceptible than men to the physiological consequences of drinking. The relationship between drinking and breast cancer remains unclear but continued drinking may have adverse effects on fertility. Women alcoholics may encounter different treatment conditions that facilitate or discourage their entry into treatment. The article concludes with a note on women as research subjects in alcohol studies. 49 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Indicators of Women's Alcohol Problems: What Women Themselves Report<BR>
<I>Klee, L.; Schmidt, C.; and Ames, G.</I></B><BR>
<I>International Journal of the Addictions</I> 26(8): 879-898, 1991<BR>
(Available from Linnea Klee, Prevention Research Center, 2532 Durant Avenue, Berkeley, CA 94704.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>In-depth interviews with 65 women in treatment contributed to a taxonomy of indicators of women's alcohol problems, with five major categories and numerous subcategories. The largest number of client indicators appeared in the individual (psychological and behavioral) category. The physiological category included unique indicators regarding physical appearance. Within the social category, family/partner relationships were emphasized. The taxonomy can be useful in therapeutic assessments, to develop survey items, in comparative research, or in alcohol program development. 37 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<H3>Other Publications</H3>
<B>Effects of Alcohol Consumption on Plasma and Urinary Hormone Concentrations in Premenopausal Women<BR>
<I>The Journal of the National Cancer Institute</I></B><BR>
(Available from the National Cancer Institute, International Cancer Information Center, Building 82, Room 103, Bethesda, MD 20892, 301-496-2794) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Most epidemiologic studies of the relationship between alcohol consumption and breast cancer risk over the past decade have shown that persons who consume a moderate amount of alcohol are at a 40 to 100 percent greater risk of breast cancer than those who do not consume alcohol. Dose-response effects have been observed, but no causal relationship has been established. This study examines the hypothesis that alcohol consumption affects levels of reproductive hormones. A controlled-diet study lasting for six consecutive menstrual cycles was conducted. Participants were randomly assigned to two groups, and a crossover design was used. During the last three menstrual cycles, alcohol consumption of the two groups was reversed. Thirty-four premenopausal women, ages 21 to 40 years, with a history of regular menstrual cycles, consumed 30g of ethanol per day for three menstrual cycles and no alcohol for the other three. All food and alcohol consumed were provided by the study. The study showed increases in total estrogen levels and amount of bioavailable estrogens in association with alcohol consumption in premenopausal women. This possible explanatory mechanism for a positive association between alcohol consumption and breast cancer risk merits further investigation.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol Consumption and Risk of Breast Cancer: A Review of the Epidemiologic Evidence<BR>
<I>Rosenberg, L.; Metzger, L. S.; and Palmer, J. R.</I></B><BR>
<I>&quotBreast Cancer&quot In Epidemiologic Reviews</I>, Volume 15, Number 1, 1993<BR> 
(Available from Epidemiologic Reviews, 2007 E. Monument Street, Baltimore, MD 21205-2216.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Positive associations between alcohol and breast cancer have been observed in many epidemiologic studies. Confounding cannot be ruled out as an explanation: the associations have been weak and inconsistent, the causes of breast cancer are to a large extent unknown, and lifestyle correlates of alcohol use are poorly defined. Several biologic mechanisms have been suggested; however, they have little credibility. Epidemiologic methods have improved over the years. Case-control and follow-up studies of alcohol and breast cancer acceptable a decade ago are now considered inadequate. Rigorous attempts have been made to improve participation rates, decrease losses to follow-up, and obtain more detailed information on alcohol exposure and confounding factors. Further investigations must be more rigorous, with particular attention paid to alcohol use at various points in a woman's life and in various subgroups, and to more control of potentially confounding factors. This, coupled with investigation of the postulated mechanisms and with more knowledge of the biology of breast cancer, should eventually enable us to decide if alcohol and breast cancer are causally related.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcoholism, Chemical Dependency and the Lesbian Client<BR>
<I>Glaus, K. O.</I></B><BR>
<I>Women & Therapy</I> 8(1/2): 131-144, 1989<BR>
(Available from Kathleen O'Halleran Glaus, Associate Professor of Professional Psychology, Wright State University, Dayton, OH 45431.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>The chemically dependent lesbian carries a double stigma in U.S. society. Little is known about lesbian alcoholism and drug abuse because society denies the existence of both lesbians and alcoholic women. Issues unique to the lesbian client are outlined, including the high proportion of lesbians who are adult children of alcoholics (ACOAs), heavy reliance on social support in a bar or other public area where drinking is prevalent, excessive isolation, and ambivalent sexual feelings.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Women, Work, and Wellness<BR>
<I>Carver, V., and Ponee, C. (Eds.)</I></B><BR>
Toronto, Canada: Alcoholism and Drug Addiction Research Foundation, 1989<BR>
(Available from Alcoholism and Drug Addiction Research Foundation, 33 Russell Street, Toronto, M5S 2S1 Canada.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This book contains information, ideas, concerns, and experiences on the health of women in the worksite. It is an effort to ensure that employee assistance program personnel, health care providers, union officials, and managers promote the health of all workers, especially women, who have special needs. An underlying concept of this book is that employers have a moral and economic responsibility to optimize the health opportunities for all employees and their dependents, as well as retirees. It is designed as a reference for workplace leaders. Sections include: women and current social issues, including rural women; health issues, including stress; domestic violence; women and chemical dependency, including drug and alcohol use, identification, assessment, and referral; treatment for working women; and innovative worksite programs.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Substance Abuse among Elderly Women<BR>
<I>Glantz, M.D., and Backenheimer, M.S.</I></B><BR>
<I>Clinical Gerontologist </I>8(1): 3-23, 1988<BR>
(Available from Meyer D. Glantz, National Institute on Drug Abuse, Division of Clinical Research, Room 10-A-20, 5600 Fishers Lane, Rockville, MD 20857.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Many elderly are likely to be involved in inappropriate drug and/or alcohol use. The probable forms of the inappropriate use are more varied than with other age populations, the elderly themselves may not be the perpetrators, and identification and differential diagnosis will often be difficult. As sparse as the data on elderly drug use, misuse, and abuse are, the data related to elderly women are less complete. Nevertheless, research support is available for the following conclusions: (1) alcohol abuse and the abuse of illegal drugs are not widespread problems for elderly women; however, they are likely to increasingly become problems as younger women drinkers and illicit drug users age; (2) elderly women are at risk for self- and other-perpetrated drug misuse, including drug-drug and drug-alcohol interactions, and may also be at some risk for self-perpetrated abuse involving legal psychotropics; and (3) elderly women are at greater risk for physician-perpetrated drug abuse involving prescription psychoactive drugs than any other age by gender group.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Drinking and Driving by Young Females<BR>
<I>Popkin, C. L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Accident Analysis and Prevention </I>23(1): 37-44, 1991<BR>
(Available from Carol L. Popkin, Highway Safety Research Center, University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, NC 27514.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Recent research shows that women are drinking and driving more often and that the proportion of female drivers involved in fatal crashes is increasing. U.S. Fatal Accident Reporting System data (Fell 1987) suggest that although alcohol involvement rates in fatal crashes have been declining for the past 4 years, the rates for females ages 21 to 24 have not, and their alcohol involvement rate in late-night single vehicle (SV) crashes, a surrogate measure of alcohol-related (A/R) crashes, is almost as high as that of male drivers. This paper examines the involvement of North Carolina female drivers who are less than 35 years old from 1976 through 1985. It reports on trends in driver licensing, arrests for drinking and driving, SV nighttime and A/R crashes, and measured blood alcohol levels in fatalities. It identifies an emerging driving-while-impaired (DWI) problem for younger women, particularly those 21 to 24 years of age. Significant trends on the involvement of women will have implications for the design and implementation of educational, deterrence, enforcement, and rehabilitation programs.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Women in Treatment<BR>
<I>Aydelotte, R.</I></B><BR>
<I>Employee Assistance</I> August 1991, pp. 20, 23 
<BLOCKQUOTE>In this brief article the author examines the treatment barriers faced by women seeking recovery. Women come into recovery with more guilt and shame than their male counterparts, and many feel that they do not even deserve treatment. Certain stereotypes can keep women from seeking treatment, such as the tendency among employers and physicians not to recognize and/or acknowledge the addicted female. Denial becomes a major impediment to treatment; often those who should be supportive of a woman will instead blame her problem on premenstrual syndrome or the like. According to the 
author, a host of issues and problems affect the quality of treatment offered to women, including the medical profession's prejudice against females. Physical problems associated with alcoholism and drug abuse, as well as pregnancy, are also discussed. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol and Drug Abuse among Female Adolescents<BR>
<I>Waite-O'Brian, N.</I></B><BR>
In<I> Adolescent Substance Abuse: Etiology, Treatment, and Prevention</I>, G. W. Lawson and A. W. Lawson, Eds., pp. 367-380. Gaithersburg, MD: Aspen Publishers, 1992<BR>
(Available from Aspen Publishers, Inc., 200 Orchard Ridge Drive, Suite 200, Gaithersburg, MD 20878.)  
<BLOCKQUOTE>Early adolescence is characterized by a heightened consciousness of self and others. The availability of drugs and alcohol to adolescent females, patterns of drug use, and stages of drug use are explored. Predictive influences of female adolescent drug use are discussed, including age, education and socioeconomic class, ethnicity, and regional use patterns, parental attitudes, family size and structure, and peer influences. Many personality factors are correlates of female adolescent drug use, including alienation and independence, ego strength, antisocial behaviors, and affiliated needs. Special problems for this population include rape, depression, and pregnancy. 24 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Prescription for Despair: Women and Psychotropic Drugs <BR>
<I>Prather, J.E., and Minkow, N.V. </I></B><BR>
In:  <I>Feminist Perspectives on Addictions</I>, N. Van Den Bergh, Ed., pp.87-100. New York: Springer Publishing Company, 1991<BR> 
(Available from Springer Publishing Co., Inc., 536 Broadway, New York, NY 10012-3955.)  
<BLOCKQUOTE>A feminist perspective is presented on the issues affecting treatment for women who suffer from psychotropic drug dependencies. The reasons that almost two-thirds of prescription drugs are taken by women are outlined. The psychotropic drug literature is reviewed. Analysis of these studies reveals that assumptions are made about women's psychological status and mental health that should be challenged from a feminist perspective. As long as pharmaceutical companies and medical professionals perpetuate the belief that women need psychotropic drugs, which is reinforced by sex-role stereotypes of women as dependent, then any consequences women suffer from overuse or abuse will be ignored. Macro level recommendations for changes in social policy and social institutions and micro level suggestions for clinicians treating psychotropic addictions are presented. 55 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Report of the Tobacco Policy Research Group on Marketing and Promotions Targeted at African Americans, Latinos, and Women<BR>
<I>Robinson, R. G.; Barry, M.; Bloch, M.; Glantz, S.; Jordan, J.; Murray, K. B.; Popper, E.; Sutton, C; Tarr-Whelan, K.; Themba, M.; and Younger, S.</I></B><BR>
<I>Tobacco Control </I>1(suppl):S24-S30, 1992<BR>
(Available from Dr. Robert G. Robinson, Fox Chase Cancer Center, 510 Township Line Road, Cheltenham, PA 19012.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>The marketing and promotion activities of the U.S. tobacco industry are reviewed in relation to African Americans, Latinos, and women. Specific areas include social and economic characteristics, marketing and promotion through support to minority-owned business, journalism scholarship endowments, cultural activity support, art sponsorships, employment, majority advertising in minority publications, political contributions, and sponsorship of athletic events. The tobacco industry has been investing in African-American and Latino communities and in women's organizations for a long time. In return, it has achieved a status among these groups that is more than the sum of money received. The author recommends the following: analysis of marketing and promotion to targeted communities; assessment of community factors that aid targeting by the tobacco industry; study of the relationship between marketing and promotion and the use of tobacco by members of the respective communities; identification of the common features in the targeted marketing and promotion strategies in the United States and other countries; identification of the common strategies for alcohol, tobacco, and 
illicit drugs; and an examination of the shift from advertising to promotion that has occurred with these targeted groups. 48 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Quality Treatment for Women<BR>
<I>Eisenstadt, B.L.</I></B><BR>
<I>Employee Assistance</I> February 1993, pp. 31-33, 35 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Basic guidelines are presented for discerning quality treatment programs for women. These include: (1) making the program physically welcoming and hospitable; (2) using supportive experienced clinicians or trained recovering counselors as part of the admission team; (3) making sure the woman knows she is thought of as a human being, not a statistic; (4) offering a variety of counseling modalities, including women only groups as part of the treatment regimen; (5) addressing the many problems faced by addicted women because of societal role factors; (6) employing a staff that is multiculturally competent in dealing with family systems; (7) avoiding the misdiagnosis of alcoholic women as depressed; (8) offering services that are sensitive to lesbian women's needs; and (9) having an HIV/AIDS education component in all substance abuse services offered. 7 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Relationship of Dieting Severity and Bulimic Behaviors to Alcohol and Other Drug Use in Young Women<BR>
<I>Krahn, D.; Kurth, C.; Demitrack, M.; and Drewnowski, A.</I></B><BR>
<I>Journal of Substance Abuse </I>4(4): 341-353, 1992<BR>
(Available from Dean Krahn, William S. Middleton Memorial Veterans Hospital, 2500 Overlook Terrace, Madison, WI 53705.) 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Patients with bulimia nervosa frequently have problems with alcoholism and other substance abuse. This study assessed whether the relationship between eating abnormalities and substance abuse extends to subthreshold levels of dieting and substance use. A self-administered questionnaire assessing dieting and substance use (alcohol, cigarettes, and marijuana) was completed by 1,796 women before their first year in college. Using a scale derived from DSM-III-R criteria for bulimia nervosa and previous research in this population, subjects were categorized as nondieters, casual, intense, severe, at-risk, or bulimic dieters. The relationship between the dieting-severity category and frequency and intensity of alcohol use and frequency of marijuana and cigarette use was assessed. DSM-III-R criteria for bulimia nervosa were met by 1.6 percent of the women. Only 13.8 percent of these women were nondieters. Increasing dieting severity was positively associated with increasing prevalence of alcohol, cigarette, and marijuana use and with increasing frequency and intensity of alcohol use. The bulimic and at-risk dieters were similar in their alcohol and other drug use. The relationship between eating disorders and alcoholism and other substance abuse noted in clinical populations extends in a continuous, graded manner to subthreshold levels of dieting and substance use behaviors. Dieting-related attitudes and behaviors in young women may be related to increased susceptibility to alcohol and drug abuse.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol and Drugs Are Women's Issues: Volume 1. A Review of the Issues<BR>
<I>Roth, P. (Ed.)</I></B><BR>
Metuchen, NJ: The Scarecrow Press, Inc., 1991. 192 p. 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This book reviews issues for multicultural groups of women and explores the linkages between women's health, social, and policy issues and alcohol and drugs. A broad range of issues affecting women's lives is examined in volume one of this two-volume set. The connections between alcohol and other drug problems and other issues such as incest and sexual abuse, domestic violence, teen pregnancy, sexism, racism, underemployment, and poverty are described. Familial and environmental influences affect women's use of alcohol and other drugs. Poverty, access to medical care and adequate treatment, problems related to homelessness, the effects of drug use during pregnancy, living with an alcoholic or drug dependent parent, and the effects of advertising on women are all critical issues examined in this book. Self-help groups for women with alcohol and drug problems are assessed, as is the importance of women advocating for women to generate gender-sensitive alcohol and drug prevention and treatment services. Issues relevant to adolescent girls and young women are also included in several chapters. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Alcohol and Drugs Are Women's Issues:  Volume Two. Model Program Guide<BR>
<I>Roth, P. (Ed.)</I></B><BR>
Metuchen, NJ:  The Scarecrow Press, Inc., 1991. 144 pp. 
<BLOCKQUOTE>This book provides a step-by-step guide to replicating the innovative, award winning model program developed by the Women's Alcohol and Drug Education Project of the Women's Action Alliance. The program was tested at six diverse women's centers in different regions of the country. The model program and guide focus on alcohol, drugs, and related issues most relevant for Latino, African-American, and low-income white women and their children. The model program can be easily carried out in a broad range of women's centers and service organizations that serve adult women and/or teens. Sections cover: getting started, support from the community, staffing, training, organization, program activities, community activities, evaluation of the model, a cycle of classes, and resources.</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<B>Women, Alcohol, and Drugs<BR>
<I>Blume, S. B.</I></B><BR>
In: <I> Comprehensive Handbook of Drug and Alcohol Addiction</I>, N.S. Miller, Ed., pp. 147-177. New York, NY: Marcel Dekker, 1991 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Societal attitudes toward intoxicated women are discussed and traced from biblical times. These attitudes are said to have evolved into a double-edged sword that simultaneously seeks to protect and inaccurately stereotype women. Both female alcoholics and female addicts are victims of a threefold stigma. First, they are victims of the same stigma attached to all alcoholics and addicts. Secondly, a higher standard of behavior is expected of women. The result is that the same behavior considered acceptable for men is considered scandalous for women. Thirdly, and most injurious, is the sexual stigma attached to women who drink or use drugs, and are hence acceptable targets for sexual aggression. The stereotypical connection between drinking and sexual promiscuity in women is also traced to the ancient world. This chapter provides an indepth examination of these social stigmas associated with women who drink, and how these stigmas in turn affect the woman herself. Growing up in a society dominated by these stereotypes, the chemically dependent woman reacts to her problem 
with guilt and shame. Also discussed in this chapter are screening methods, diagnosis, psychosocial and hereditary factors, treatment, mortality, and policy issues that deal with prevention and removing treatment barriers. 183 Ref.</BLOCKQUOTE>

